147 VOID
148 IoAcquireCancelSpinLock(
149  OUT PKIRQL Irql
150  )
151 
152 /*++
153 
154 Routine Description:
155 
156  This routine is invoked to acquire the cancel spin lock. This spin lock
157  must be acquired before setting the address of a cancel routine in an
158  IRP.
159 
160 Arguments:
161 
162  Irql - Address of a variable to receive the old IRQL.
163 
164 Return Value:
165 
166  None.
167 
168 --*/
169 
170 {
171 
172  //
173  // Simply acquire the cancel spin lock and return.
174  //
175 
176  *Irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoCancelLock );
177 }

179 VOID
180 IoAcquireVpbSpinLock(
181  OUT PKIRQL Irql
182  )
183 
184 /*++
185 
186 Routine Description:
187 
188  This routine is invoked to acquire the Volume Parameter Block (VPB) spin
189  lock. This spin lock must be acquired before accessing the mount flag,
190  reference count, and device object fields of a VPB.
191 
192 Arguments:
193 
194  Irql - Address of a variable to receive the old IRQL.
195 
196 Return Value:
197 
198  None.
199 
200 --*/
201 
202 {
203 
204  //
205  // Simply acquire the IopLoadFileSystemDriverVPB spin lock and return.
206  //
207 
208  *Irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoVpbLock );
209  return;
210 }

213 NTSTATUS
214 IoAllocateAdapterChannel(
215  IN PADAPTER_OBJECT AdapterObject,
216  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
217  IN ULONG NumberOfMapRegisters,
218  IN PDRIVER_CONTROL ExecutionRoutine,
219  IN PVOID Context
220  )
221 
222 /*++
223 
224 Routine Description:
225 
226  This routine allocates the adapter channel specified by the adapter object.
227  This is accomplished by calling HalAllocateAdapterChannel which does all of
228  the work.
229 
230 Arguments:
231 
232  AdapterObject - Pointer to the adapter control object to allocate to the
233  driver.
234 
235  DeviceObject - Pointer to the driver's device object that represents the
236  device allocating the adapter.
237 
238  NumberOfMapRegisters - The number of map registers that are to be allocated
239  from the channel, if any.
240 
241  ExecutionRoutine - The address of the driver's execution routine that is
242  invoked once the adapter channel (and possibly map registers) have been
243  allocated.
244 
245  Context - An untyped longword context parameter passed to the driver's
246  execution routine.
247 
248 Return Value:
249 
250  Returns STATUS_SUCESS unless too many map registers are requested.
251 
252 Notes:
253 
254  Note that this routine MUST be invoked at DISPATCH_LEVEL or above.
255 
256 --*/
257 
258 {
259 #if !defined(NO_LEGACY_DRIVERS)
260  PWAIT_CONTEXT_BLOCK wcb;
261 
262  wcb = &DeviceObject->Queue.Wcb;
263 
264  wcb->DeviceObject = DeviceObject;
265  wcb->CurrentIrp = DeviceObject->CurrentIrp;
266  wcb->DeviceContext = Context;
267 
268  return( HalAllocateAdapterChannel( AdapterObject,
269  wcb,
270  NumberOfMapRegisters,
271  ExecutionRoutine ) );
272 #else
273  return( (*((PDMA_ADAPTER)AdapterObject)->DmaOperations->
274  AllocateAdapterChannel)( (PDMA_ADAPTER)AdapterObject,
275  DeviceObject,
276  NumberOfMapRegisters,
277  ExecutionRoutine,
278  Context) );
279 
280 #endif // NO_LEGACY_DRIVERS
281 }
282 
283 
284 VOID
285 IoAllocateController(
286  IN PCONTROLLER_OBJECT ControllerObject,
287  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
288  IN PDRIVER_CONTROL ExecutionRoutine,
289  IN PVOID Context
290  )
291 
292 /*++
293 
294 Routine Description:
295 
296  This routine allocates the controller specified by the controller object.
297  This is accomplished by placing the device object of the driver that wants
298  to allocate the controller on the controller's queue. If the queue is
299  already "busy", then the controller has already been allocated, so the
300  device object is simply placed onto the queue and waits until the controller
301  becomes free.
302 
303  Once the controller becomes free (or if it already is), then the driver's
304  execution routine is invoked.
305 
306 Arguments:
307 
308  ControllerObject - Pointer to the controller object to allocate to the
309  driver.
310 
311  DeviceObject - Pointer to the driver's device object that represents the
312  device allocating the controller.
313 
314  ExecutionRoutine - The address of the driver's execution routine that is
315  invoked once the controller has been allocated.
316 
317  Context - An untyped longword context parameter passed to the driver's
318  execution routine.
319 
320 Return Value:
321 
322  None.
323 
324 Notes:
325 
326  Note that this routine MUST be invoked at DISPATCH_LEVEL or above.
327 
328 --*/
329 
330 {
331  IO_ALLOCATION_ACTION action;
332 
333  //
334  // Initialize the device object's wait context block in case this device
335  // must wait before being able to allocate the controller.
336  //
337 
338  DeviceObject->Queue.Wcb.DeviceRoutine = ExecutionRoutine;
339  DeviceObject->Queue.Wcb.DeviceContext = Context;
340 
341  //
342  // Allocate the controller object for this particular device. If the
343  // controller cannot be allocated because it has already been allocated
344  // to another device, then return to the caller now; otherwise,
345  // continue.
346  //
347 
348  if (!KeInsertDeviceQueue( &ControllerObject->DeviceWaitQueue,
349  &DeviceObject->Queue.Wcb.WaitQueueEntry )) {
350 
351  //
352  // The controller was not busy so it has been allocated. Simply
353  // invoke the driver's execution routine now.
354  //
355 
356  action = ExecutionRoutine( DeviceObject,
357  DeviceObject->CurrentIrp,
358  0,
359  Context );
360 
361  //
362  // If the driver would like to have the controller deallocated,
363  // then deallocate it now.
364  //
365 
366  if (action == DeallocateObject) {
367  IoFreeController( ControllerObject );
368  }
369  }
370 }

372 NTSTATUS
373 IoAllocateDriverObjectExtension(
374  IN PDRIVER_OBJECT DriverObject,
375  IN PVOID ClientIdentificationAddress,
376  IN ULONG DriverObjectExtensionSize,
377  OUT PVOID *DriverObjectExtension
378  )
379 
380 /*++
381 
382 Routine Description:
383  This routine allocates per driver storage for helper or class drivers
384  which may support several different mini-drivers. The storage is tagged
385  with a client identification address which is used to retrieve a pointer
386  to the storage. The client id must be unique.
387 
388  The allocated storage is freed when the driver object is deleted.
389 
390 Arguments:
391 
392  DriverObject - The driver object to which the extension is to be
393  associated.
394 
395  ClientIdentificationAddress - Unique identifier used to retrieve the
396  extension.
397 
398  DriverObjectExtensionSize - Specifies the size in bytes of the extension.
399 
400  DriverObjectExtension - Returns a pointer to the allocated extension.
401 
402 Return Value:
403 
404  Returns the status of the operation. Failure cases are
405  STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES and STATUS_OBJECT_NAME_COLLISION.
406 
407 --*/
408 
409 {
410  KIRQL irql;
411  BOOLEAN inserted = FALSE;
412  PIO_CLIENT_EXTENSION extension;
413  PIO_CLIENT_EXTENSION newExtension;
414 
415  *DriverObjectExtension = NULL;
416 
417  newExtension = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( NonPagedPool,
418  DriverObjectExtensionSize +
419  sizeof( IO_CLIENT_EXTENSION ),
420  'virD');
421 
422  if (newExtension == NULL) {
423  return(STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES);
424  }
425 
426  RtlZeroMemory( newExtension,
427  DriverObjectExtensionSize +
428  sizeof( IO_CLIENT_EXTENSION )
429  );
430 
431  newExtension->ClientIdentificationAddress = ClientIdentificationAddress;
432 
433  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock );
434  extension = DriverObject->DriverExtension->ClientDriverExtension;
435  while (extension != NULL) {
436 
437  if (extension->ClientIdentificationAddress == ClientIdentificationAddress) {
438  break;
439  }
440 
441  extension = extension->NextExtension;
442  }
443 
444  if (extension == NULL) {
445 
446  //
447  // The client id does not exist. Insert the new extension in the
448  // list.
449  //
450 
451  newExtension->NextExtension =
452  DriverObject->DriverExtension->ClientDriverExtension;
453  DriverObject->DriverExtension->ClientDriverExtension = newExtension;
454  inserted = TRUE;
455  }
456 
457  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
458 
459  if (!inserted) {
460  ExFreePool( newExtension );
461  return(STATUS_OBJECT_NAME_COLLISION);
462  }
463 
464  //
465  // Return a pointer to the client's data area.
466  //
467 
468  *DriverObjectExtension = newExtension + 1;
469  return(STATUS_SUCCESS);
470 }
471 
472 PVOID
473 IoAllocateErrorLogEntry(
474  IN PVOID IoObject,
475  IN UCHAR EntrySize
476  )
477 
478 /*++
479 
480 Routine Description:
481 
482  This routine allocates and initializes an error log entry buffer and returns
483  a pointer to the data entry portion of the buffer.
484 
485 Arguments:
486 
487  IoObject - Pointer to driver's device object or driver object.
488 
489  EntrySize - Size of entry to be allocated, in bytes. The maximum size is
490  specified by ERROR_LOG_MAXIMUM_SIZE.
491 
492 Return Value:
493 
494  Pointer to the body of the allocated error log entry, or NULL, if there are
495  no free entries in the system.
496 
497 Note:
498 
499  This routine assumes that the caller wants an error log entry within the
500  bounds of the maximum size.
501 
502 --*/
503 
504 {
505  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
506  PDRIVER_OBJECT driverObject;
507 
508  //
509  // Make sure that a I/O object pointer was passed in.
510  //
511 
512  if (IoObject == NULL) {
513  return(NULL);
514  }
515 
516  //
517  // Assume for a moment this is a device object.
518  //
519 
520  deviceObject = IoObject;
521 
522  //
523  // Determine if this is a driver object or device object or if we
524  // are allocating a generic error log entry. This is determined
525  // from the Type field of the object passed in.
526  //
527 
528  if (deviceObject->Type == IO_TYPE_DEVICE) {
529 
530  driverObject = deviceObject->DriverObject;
531 
532  } else if (deviceObject->Type == IO_TYPE_DRIVER) {
533 
534  driverObject = (PDRIVER_OBJECT) IoObject;
535  deviceObject = NULL;
536 
537  } else {
538 
539  return(NULL);
540 
541  }
542 
543  return (IopAllocateErrorLogEntry(
544  deviceObject,
545  driverObject,
546  EntrySize));
547 
548 }
549 
550 PVOID
551 IoAllocateGenericErrorLogEntry(
552  IN UCHAR EntrySize
553  )
554 
555 /*++
556 
557 Routine Description:
558 
559  This routine allocates and initializes an error log entry buffer and returns
560  a pointer to the data entry portion of the buffer. It's expected to be
561  called from inside the kernel where there may not be a driver object
562  or a device object.
563 
564 Arguments:
565 
566 
567  EntrySize - Size of entry to be allocated, in bytes. The maximum size is
568  specified by ERROR_LOG_MAXIMUM_SIZE.
569 
570 Return Value:
571 
572  Pointer to the body of the allocated error log entry, or NULL, if there are
573  no free entries in the system.
574 
575 Note:
576 
577  This routine assumes that the caller wants an error log entry within the
578  bounds of the maximum size.
579 
580 --*/
581 
582 {
583  return(IopAllocateErrorLogEntry(NULL, NULL, EntrySize));
584 }
585 
586 PVOID
587 IopAllocateErrorLogEntry(
588  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject,
589  IN PDRIVER_OBJECT driverObject,
590  IN UCHAR EntrySize
591  )
592 {
593  PERROR_LOG_ENTRY elEntry;
594  PVOID returnValue;
595  ULONG size;
596  ULONG oldSize;
597 
598  //
599  // Make sure the packet is large enough but not too large.
600  //
601 
602  if (EntrySize < sizeof(IO_ERROR_LOG_PACKET) ||
603  EntrySize > ERROR_LOG_MAXIMUM_SIZE) {
604 
605  return(NULL);
606  }
607 
608  //
609  // Round entry size to a PVOID size boundary.
610  //
611 
612  EntrySize = (UCHAR) ((EntrySize + sizeof(PVOID) - 1) & ~(sizeof(PVOID) - 1));
613 
614  //
615  // Calculate the size of the entry needed.
616  //
617 
618  size = sizeof(ERROR_LOG_ENTRY) + EntrySize;
619 
620  //
621  // Make sure that there are not too many outstanding packets.
622  //
623 
624 
625  oldSize = InterlockedExchangeAdd(&IopErrorLogAllocation, size);
626 
627  if (oldSize > IOP_MAXIMUM_LOG_ALLOCATION) {
628 
629  //
630  // Fail the request.
631  //
632 
633  InterlockedExchangeAdd(&IopErrorLogAllocation, -(LONG)size);
634 
635  return(NULL);
636  }
637 
638  //
639  // Allocate the packet.
640  //
641 
642  elEntry = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( NonPagedPool, size, 'rEoI' );
643 
644  if (elEntry == NULL) {
645 
646  //
647  // Drop the allocation and return.
648  //
649 
650  InterlockedExchangeAdd(&IopErrorLogAllocation, -(LONG)size);
651 
652  return(NULL);
653  }
654 
655  //
656  // Reference the device object and driver object. So they don't
657  // go away before the name gets pulled out.
658  //
659 
660  if (deviceObject != NULL) {
661 
662  ObReferenceObject( deviceObject );
663  }
664 
665  if (driverObject != NULL) {
666 
667  ObReferenceObject( driverObject );
668  }
669 
670  //
671  // Initialize the fields.
672  //
673 
674  RtlZeroMemory(elEntry, size);
675 
676  elEntry->Type = IO_TYPE_ERROR_LOG;
677  elEntry->Size = (USHORT) size;
678  elEntry->DeviceObject = deviceObject;
679  elEntry->DriverObject = driverObject;
680 
681  returnValue = elEntry+1;
682 
683 
684  return returnValue;
685 }
686 
687 VOID
688 IoFreeErrorLogEntry(
689  IN PVOID ElEntry
690  )
691 /*++
692 
693 Routine Description:
694 
695  This routine frees an entry allocated using IoAllocateErrorLogEntry. Its used to
696  free an entry if its not used to actually write an errorlog entry.
697 
698 Arguments:
699 
700  ElEntry - Pointer to the entry that was allocated by IoAllocateErrorLogEntry.
701 
702 Return Value:
703 
704 --*/
705 {
706  PERROR_LOG_ENTRY entry;
707 
708  //
709  // Get the address of the error log entry header,
710  //
711 
712  entry = ((PERROR_LOG_ENTRY) ElEntry) - 1;
713 
714  //
715  // Drop the reference counts.
716  //
717 
718  if (entry->DeviceObject != NULL) {
719  ObDereferenceObject (entry->DeviceObject);
720  }
721 
722  if (entry->DriverObject != NULL) {
723  ObDereferenceObject (entry->DriverObject);
724  }
725 
726  InterlockedExchangeAdd( &IopErrorLogAllocation,
727  -((LONG) (entry->Size )));
728 
729  ExFreePool (entry);
730 
731  return;
732 }

743 
744 PIRP
745 IopAllocateIrpPrivate(
746  IN CCHAR StackSize,
747  IN BOOLEAN ChargeQuota
748  )
749 
750 /*++
751 
752 Routine Description:
753 
754  This routine allocates an I/O Request Packet from the system nonpaged pool.
755  The packet will be allocated to contain StackSize stack locations. The IRP
756  will also be initialized.
757 
758 Arguments:
759 
760  StackSize - Specifies the maximum number of stack locations required.
761 
762  ChargeQuota - Specifies whether quota should be charged against thread.
763 
764 Return Value:
765 
766  The function value is the address of the allocated/initialized IRP,
767  or NULL if one could not be allocated.
768 
769 --*/
770 
771 {
772  USHORT allocateSize;
773  UCHAR fixedSize;
774  PIRP irp;
775  UCHAR lookasideAllocation;
776  PGENERAL_LOOKASIDE lookasideList;
777  PP_NPAGED_LOOKASIDE_NUMBER number;
778  USHORT packetSize;
779  PKPRCB prcb;
780  CCHAR largeIrpStackLocations;
781 
782  //
783  // If the size of the packet required is less than or equal to those on
784  // the lookaside lists, then attempt to allocate the packet from the
785  // lookaside lists.
786  //
787 
788  if (IopIrpProfileStackCountEnabled()) {
789  IopProfileIrpStackCount(StackSize);
790  }
791 
792 
793  irp = NULL;
794 
795  fixedSize = 0;
796  packetSize = IoSizeOfIrp(StackSize);
797  allocateSize = packetSize;
798  prcb = KeGetCurrentPrcb();
799 
800  //
801  // Capture this value once as it can change and use it.
802  //
803 
804  largeIrpStackLocations = (CCHAR)IopLargeIrpStackLocations;
805 
806  if ((StackSize <= (CCHAR)largeIrpStackLocations) &&
807  ((ChargeQuota == FALSE) || (prcb->LookasideIrpFloat > 0))) {
808  fixedSize = IRP_ALLOCATED_FIXED_SIZE;
809  number = LookasideSmallIrpList;
810  if (StackSize != 1) {
811  allocateSize = IoSizeOfIrp((CCHAR)largeIrpStackLocations);
812  number = LookasideLargeIrpList;
813  }
814 
815  lookasideList = prcb->PPLookasideList[number].P;
816  lookasideList->TotalAllocates += 1;
817  irp = (PIRP)InterlockedPopEntrySList(&lookasideList->ListHead);
818 
819  if (irp == NULL) {
820  lookasideList->AllocateMisses += 1;
821  lookasideList = prcb->PPLookasideList[number].L;
822  lookasideList->TotalAllocates += 1;
823  irp = (PIRP)InterlockedPopEntrySList(&lookasideList->ListHead);
824  if (irp == NULL) {
825  lookasideList->AllocateMisses += 1;
826  }
827  }
828 
829  if (IopIrpAutoSizingEnabled() && irp) {
830 
831  //
832  // See if this IRP is a stale entry. If so just free it.
833  // This can happen if we decided to change the lookaside list size.
834  // We need to get the size of the IRP from the information field as the size field
835  // is overlayed with single list entry.
836  //
837 
838  if (irp->IoStatus.Information < packetSize) {
839  lookasideList->TotalFrees += 1;
840  ExFreePool(irp);
841  irp = NULL;
842 
843  } else {
844 
845  //
846  // Update allocateSize to the correct value.
847  //
848  allocateSize = (USHORT)irp->IoStatus.Information;
849  }
850  }
851  }
852 
853 
854  //
855  // If an IRP was not allocated from the lookaside list, then allocate
856  // the packet from nonpaged pool and charge quota if requested.
857  //
858 
859  lookasideAllocation = 0;
860  if (!irp) {
861 
862  //
863  // There are no free packets on the lookaside list, or the packet is
864  // too large to be allocated from one of the lists, so it must be
865  // allocated from nonpaged pool. If quota is to be charged, charge it
866  // against the current process. Otherwise, allocate the pool normally.
867  //
868 
869  if (ChargeQuota) {
870  irp = ExAllocatePoolWithQuotaTag(NonPagedPool|POOL_QUOTA_FAIL_INSTEAD_OF_RAISE,
871  allocateSize,' prI');
872 
873  } else {
874 
875  //
876  // Attempt to allocate the pool from non-paged pool. If this
877  // fails, and the caller's previous mode was kernel then allocate
878  // the pool as must succeed.
879  //
880 
881  irp = ExAllocatePoolWithTag(NonPagedPool, allocateSize, ' prI');
882  }
883 
884  if (!irp) {
885  return NULL;
886  }
887 
888  } else {
889  if (ChargeQuota != FALSE) {
890  lookasideAllocation = IRP_LOOKASIDE_ALLOCATION;
891  InterlockedDecrement( &prcb->LookasideIrpFloat );
892  }
893 
894  ChargeQuota = FALSE;
895  }
896 
897  //
898  // Initialize the packet.
899  // Note that irp->Size may not be equal to IoSizeOfIrp(StackSize)
900  //
901 
902  IopInitializeIrp(irp, allocateSize, StackSize);
903  irp->AllocationFlags = (fixedSize | lookasideAllocation);
904  if (ChargeQuota) {
905  irp->AllocationFlags |= IRP_QUOTA_CHARGED;
906  }
907 
908  return irp;
909 }
910 
911 PMDL
912 IoAllocateMdl(
913  IN PVOID VirtualAddress,
914  IN ULONG Length,
915  IN BOOLEAN SecondaryBuffer,
916  IN BOOLEAN ChargeQuota,
917  IN OUT PIRP Irp OPTIONAL
918  )
919 
920 /*++
921 
922 Routine Description:
923 
924  This routine allocates a Memory Descriptor List (MDL) large enough to map
925  the buffer specified by the VirtualAddress and Length parameters. If the
926  routine is given a pointer to an Irp, then it will chain the MDL to the
927  IRP in the appropriate way.
928 
929  If this routine is not given a pointer to an Irp it is up to the caller to
930  set the MDL address in the IRP that the MDL is being allocated for.
931 
932  Note that the header information of the MDL will also be initialized.
933 
934 Arguments:
935 
936  VirtualAddress - Starting virtual address of the buffer to be mapped.
937 
938  Length - Length, in bytes, of the buffer to be mapped.
939 
940  SecondaryBuffer - Indicates whether this is a chained buffer.
941 
942  ChargeQuota - Indicates whether quota should be charged if MDL allocated.
943 
944  N.B. This parameter is ignored.
945 
946  Irp - Optional pointer to IRP that MDL is being allocated for.
947 
948 Return Value:
949 
950  A pointer to the allocated MDL, or NULL if one could not be allocated.
951  Note that if no MDL could be allocated because there was not enough quota,
952  then it is up to the caller to catch the raised exception.
953 
954 --*/
955 
956 {
957  ULONG allocateSize;
958  USHORT fixedSize;
959  PMDL mdl;
960  ULONG size;
961  PMDL tmpMdlPtr;
962 
963  ASSERT(Length);
964 
965  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER (ChargeQuota);
966 
967  //
968  // If the requested length is greater than 2Gb, then we're not going
969  // to be able to map the memory, so fail the request.
970  //
971 
972  if (Length & 0x80000000) {
973  return NULL;
974  }
975 
976 
977  //
978  // Allocate an MDL from the lookaside list or pool as appropriate.
979  //
980 
981  mdl = NULL;
982  fixedSize = 0;
983  size = ADDRESS_AND_SIZE_TO_SPAN_PAGES(VirtualAddress, Length);
984  if (size > IOP_FIXED_SIZE_MDL_PFNS) {
985  allocateSize = sizeof(MDL) + (sizeof(PFN_NUMBER) * size);
986  if (allocateSize > MAXUSHORT) {
987  return NULL;
988  }
989 
990  } else {
991  fixedSize = MDL_ALLOCATED_FIXED_SIZE;
992  allocateSize = sizeof(MDL) + (sizeof(PFN_NUMBER) * IOP_FIXED_SIZE_MDL_PFNS);
993  mdl = (PMDL)ExAllocateFromPPLookasideList(LookasideMdlList);
994  }
995 
996  if (!mdl) {
997  mdl = ExAllocatePoolWithTag(NonPagedPool, allocateSize, ' ldM');
998  if (!mdl) {
999  return NULL;
1000  }
1001  }
1002 
1003  //
1004  // Now fill in the header of the MDL.
1005  //
1006 
1007  MmInitializeMdl(mdl, VirtualAddress, Length);
1008  mdl->MdlFlags |= (fixedSize);
1009 
1010  //
1011  // Finally, if an IRP was specified, store the address of the MDL
1012  // based on whether or not this is a secondary buffer.
1013  //
1014 
1015  if (Irp) {
1016  if (!SecondaryBuffer) {
1017  Irp->MdlAddress = mdl;
1018 
1019  } else {
1020  tmpMdlPtr = Irp->MdlAddress;
1021  while (tmpMdlPtr->Next != NULL) {
1022  tmpMdlPtr = tmpMdlPtr->Next;
1023  }
1024 
1025  tmpMdlPtr->Next = mdl;
1026  }
1027  }
1028 
1029  return mdl;
1030 }
1031 
1032 NTSTATUS
1033 IoAsynchronousPageWrite(
1034  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
1035  IN PMDL MemoryDescriptorList,
1036  IN PLARGE_INTEGER StartingOffset,
1037  IN PIO_APC_ROUTINE ApcRoutine,
1038  IN PVOID ApcContext,
1039  IN IO_PAGING_PRIORITY Priority,
1040  OUT PIO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatusBlock,
1041  OUT PIRP *Irp OPTIONAL
1042  )
1043 
1044 /*++
1045 
1046 Routine Description:
1047 
1048  This routine provides a special, fast interface for the Modified Page Writer
1049  (MPW) to write pages to the disk quickly and with very little overhead. All
1050  of the special handling for this request is recognized by setting the
1051  IRP_PAGING_IO flag in the IRP flags word.
1052 
1053 Arguments:
1054 
1055  FileObject - A pointer to a referenced file object describing which file
1056  the write should be performed on.
1057 
1058  MemoryDescriptorList - An MDL which describes the physical pages that the
1059  pages should be written to the disk. All of the pages have been locked
1060  in memory. The MDL also describes the length of the write operation.
1061 
1062  StartingOffset - Pointer to the offset in the file from which the write
1063  should take place.
1064 
1065  ApcRoutine - The address of a kernel APC routine which should be executed
1066  after the write operation has completed.
1067 
1068  ApcContext - A context parameter which should be supplied to the kernel APC
1069  routine when it executes.
1070 
1071  Priority - Priority that should be given to this request by the storage stack
1072 
1073  IoStatusBlock - A pointer to the I/O status block in which the final status
1074  and information should be stored.
1075 
1076  Irp - If specified, allows the caller to squirrel away a pointer to the Irp.
1077 
1078 Return Value:
1079 
1080  The function value is the final status of the queue request to the I/O
1081  system subcomponents.
1082 
1083 
1084 --*/
1085 
1086 {
1087  PIRP irp;
1088  KIRQL irql;
1089  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
1090  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
1091  NTSTATUS status;
1092 
1093  //
1094  // Increment performance counters
1095  //
1096 
1097  if (CcIsFileCached(FileObject)) {
1098  CcDataFlushes += 1;
1099  CcDataPages += (MemoryDescriptorList->ByteCount + PAGE_SIZE - 1) >> PAGE_SHIFT;
1100  }
1101 
1102  //
1103  // Begin by getting a pointer to the device object that the file resides
1104  // on.
1105  //
1106 
1107  deviceObject = IoGetRelatedDeviceObject( FileObject );
1108 
1109  //
1110  // Allocate an I/O Request Packet (IRP) for this out-page operation.
1111  //
1112 
1113  irp = IoAllocateIrp( deviceObject->StackSize, FALSE );
1114  if (!irp) {
1115  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
1116  }
1117 
1118  //
1119  // If specified, let the caller know what Irp is responsible for this
1120  // transfer. While this is mainly for debugging purposes, it is
1121  // absolutely essential to debug certain types of problems, and is
1122  // very cheap, thus is included in the FREE build as well.
1123  //
1124 
1125  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT(Irp)) {
1126  *Irp = irp;
1127  }
1128 
1129  //
1130  // Get a pointer to the first stack location in the packet. This location
1131  // will be used to pass the function codes and parameters to the first
1132  // driver.
1133  //
1134 
1135  irpSp = IoGetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
1136 
1137  //
1138  // Fill in the IRP according to this request.
1139  //
1140 
1141  irp->MdlAddress = MemoryDescriptorList;
1142  irp->Flags = IRP_PAGING_IO | IRP_NOCACHE;
1143 
1144  if ( Priority == IoPagingPriorityHigh ) {
1145  irp->Flags |= IRP_HIGH_PRIORITY_PAGING_IO;
1146  }
1147 
1148  irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread = PsGetCurrentThread();
1149  irp->Tail.Overlay.OriginalFileObject = FileObject;
1150  irp->UserBuffer = (PVOID) ((PCHAR) MemoryDescriptorList->StartVa + MemoryDescriptorList->ByteOffset);
1151  irp->RequestorMode = KernelMode;
1152  irp->UserIosb = IoStatusBlock;
1153  irp->Overlay.AsynchronousParameters.UserApcRoutine = ApcRoutine;
1154  irp->Overlay.AsynchronousParameters.UserApcContext = ApcContext;
1155 
1156  //
1157  // Fill in the normal write parameters.
1158  //
1159 
1160  irpSp->MajorFunction = IRP_MJ_WRITE;
1161  irpSp->Parameters.Write.Length = MemoryDescriptorList->ByteCount;
1162  irpSp->Parameters.Write.ByteOffset = *StartingOffset;
1163  irpSp->FileObject = FileObject;
1164 
1165 
1166  //
1167  // Queue the packet to the appropriate driver based on whether or not there
1168  // is a VPB associated with the device.
1169  //
1170 
1171  status = IoCallDriver( deviceObject, irp );
1172 
1173  if (NT_ERROR( status )) {
1174  IoStatusBlock->Status = status;
1175  IoStatusBlock->Information = 0;
1176  KeRaiseIrql( APC_LEVEL, &irql );
1177  ApcRoutine( ApcContext, IoStatusBlock, 0 );
1178  KeLowerIrql( irql );
1179  status = STATUS_PENDING;
1180  }
1181 
1182  return status;
1183 }
1184 
1185 
1186 NTSTATUS
1187 IoAttachDevice(
1188  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT SourceDevice,
1189  IN PUNICODE_STRING TargetDevice,
1190  OUT PDEVICE_OBJECT *AttachedDevice
1191  )
1192 
1193 /*++
1194 
1195 Routine Description:
1196 
1197  This routine "attaches" a device to another device. That is, it associates
1198  the source device to a target device which enables the I/O system to ensure
1199  that the target device a) exists, and b) cannot be unloaded until the source
1200  device has detached. Also, requests bound for the target device are given
1201  to the source device first, where applicable.
1202 
1203 Arguments:
1204 
1205  SourceDevice - Pointer to device object to be attached to the target.
1206 
1207  TargetDevice - Supplies the name of the target device to which the attach
1208  is to occur.
1209 
1210  AttachedDevice - Returns a pointer to the device to which the attach
1211  occurred. This is the device object that the source driver should
1212  use to communicate with the target driver.
1213 
1214 Return Value:
1215 
1216  The function value is the final status of the operation.
1217 
1218 --*/
1219 
1220 {
1221  NTSTATUS status;
1222  PDEVICE_OBJECT targetDevice;
1223  PFILE_OBJECT fileObject;
1224  OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES objectAttributes;
1225  HANDLE fileHandle;
1226  IO_STATUS_BLOCK ioStatus;
1227 
1228  PAGED_CODE();
1229 
1230  //
1231  // Attempt to open the target device for attach access. This ensures that
1232  // the device itself will be opened, with all of the special considerations
1233  // thereof.
1234  //
1235 
1236  InitializeObjectAttributes( &objectAttributes,
1237  TargetDevice,
1238  OBJ_KERNEL_HANDLE,
1239  (HANDLE) NULL,
1240  (PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR) NULL );
1241 
1242  status = ZwOpenFile( &fileHandle,
1243  FILE_READ_ATTRIBUTES,
1244  &objectAttributes,
1245  &ioStatus,
1246  0,
1247  FILE_NON_DIRECTORY_FILE | IO_ATTACH_DEVICE_API );
1248 
1249  if (NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
1250 
1251  //
1252  // The open operation was successful. Dereference the file handle
1253  // and obtain a pointer to the device object for the handle.
1254  //
1255 
1256  status = ObReferenceObjectByHandle( fileHandle,
1257  0,
1258  IoFileObjectType,
1259  KernelMode,
1260  (PVOID *) &fileObject,
1261  NULL );
1262  if (NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
1263 
1264  //
1265  // Get a pointer to the device object for this file, and close
1266  // the handle.
1267  //
1268 
1269  targetDevice = IoGetRelatedDeviceObject( fileObject );
1270  (VOID) ZwClose( fileHandle );
1271 
1272  } else {
1273 
1274  return status;
1275  }
1276 
1277  } else {
1278 
1279  return status;
1280 
1281  }
1282 
1283  //
1284  // Set the attached device pointer so that the driver being attached to
1285  // cannot unload until the detach occurs, and so that attempts to open the
1286  // device object go through the attached driver. Note that the reference
1287  // count is not incremented since exclusive drivers can only be opened once
1288  // and this would count as an open. At that point, both device objects
1289  // would become useless.
1290  //
1291 
1292  status = IoAttachDeviceToDeviceStackSafe( SourceDevice, targetDevice, AttachedDevice );
1293 
1294  //
1295  // Finally, dereference the file object. This decrements the reference
1296  // count for the target device so that when the detach occurs the device
1297  // can go away if necessary.
1298  //
1299 
1300  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
1301 
1302  //
1303  // Return the final status of the operation.
1304  //
1305 
1306  return status;
1307 }
1308 
1309 NTSTATUS
1310 IoAttachDeviceByPointer(
1311  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT SourceDevice,
1312  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT TargetDevice
1313  )
1314 
1315 /*++
1316 
1317 Routine Description:
1318 
1319  This routine attaches the source device object to the target device
1320  object.
1321 
1322 Arguments:
1323 
1324  SourceDevice - Specifies the device object that is to be attached to
1325  the target device.
1326 
1327  TargetDevice - Specifies the device object to which the attachment is
1328  to take place.
1329 
1330 Return Value:
1331 
1332  The function value is the final status of the attach operation.
1333 
1334 Note:
1335 
1336  THIS FUNCTION IS OBSOLETE!!! see IoAttachDeviceToDeviceStack
1337 
1338 --*/
1339 
1340 {
1341  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
1342  NTSTATUS status;
1343 
1344  //
1345  // Get a pointer to the topmost device object in the stack of devices,
1346  // beginning with the TargetDevice.
1347  //
1348 
1349  deviceObject = IoAttachDeviceToDeviceStack( SourceDevice, TargetDevice );
1350  if( deviceObject == NULL ){
1351  status = STATUS_NO_SUCH_DEVICE;
1352  } else {
1353  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
1354  }
1355 
1356  return status;
1357 }
1358 
1359 PDEVICE_OBJECT
1360 IoAttachDeviceToDeviceStack(
1361  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT SourceDevice,
1362  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT TargetDevice
1363  )
1364 /*++
1365 
1366 Routine Description:
1367 
1368  This routine attaches the source device object to the target device
1369  object and returns a pointer to the actual device attached to, if
1370  successful.
1371 
1372 Arguments:
1373 
1374  SourceDevice - Specifies the device object that is to be attached to
1375  the target device.
1376 
1377  TargetDevice - Specifies the device object to which the attachment is
1378  to occur.
1379 
1380 Return Value:
1381 
1382  If successful, this function returns a pointer to the device object to
1383  which the attachment actually occurred.
1384 
1385  If unsuccessful, this function returns NULL. (This could happen if the
1386  device currently at the top of the attachment chain is being unloaded,
1387  deleted or initialized.)
1388 
1389 --*/
1390 {
1391 
1392  return (IopAttachDeviceToDeviceStackSafe(SourceDevice, TargetDevice, NULL));
1393 
1394 }
1395 
1396 NTSTATUS
1397 IoAttachDeviceToDeviceStackSafe(
1398  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT SourceDevice,
1399  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT TargetDevice,
1400  IN OUT PDEVICE_OBJECT *AttachedToDeviceObject
1401  )
1402 /*++
1403 
1404 Routine Description:
1405 
1406  This routine attaches the source device object to the target device
1407  object.
1408 
1409 Arguments:
1410 
1411  SourceDevice - Specifies the device object that is to be attached to
1412  the target device.
1413 
1414  TargetDevice - Specifies the device object to which the attachment is
1415  to occur.
1416 
1417  AttachedToDeviceObject - Specifies a pointer where the attached to device object
1418  is stored. Its updated while holding the database lock so that when a filter gets an IRP
1419  its attached to device object field is updated correctly.
1420 
1421 Return Value:
1422 
1423  None.
1424 
1425 --*/
1426 {
1427 
1428  if (IopAttachDeviceToDeviceStackSafe(SourceDevice, TargetDevice, AttachedToDeviceObject) == NULL)
1429  return STATUS_NO_SUCH_DEVICE;
1430  else
1431  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
1432 }
1433 
1434 PDEVICE_OBJECT
1435 IopAttachDeviceToDeviceStackSafe(
1436  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT SourceDevice,
1437  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT TargetDevice,
1438  OUT PDEVICE_OBJECT *AttachedToDeviceObject OPTIONAL
1439  )
1440 
1441 /*++
1442 
1443 Routine Description:
1444 
1445  This routine attaches the source device object to the target device
1446  object and returns a pointer to the actual device attached to, if
1447  successful.
1448 
1449 Arguments:
1450 
1451  SourceDevice - Specifies the device object that is to be attached to
1452  the target device.
1453 
1454  TargetDevice - Specifies the device object to which the attachment is
1455  to occur.
1456 
1457  AttachedToDeviceObject - Specifies a pointer where the attached to device object
1458  is stored. Its updated while holding the database lock so that when a filter gets an IRP
1459  its attached to device object field is updated correctly.
1460 
1461 Return Value:
1462 
1463  If successful, this function returns a pointer to the device object to
1464  which the attachment actually occurred.
1465 
1466  If unsuccessful, this function returns NULL. (This could happen if the
1467  device currently at the top of the attachment chain is being unloaded,
1468  deleted or initialized.)
1469 
1470 --*/
1471 
1472 {
1473  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
1474  PDEVOBJ_EXTENSION sourceExtension;
1475  KIRQL irql;
1476 
1477  //
1478  // Retrieve a pointer to the source device object's extension outside
1479  // of the IopDatabaseLock, since it isn't protected by that.
1480  //
1481 
1482  sourceExtension = SourceDevice->DeviceObjectExtension;
1483 
1484  //
1485  // Get a pointer to the topmost device object in the stack of devices,
1486  // beginning with the TargetDevice, and attach to it.
1487  //
1488 
1489  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock );
1490 
1491  //
1492  // Tell the Special IRP code the stack has changed. Code that will reexamine
1493  // the stack takes the database lock, so we can place the call here. This
1494  // also allows us to assert correct behavior *before* the stack is built up.
1495  //
1496 
1497  IOV_ATTACH_DEVICE_TO_DEVICE_STACK(SourceDevice, TargetDevice);
1498 
1499  deviceObject = IoGetAttachedDevice( TargetDevice );
1500 
1501  //
1502  // Make sure that the SourceDevice object isn't already attached to
1503  // something else, this is now illegal.
1504  //
1505 
1506  ASSERT( sourceExtension->AttachedTo == NULL );
1507 
1508  //
1509  // Now attach to the device, provided that it is not being unloaded,
1510  // deleted or initializing.
1511  //
1512 
1513  if (deviceObject->Flags & DO_DEVICE_INITIALIZING ||
1514  deviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->ExtensionFlags &
1515  (DOE_UNLOAD_PENDING | DOE_DELETE_PENDING | DOE_REMOVE_PENDING | DOE_REMOVE_PROCESSED)) {
1516 
1517  //
1518  // The device currently at the top of the attachment chain is being
1519  // unloaded, deleted or initialized.
1520  //
1521 
1522  deviceObject = (PDEVICE_OBJECT) NULL;
1523 
1524  } else {
1525 
1526  //
1527  // Perform the attachment. First update the device previously at the
1528  // top of the attachment chain.
1529  //
1530  deviceObject->AttachedDevice = SourceDevice;
1531  deviceObject->Spare1++;
1532 
1533  //
1534  // Now update the new top-of-attachment-chain.
1535  //
1536 
1537  SourceDevice->StackSize = (UCHAR) (deviceObject->StackSize + 1);
1538  SourceDevice->AlignmentRequirement = deviceObject->AlignmentRequirement;
1539  SourceDevice->SectorSize = deviceObject->SectorSize;
1540 
1541  if (deviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->ExtensionFlags & DOE_START_PENDING) {
1542  SourceDevice->DeviceObjectExtension->ExtensionFlags |= DOE_START_PENDING;
1543  }
1544 
1545  //
1546  // Attachment chain is doubly-linked.
1547  //
1548 
1549  sourceExtension->AttachedTo = deviceObject;
1550  }
1551 
1552  //
1553  // Atomically update this field inside the lock.
1554  // The caller has to ensure that this location is in non-paged pool.
1555  // This is required so that a filesystem filter can attach to a device and before it
1556  // gets an IRP it can update its lower device object pointer.
1557  //
1558 
1559  if (AttachedToDeviceObject) {
1560  *AttachedToDeviceObject = deviceObject;
1561  }
1562 
1563  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
1564 
1565  return deviceObject;
1566 }
1567 
1568 PIRP
1569 IoBuildAsynchronousFsdRequest(
1570  IN ULONG MajorFunction,
1571  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
1572  IN OUT PVOID Buffer OPTIONAL,
1573  IN ULONG Length OPTIONAL,
1574  IN PLARGE_INTEGER StartingOffset OPTIONAL,
1575  IN PIO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatusBlock OPTIONAL
1576  )
1577 
1578 /*++
1579 
1580 Routine Description:
1581 
1582  This routine builds an I/O Request Packet (IRP) suitable for a File System
1583  Driver (FSD) to use in requesting an I/O operation from a device driver.
1584  The request must be one of the following request codes:
1585 
1586  IRP_MJ_READ
1587  IRP_MJ_WRITE
1588  IRP_MJ_FLUSH_BUFFERS
1589  IRP_MJ_SHUTDOWN
1590  IRP_MJ_POWER
1591 
1592  This routine provides a simple, fast interface to the device driver w/o
1593  having to put the knowledge of how to build an IRP into all of the FSDs
1594  (and device drivers) in the system.
1595 
1596 Arguments:
1597 
1598  MajorFunction - Function to be performed; see previous list.
1599 
1600  DeviceObject - Pointer to device object on which the I/O will be performed.
1601 
1602  Buffer - Pointer to buffer to get data from or write data into. This
1603  parameter is required for read/write, but not for flush or shutdown
1604  functions.
1605 
1606  Length - Length of buffer in bytes. This parameter is required for
1607  read/write, but not for flush or shutdown functions.
1608 
1609  StartingOffset - Pointer to the offset on the disk to read/write from/to.
1610  This parameter is required for read/write, but not for flush or
1611  shutdown functions.
1612 
1613  IoStatusBlock - Pointer to the I/O status block for completion status
1614  information. This parameter is optional since most asynchronous FSD
1615  requests will be synchronized by using completion routines, and so the
1616  I/O status block will not be written.
1617 
1618 Return Value:
1619 
1620  The function value is a pointer to the IRP representing the specified
1621  request.
1622 
1623 --*/
1624 
1625 {
1626  PIRP irp;
1627  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
1628 
1629  //
1630  // Begin by allocating the IRP for this request. Do not charge quota to
1631  // the current process for this IRP.
1632  //
1633 
1634  irp = IoAllocateIrp( DeviceObject->StackSize, FALSE );
1635  if (!irp) {
1636  return irp;
1637  }
1638 
1639  //
1640  // Set current thread for IoSetHardErrorOrVerifyDevice.
1641  //
1642 
1643  irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread = PsGetCurrentThread();
1644 
1645  //
1646  // Get a pointer to the stack location of the first driver which will be
1647  // invoked. This is where the function codes and the parameters are set.
1648  //
1649 
1650  irpSp = IoGetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
1651 
1652  //
1653  // Set the major function code.
1654  //
1655 
1656  irpSp->MajorFunction = (UCHAR) MajorFunction;
1657 
1658  if (MajorFunction != IRP_MJ_FLUSH_BUFFERS &&
1659  MajorFunction != IRP_MJ_SHUTDOWN &&
1660  MajorFunction != IRP_MJ_PNP &&
1661  MajorFunction != IRP_MJ_POWER) {
1662 
1663  //
1664  // Now allocate a buffer or lock the pages of the caller's buffer into
1665  // memory based on whether the target device performs direct or buffered
1666  // I/O operations.
1667  //
1668 
1669  if (DeviceObject->Flags & DO_BUFFERED_IO) {
1670 
1671  //
1672  // The target device supports buffered I/O operations. Allocate a
1673  // system buffer and, if this is a write, fill it in. Otherwise,
1674  // the copy will be done into the caller's buffer in the completion
1675  // code. Also note that the system buffer should be deallocated on
1676  // completion. Also, set the parameters based on whether this is a
1677  // read or a write operation.
1678  //
1679 
1680  irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( NonPagedPoolCacheAligned,
1681  Length,
1682  ' oI' );
1683  if (irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer == NULL) {
1684  IoFreeIrp( irp );
1685  return (PIRP) NULL;
1686  }
1687 
1688  if (MajorFunction == IRP_MJ_WRITE) {
1689  RtlCopyMemory( irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer, Buffer, Length );
1690  irp->Flags = IRP_BUFFERED_IO | IRP_DEALLOCATE_BUFFER;
1691  } else {
1692  irp->Flags = IRP_BUFFERED_IO | IRP_DEALLOCATE_BUFFER | IRP_INPUT_OPERATION;
1693  irp->UserBuffer = Buffer;
1694  }
1695 
1696  } else if (DeviceObject->Flags & DO_DIRECT_IO) {
1697 
1698  //
1699  // The target device supports direct I/O operations. Allocate
1700  // an MDL large enough to map the buffer and lock the pages into
1701  // memory.
1702  //
1703 
1704  irp->MdlAddress = IoAllocateMdl( Buffer,
1705  Length,
1706  FALSE,
1707  FALSE,
1708  NULL );
1709 
1710  if (irp->MdlAddress == NULL) {
1711  IoFreeIrp( irp );
1712  return (PIRP) NULL;
1713  }
1714 
1715  try {
1716  MmProbeAndLockPages( irp->MdlAddress,
1717  KernelMode,
1718  (LOCK_OPERATION) (MajorFunction == IRP_MJ_READ ? IoWriteAccess : IoReadAccess) );
1719  } except(EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
1720  if (irp->MdlAddress != NULL) {
1721  IoFreeMdl( irp->MdlAddress );
1722  }
1723  IoFreeIrp( irp );
1724  return (PIRP) NULL;
1725  }
1726 
1727  } else {
1728 
1729  //
1730  // The operation is neither buffered nor direct. Simply pass the
1731  // address of the buffer in the packet to the driver.
1732  //
1733 
1734  irp->UserBuffer = Buffer;
1735  }
1736 
1737  //
1738  // Set the parameters according to whether this is a read or a write
1739  // operation. Notice that these parameters must be set even if the
1740  // driver has not specified buffered or direct I/O.
1741  //
1742 
1743  if (MajorFunction == IRP_MJ_WRITE) {
1744  irpSp->Parameters.Write.Length = Length;
1745  irpSp->Parameters.Write.ByteOffset = *StartingOffset;
1746  } else {
1747  irpSp->Parameters.Read.Length = Length;
1748  irpSp->Parameters.Read.ByteOffset = *StartingOffset;
1749  }
1750  }
1751 
1752  //
1753  // Finally, set the address of the I/O status block and return a pointer
1754  // to the IRP.
1755  //
1756 
1757  irp->UserIosb = IoStatusBlock;
1758  return irp;
1759 }
1760 
1761 PIRP
1762 IoBuildDeviceIoControlRequest(
1763  IN ULONG IoControlCode,
1764  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
1765  IN PVOID InputBuffer OPTIONAL,
1766  IN ULONG InputBufferLength,
1767  OUT PVOID OutputBuffer OPTIONAL,
1768  IN ULONG OutputBufferLength,
1769  IN BOOLEAN InternalDeviceIoControl,
1770  IN PKEVENT Event,
1771  OUT PIO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatusBlock
1772  )
1773 
1774 /*++
1775 
1776 Routine Description:
1777 
1778  This routine builds an I/O Request Packet (IRP) that can be used to
1779  perform a synchronous internal or normal device I/O control function.
1780 
1781 Arguments:
1782 
1783  IoControlCode - Specifies the device I/O control code that is to be
1784  performed by the target device driver.
1785 
1786  DeviceObject - Specifies the target device on which the I/O control
1787  function is to be performed.
1788 
1789  InputBuffer - Optional pointer to an input buffer that is to be passed
1790  to the device driver.
1791 
1792  InputBufferLength - Length of the InputBuffer in bytes. If the Input-
1793  Buffer parameter is not passed, this parameter must be zero.
1794 
1795  OutputBuffer - Optional pointer to an output buffer that is to be passed
1796  to the device driver.
1797 
1798  OutputBufferLength - Length of the OutputBuffer in bytes. If the
1799  OutputBuffer parameter is not passed, this parameter must be zero.
1800 
1801  InternalDeviceIoControl - A BOOLEAN parameter that specifies whether
1802  the packet that gets generated should have a major function code
1803  of IRP_MJ_INTERNAL_DEVICE_CONTROL (the parameter is TRUE), or
1804  IRP_MJ_DEVICE_CONTROL (the parameter is FALSE).
1805 
1806  Event - Supplies a pointer to a kernel event that is to be set to the
1807  Signaled state when the I/O operation is complete. Note that the
1808  Event must already be set to the Not-Signaled state.
1809 
1810  IoStatusBlock - Supplies a pointer to an I/O status block that is to
1811  be filled in with the final status of the operation once it
1812  completes.
1813 
1814 Return Value:
1815 
1816  The function value is a pointer to the generated IRP suitable for calling
1817  the target device driver.
1818 
1819 --*/
1820 
1821 {
1822  PIRP irp;
1823  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
1824  ULONG method;
1825 
1826  //
1827  // Begin by allocating the IRP for this request. Do not charge quota to
1828  // the current process for this IRP.
1829  //
1830 
1831  irp = IoAllocateIrp( DeviceObject->StackSize, FALSE );
1832  if (!irp) {
1833  return irp;
1834  }
1835 
1836  //
1837  // Get a pointer to the stack location of the first driver which will be
1838  // invoked. This is where the function codes and the parameters are set.
1839  //
1840 
1841  irpSp = IoGetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
1842 
1843  //
1844  // Set the major function code based on the type of device I/O control
1845  // function the caller has specified.
1846  //
1847 
1848  if (InternalDeviceIoControl) {
1849  irpSp->MajorFunction = IRP_MJ_INTERNAL_DEVICE_CONTROL;
1850  } else {
1851  irpSp->MajorFunction = IRP_MJ_DEVICE_CONTROL;
1852  }
1853 
1854  //
1855  // Copy the caller's parameters to the service-specific portion of the
1856  // IRP for those parameters that are the same for all four methods.
1857  //
1858 
1859  irpSp->Parameters.DeviceIoControl.OutputBufferLength = OutputBufferLength;
1860  irpSp->Parameters.DeviceIoControl.InputBufferLength = InputBufferLength;
1861  irpSp->Parameters.DeviceIoControl.IoControlCode = IoControlCode;
1862 
1863  //
1864  // Get the method bits from the I/O control code to determine how the
1865  // buffers are to be passed to the driver.
1866  //
1867 
1868  method = IoControlCode & 3;
1869 
1870  //
1871  // Based on the method that the buffers are being passed, either allocate
1872  // buffers or build MDLs or do nothing.
1873  //
1874 
1875  switch ( method ) {
1876 
1877  case METHOD_BUFFERED:
1878 
1879  //
1880  // For this case, allocate a buffer that is large enough to contain
1881  // both the input and the output buffers. Copy the input buffer
1882  // to the allocated buffer and set the appropriate IRP fields.
1883  //
1884 
1885  if (InputBufferLength != 0 || OutputBufferLength != 0) {
1886  irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( NonPagedPoolCacheAligned,
1887  InputBufferLength > OutputBufferLength ? InputBufferLength : OutputBufferLength,
1888  ' oI' );
1889  if (irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer == NULL) {
1890  IoFreeIrp( irp );
1891  return (PIRP) NULL;
1892  }
1893  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( InputBuffer )) {
1894  RtlCopyMemory( irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer,
1895  InputBuffer,
1896  InputBufferLength );
1897  }
1898  irp->Flags = IRP_BUFFERED_IO | IRP_DEALLOCATE_BUFFER;
1899  irp->UserBuffer = OutputBuffer;
1900  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( OutputBuffer )) {
1901  irp->Flags |= IRP_INPUT_OPERATION;
1902  }
1903  } else {
1904  irp->Flags = 0;
1905  irp->UserBuffer = (PVOID) NULL;
1906  }
1907 
1908  break;
1909 
1910  case METHOD_IN_DIRECT:
1911  case METHOD_OUT_DIRECT:
1912 
1913  //
1914  // For these two cases, allocate a buffer that is large enough to
1915  // contain the input buffer, if any, and copy the information to
1916  // the allocated buffer. Then build an MDL for either read or write
1917  // access, depending on the method, for the output buffer. Note
1918  // that an output buffer must have been specified.
1919  //
1920 
1921  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( InputBuffer )) {
1922  irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( NonPagedPoolCacheAligned,
1923  InputBufferLength,
1924  ' oI' );
1925  if (irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer == NULL) {
1926  IoFreeIrp( irp );
1927  return (PIRP) NULL;
1928  }
1929  RtlCopyMemory( irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer,
1930  InputBuffer,
1931  InputBufferLength );
1932  irp->Flags = IRP_BUFFERED_IO | IRP_DEALLOCATE_BUFFER;
1933  } else {
1934  irp->Flags = 0;
1935  }
1936 
1937  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( OutputBuffer )) {
1938  irp->MdlAddress = IoAllocateMdl( OutputBuffer,
1939  OutputBufferLength,
1940  FALSE,
1941  FALSE,
1942  NULL );
1943  if (irp->MdlAddress == NULL) {
1944  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( InputBuffer )) {
1945  ExFreePool( irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer );
1946  }
1947  IoFreeIrp( irp );
1948  return (PIRP) NULL;
1949  }
1950 
1951  try {
1952 
1953  MmProbeAndLockPages( irp->MdlAddress,
1954  KernelMode,
1955  (LOCK_OPERATION) ((method == 1) ? IoReadAccess : IoWriteAccess) );
1956 
1957  } except (EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
1958 
1959  if (irp->MdlAddress != NULL) {
1960  IoFreeMdl( irp->MdlAddress );
1961  }
1962 
1963  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( InputBuffer )) {
1964  ExFreePool( irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer );
1965  }
1966 
1967  IoFreeIrp( irp );
1968  return (PIRP) NULL;
1969  }
1970  }
1971 
1972  break;
1973 
1974  case METHOD_NEITHER:
1975 
1976  //
1977  // For this case, do nothing. Everything is up to the driver.
1978  // Simply give the driver a copy of the caller's parameters and
1979  // let the driver do everything itself.
1980  //
1981 
1982  irp->UserBuffer = OutputBuffer;
1983  irpSp->Parameters.DeviceIoControl.Type3InputBuffer = InputBuffer;
1984  }
1985 
1986  //
1987  // Finally, set the address of the I/O status block and the address of
1988  // the kernel event object. Note that I/O completion will not attempt
1989  // to dereference the event since there is no file object associated
1990  // with this operation.
1991  //
1992 
1993  irp->UserIosb = IoStatusBlock;
1994  irp->UserEvent = Event;
1995 
1996  //
1997  // Also set the address of the current thread in the packet so the
1998  // completion code will have a context to execute in. The IRP also
1999  // needs to be queued to the thread since the caller is going to set
2000  // the file object pointer.
2001  //
2002 
2003  irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread = PsGetCurrentThread();
2004  IopQueueThreadIrp( irp );
2005 
2006  //
2007  // Simply return a pointer to the packet.
2008  //
2009 
2010  return irp;
2011 }
2012 
2013 VOID
2014 IoBuildPartialMdl(
2015  IN PMDL SourceMdl,
2016  IN OUT PMDL TargetMdl,
2017  IN PVOID VirtualAddress,
2018  IN ULONG Length
2019  )
2020 
2021 /*++
2022 
2023 Routine Description:
2024 
2025  This routine maps a portion of a buffer as described by an MDL. The
2026  portion of the buffer to be mapped is specified via a virtual address
2027  and an optional length. If the length is not supplied, then the
2028  remainder of the buffer is mapped.
2029 
2030 Arguments:
2031 
2032  SourceMdl - MDL for the current buffer.
2033 
2034  TargetMdl - MDL to map the specified portion of the buffer.
2035 
2036  VirtualAddress - Base of the buffer to begin mapping.
2037 
2038  Length - Length of buffer to be mapped; if zero, remainder.
2039 
2040 Return Value:
2041 
2042  None.
2043 
2044 Notes:
2045 
2046  This routine assumes that the target MDL is large enough to map the
2047  desired portion of the buffer. If the target is not large enough
2048  then an exception will be raised.
2049 
2050  It is also assumed that the remaining length of the buffer to be mapped
2051  is non-zero.
2052 
2053 --*/
2054 
2055 {
2056  ULONG_PTR baseVa;
2057  ULONG offset;
2058  ULONG newLength;
2059  ULONG pageOffset;
2060  PPFN_NUMBER basePointer;
2061  PPFN_NUMBER copyPointer;
2062 
2063  //
2064  // Calculate the base address of the buffer that the source Mdl maps.
2065  // Then, determine the length of the buffer to be mapped, if not
2066  // specified.
2067  //
2068 
2069  baseVa = (ULONG_PTR) MmGetMdlBaseVa( SourceMdl );
2070  offset = (ULONG) ((ULONG_PTR)VirtualAddress - baseVa) - MmGetMdlByteOffset(SourceMdl);
2071 
2072  if (Length == 0) {
2073  newLength = MmGetMdlByteCount( SourceMdl ) - offset;
2074  } else {
2075  newLength = Length;
2076  //if (newLength > (MmGetMdlByteCount(SourceMdl) - offset)) {
2077  // KeBugCheck( TARGET_MDL_TOO_SMALL );
2078  //}
2079  }
2080 
2081  //
2082  // Initialize the target MDL header. Note that the original size of
2083  // the MDL structure itself is left unchanged.
2084  //
2085 
2086  TargetMdl->Process = SourceMdl->Process;
2087 
2088  TargetMdl->StartVa = (PVOID) PAGE_ALIGN( VirtualAddress );
2089  pageOffset = ((ULONG)((ULONG_PTR) TargetMdl->StartVa - (ULONG_PTR) SourceMdl->StartVa)) >> PAGE_SHIFT;
2090 
2091 
2092  TargetMdl->ByteCount = newLength;
2093  TargetMdl->ByteOffset = BYTE_OFFSET( VirtualAddress );
2094  newLength = ADDRESS_AND_SIZE_TO_SPAN_PAGES( VirtualAddress, newLength );
2095  if (((TargetMdl->Size - sizeof( MDL )) / sizeof (PFN_NUMBER)) < newLength ) {
2096  KeBugCheck( TARGET_MDL_TOO_SMALL );
2097  }
2098 
2099  //
2100  // Set the MdlFlags in the target MDL. Clear all flags but
2101  // carry across the allocation information, page read and the
2102  // system mapped info.
2103  //
2104 
2105  TargetMdl->MdlFlags &= (MDL_ALLOCATED_FIXED_SIZE | MDL_ALLOCATED_MUST_SUCCEED);
2106  TargetMdl->MdlFlags |= SourceMdl->MdlFlags & (MDL_SOURCE_IS_NONPAGED_POOL |
2107  MDL_MAPPED_TO_SYSTEM_VA |
2108  MDL_IO_PAGE_READ |
2109  MDL_IO_SPACE );
2110  TargetMdl->MdlFlags |= MDL_PARTIAL;
2111 
2112 #if DBG
2113  if (TargetMdl->MdlFlags & MDL_MAPPED_TO_SYSTEM_VA) {
2114  TargetMdl->MdlFlags |= MDL_PARENT_MAPPED_SYSTEM_VA;
2115  }
2116 #endif //DBG
2117 
2118  //
2119  // Preserved the mapped system address.
2120  //
2121 
2122  TargetMdl->MappedSystemVa = (PUCHAR)SourceMdl->MappedSystemVa + offset;
2123 
2124  //
2125  // Determine the base address of the first PFN in the source MDL that
2126  // needs to be copied to the target. Then, copy as many PFNs as are
2127  // needed.
2128  //
2129 
2130  basePointer = MmGetMdlPfnArray(SourceMdl);
2131  basePointer += pageOffset;
2132  copyPointer = MmGetMdlPfnArray(TargetMdl);
2133 
2134  while (newLength > 0) {
2135  *copyPointer = *basePointer;
2136  copyPointer++;
2137  basePointer++;
2138  newLength--;
2139  }
2140 }
2141 
2142 PIRP
2143 IoBuildSynchronousFsdRequest(
2144  IN ULONG MajorFunction,
2145  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
2146  IN OUT PVOID Buffer OPTIONAL,
2147  IN ULONG Length OPTIONAL,
2148  IN PLARGE_INTEGER StartingOffset OPTIONAL,
2149  IN PKEVENT Event,
2150  OUT PIO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatusBlock
2151  )
2152 
2153 /*++
2154 
2155 Routine Description:
2156 
2157  This routine builds an I/O Request Packet (IRP) suitable for a File System
2158  Driver (FSD) to use in requesting an I/O operation from a device driver.
2159  The request must be one of the following request codes:
2160 
2161  IRP_MJ_READ
2162  IRP_MJ_WRITE
2163  IRP_MJ_FLUSH_BUFFERS
2164  IRP_MJ_SHUTDOWN
2165 
2166  This routine provides a simple, fast interface to the device driver w/o
2167  having to put the knowledge of how to build an IRP into all of the FSDs
2168  (and device drivers) in the system.
2169 
2170  The IRP created by this function causes the I/O system to complete the
2171  request by setting the specified event to the Signaled state.
2172 
2173 Arguments:
2174 
2175  MajorFunction - Function to be performed; see previous list.
2176 
2177  DeviceObject - Pointer to device object on which the I/O will be performed.
2178 
2179  Buffer - Pointer to buffer to get data from or write data into. This
2180  parameter is required for read/write, but not for flush or shutdown
2181  functions.
2182 
2183  Length - Length of buffer in bytes. This parameter is required for
2184  read/write, but not for flush or shutdown functions.
2185 
2186  StartingOffset - Pointer to the offset on the disk to read/write from/to.
2187  This parameter is required for read/write, but not for flush or
2188  shutdown functions.
2189 
2190  Event - Pointer to a kernel event structure for synchronization. The event
2191  will be set to the Signaled state when the I/O has completed.
2192 
2193  IoStatusBlock - Pointer to I/O status block for completion status info.
2194 
2195 Return Value:
2196 
2197  The function value is a pointer to the IRP representing the specified
2198  request.
2199 
2200 --*/
2201 
2202 {
2203  PIRP irp;
2204 
2205  //
2206  // Do all of the real work in real IRP build routine.
2207  //
2208 
2209  irp = IoBuildAsynchronousFsdRequest( MajorFunction,
2210  DeviceObject,
2211  Buffer,
2212  Length,
2213  StartingOffset,
2214  IoStatusBlock );
2215  if (irp == NULL) {
2216  return irp;
2217  }
2218 
2219  //
2220  // Now fill in the event to the completion code will do the right thing.
2221  // Notice that because there is no FileObject, the I/O completion code
2222  // will not attempt to dereference the event.
2223  //
2224 
2225  irp->UserEvent = Event;
2226 
2227  //
2228  // There will be a file object associated w/this packet, so it must be
2229  // queued to the thread.
2230  //
2231 
2232  IopQueueThreadIrp( irp );
2233  return irp;
2234 }

2237 NTSTATUS
2238 FASTCALL
2239 IofCallDriver(
2240  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
2241  IN OUT PIRP Irp
2242  )
2243 {
2244  if (pIofCallDriver != NULL) {
2245 
2246  //
2247  // This routine will either jump immediately to IovCallDriver or
2248  // IoPerfCallDriver.
2249  //
2250  return pIofCallDriver(DeviceObject, Irp, _ReturnAddress());
2251  }
2252 
2253  return IopfCallDriver(DeviceObject, Irp);
2254 }
2255 
2256 NTSTATUS
2257 FASTCALL
2258 IofCallDriverSpecifyReturn(
2259  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
2260  IN OUT PIRP Irp,
2261  IN PVOID ReturnAddress OPTIONAL
2262  )
2263 {
2264  if (pIofCallDriver != NULL) {
2265 
2266  //
2267  // This routine will either jump immediately to IovCallDriver or
2268  // IoPerfCallDriver.
2269  //
2270  return pIofCallDriver(DeviceObject, Irp, ReturnAddress);
2271  }
2272 
2273  return IopfCallDriver(DeviceObject, Irp);

2275 
2276 
2277 BOOLEAN
2278 IoCancelIrp(
2279  IN PIRP Irp
2280  )
2281 
2282 /*++
2283 
2284 Routine Description:
2285 
2286  This routine is invoked to cancel an individual I/O Request Packet.
2287  It acquires the cancel spin lock, sets the cancel flag in the IRP, and
2288  then invokes the cancel routine specified by the appropriate field in
2289  the IRP, if a routine was specified. It is expected that the cancel
2290  routine will release the cancel spinlock. If there is no cancel routine,
2291  then the cancel spin lock is released.
2292 
2293 Arguments:
2294 
2295  Irp - Supplies a pointer to the IRP to be cancelled.
2296 
2297 Return Value:
2298 
2299  The function value is TRUE if the IRP was in a cancelable state (it
2300  had a cancel routine), else FALSE is returned.
2301 
2302 Notes:
2303 
2304  It is assumed that the caller has taken the necessary action to ensure
2305  that the packet cannot be fully completed before invoking this routine.
2306 
2307 --*/
2308 
2309 {
2310  PDRIVER_CANCEL cancelRoutine;
2311  KIRQL irql;
2312  BOOLEAN returnValue;
2313 
2314 
2315  ASSERT( Irp->Type == IO_TYPE_IRP );
2316 
2317  if (IopVerifierOn) {
2318  if (IOV_CANCEL_IRP(Irp, &returnValue)) {
2319  return returnValue;
2320  }
2321  }
2322 
2323  //
2324  // Acquire the cancel spin lock.
2325  //
2326 
2327  IoAcquireCancelSpinLock( &irql );
2328 
2329  //
2330  // Set the cancel flag in the IRP.
2331  //
2332 
2333  Irp->Cancel = TRUE;
2334 
2335  //
2336  // Obtain the address of the cancel routine, and if one was specified,
2337  // invoke it.
2338  //
2339 
2340  cancelRoutine = (PDRIVER_CANCEL) (ULONG_PTR) InterlockedExchangePointer( (PVOID *) &Irp->CancelRoutine,
2341  NULL );
2342 
2343  if (cancelRoutine) {
2344  if (Irp->CurrentLocation > (CCHAR) (Irp->StackCount + 1)) {
2345  KeBugCheckEx( CANCEL_STATE_IN_COMPLETED_IRP, (ULONG_PTR) Irp, (ULONG_PTR) cancelRoutine, 0, 0 );
2346  }
2347  Irp->CancelIrql = irql;
2348 
2349  cancelRoutine( Irp->Tail.Overlay.CurrentStackLocation->DeviceObject,
2350  Irp );
2351  //
2352  // The cancel spinlock should have been released by the cancel routine.
2353  //
2354 
2355  return(TRUE);
2356 
2357  } else {
2358 
2359  //
2360  // There was no cancel routine, so release the cancel spinlock and
2361  // return indicating the Irp was not currently cancelable.
2362  //
2363 
2364  IoReleaseCancelSpinLock( irql );
2365 
2366  return(FALSE);
2367  }
2368 }
2369 
2370 
2371 
2372 VOID
2373 IoCancelThreadIo(
2374  IN PETHREAD Thread
2375  )
2376 
2377 /*++
2378 
2379 Routine Description:
2380 
2381  This routine cancels all of the I/O operations for the specified thread.
2382  This is accomplished by walking the list of IRPs in the thread IRP list
2383  and canceling each one individually. No other I/O operations can be
2384  started for the thread since this routine has control of the thread itself.
2385 
2386 Arguments:
2387 
2388  Tcb - Pointer to the Thread Control Block for the thread.
2389 
2390 Return Value:
2391 
2392  None.
2393 
2394 --*/
2395 
2396 {
2397  PLIST_ENTRY header;
2398  PLIST_ENTRY entry;
2399  KIRQL irql;
2400  PETHREAD thread;
2401  PIRP irp;
2402  ULONG count;
2403  LARGE_INTEGER interval;
2404 
2405  PAGED_CODE();
2406 
2407  DBG_UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( Thread );
2408 
2409  thread = PsGetCurrentThread();
2410 
2411  header = &thread->IrpList;
2412 
2413  if ( IsListEmpty( header )) {
2414  return;
2415  }
2416 
2417  //
2418  // Raise the IRQL so that the IrpList cannot be modified by a completion
2419  // APC.
2420  //
2421 
2422  KeRaiseIrql( APC_LEVEL, &irql );
2423 
2424  entry = header->Flink;
2425 
2426  //
2427  // Walk the list of pending IRPs, canceling each of them.
2428  //
2429 
2430  while (header != entry) {
2431  irp = CONTAINING_RECORD( entry, IRP, ThreadListEntry );
2432  IoCancelIrp( irp );
2433  entry = entry->Flink;
2434  }
2435 
2436  //
2437  // Wait for the requests to complete. Note that waiting may eventually
2438  // timeout, in which case more work must be done.
2439  //
2440 
2441  count = 0;
2442  interval.QuadPart = -10 * 1000 * 100;
2443 
2444  while (!IsListEmpty( header )) {
2445 
2446  //
2447  // Lower the IRQL so that the thread APC can fire which will complete
2448  // the requests. Delay execution for a time and let the request
2449  // finish. The delay time is 100ms.
2450  //
2451 
2452  KeLowerIrql( irql );
2453  KeDelayExecutionThread( KernelMode, FALSE, &interval );
2454 
2455  if (count++ > 3000) {
2456 
2457  //
2458  // This I/O request has timed out, as it has not been completed
2459  // for a full 5 minutes. Attempt to remove the packet's association
2460  // with this thread. Note that by not resetting the count, the
2461  // next time through the loop the next packet, if there is one,
2462  // which has also timed out, will be dealt with, although it
2463  // will be given another 100ms to complete.
2464  //
2465 
2466  IopDisassociateThreadIrp();
2467  }
2468 
2469  KeRaiseIrql( APC_LEVEL, &irql );
2470  }
2471 
2472  KeLowerIrql( irql );
2473 }
2474 
2475 NTSTATUS
2476 IoCheckDesiredAccess(
2477  IN OUT PACCESS_MASK DesiredAccess,
2478  IN ACCESS_MASK GrantedAccess
2479  )
2480 
2481 /*++
2482 
2483 Routine Description:
2484 
2485  This routine is invoked to determine whether or not the granted access
2486  to a file allows the access specified by a desired access.
2487 
2488 Arguments:
2489 
2490  DesiredAccess - Pointer to a variable containing the access desired to
2491  the file.
2492 
2493  GrantedAccess - Access currently granted to the file.
2494 
2495 Return Value:
2496 
2497  The final status of the access check is the function value. If the
2498  accessor has the access to the file, then STATUS_SUCCESS is returned;
2499  otherwise, STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED is returned.
2500 
2501  Also, the DesiredAccess is returned with no generic mapping.
2502 
2503 --*/
2504 
2505 {
2506  PAGED_CODE();
2507 
2508  //
2509  // Convert the desired access to a non-generic access mask.
2510  //
2511 
2512  RtlMapGenericMask( DesiredAccess,
2513  &IoFileObjectType->TypeInfo.GenericMapping );
2514 
2515  //
2516  // Determine whether the desired access to the file is allowed, given
2517  // the current granted access.
2518  //
2519 
2520  if (!SeComputeDeniedAccesses( GrantedAccess, *DesiredAccess )) {
2521  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
2522  } else {
2523  return STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED;
2524  }
2525 }

2527 NTSTATUS
2528 IoCheckEaBufferValidity(
2529  IN PFILE_FULL_EA_INFORMATION EaBuffer,
2530  IN ULONG EaLength,
2531  OUT PULONG ErrorOffset
2532  )
2533 
2534 /*++
2535 
2536 Routine Description:
2537 
2538  This routine checks the validity of the specified EA buffer to guarantee
2539  that its format is proper, no fields hang over, that it is not recursive,
2540  etc.
2541 
2542 Arguments:
2543 
2544  EaBuffer - Pointer to the buffer containing the EAs to be checked.
2545 
2546  EaLength - Specifies the length of EaBuffer.
2547 
2548  ErrorOffset - A variable to receive the offset of the offending entry
2549  in the EA buffer if an error is incurred. This variable is only
2550  valid if an error occurs.
2551 
2552 Return Value:
2553 
2554  The function value is STATUS_SUCCESS if the EA buffer contains a valid,
2555  properly formed list, otherwise STATUS_EA_LIST_INCONSISTENT.
2556 
2557 --*/
2558 
2559 #define ALIGN_LONG( Address ) ( (ULONG) ((Address + 3) & ~3) )
2560 
2561 #define GET_OFFSET_LENGTH( CurrentEa, EaBase ) ( \
2562  (ULONG) ((PCHAR) CurrentEa - (PCHAR) EaBase) )
2563 
2564 {
2565  LONG tempLength;
2566  ULONG entrySize;
2567  PFILE_FULL_EA_INFORMATION eas;
2568 
2569  PAGED_CODE();
2570 
2571  //
2572  // Walk the buffer and ensure that its format is valid. That is, ensure
2573  // that it does not walk off the end of the buffer, is not recursive,
2574  // etc.
2575  //
2576 
2577  eas = EaBuffer;
2578  tempLength = EaLength;
2579 
2580  for (;;) {
2581 
2582  //
2583  // Get the size of the current entry in the buffer. The minimum
2584  // size of the entry is the fixed size part of the structure plus
2585  // the length of the name, a single termination character byte which
2586  // must be present (a 0), plus the length of the value. If this
2587  // is not the last entry, then there will also be pad bytes to get
2588  // to the next longword boundary.
2589  //
2590 
2591  //
2592  // Start by checking that the fixed size lies within the stated length.
2593  //
2594 
2595  if (tempLength < FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_FULL_EA_INFORMATION, EaName[0])) {
2596 
2597  *ErrorOffset = GET_OFFSET_LENGTH( eas, EaBuffer );
2598  return STATUS_EA_LIST_INCONSISTENT;
2599  }
2600 
2601  entrySize = FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_FULL_EA_INFORMATION, EaName[0] ) +
2602  eas->EaNameLength + 1 + eas->EaValueLength;
2603 
2604  //
2605  // Confirm that the full length lies within the stated buffer length.
2606  //
2607 
2608  if ((ULONG) tempLength < entrySize) {
2609 
2610  *ErrorOffset = GET_OFFSET_LENGTH( eas, EaBuffer );
2611  return STATUS_EA_LIST_INCONSISTENT;
2612  }
2613 
2614  //
2615  // Confirm that there is a NULL terminator after the name.
2616  //
2617 
2618  if (eas->EaName[eas->EaNameLength] != '\0') {
2619 
2620  *ErrorOffset = GET_OFFSET_LENGTH( eas, EaBuffer );
2621  return STATUS_EA_LIST_INCONSISTENT;
2622  }
2623 
2624  if (eas->NextEntryOffset) {
2625 
2626  //
2627  // There is another entry in the buffer and it must be longword
2628  // aligned. Ensure that the offset indicates that it is. If it
2629  // isn't, return invalid parameter.
2630  //
2631 
2632  if (ALIGN_LONG( entrySize ) != eas->NextEntryOffset ||
2633  (LONG) eas->NextEntryOffset < 0) {
2634  *ErrorOffset = GET_OFFSET_LENGTH( eas, EaBuffer );
2635  return STATUS_EA_LIST_INCONSISTENT;
2636 
2637  } else {
2638 
2639  //
2640  // There is another entry in the buffer, so account for the
2641  // size of the current entry in the length and get a pointer
2642  // to the next entry.
2643  //
2644 
2645  tempLength -= eas->NextEntryOffset;
2646  if (tempLength < 0) {
2647  *ErrorOffset = GET_OFFSET_LENGTH( eas, EaBuffer );
2648  return STATUS_EA_LIST_INCONSISTENT;
2649  }
2650  eas = (PFILE_FULL_EA_INFORMATION) ((PCHAR) eas + eas->NextEntryOffset);
2651 
2652  }
2653 
2654  } else {
2655 
2656  //
2657  // There are no other entries in the buffer. Simply account for
2658  // the overall buffer length according to the size of the current
2659  // entry and exit the loop.
2660  //
2661 
2662  tempLength -= entrySize;
2663  break;
2664 
2665  }
2666  }
2667 
2668  //
2669  // All of the entries in the buffer have been processed. Check to see
2670  // whether the overall buffer length went negative. If so, return an
2671  // error.
2672  //
2673 
2674  if (tempLength < 0) {
2675  *ErrorOffset = GET_OFFSET_LENGTH( eas, EaBuffer );
2676  return STATUS_EA_LIST_INCONSISTENT;
2677  }
2678 
2679  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
2680 }
2681 
2682 NTSTATUS
2683 IoCheckFunctionAccess(
2684  IN ACCESS_MASK GrantedAccess,
2685  IN UCHAR MajorFunction,
2686  IN UCHAR MinorFunction,
2687  IN ULONG IoControlCode,
2688  IN PVOID Arg1 OPTIONAL,
2689  IN PVOID Arg2 OPTIONAL
2690  )
2691 
2692 /*++
2693 
2694 Routine Description:
2695 
2696  This routine checks the parameters and access for the function and
2697  parameters specified by the input parameters against the current access
2698  to the file as described by the GrantedAccess mask parameter. If the
2699  caller has the access to the file, then a successful status code is
2700  returned. Otherwise, an error status code is returned as the function
2701  value.
2702 
2703 Arguments:
2704 
2705  GrantedAccess - Access granted to the file for the caller.
2706 
2707  MajorFunction - Major function code for the operation being performed.
2708 
2709  MinorFunction - Minor function code for the operation being performed.
2710 
2711  IoControlCode - I/O function control code for a device or file system I/O
2712  code. Used only for those two function types.
2713 
2714  Arg1 - Optional argument that depends on the major function. Its
2715  FileInformationClass if the major function code indicates a query or set
2716  file information function is being performed. It points to Security Info
2717  if major function code is IRP_MJ_*_SECURITY.
2718 
2719  Arg2 - Optional second argument that depends on the major function. Currently its
2720  FsInformationClass.This parameter MUST be supplied if the major function
2721  code indicates that a query or set file system information function is
2722  being performed.
2723 
2724 Return Value:
2725 
2726  The final status of the access check is the function value. If the
2727  accessor has the access to the file, then STATUS_SUCCESS is returned;
2728  otherwise, STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED is returned.
2729 
2730 Note:
2731 
2732  The GrantedAccess mask may not contain any generic mappings. That is,
2733  the IoCheckDesiredAccess function must have been previously invoked to
2734  return a full mask.
2735 
2736 --*/
2737 
2738 {
2739  NTSTATUS status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
2740  PFILE_INFORMATION_CLASS FileInformationClass;
2741  PFS_INFORMATION_CLASS FsInformationClass;
2742  SECURITY_INFORMATION SecurityInformation;
2743  ACCESS_MASK DesiredAccess;
2744 
2745  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( MinorFunction );
2746 
2747  PAGED_CODE();
2748 
2749  //
2750  // Determine the major function being performed. If the function code
2751  // is invalid, then return an error.
2752  //
2753 
2754  FileInformationClass = (PFILE_INFORMATION_CLASS)Arg1;
2755  FsInformationClass = (PFS_INFORMATION_CLASS)Arg2;
2756 
2757  switch( MajorFunction ) {
2758 
2759  case IRP_MJ_CREATE:
2760  case IRP_MJ_CLOSE:
2761 
2762  break;
2763 
2764  case IRP_MJ_READ:
2765 
2766  if (SeComputeDeniedAccesses( GrantedAccess, FILE_READ_DATA )) {
2767  status = STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED;
2768  }
2769  break;
2770 
2771  case IRP_MJ_WRITE:
2772 
2773  if (!SeComputeGrantedAccesses( GrantedAccess, FILE_WRITE_DATA | FILE_APPEND_DATA )) {
2774  status = STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED;
2775  }
2776  break;
2777 
2778  case IRP_MJ_QUERY_INFORMATION:
2779 
2780  if (IopQueryOperationAccess[*FileInformationClass] != 0) {
2781  if (SeComputeDeniedAccesses( GrantedAccess, IopQueryOperationAccess[*FileInformationClass] )) {
2782  status = STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED;
2783  }
2784  }
2785  break;
2786 
2787  case IRP_MJ_SET_INFORMATION:
2788 
2789  if (IopSetOperationAccess[*FileInformationClass] != 0) {
2790  if (SeComputeDeniedAccesses( GrantedAccess, IopSetOperationAccess[*FileInformationClass] )) {
2791  status = STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED;
2792  }
2793  }
2794  break;
2795 
2796  case IRP_MJ_QUERY_EA:
2797 
2798  if (SeComputeDeniedAccesses( GrantedAccess, FILE_READ_EA )) {
2799  status = STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED;
2800  }
2801  break;
2802 
2803  case IRP_MJ_SET_EA:
2804 
2805  if (SeComputeDeniedAccesses( GrantedAccess, FILE_WRITE_EA )) {
2806  status = STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED;
2807  }
2808  break;
2809 
2810  case IRP_MJ_FLUSH_BUFFERS:
2811 
2812  if (SeComputeDeniedAccesses( GrantedAccess, FILE_WRITE_DATA )) {
2813  status = STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED;
2814  }
2815  break;
2816 
2817  case IRP_MJ_QUERY_VOLUME_INFORMATION:
2818 
2819  if (SeComputeDeniedAccesses( GrantedAccess, IopQueryFsOperationAccess[*FsInformationClass] )) {
2820  status = STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED;
2821  }
2822  break;
2823 
2824  case IRP_MJ_SET_VOLUME_INFORMATION:
2825 
2826  if (SeComputeDeniedAccesses( GrantedAccess, IopSetFsOperationAccess[*FsInformationClass] )) {
2827  status = STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED;
2828  }
2829  break;
2830 
2831  case IRP_MJ_DIRECTORY_CONTROL:
2832 
2833  if (SeComputeDeniedAccesses( GrantedAccess, FILE_LIST_DIRECTORY )) {
2834  status = STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED;
2835  }
2836  break;
2837 
2838  case IRP_MJ_FILE_SYSTEM_CONTROL:
2839  case IRP_MJ_DEVICE_CONTROL:
2840  case IRP_MJ_INTERNAL_DEVICE_CONTROL:
2841 
2842  {
2843  ULONG accessMode = (IoControlCode >> 14) & 3;
2844 
2845  if (accessMode != FILE_ANY_ACCESS) {
2846 
2847  //
2848  // This I/O control requires that the caller have read, write,
2849  // or read/write access to the object. If this is not the case,
2850  // then cleanup and return an appropriate error status code.
2851  //
2852 
2853  if (!(SeComputeGrantedAccesses( GrantedAccess, accessMode ))) {
2854  status = STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED;
2855  }
2856  }
2857 
2858  }
2859  break;
2860 
2861  case IRP_MJ_LOCK_CONTROL:
2862 
2863  if (!SeComputeGrantedAccesses( GrantedAccess, FILE_READ_DATA | FILE_WRITE_DATA )) {
2864  status = STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED;
2865  }
2866  break;
2867 
2868  case IRP_MJ_SET_SECURITY:
2869 
2870  SecurityInformation = *((PSECURITY_INFORMATION)Arg1);
2871  SeSetSecurityAccessMask(SecurityInformation, &DesiredAccess);
2872 
2873  if (SeComputeDeniedAccesses( GrantedAccess, DesiredAccess )) {
2874  status = STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED;
2875  }
2876  break;
2877 
2878  case IRP_MJ_QUERY_SECURITY:
2879 
2880  SecurityInformation = *((PSECURITY_INFORMATION)Arg1);
2881  SeQuerySecurityAccessMask(SecurityInformation, &DesiredAccess);
2882 
2883  if (SeComputeDeniedAccesses( GrantedAccess, DesiredAccess )) {
2884  status = STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED;
2885  }
2886  break;
2887  default:
2888 
2889  status = STATUS_INVALID_DEVICE_REQUEST;
2890  }
2891  return status;
2892 }
