2894 NTKERNELAPI
2895 NTSTATUS
2896 IoCheckQuerySetFileInformation(
2897  IN FILE_INFORMATION_CLASS FileInformationClass,
2898  IN ULONG Length,
2899  IN BOOLEAN SetOperation
2900  )
2901 
2902 /*++
2903 
2904 Routine Description:
2905 
2906  This routine checks the validity of the parameters for either a query or a
2907  set file information operation. It is used primarily by network servers
2908  running in kernel mode since no such parameter validity checking is done
2909  in the normal path.
2910 
2911 Arguments:
2912 
2913  FileInformationClass - Specifies the information class to check checked.
2914 
2915  Length - Specifies the length of the buffer supplied.
2916 
2917  SetOperation - Specifies that the operation was a set file information as
2918  opposed to a query operation.
2919 
2920 Return Value:
2921 
2922  The function value is STATUS_SUCCESS if the parameters were valid,
2923  otherwise an appropriate error is returned.
2924 
2925 --*/
2926 
2927 {
2928  PCHAR operationLength;
2929 
2930  //
2931  // The file information class itself must be w/in the valid range of file
2932  // information classes, otherwise this is an invalid information class.
2933  //
2934 
2935  if ((ULONG) FileInformationClass >= FileMaximumInformation) {
2936  return STATUS_INVALID_INFO_CLASS;
2937  }
2938 
2939  //
2940  // Determine whether this is a query or a set operation and act accordingly.
2941  //
2942 
2943  if (SetOperation) {
2944  operationLength = (PCHAR) IopSetOperationLength;
2945  }
2946  else {
2947  operationLength = (PCHAR) IopQueryOperationLength;
2948  }
2949 
2950  if (!operationLength[FileInformationClass]) {
2951  return STATUS_INVALID_INFO_CLASS;
2952  }
2953  if (Length < (ULONG) operationLength[FileInformationClass]) {
2954  return STATUS_INFO_LENGTH_MISMATCH;
2955  }
2956 
2957  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
2958 }
2959 NTKERNELAPI
2960 NTSTATUS
2961 IoCheckQuerySetVolumeInformation(
2962  IN FS_INFORMATION_CLASS FsInformationClass,
2963  IN ULONG Length,
2964  IN BOOLEAN SetOperation
2965  )
2966 
2967 /*++
2968 
2969 Routine Description:
2970 
2971  This routine checks the validity of the parameters for either a query or a
2972  set volume information operation. It is used primarily by network servers
2973  running in kernel mode since no such parameter validity checking is done
2974  in the normal path.
2975 
2976 Arguments:
2977 
2978  FsInformationClass - Specifies the information class to check.
2979 
2980  Length - Specifies the length of the buffer supplied.
2981 
2982  SetOperation - Specifies that the operation was a set volume information as
2983  opposed to a query operation.
2984 
2985 Return Value:
2986 
2987  The function value is STATUS_SUCCESS if the parameters were valid,
2988  otherwise an appropriate error is returned.
2989 
2990 --*/
2991 
2992 {
2993  PCHAR operationLength;
2994 
2995  if (SetOperation) {
2996  operationLength = (PCHAR) IopSetFsOperationLength;
2997  }
2998  else {
2999  operationLength = (PCHAR) IopQueryFsOperationLength;
3000  }
3001 
3002  //
3003  // The volume information class itself must be w/in the valid range of file
3004  // information classes, otherwise this is an invalid information class.
3005  //
3006  if ((ULONG) FsInformationClass >= FileFsMaximumInformation ||
3007  operationLength[ FsInformationClass ] == 0 ) {
3008 
3009  return STATUS_INVALID_INFO_CLASS;
3010  }
3011 
3012  if (Length < (ULONG) operationLength[FsInformationClass]) {
3013  return STATUS_INFO_LENGTH_MISMATCH;
3014  }
3015 
3016  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
3017 }

3019 NTSTATUS
3020 IoCheckQuotaBufferValidity(
3021  IN PFILE_QUOTA_INFORMATION QuotaBuffer,
3022  IN ULONG QuotaLength,
3023  OUT PULONG ErrorOffset
3024  )
3025 
3026 /*++
3027 
3028 Routine Description:
3029 
3030  This routine checks the validity of the specified quota buffer to guarantee
3031  that its format is proper, no fields hang over, that it is not recursive,
3032  etc.
3033 
3034 Arguments:
3035 
3036  QuotaBuffer - Pointer to the buffer containing the quota entries to be
3037  checked.
3038 
3039  QuotaLength - Specifies the length of the QuotaBuffer.
3040 
3041  ErrorOffset - A variable to receive the offset of the offending entry in
3042  the quota buffer if an error is incurred. This variable is only valid
3043  if an error occurs.
3044 
3045 Return Value:
3046 
3047  The function value is STATUS_SUCCESS if the quota buffer contains a valid,
3048  properly formed list, otherwise STATUS_QUOTA_LIST_INCONSISTENT.
3049 
3050 --*/
3051 
3052 #if defined(_X86_)
3053 #define REQUIRED_QUOTA_ALIGNMENT sizeof( ULONG )
3054 #else
3055 #define REQUIRED_QUOTA_ALIGNMENT sizeof( ULONGLONG )
3056 #endif
3057 
3058 #define ALIGN_QUAD( Address ) ( (ULONG) ((Address + 7) & ~7) )
3059 
3060 #define GET_OFFSET_LENGTH( CurrentEntry, QuotaBase ) (\
3061  (ULONG) ((PCHAR) CurrentEntry - (PCHAR) QuotaBase) )
3062 
3063 {
3064  LONG tempLength;
3065  ULONG entrySize;
3066  PFILE_QUOTA_INFORMATION quotas;
3067 
3068  PAGED_CODE();
3069 
3070  //
3071  // Walk the buffer and ensure that its format is valid. That is, ensure
3072  // that it does not walk off the end of the buffer, is not recursive,
3073  // etc.
3074  //
3075 
3076  quotas = QuotaBuffer;
3077  tempLength = QuotaLength;
3078 
3079  //
3080  // Ensure the buffer has the correct alignment.
3081  //
3082 
3083  if ((ULONG_PTR) quotas & (REQUIRED_QUOTA_ALIGNMENT - 1)) {
3084  *ErrorOffset = 0;
3085  return STATUS_DATATYPE_MISALIGNMENT;
3086  }
3087 
3088  for (;;) {
3089 
3090  ULONG sidLength;
3091 
3092  //
3093  // Get the size of the current entry in the buffer. The minimum size
3094  // of the entry is the fixed size part of the structure plus the actual
3095  // length of the SID. If this is not the last entry, then there will
3096  // also be pad bytes to get to the next longword boundary. Likewise,
3097  // ensure that the SID itself is valid.
3098  //
3099 
3100  if (tempLength < FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_QUOTA_INFORMATION, Sid ) ||
3101  !RtlValidSid( &quotas->Sid )) {
3102  goto error_exit;
3103  }
3104 
3105  sidLength = RtlLengthSid( (&quotas->Sid) );
3106  entrySize = FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_QUOTA_INFORMATION, Sid ) + sidLength;
3107 
3108  //
3109  // Confirm that the full length lies within the stated buffer length.
3110  //
3111 
3112  if ((ULONG) tempLength < entrySize ||
3113  quotas->SidLength != sidLength) {
3114  goto error_exit;
3115  }
3116 
3117  if (quotas->NextEntryOffset) {
3118 
3119  //
3120  // There is another entry in the buffer and it must be longword
3121  // aligned. Ensure that the offset indicates that it is. If it
3122  // is not, return error status code.
3123  //
3124 
3125  if (entrySize > quotas->NextEntryOffset ||
3126  quotas->NextEntryOffset & (REQUIRED_QUOTA_ALIGNMENT - 1) ||
3127  (LONG) quotas->NextEntryOffset < 0) {
3128  goto error_exit;
3129 
3130  } else {
3131 
3132  //
3133  // There is another entry in the buffer, so account for the size
3134  // of the current entry in the length and get a pointer to the
3135  // next entry.
3136  //
3137 
3138  tempLength -= quotas->NextEntryOffset;
3139  if (tempLength < 0) {
3140  goto error_exit;
3141  }
3142  quotas = (PFILE_QUOTA_INFORMATION) ((PCHAR) quotas + quotas->NextEntryOffset);
3143  }
3144 
3145  } else {
3146 
3147  //
3148  // There are no more entries in the buffer. Simply account for the
3149  // overall buffer length according to the size of the current
3150  // entry and exit the loop.
3151  //
3152 
3153  tempLength -= entrySize;
3154  break;
3155  }
3156  }
3157 
3158  //
3159  // All of the entries in the buffer have been processed. Check to see
3160  // whether the overall buffer length went negative. If so, return an
3161  // error.
3162  //
3163 
3164  if (tempLength < 0) {
3165  goto error_exit;
3166  }
3167 
3168  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
3169 
3170 error_exit:
3171 
3172  *ErrorOffset = GET_OFFSET_LENGTH( quotas, QuotaBuffer );
3173  return STATUS_QUOTA_LIST_INCONSISTENT;
3174 
3175 }
3176 
3177 NTSTATUS
3178 IoCheckShareAccess(
3179  IN ACCESS_MASK DesiredAccess,
3180  IN ULONG DesiredShareAccess,
3181  IN OUT PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
3182  IN OUT PSHARE_ACCESS ShareAccess,
3183  IN BOOLEAN Update
3184  )
3185 
3186 /*++
3187 
3188 Routine Description:
3189 
3190  This routine is invoked to determine whether or not a new accessor to
3191  a file actually has shared access to it. The check is made according
3192  to:
3193 
3194  1) How the file is currently opened.
3195 
3196  2) What types of shared accesses are currently specified.
3197 
3198  3) The desired and shared accesses that the new open is requesting.
3199 
3200  If the open should succeed, then the access information about how the
3201  file is currently opened is updated, according to the Update parameter.
3202 
3203 Arguments:
3204 
3205  DesiredAccess - Desired access of current open request.
3206 
3207  DesiredShareAccess - Shared access requested by current open request.
3208 
3209  FileObject - Pointer to the file object of the current open request.
3210 
3211  ShareAccess - Pointer to the share access structure that describes how
3212  the file is currently being accessed.
3213 
3214  Update - Specifies whether or not the share access information for the
3215  file is to be updated.
3216 
3217 Return Value:
3218 
3219  The final status of the access check is the function value. If the
3220  accessor has access to the file, STATUS_SUCCESS is returned. Otherwise,
3221  STATUS_SHARING_VIOLATION is returned.
3222 
3223 Note:
3224 
3225  Note that the ShareAccess parameter must be locked against other accesses
3226  from other threads while this routine is executing. Otherwise the counts
3227  will be out-of-synch.
3228 
3229 --*/
3230 
3231 {
3232  ULONG ocount;
3233 
3234  PAGED_CODE();
3235 
3236  //
3237  // Set the access type in the file object for the current accessor.
3238  // Note that reading and writing attributes are not included in the
3239  // access check.
3240  //
3241 
3242  FileObject->ReadAccess = (BOOLEAN) ((DesiredAccess & (FILE_EXECUTE
3243  | FILE_READ_DATA)) != 0);
3244  FileObject->WriteAccess = (BOOLEAN) ((DesiredAccess & (FILE_WRITE_DATA
3245  | FILE_APPEND_DATA)) != 0);
3246  FileObject->DeleteAccess = (BOOLEAN) ((DesiredAccess & DELETE) != 0);
3247 
3248 
3249  //
3250  // There is no more work to do unless the user specified one of the
3251  // sharing modes above.
3252  //
3253 
3254  if (FileObject->ReadAccess ||
3255  FileObject->WriteAccess ||
3256  FileObject->DeleteAccess) {
3257 
3258  FileObject->SharedRead = (BOOLEAN) ((DesiredShareAccess & FILE_SHARE_READ) != 0);
3259  FileObject->SharedWrite = (BOOLEAN) ((DesiredShareAccess & FILE_SHARE_WRITE) != 0);
3260  FileObject->SharedDelete = (BOOLEAN) ((DesiredShareAccess & FILE_SHARE_DELETE) != 0);
3261 
3262  //
3263  // If this is a special filter fileobject ignore share access check if necessary.
3264  //
3265 
3266  if (FileObject->Flags & FO_FILE_OBJECT_HAS_EXTENSION) {
3267  PIOP_FILE_OBJECT_EXTENSION fileObjectExtension =(PIOP_FILE_OBJECT_EXTENSION)(FileObject + 1);
3268 
3269  if (fileObjectExtension->FileObjectExtensionFlags & FO_EXTENSION_IGNORE_SHARE_ACCESS_CHECK) {
3270  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
3271  }
3272  }
3273 
3274  //
3275  // Now check to see whether or not the desired accesses are compatible
3276  // with the way that the file is currently open.
3277  //
3278 
3279  ocount = ShareAccess->OpenCount;
3280 
3281  if ( (FileObject->ReadAccess && (ShareAccess->SharedRead < ocount))
3282  ||
3283  (FileObject->WriteAccess && (ShareAccess->SharedWrite < ocount))
3284  ||
3285  (FileObject->DeleteAccess && (ShareAccess->SharedDelete < ocount))
3286  ||
3287  ((ShareAccess->Readers != 0) && !FileObject->SharedRead)
3288  ||
3289  ((ShareAccess->Writers != 0) && !FileObject->SharedWrite)
3290  ||
3291  ((ShareAccess->Deleters != 0) && !FileObject->SharedDelete)
3292  ) {
3293 
3294  //
3295  // The check failed. Simply return to the caller indicating that the
3296  // current open cannot access the file.
3297  //
3298 
3299  return STATUS_SHARING_VIOLATION;
3300 
3301  //
3302  // The check was successful. Update the counter information in the
3303  // shared access structure for this open request if the caller
3304  // specified that it should be updated.
3305  //
3306 
3307  } else if (Update) {
3308 
3309  ShareAccess->OpenCount++;
3310 
3311  ShareAccess->Readers += FileObject->ReadAccess;
3312  ShareAccess->Writers += FileObject->WriteAccess;
3313  ShareAccess->Deleters += FileObject->DeleteAccess;
3314 
3315  ShareAccess->SharedRead += FileObject->SharedRead;
3316  ShareAccess->SharedWrite += FileObject->SharedWrite;
3317  ShareAccess->SharedDelete += FileObject->SharedDelete;
3318  }
3319  }
3320  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
3321 }
3322 
3323 VOID
3324 FASTCALL
3325 IofCompleteRequest(
3326  IN PIRP Irp,
3327  IN CCHAR PriorityBoost
3328  )
3329 {
3330  //
3331  // This routine will either jump immediately to IopfCompleteRequest, or
3332  // rather IovCompleteRequest.
3333  //
3334  pIofCompleteRequest(Irp, PriorityBoost);
3335 }
3336 
3337 VOID
3338 FASTCALL
3339 IopfCompleteRequest(
3340  IN PIRP Irp,
3341  IN CCHAR PriorityBoost
3342  )
3343 
3344 /*++
3345 
3346 Routine Description:
3347 
3348  This routine is invoked to complete an I/O request. It is invoked by the
3349  driver in its DPC routine to perform the final completion of the IRP. The
3350  functions performed by this routine are as follows.
3351 
3352  1. A check is made to determine whether the packet's stack locations
3353  have been exhausted. If not, then the stack location pointer is set
3354  to the next location and if there is a routine to be invoked, then
3355  it will be invoked. This continues until there are either no more
3356  routines which are interested or the packet runs out of stack.
3357 
3358  If a routine is invoked to complete the packet for a specific driver
3359  which needs to perform work a lot of work or the work needs to be
3360  performed in the context of another process, then the routine will
3361  return an alternate success code of STATUS_MORE_PROCESSING_REQUIRED.
3362  This indicates that this completion routine should simply return to
3363  its caller because the operation will be "completed" by this routine
3364  again sometime in the future.
3365 
3366  2. A check is made to determine whether this IRP is an associated IRP.
3367  If it is, then the count on the master IRP is decremented. If the
3368  count for the master becomes zero, then the master IRP will be
3369  completed according to the steps below taken for a normal IRP being
3370  completed. If the count is still non-zero, then this IRP (the one
3371  being completed) will simply be deallocated.
3372 
3373  3. If this is paging I/O or a close operation, then simply write the
3374  I/O status block and set the event to the signaled state, and
3375  dereference the event. If this is paging I/O, deallocate the IRP
3376  as well.
3377 
3378  4. Unlock the pages, if any, specified by the MDL by calling
3379  MmUnlockPages.
3380 
3381  5. A check is made to determine whether or not completion of the
3382  request can be deferred until later. If it can be, then this
3383  routine simply exits and leaves it up to the originator of the
3384  request to fully complete the IRP. By not initializing and queueing
3385  the special kernel APC to the calling thread (which is the current
3386  thread by definition), a lot of interrupt and queueing processing
3387  can be avoided.
3388 
3389 
3390  6. The final rundown routine is invoked to queue the request packet to
3391  the target (requesting) thread as a special kernel mode APC.
3392 
3393 Arguments:
3394 
3395  Irp - Pointer to the I/O Request Packet to complete.
3396 
3397  PriorityBoost - Supplies the amount of priority boost that is to be given
3398  to the target thread when the special kernel APC is queued.
3399 
3400 Return Value:
3401 
3402  None.
3403 
3404 --*/
3405 
3406 #define ZeroIrpStackLocation( IrpSp ) { \
3407  (IrpSp)->MinorFunction = 0; \
3408  (IrpSp)->Flags = 0; \
3409  (IrpSp)->Control &= SL_ERROR_RETURNED ; \
3410  (IrpSp)->Parameters.Others.Argument1 = 0; \
3411  (IrpSp)->Parameters.Others.Argument2 = 0; \
3412  (IrpSp)->Parameters.Others.Argument3 = 0; \
3413  (IrpSp)->FileObject = (PFILE_OBJECT) NULL; }
3414 
3415 {
3416  PIRP masterIrp;
3417  NTSTATUS status;
3418  PIO_STACK_LOCATION stackPointer;
3419  PIO_STACK_LOCATION bottomSp;
3420  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
3421  PMDL mdl;
3422  PETHREAD thread;
3423  PFILE_OBJECT fileObject;
3424  KIRQL irql;
3425  PVOID saveAuxiliaryPointer = NULL;
3426  NTSTATUS errorStatus;
3427 
3428  //
3429  // Begin by ensuring that this packet has not already been completed
3430  // by someone.
3431  //
3432 
3433  if (Irp->CurrentLocation > (CCHAR) (Irp->StackCount + 1) ||
3434  Irp->Type != IO_TYPE_IRP) {
3435  KeBugCheckEx( MULTIPLE_IRP_COMPLETE_REQUESTS, (ULONG_PTR) Irp, __LINE__, 0, 0 );
3436  }
3437 
3438  //
3439  // Ensure that the packet being completed really is still an IRP.
3440  //
3441 
3442  ASSERT( Irp->Type == IO_TYPE_IRP );
3443 
3444  //
3445  // Ensure that no one believes that this request is still in a cancelable
3446  // state.
3447  //
3448 
3449  ASSERT( !Irp->CancelRoutine );
3450 
3451  //
3452  // Ensure that the packet is not being completed with a thoroughly
3453  // confusing status code. Actually completing a packet with a pending
3454  // status probably means that someone forgot to set the real status in
3455  // the packet.
3456  //
3457 
3458  ASSERT( Irp->IoStatus.Status != STATUS_PENDING );
3459 
3460  //
3461  // Ensure that the packet is not being completed with a minus one. This
3462  // is apparently a common problem in some drivers, and has no meaning
3463  // as a status code.
3464  //
3465 
3466  ASSERT( Irp->IoStatus.Status != 0xffffffff );
3467 
3468  //
3469  // Diagnosability support.
3470  //
3471 
3472  bottomSp = ((PIO_STACK_LOCATION) ((UCHAR *) (Irp) + sizeof( IRP )));
3473 
3474  if (bottomSp->Control & SL_ERROR_RETURNED) {
3475  errorStatus = (NTSTATUS)(ULONG_PTR)(bottomSp->Parameters.Others.Argument4);
3476  } else {
3477  errorStatus = STATUS_SUCCESS;
3478  }
3479 
3480  //
3481  // Now check to see whether this is the last driver that needs to be
3482  // invoked for this packet. If not, then bump the stack and check to
3483  // see whether the driver wishes to see the completion. As each stack
3484  // location is examined, invoke any routine which needs to be invoked.
3485  // If the routine returns STATUS_MORE_PROCESSING_REQUIRED, then stop the
3486  // processing of this packet.
3487  //
3488 
3489  for (stackPointer = IoGetCurrentIrpStackLocation( Irp ),
3490  Irp->CurrentLocation++,
3491  Irp->Tail.Overlay.CurrentStackLocation++;
3492  Irp->CurrentLocation <= (CCHAR) (Irp->StackCount + 1);
3493  stackPointer++,
3494  Irp->CurrentLocation++,
3495  Irp->Tail.Overlay.CurrentStackLocation++) {
3496 
3497  //
3498  // A stack location was located. Check to see whether or not it
3499  // has a completion routine and if so, whether or not it should be
3500  // invoked.
3501  //
3502  // Begin by saving the pending returned flag in the current stack
3503  // location in the fixed part of the IRP.
3504  //
3505 
3506  Irp->PendingReturned = stackPointer->Control & SL_PENDING_RETURNED;
3507 
3508  //
3509  // If a completion routine changed the status then
3510  // mark the upper level stack pointer as the one
3511  // that flagged the error.
3512  //
3513 
3514  if (!NT_SUCCESS(Irp->IoStatus.Status)) {
3515 
3516  if (Irp->IoStatus.Status != errorStatus) {
3517  errorStatus = Irp->IoStatus.Status;
3518  stackPointer->Control |= SL_ERROR_RETURNED;
3519  bottomSp->Parameters.Others.Argument4 = (PVOID)(ULONG_PTR)errorStatus;
3520  bottomSp->Control |= SL_ERROR_RETURNED; // Mark that there is status in this location
3521  }
3522  }
3523 
3524  if ( (NT_SUCCESS( Irp->IoStatus.Status ) &&
3525  stackPointer->Control & SL_INVOKE_ON_SUCCESS) ||
3526  (!NT_SUCCESS( Irp->IoStatus.Status ) &&
3527  stackPointer->Control & SL_INVOKE_ON_ERROR) ||
3528  (Irp->Cancel &&
3529  stackPointer->Control & SL_INVOKE_ON_CANCEL)
3530  ) {
3531 
3532  //
3533  // This driver has specified a completion routine. Invoke the
3534  // routine passing it a pointer to its device object and the
3535  // IRP that is being completed.
3536  //
3537 
3538  ZeroIrpStackLocation( stackPointer );
3539 
3540  if (Irp->CurrentLocation == (CCHAR) (Irp->StackCount + 1)) {
3541  deviceObject = NULL;
3542  }
3543  else {
3544  deviceObject = IoGetCurrentIrpStackLocation( Irp )->DeviceObject;
3545  }
3546 
3547  status = stackPointer->CompletionRoutine( deviceObject,
3548  Irp,
3549  stackPointer->Context );
3550 
3551  if (status == STATUS_MORE_PROCESSING_REQUIRED) {
3552 
3553  //
3554  // Note: Notice that if the driver has returned the above
3555  // status value, it may have already DEALLOCATED the
3556  // packet! Therefore, do NOT touch any part of the
3557  // IRP in the following code.
3558  //
3559 
3560  return;
3561  }
3562 
3563  } else {
3564  if (Irp->PendingReturned && Irp->CurrentLocation <= Irp->StackCount) {
3565  IoMarkIrpPending( Irp );
3566  }
3567  ZeroIrpStackLocation( stackPointer );
3568  }
3569  }
3570 
3571  //
3572  // Check to see whether this is an associated IRP. If so, then decrement
3573  // the count in the master IRP. If the count is decremented to zero,
3574  // then complete the master packet as well.
3575  //
3576 
3577  if (Irp->Flags & IRP_ASSOCIATED_IRP) {
3578  ULONG count;
3579 
3580  masterIrp = Irp->AssociatedIrp.MasterIrp;
3581 
3582  //
3583  // After this decrement master IRP cannot be touched except if count == 1.
3584  //
3585 
3586  count = IopInterlockedDecrementUlong( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock,
3587  &masterIrp->AssociatedIrp.IrpCount );
3588 
3589  //
3590  // Deallocate this packet and any MDLs that are associated with it
3591  // by either doing direct deallocations if they were allocated from
3592  // a zone or by queueing the packet to a thread to perform the
3593  // deallocation.
3594  //
3595  // Also, check the count of the master IRP to determine whether or not
3596  // the count has gone to zero. If not, then simply get out of here.
3597  // Otherwise, complete the master packet.
3598  //
3599 
3600  IopFreeIrpAndMdls( Irp );
3601  if (count == 1) {
3602  IoCompleteRequest( masterIrp, PriorityBoost );
3603  }
3604  return;
3605  }
3606 
3607  //
3608  // Check to see if we have a name junction. If so set the stage to
3609  // transmogrify the reparse point data in IopCompleteRequest.
3610  //
3611 
3612  if ((Irp->IoStatus.Status == STATUS_REPARSE ) &&
3613  (Irp->IoStatus.Information > IO_REPARSE_TAG_RESERVED_RANGE)) {
3614 
3615  if (Irp->IoStatus.Information == IO_REPARSE_TAG_MOUNT_POINT) {
3616 
3617  //
3618  // For name junctions, we save the pointer to the auxiliary
3619  // buffer and use it below.
3620  //
3621 
3622  ASSERT( Irp->Tail.Overlay.AuxiliaryBuffer != NULL );
3623 
3624  saveAuxiliaryPointer = (PVOID) Irp->Tail.Overlay.AuxiliaryBuffer;
3625 
3626  //
3627  // We NULL the entry to avoid its de-allocation at this time.
3628  // This buffer get deallocated in IopDoNameTransmogrify
3629  //
3630 
3631  Irp->Tail.Overlay.AuxiliaryBuffer = NULL;
3632  } else {
3633 
3634  //
3635  // Fail the request. A driver needed to act on this IRP prior
3636  // to getting to this point.
3637  //
3638 
3639  Irp->IoStatus.Status = STATUS_IO_REPARSE_TAG_NOT_HANDLED;
3640  }
3641  }
3642 
3643  //
3644  // Check the auxiliary buffer pointer in the packet and if a buffer was
3645  // allocated, deallocate it now. Note that this buffer must be freed
3646  // here since the pointer is overlayed with the APC that will be used
3647  // to get to the requesting thread's context.
3648  //
3649 
3650  if (Irp->Tail.Overlay.AuxiliaryBuffer) {
3651  ExFreePool( Irp->Tail.Overlay.AuxiliaryBuffer );
3652  Irp->Tail.Overlay.AuxiliaryBuffer = NULL;
3653  }
3654 
3655  //
3656  // Check to see if this is paging I/O or a close operation. If either,
3657  // then special processing must be performed. The reasons that special
3658  // processing must be performed is different based on the type of
3659  // operation being performed. The biggest reasons for special processing
3660  // on paging operations are that using a special kernel APC for an in-
3661  // page operation cannot work since the special kernel APC can incur
3662  // another pagefault. Likewise, all paging I/O uses MDLs that belong
3663  // to the memory manager, not the I/O system.
3664  //
3665  // Close operations are special because the close may have been invoked
3666  // because of a special kernel APC (some IRP was completed which caused
3667  // the reference count on the object to become zero while in the I/O
3668  // system's special kernel APC routine). Therefore, a special kernel APC
3669  // cannot be used since it cannot execute until the close APC finishes.
3670  //
3671  // The special steps are as follows for a synchronous paging operation
3672  // and close are:
3673  //
3674  // 1. Copy the I/O status block (it is in SVAS, nonpaged).
3675  // 2. Signal the event
3676  // 3. If paging I/O, deallocate the IRP
3677  //
3678  // The special steps taken for asynchronous paging operations (out-pages)
3679  // are as follows:
3680  //
3681  // 1. Initialize a special kernel APC just for page writes.
3682  // 1. Queue the special kernel APC.
3683  //
3684  // It should also be noted that the logic for completing a Mount request
3685  // operation is exactly the same as a Page Read. No assumptions should be
3686  // made here about this being a Page Read operation w/o carefully checking
3687  // to ensure that they are also true for a Mount. That is:
3688  //
3689  // IRP_PAGING_IO and IRP_MOUNT_COMPLETION
3690  //
3691  // are the same flag in the IRP.
3692  //
3693  // Also note that the last time the IRP is touched for a close operation
3694  // must be just before the event is set to the signaled state. Once this
3695  // occurs, the IRP can be deallocated by the thread waiting for the event.
3696  //
3697  //
3698  // IRP_CLOSE_OPERATION and IRP_SET_USER_EVENT are the same flags. They both indicate
3699  // that only the user event field should be set and no APC should be queued. Unfortunately
3700  // IRP_CLOSE_OPERATION is used by some drivers to do exactly this so it cannot be renamed.
3701  //
3702  //
3703 
3704  if (Irp->Flags & (IRP_PAGING_IO | IRP_CLOSE_OPERATION |IRP_SET_USER_EVENT)) {
3705  if (Irp->Flags & (IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_PAGING_IO | IRP_CLOSE_OPERATION |IRP_SET_USER_EVENT)) {
3706  ULONG flags;
3707 
3708  flags = Irp->Flags & (IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_PAGING_IO|IRP_PAGING_IO);
3709  *Irp->UserIosb = Irp->IoStatus;
3710  (VOID) KeSetEvent( Irp->UserEvent, PriorityBoost, FALSE );
3711  if (flags) {
3712  if (IopIsReserveIrp(Irp)) {
3713  IopFreeReserveIrp(PriorityBoost);
3714  } else {
3715  IoFreeIrp( Irp );
3716  }
3717  }
3718  } else {
3719  thread = Irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread;
3720  KeInitializeApc( &Irp->Tail.Apc,
3721  &thread->Tcb,
3722  Irp->ApcEnvironment,
3723  IopCompletePageWrite,
3724  (PKRUNDOWN_ROUTINE) NULL,
3725  (PKNORMAL_ROUTINE) NULL,
3726  KernelMode,
3727  (PVOID) NULL );
3728  (VOID) KeInsertQueueApc( &Irp->Tail.Apc,
3729  (PVOID) NULL,
3730  (PVOID) NULL,
3731  PriorityBoost );
3732  }
3733  return;
3734  }
3735 
3736  //
3737  // Check to see whether any pages need to be unlocked.
3738  //
3739 
3740  if (Irp->MdlAddress != NULL) {
3741 
3742  //
3743  // Unlock any pages that may be described by MDLs.
3744  //
3745 
3746  mdl = Irp->MdlAddress;
3747  while (mdl != NULL) {
3748  MmUnlockPages( mdl );
3749  mdl = mdl->Next;
3750  }
3751  }
3752 
3753  //
3754  // Make a final check here to determine whether or not this is a
3755  // synchronous I/O operation that is being completed in the context
3756  // of the original requestor. If so, then an optimal path through
3757  // I/O completion can be taken.
3758  //
3759 
3760  if (Irp->Flags & IRP_DEFER_IO_COMPLETION && !Irp->PendingReturned) {
3761 
3762  if ((Irp->IoStatus.Status == STATUS_REPARSE ) &&
3763  (Irp->IoStatus.Information == IO_REPARSE_TAG_MOUNT_POINT)) {
3764 
3765  //
3766  // For name junctions we reinstate the address of the appropriate
3767  // buffer. It is freed in parse.c
3768  //
3769 
3770  Irp->Tail.Overlay.AuxiliaryBuffer = saveAuxiliaryPointer;
3771  }
3772 
3773  return;
3774  }
3775 
3776  //
3777  // Finally, initialize the IRP as an APC structure and queue the special
3778  // kernel APC to the target thread.
3779  //
3780 
3781  thread = Irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread;
3782  fileObject = Irp->Tail.Overlay.OriginalFileObject;
3783 
3784  if (!Irp->Cancel) {
3785 
3786  KeInitializeApc( &Irp->Tail.Apc,
3787  &thread->Tcb,
3788  Irp->ApcEnvironment,
3789  IopCompleteRequest,
3790  IopAbortRequest,
3791  (PKNORMAL_ROUTINE) NULL,
3792  KernelMode,
3793  (PVOID) NULL );
3794 
3795  (VOID) KeInsertQueueApc( &Irp->Tail.Apc,
3796  fileObject,
3797  (PVOID) saveAuxiliaryPointer,
3798  PriorityBoost );
3799  } else {
3800 
3801  //
3802  // This request has been cancelled. Ensure that access to the thread
3803  // is synchronized, otherwise it may go away while attempting to get
3804  // through the remainder of completion for this request. This happens
3805  // when the thread times out waiting for the request to be completed
3806  // once it has been cancelled.
3807  //
3808  // Note that it is safe to capture the thread pointer above, w/o having
3809  // the lock because the cancel flag was not set at that point, and
3810  // the code that disassociates IRPs must set the flag before looking to
3811  // see whether or not the packet has been completed, and this packet
3812  // will appear to be completed because it no longer belongs to a driver.
3813  //
3814 
3815  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoCompletionLock );
3816 
3817  thread = Irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread;
3818 
3819  if (thread) {
3820 
3821  KeInitializeApc( &Irp->Tail.Apc,
3822  &thread->Tcb,
3823  Irp->ApcEnvironment,
3824  IopCompleteRequest,
3825  IopAbortRequest,
3826  (PKNORMAL_ROUTINE) NULL,
3827  KernelMode,
3828  (PVOID) NULL );
3829 
3830  (VOID) KeInsertQueueApc( &Irp->Tail.Apc,
3831  fileObject,
3832  (PVOID) saveAuxiliaryPointer,
3833  PriorityBoost );
3834 
3835  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoCompletionLock, irql );
3836 
3837  } else {
3838 
3839  //
3840  // This request has been aborted from completing in the caller's
3841  // thread. This can only occur if the packet was cancelled, and
3842  // the driver did not complete the request, so it was timed out.
3843  // Attempt to drop things on the floor, since the originating thread
3844  // has probably exited at this point.
3845  //
3846 
3847  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoCompletionLock, irql );
3848 
3849  ASSERT( Irp->Cancel );
3850 
3851  //
3852  // Drop the IRP on the floor.
3853  //
3854 
3855  IopDropIrp( Irp, fileObject );
3856 
3857  }
3858  }
3859 }
3860 
3861 NTSTATUS
3862 IoConnectInterrupt(
3863  OUT PKINTERRUPT *InterruptObject,
3864  IN PKSERVICE_ROUTINE ServiceRoutine,
3865  IN PVOID ServiceContext,
3866  IN PKSPIN_LOCK SpinLock OPTIONAL,
3867  IN ULONG Vector,
3868  IN KIRQL Irql,
3869  IN KIRQL SynchronizeIrql,
3870  IN KINTERRUPT_MODE InterruptMode,
3871  IN BOOLEAN ShareVector,
3872  IN KAFFINITY ProcessorEnableMask,
3873  IN BOOLEAN FloatingSave
3874  )
3875 
3876 /*++
3877 
3878 Routine Description:
3879 
3880  This routine allocates, initializes, and connects interrupt objects for
3881  all of the processors specified in the processor enable mask.
3882 
3883 Arguments:
3884 
3885  InterruptObject - Address of a variable to receive a pointer to the first
3886  interrupt object allocated and initialized.
3887 
3888  ServiceRoutine - Address of the interrupt service routine (ISR) that should
3889  be executed when the interrupt occurs.
3890 
3891  ServiceContext - Supplies a pointer to the context information required
3892  by the ISR.
3893 
3894  SpinLock - Supplies a pointer to a spin lock to be used when synchronizing
3895  with the ISR.
3896 
3897  Vector - Supplies the vector upon which the interrupt occurs.
3898 
3899  Irql - Supplies the IRQL upon which the interrupt occurs.
3900 
3901  SynchronizeIrql - The request priority that the interrupt should be
3902  synchronized with.
3903 
3904  InterruptMode - Specifies the interrupt mode of the device.
3905 
3906  ShareVector - Supplies a boolean value that specifies whether the
3907  vector can be shared with other interrupt objects or not. If FALSE
3908  then the vector may not be shared, if TRUE it may be.
3909  Latched.
3910 
3911  ProcessorEnableMask - Specifies a bit-vector for each processor on which
3912  the interrupt is to be connected. A value of one in the bit position
3913  corresponding to the processor number indicates that the interrupt
3914  should be allowed on that processor. At least one bit must be set.
3915 
3916  FloatingSave - A BOOLEAN that specifies whether or not the machine's
3917  floating point state should be saved before invoking the ISR.
3918 
3919 Return Value:
3920 
3921  The function value is the final function status. The three status values
3922  that this routine can itself return are:
3923 
3924  STATUS_SUCCESS - Everything worked successfully.
3925  STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER - No processors were specified.
3926  STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES - There was not enough nonpaged pool.
3927 
3928 --*/
3929 
3930 {
3931  CCHAR count;
3932  BOOLEAN builtinUsed;
3933  PKINTERRUPT interruptObject;
3934  KAFFINITY processorMask;
3935  NTSTATUS status;
3936  PIO_INTERRUPT_STRUCTURE interruptStructure;
3937  PKSPIN_LOCK spinLock;
3938 #ifdef INTR_BINDING
3939  ULONG AssignedProcessor;
3940 #endif // INTR_BINDING
3941 
3942  PAGED_CODE();
3943 
3944  //
3945  // Initialize the return pointer and assume success.
3946  //
3947 
3948  *InterruptObject = (PKINTERRUPT) NULL;
3949  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
3950 
3951  //
3952  // Determine how much memory is to be allocated based on how many
3953  // processors this system may have and how many bits are set in the
3954  // processor enable mask.
3955  //
3956 
3957  processorMask = ProcessorEnableMask & KeActiveProcessors;
3958  count = 0;
3959 
3960  while (processorMask) {
3961  if (processorMask & 1) {
3962  count++;
3963  }
3964  processorMask >>= 1;
3965  }
3966 
3967  //
3968  // If any interrupt objects are to be allocated and initialized, allocate
3969  // the memory now.
3970  //
3971 
3972  if (count) {
3973 
3974  interruptStructure = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( NonPagedPool,
3975  ((count - 1) * sizeof( KINTERRUPT )) +
3976  sizeof( IO_INTERRUPT_STRUCTURE ),
3977  'nioI' );
3978  if (interruptStructure == NULL) {
3979  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
3980  }
3981  } else {
3982  return STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER;
3983  }
3984 
3985  //
3986  // If the caller specified a spin lock to be used for the interrupt object,
3987  // use it. Otherwise, provide one by using the one in the structure that
3988  // was just allocated.
3989  //
3990 
3991  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( SpinLock )) {
3992  spinLock = SpinLock;
3993  } else {
3994  spinLock = &interruptStructure->SpinLock;
3995  }
3996 
3997  //
3998  // Initialize and connect the
3999  // interrupt objects to the appropriate processors.
4000  //
4001 
4002  //
4003  // Return the address of the first interrupt object in case an
4004  // interrupt is pending for the device when it is initially connected
4005  // and the driver must synchronize its execution with the ISR.
4006  //
4007 
4008  *InterruptObject = &interruptStructure->InterruptObject;
4009 
4010  //
4011  // Begin by getting a pointer to the start of the memory to be used
4012  // for interrupt objects other than the builtin object.
4013  //
4014 
4015  interruptObject = (PKINTERRUPT) (interruptStructure + 1);
4016  builtinUsed = FALSE;
4017  processorMask = ProcessorEnableMask & KeActiveProcessors;
4018 
4019  //
4020  // Now zero the interrupt structure itself so that if something goes
4021  // wrong it can be backed out.
4022  //
4023 
4024  RtlZeroMemory( interruptStructure, sizeof( IO_INTERRUPT_STRUCTURE ) );
4025 
4026  //
4027  // For each entry in the processor enable mask that is set, connect
4028  // and initialize an interrupt object. The first bit that is set
4029  // uses the builtin interrupt object, and all others use the pointers
4030  // that follow it.
4031  //
4032 
4033  for (count = 0; processorMask; count++, processorMask >>= 1) {
4034 
4035  if (processorMask & 1) {
4036  KeInitializeInterrupt( builtinUsed ?
4037  interruptObject :
4038  &interruptStructure->InterruptObject,
4039  ServiceRoutine,
4040  ServiceContext,
4041  spinLock,
4042  Vector,
4043  Irql,
4044  SynchronizeIrql,
4045  InterruptMode,
4046  ShareVector,
4047  count,
4048  FloatingSave );
4049 
4050  if (!KeConnectInterrupt( builtinUsed ?
4051  interruptObject :
4052  &interruptStructure->InterruptObject )) {
4053 
4054  //
4055  // An error occurred while attempting to connect the
4056  // interrupt. This means that the driver either specified
4057  // the wrong type of interrupt mode, or attempted to connect
4058  // to some processor that didn't exist, or whatever. In
4059  // any case, the problem turns out to be an invalid
4060  // parameter was specified. Simply back everything out
4061  // and return an error status.
4062  //
4063  // Note that if the builtin entry was used, then the entire
4064  // structure needs to be walked as there are entries that
4065  // were successfully connected. Otherwise, the first
4066  // attempt to connect failed, so simply free everything
4067  // in-line.
4068  //
4069 
4070  if (builtinUsed) {
4071  IoDisconnectInterrupt( &interruptStructure->InterruptObject );
4072  } else {
4073  ExFreePool( interruptStructure );
4074  }
4075  status = STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER;
4076  break;
4077  }
4078 
4079 
4080  //
4081  // If the builtin entry has been used, then the interrupt
4082  // object just connected was one of the pointers, so fill
4083  // it in with the address of the memory actually used.
4084  //
4085 
4086  if (builtinUsed) {
4087  interruptStructure->InterruptArray[count] = interruptObject++;
4088 
4089  } else {
4090 
4091  //
4092  // Otherwise, the builtin entry was used, so indicate
4093  // that it is no longer valid to use and start using
4094  // the pointers instead.
4095  //
4096 
4097  builtinUsed = TRUE;
4098  }
4099  }
4100  }
4101 
4102  //
4103  // Finally, reset the address of the interrupt object if the function
4104  // failed and return the final status of the operation.
4105  //
4106 
4107  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
4108  *InterruptObject = (PKINTERRUPT) NULL;
4109  }
4110 
4111  return status;
4112 }
4113 
4114 PCONTROLLER_OBJECT
4115 IoCreateController(
4116  IN ULONG Size
4117  )
4118 
4119 /*++
4120 
4121 Routine Description:
4122 
4123  This routine creates a controller object that can be used to synchronize
4124  access to a physical device controller from two or more devices.
4125 
4126 Arguments:
4127 
4128  Size - Size of the adapter extension in bytes.
4129 
4130 Return Value:
4131 
4132  A pointer to the controller object that was created or a NULL pointer.
4133 
4134 --*/
4135 
4136 {
4137  OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES objectAttributes;
4138  PCONTROLLER_OBJECT controllerObject;
4139  HANDLE handle;
4140  NTSTATUS status;
4141 
4142  PAGED_CODE();
4143 
4144  //
4145  // Initialize the object attributes structure in preparation for creating
4146  // the controller object.
4147  //
4148 
4149  InitializeObjectAttributes( &objectAttributes,
4150  (PUNICODE_STRING) NULL,
4151  OBJ_KERNEL_HANDLE,
4152  (HANDLE) NULL,
4153  (PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR) NULL );
4154 
4155  //
4156  // Create the controller object itself.
4157  //
4158 
4159  status = ObCreateObject( KernelMode,
4160  IoControllerObjectType,
4161  &objectAttributes,
4162  KernelMode,
4163  (PVOID) NULL,
4164  (ULONG) sizeof( CONTROLLER_OBJECT ) + Size,
4165  0,
4166  0,
4167  (PVOID *) &controllerObject );
4168  if (NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
4169 
4170  //
4171  // Insert the controller object into the table.
4172  //
4173 
4174  status = ObInsertObject( controllerObject,
4175  NULL,
4176  FILE_READ_DATA | FILE_WRITE_DATA,
4177  1,
4178  (PVOID *) &controllerObject,
4179  &handle );
4180 
4181  //
4182  // If the insert operation fails, set return value to NULL.
4183  //
4184 
4185  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
4186  controllerObject = (PCONTROLLER_OBJECT) NULL;
4187  } else {
4188 
4189  //
4190  // The insert completed successfully. Close the handle so that if
4191  // the driver is unloaded, the controller object can go away.
4192  //
4193 
4194  (VOID) ObCloseHandle( handle, KernelMode );
4195 
4196  //
4197  // Zero the memory for the controller object.
4198  //
4199 
4200  RtlZeroMemory( controllerObject, sizeof( CONTROLLER_OBJECT ) + Size );
4201 
4202  //
4203  // Set the type and size of this controller object.
4204  //
4205 
4206  controllerObject->Type = IO_TYPE_CONTROLLER;
4207  controllerObject->Size = (USHORT) (sizeof( CONTROLLER_OBJECT ) + Size);
4208  controllerObject->ControllerExtension = (PVOID) (controllerObject + 1);
4209 
4210  //
4211  // Finally, initialize the controller's device queue.
4212  //
4213 
4214  KeInitializeDeviceQueue( &controllerObject->DeviceWaitQueue );
4215  }
4216  } else {
4217  controllerObject = (PCONTROLLER_OBJECT) NULL;
4218  }
4219 
4220  return controllerObject;
4221 }
4222 
4223 VOID
4224 IopInsertRemoveDevice(
4225  IN PDRIVER_OBJECT DriverObject,
4226  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
4227  IN BOOLEAN Insert
4228  )
4229 
4230 {
4231  KIRQL irql;
4232 
4233  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock );
4234  if (Insert) {
4235  DeviceObject->NextDevice = DriverObject->DeviceObject;
4236  DriverObject->DeviceObject = DeviceObject;
4237  }
4238  else {
4239  PDEVICE_OBJECT *prevPoint;
4240 
4241  prevPoint = &DeviceObject->DriverObject->DeviceObject;
4242  while (*prevPoint != DeviceObject) {
4243  prevPoint = &(*prevPoint)->NextDevice;
4244  }
4245  *prevPoint = DeviceObject->NextDevice;
4246  }
4247  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
4248 }
4249 
4250 NTSTATUS
4251 IopCreateVpb (
4252  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject
4253  )
4254 {
4255  PVPB Vpb;
4256 
4257  Vpb = ExAllocatePoolWithTag(
4258  NonPagedPool,
4259  sizeof( VPB ),
4260  ' bpV'
4261  );
4262 
4263  if (!Vpb) {
4264  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
4265  }
4266  RtlZeroMemory (Vpb, sizeof(VPB));
4267  Vpb->Type = IO_TYPE_VPB;
4268  Vpb->Size = sizeof( VPB );
4269  Vpb->RealDevice = DeviceObject;
4270  DeviceObject->Vpb = Vpb;
4271 
4272  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
4273 }
4274 
4275 NTSTATUS
4276 IoCreateDevice(
4277  IN PDRIVER_OBJECT DriverObject,
4278  IN ULONG DeviceExtensionSize,
4279  IN PUNICODE_STRING DeviceName OPTIONAL,
4280  IN DEVICE_TYPE DeviceType,
4281  IN ULONG DeviceCharacteristics,
4282  IN BOOLEAN Exclusive,
4283  OUT PDEVICE_OBJECT *DeviceObject
4284  )
4285 /*++
4286 
4287 Routine Description:
4288 
4289  This routine creates a device object and links it into the I/O database.
4290 
4291 Arguments:
4292 
4293  DriverObject - A pointer to the driver object for this device.
4294 
4295  DeviceExtensionSize - Size, in bytes, of extension to device object;
4296  i.e., the size of the driver-specific data for this device object.
4297 
4298  DeviceName - Optional name that should be associated with this device.
4299  If the DeviceCharacteristics has the FILE_AUTOGENERATED_DEVICE_NAME
4300  flag set, this parameter is ignored.
4301 
4302  DeviceType - The type of device that the device object should represent.
4303 
4304  DeviceCharacteristics - The characteristics for the device.
4305 
4306  Exclusive - Indicates that the device object should be created with using
4307  the exclusive object attribute.
4308 
4309  NOTE: This flag should not be used for WDM drivers. Since only the
4310  PDO is named, it is the only device object in a devnode attachment
4311  stack that is openable. However, since this device object is created
4312  by the underlying bus driver (which has no knowledge about what type
4313  of device this is), there is no way to know whether this flag should
4314  be set. Therefore, this parameter should always be FALSE for WDM
4315  drivers. Drivers attached to the PDO (e.g., the function driver) must
4316  enforce any exclusivity rules.
4317 
4318  DeviceObject - Pointer to the device object pointer we will return.
4319 
4320 Return Value:
4321 
4322  The function value is the final status of the operation.
4323 
4324 
4325 --*/
4326 
4327 {
4328  OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES objectAttributes;
4329  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
4330  PDEVOBJ_EXTENSION deviceObjectExt;
4331  HANDLE handle;
4332  BOOLEAN deviceHasName = FALSE;
4333  UCHAR localSecurityDescriptor[SECURITY_DESCRIPTOR_MIN_LENGTH];
4334  PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR securityDescriptor = NULL;
4335  PACL acl;
4336  ULONG RoundedSize;
4337  NTSTATUS status;
4338  USHORT sectorSize = 0;
4339  LONG nextUniqueDeviceObjectNumber;
4340  UNICODE_STRING autoGeneratedDeviceName;
4341  BOOLEAN retryWithNewName = FALSE;
4342  WCHAR deviceNameBuffer[17]; // "\Device\xxxxxxxx"
4343 
4344  PAGED_CODE();
4345 
4346  acl = NULL;
4347 
4348  //
4349  // Enclose the creation of the device object in a do/while, in the rare
4350  // event where we have to retry because some other driver is using our
4351  // naming scheme for auto-generated device object names.
4352  //
4353 
4354  do {
4355 
4356  if (DeviceCharacteristics & FILE_AUTOGENERATED_DEVICE_NAME) {
4357 
4358  //
4359  // The caller has requested that we automatically generate a device
4360  // object name. Retrieve the next available number to use for this
4361  // purpose, and create a name of the form "\Device<n>", where <n>
4362  // is the (8 hexadecimal digit) character representation of the unique
4363  // number we retrieve.
4364  //
4365 
4366  nextUniqueDeviceObjectNumber = InterlockedIncrement( &IopUniqueDeviceObjectNumber );
4367  swprintf( deviceNameBuffer, L"\\Device\\%08lx", nextUniqueDeviceObjectNumber );
4368 
4369  if (retryWithNewName) {
4370 
4371  //
4372  // We've already done this once (hence, the unicode device name string
4373  // is all set up, as is all the security information). Thus, we can
4374  // skip down to where we re-attempt the creation of the device object
4375  // using our new name.
4376  //
4377 
4378  retryWithNewName = FALSE;
4379  goto attemptDeviceObjectCreation;
4380 
4381  } else {
4382 
4383  //
4384  // Set the DeviceName parameter to point to our unicode string, just as
4385  // if the caller had specified it (note, we explicitly ignore anything
4386  // the caller passes us for device name if the FILE_AUTOGENERATED_DEVICE_NAME
4387  // characteristic is specified.
4388  //
4389 
4390  RtlInitUnicodeString( &autoGeneratedDeviceName, deviceNameBuffer );
4391  DeviceName = &autoGeneratedDeviceName;
4392  }
4393  }
4394 
4395  //
4396  // Remember whether or not this device was created with a name so that
4397  // it can be deallocated later.
4398  //
4399 
4400  deviceHasName = (BOOLEAN) (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( DeviceName ) ? TRUE : FALSE);
4401 
4402 
4403  //
4404  // Determine whether or not this device needs to have a security descriptor
4405  // placed on it that allows read/write access, or whether the system default
4406  // should be used. Disks, virtual disks, and file systems simply use the
4407  // system default descriptor. All others allow read/write access.
4408  //
4409  // NOTE: This routine assumes that it is in the system's security context.
4410  // In particular, it assumes that the Default DACL is the system's
4411  // Default DACL. If this assumption changes in future releases,
4412  // then use of the Default DACL below should be reviewed for
4413  // appropriateness.
4414  //
4415 
4416  //
4417  // If the device is a pnp device then wait until it registers a device
4418  // class before doing the default setup.
4419  //
4420 
4421  securityDescriptor = IopCreateDefaultDeviceSecurityDescriptor(
4422  DeviceType,
4423  DeviceCharacteristics,
4424  deviceHasName,
4425  localSecurityDescriptor,
4426  &acl,
4427  NULL
4428  );
4429 
4430  switch ( DeviceType ) {
4431 
4432  case FILE_DEVICE_DISK_FILE_SYSTEM:
4433 
4434  sectorSize = 512;
4435  break;
4436 
4437  case FILE_DEVICE_CD_ROM_FILE_SYSTEM:
4438 
4439  sectorSize = 2048;
4440  break;
4441 
4442  case FILE_DEVICE_DISK:
4443  case FILE_DEVICE_VIRTUAL_DISK:
4444 
4445  sectorSize = 512;
4446  break;
4447  }
4448 
4449 attemptDeviceObjectCreation:
4450  //
4451  // Initialize the object attributes structure in preparation for creating
4452  // device object. Note that the device may be created as an exclusive
4453  // device so that only one open can be done to it at a time. This saves
4454  // single user devices from having drivers that implement special code to
4455  // make sure that only one connection is ever valid at any given time.
4456  //
4457 
4458  InitializeObjectAttributes( &objectAttributes,
4459  DeviceName,
4460  OBJ_KERNEL_HANDLE,
4461  (HANDLE) NULL,
4462  securityDescriptor );
4463 
4464 
4465 
4466  if (Exclusive) {
4467  objectAttributes.Attributes |= OBJ_EXCLUSIVE;
4468  } else {
4469  objectAttributes.Attributes |= 0;
4470  }
4471 
4472  if (deviceHasName) {
4473  objectAttributes.Attributes |= OBJ_PERMANENT;
4474  }
4475 
4476  //
4477  // Create the device object itself.
4478  //
4479 
4480  RoundedSize = (sizeof( DEVICE_OBJECT ) + DeviceExtensionSize)
4481  % sizeof (LONGLONG);
4482  if (RoundedSize) {
4483  RoundedSize = sizeof (LONGLONG) - RoundedSize;
4484  }
4485 
4486  RoundedSize += DeviceExtensionSize;
4487 
4488  status = ObCreateObject( KernelMode,
4489  IoDeviceObjectType,
4490  &objectAttributes,
4491  KernelMode,
4492  (PVOID) NULL,
4493  (ULONG) sizeof( DEVICE_OBJECT ) + sizeof ( DEVOBJ_EXTENSION ) +
4494  RoundedSize,
4495  0,
4496  0,
4497  (PVOID *) &deviceObject );
4498 
4499  if ((status == STATUS_OBJECT_NAME_COLLISION) &&
4500  (DeviceCharacteristics & FILE_AUTOGENERATED_DEVICE_NAME)) {
4501 
4502  //
4503  // Some other driver is using our naming scheme, and we've picked a
4504  // device name already in use. Try again, with a new number.
4505  //
4506 
4507  retryWithNewName = TRUE;
4508  }
4509 
4510  } while (retryWithNewName);
4511 
4512  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
4513 
4514  //
4515  // Creating the device object was not successful. Clean everything
4516  // up and indicate that the object was not created.
4517  //
4518 
4519  deviceObject = (PDEVICE_OBJECT) NULL;
4520 
4521  } else {
4522 
4523  //
4524  // The device was successfully created. Initialize the object so
4525  // that it can be inserted into the object table. Begin by zeroing
4526  // the memory for the device object.
4527  //
4528 
4529  RtlZeroMemory( deviceObject,
4530  sizeof( DEVICE_OBJECT ) + sizeof ( DEVOBJ_EXTENSION ) +
4531  RoundedSize );
4532 
4533  //
4534  // Fill in deviceObject & deviceObjectExtension cross pointers
4535  //
4536 
4537  deviceObjectExt = (PDEVOBJ_EXTENSION) (((PCHAR) deviceObject) +
4538  sizeof (DEVICE_OBJECT) + RoundedSize);
4539 
4540  deviceObjectExt->DeviceObject = deviceObject;
4541  deviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension = deviceObjectExt;
4542 
4543  //
4544  // Initialize deviceObjectExt
4545  // Note: the size of a Device Object Extension is initialized specifically
4546  // to ZERO so no driver will depend on it.
4547  //
4548 
4549  deviceObjectExt->Type = IO_TYPE_DEVICE_OBJECT_EXTENSION;
4550  deviceObjectExt->Size = 0;
4551 
4552  PoInitializeDeviceObject(deviceObjectExt);
4553 
4554  //
4555  // Set the type and size of this device object.
4556  //
4557 
4558  deviceObject->Type = IO_TYPE_DEVICE;
4559  deviceObject->Size = (USHORT) (sizeof( DEVICE_OBJECT ) + DeviceExtensionSize);
4560 
4561  //
4562  // Set the device type field in the object so that later code can
4563  // check the type. Likewise, set the device characteristics.
4564  //
4565 
4566  deviceObject->DeviceType = DeviceType;
4567  deviceObject->Characteristics = DeviceCharacteristics;
4568 
4569  //
4570  // If this device is either a tape or a disk, allocate a Volume
4571  // Parameter Block (VPB) which indicates that the volume has
4572  // never been mounted, and set the device object's VPB pointer to
4573  // it.
4574  //
4575 
4576  if ((DeviceType == FILE_DEVICE_DISK) ||
4577  (DeviceType == FILE_DEVICE_TAPE) ||
4578  (DeviceType == FILE_DEVICE_CD_ROM) ||
4579  (DeviceType == FILE_DEVICE_VIRTUAL_DISK)) {
4580 
4581  status = IopCreateVpb (deviceObject);
4582 
4583  if (!NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
4584 
4585  ObDereferenceObject(deviceObject);
4586 
4587  if (acl != NULL) {
4588  ExFreePool( acl );
4589  }
4590 
4591  *DeviceObject = (PDEVICE_OBJECT)NULL;
4592  return status;
4593  }
4594 
4595  KeInitializeEvent( &deviceObject->DeviceLock,
4596  SynchronizationEvent,
4597  TRUE );
4598  }
4599 
4600  //
4601  // Initialize the remainder of the device object.
4602  //
4603  deviceObject->AlignmentRequirement = HalGetDmaAlignmentRequirement() - 1;
4604  deviceObject->SectorSize = sectorSize;
4605  deviceObject->Flags = DO_DEVICE_INITIALIZING;
4606 
4607  if (Exclusive) {
4608  deviceObject->Flags |= DO_EXCLUSIVE;
4609  }
4610  if (deviceHasName) {
4611  deviceObject->Flags |= DO_DEVICE_HAS_NAME;
4612  }
4613 
4614  if(DeviceExtensionSize) {
4615  deviceObject->DeviceExtension = deviceObject + 1;
4616  } else {
4617  deviceObject->DeviceExtension = NULL;
4618  }
4619 
4620  deviceObject->StackSize = 1;
4621  switch ( DeviceType ) {
4622 
4623  case FILE_DEVICE_CD_ROM_FILE_SYSTEM:
4624  case FILE_DEVICE_DISK_FILE_SYSTEM:
4625  case FILE_DEVICE_FILE_SYSTEM:
4626  case FILE_DEVICE_NETWORK_FILE_SYSTEM:
4627  case FILE_DEVICE_TAPE_FILE_SYSTEM:
4628 
4629  //
4630  // This device represents a file system of some sort. Simply
4631  // initialize the queue list head in the device object.
4632  //
4633 
4634  InitializeListHead( &deviceObject->Queue.ListEntry );
4635  break;
4636 
4637  default:
4638 
4639  //
4640  // This is a real device of some sort. Allocate a spin lock
4641  // and initialize the device queue object in the device object.
4642  //
4643 
4644  KeInitializeDeviceQueue( &deviceObject->DeviceQueue );
4645  break;
4646  }
4647 
4648  //
4649  // Insert the device object into the table.
4650  //
4651 
4652  status = ObInsertObject( deviceObject,
4653  NULL,
4654  FILE_READ_DATA | FILE_WRITE_DATA,
4655  1,
4656  (PVOID *) &deviceObject,
4657  &handle );
4658 
4659  if (NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
4660 
4661  //
4662  // Reference the driver object. When the device object goes
4663  // away the reference will be removed. This prevents the
4664  // driver object and driver image from going away while the
4665  // device object is in the pending delete state.
4666  //
4667 
4668  ObReferenceObject( DriverObject );
4669 
4670  ASSERT((DriverObject->Flags & DRVO_UNLOAD_INVOKED) == 0);
4671 
4672  //
4673  // The insert completed successfully. Link the device object
4674  // and driver objects together. Close the handle so that if
4675  // the driver is unloaded, the device object can go away.
4676  //
4677 
4678  deviceObject->DriverObject = DriverObject;
4679 
4680  IopInsertRemoveDevice( DriverObject, deviceObject, TRUE );
4681  if (deviceObject->Vpb) {
4682  PoVolumeDevice(deviceObject);
4683  }
4684 
4685  (VOID) ObCloseHandle( handle, KernelMode );
4686 
4687  } else {
4688 
4689  //
4690  // The insert operation failed. Fortunately it dropped the
4691  // reference count on the device - since that was the last one
4692  // all the cleanup should be done for us.
4693  //
4694 
4695  //
4696  // indicate that no device object was created.
4697  //
4698 
4699  deviceObject = (PDEVICE_OBJECT) NULL;
4700  }
4701  }
4702 
4703  //
4704  // Free the DACL if we allocated it...
4705  //
4706 
4707  if (acl != NULL) {
4708  ExFreePool( acl );
4709  }
4710 
4711  *DeviceObject = deviceObject;
4712  return status;
4713 }
4714 
4715 NTSTATUS
4716 IoCreateFile(
4717  OUT PHANDLE FileHandle,
4718  IN ACCESS_MASK DesiredAccess,
4719  IN POBJECT_ATTRIBUTES ObjectAttributes,
4720  OUT PIO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatusBlock,
4721  IN PLARGE_INTEGER AllocationSize OPTIONAL,
4722  IN ULONG FileAttributes,
4723  IN ULONG ShareAccess,
4724  IN ULONG Disposition,
4725  IN ULONG CreateOptions,
4726  IN PVOID EaBuffer OPTIONAL,
4727  IN ULONG EaLength,
4728  IN CREATE_FILE_TYPE CreateFileType,
4729  IN PVOID ExtraCreateParameters OPTIONAL,
4730  IN ULONG Options
4731  )
4732 /*++
4733 
4734 Routine Description:
4735 
4736  This is the common routine for both NtCreateFile and NtOpenFile to allow
4737  a user to create or open a file. This procedure is also used internally
4738  by kernel mode components, such as the network server, to perform the
4739  same type of operation, but allows kernel mode code to force checking
4740  arguments and access to the file, rather than bypassing these checks
4741  because the code is running in kernel mode.
4742 
4743 Arguments:
4744 
4745  FileHandle - A pointer to a variable to receive the handle to the open
4746  file.
4747 
4748  DesiredAccess - Supplies the types of access that the caller would like
4749  to the file.
4750 
4751  ObjectAttributes - Supplies the attributes to be used for the file object
4752  (name, SECURITY_DESCRIPTOR, etc.)
4753 
4754  IoStatusBlock - Specifies the address of the caller's I/O status block.
4755 
4756  AllocationSize - Initial size that should be allocated to the file.
4757  This parameter only has an affect if the file is created. Further,
4758  if not specified, then it is taken to mean zero.
4759 
4760  FileAttributes - Specifies the attributes that should be set on the file,
4761  if it is created.
4762 
4763  ShareAccess - Supplies the types of share access that the caller would
4764  like to the file.
4765 
4766  Disposition - Supplies the method for handling the create/open.
4767 
4768  CreateOptions - Caller options for how to perform the create/open.
4769 
4770  EaBuffer - Optionally specifies a set of EAs to be applied to the file
4771  if it is created.
4772 
4773  EaLength - Supplies the length of the EaBuffer.
4774 
4775  CreateFileType - The type of file to create.
4776 
4777  ExtraCreateParameters - Optionally specifies a pointer to extra create
4778  parameters. The format of the parameters depends on the value of
4779  CreateFileType.
4780 
4781  Options - Specifies the options that are to be used during generation
4782  of the create IRP.
4783 
4784 Return Value:
4785 
4786  The function value is the final status of the create/open operation.
4787 
4788 Warning:
4789 
4790  If a pointer to ExtraCreateParameters is passed the data must be
4791  readable from kernel mode.
4792 
4793 
4794 --*/
4795 {
4796 
4797 #define IOP_CREATE_FILE_TIMEOUT 1000
4798 
4799  NTSTATUS status = STATUS_SUCCESS; // compiling with W4 incorrectly reports an error at the break
4800  // instruction inside the loop
4801  LONG CapturedSequence;
4802  LONG SleepInterval = 0;
4803 
4804  //
4805  // Simply invoke the common I/O file creation routine to perform the work.
4806  //
4807 
4808  PAGED_CODE();
4809 
4810  do {
4811 
4812  //
4813  // Capture the sequence
4814  //
4815 
4816  CapturedSequence = ExHotpSyncRenameSequence;
4817 
4818  //
4819  // If another thread is in the process of atomic file
4820  // rename, we need to retry opening the file in case of failures.
4821  // If a high priority thread enters this code while a
4822  // another thread is in the middle of doing a double-rename operation,
4823  // we need to back off a bit this thread and sleep until others
4824  // threads involved in hotpatching finish the operation.
4825  //
4826  // Note: SleepInterval starts from 0, and it will be
4827  // incremented after the test. So the thread will not sleep first
4828  // time calling IoCreateFile
4829  //
4830 
4831  if ( (CapturedSequence & 1) && ( SleepInterval++ ) ) {
4832 
4833  LARGE_INTEGER interval;
4834 
4835  //
4836  // We are during an atomic rename operation. Check if this
4837  // happens in the context of this thread. Do not
4838  // attempt to retry if yes.
4839  // This handles cases where AV drivers open files synchronous
4840  // as effect of a file rename.
4841  //
4842 
4843  if ( ExSyncRenameOwner == KeGetCurrentThread() ) {
4844 
4845  //
4846  // Note that this code path is not taken for the first pass
4847  // through this do / while loop, so the correct status will be initialized
4848  // if this condition is true
4849  //
4850 
4851  break;
4852  }
4853 
4854  interval.QuadPart = - (LONGLONG)SleepInterval * 10 * 1000;
4855 
4856  if (SleepInterval > IOP_CREATE_FILE_TIMEOUT) {
4857 
4858  //
4859  // We still do not make any progress. Limit
4860  // the timeout next sleep to something reasonable
4861  // and assert a possible deadlock in checked builds.
4862  //
4863 
4864  SleepInterval = IOP_CREATE_FILE_TIMEOUT;
4865  ASSERT( FALSE );
4866  }
4867 
4868  KeDelayExecutionThread( KernelMode, FALSE, &interval );
4869  CapturedSequence = ExHotpSyncRenameSequence;
4870  }
4871 
4872  status = IopCreateFile( FileHandle,
4873  DesiredAccess,
4874  ObjectAttributes,
4875  IoStatusBlock,
4876  AllocationSize,
4877  FileAttributes,
4878  ShareAccess,
4879  Disposition,
4880  CreateOptions,
4881  EaBuffer,
4882  EaLength,
4883  CreateFileType,
4884  ExtraCreateParameters,
4885  Options,
4886  0,
4887  NULL
4888  );
4889 
4890  } while ( (!NT_SUCCESS(status))
4891  &&
4892  ((CapturedSequence & 1) || (CapturedSequence != ExHotpSyncRenameSequence)));
4893 
4894  return status;
4895 }
4896 
4897 NTSTATUS
4898 IoCreateFileSpecifyDeviceObjectHint(
4899  OUT PHANDLE FileHandle,
4900  IN ACCESS_MASK DesiredAccess,
4901  IN POBJECT_ATTRIBUTES ObjectAttributes,
4902  OUT PIO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatusBlock,
4903  IN PLARGE_INTEGER AllocationSize OPTIONAL,
4904  IN ULONG FileAttributes,
4905  IN ULONG ShareAccess,
4906  IN ULONG Disposition,
4907  IN ULONG CreateOptions,
4908  IN PVOID EaBuffer OPTIONAL,
4909  IN ULONG EaLength,
4910  IN CREATE_FILE_TYPE CreateFileType,
4911  IN PVOID ExtraCreateParameters OPTIONAL,
4912  IN ULONG Options,
4913  IN PVOID DeviceObject
4914  )
4915 {
4916 
4917  ULONG internalFlags = IOP_CREATE_DEVICE_OBJECT_EXTENSION;
4918
