4920  internalFlags |= IOP_CREATE_USE_TOP_DEVICE_OBJECT_HINT;
4921  }
4922 
4923  if (Options & IO_IGNORE_SHARE_ACCESS_CHECK) {
4924  internalFlags |= IOP_CREATE_IGNORE_SHARE_ACCESS_CHECK;
4925  }
4926 
4927  return IopCreateFile(
4928  FileHandle,
4929  DesiredAccess,
4930  ObjectAttributes,
4931  IoStatusBlock,
4932  AllocationSize,
4933  FileAttributes,
4934  ShareAccess,
4935  Disposition,
4936  CreateOptions,
4937  EaBuffer,
4938  EaLength,
4939  CreateFileType,
4940  ExtraCreateParameters,
4941  Options|IO_NO_PARAMETER_CHECKING,
4942  internalFlags,
4943  DeviceObject
4944  );
4945 }
4946 
4947 NTSTATUS
4948 IopCreateFile(
4949  OUT PHANDLE FileHandle,
4950  IN ACCESS_MASK DesiredAccess,
4951  IN POBJECT_ATTRIBUTES ObjectAttributes,
4952  OUT PIO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatusBlock,
4953  IN PLARGE_INTEGER AllocationSize OPTIONAL,
4954  IN ULONG FileAttributes,
4955  IN ULONG ShareAccess,
4956  IN ULONG Disposition,
4957  IN ULONG CreateOptions,
4958  IN PVOID EaBuffer OPTIONAL,
4959  IN ULONG EaLength,
4960  IN CREATE_FILE_TYPE CreateFileType,
4961  IN PVOID ExtraCreateParameters OPTIONAL,
4962  IN ULONG Options,
4963  IN ULONG InternalFlags,
4964  IN PVOID DeviceObject
4965  )
4966 
4967 /*++
4968 
4969 Routine Description:
4970 
4971  This is the common routine for both NtCreateFile and NtOpenFile to allow
4972  a user to create or open a file. This procedure is also used internally
4973  by kernel mode components, such as the network server, to perform the
4974  same type of operation, but allows kernel mode code to force checking
4975  arguments and access to the file, rather than bypassing these checks
4976  because the code is running in kernel mode.
4977 
4978 Arguments:
4979 
4980  FileHandle - A pointer to a variable to receive the handle to the open
4981  file.
4982 
4983  DesiredAccess - Supplies the types of access that the caller would like
4984  to the file.
4985 
4986  ObjectAttributes - Supplies the attributes to be used for the file object
4987  (name, SECURITY_DESCRIPTOR, etc.)
4988 
4989  IoStatusBlock - Specifies the address of the caller's I/O status block.
4990 
4991  AllocationSize - Initial size that should be allocated to the file.
4992  This parameter only has an affect if the file is created. Further,
4993  if not specified, then it is taken to mean zero.
4994 
4995  FileAttributes - Specifies the attributes that should be set on the file,
4996  if it is created.
4997 
4998  ShareAccess - Supplies the types of share access that the caller would
4999  like to the file.
5000 
5001  Disposition - Supplies the method for handling the create/open.
5002 
5003  CreateOptions - Caller options for how to perform the create/open.
5004 
5005  EaBuffer - Optionally specifies a set of EAs to be applied to the file
5006  if it is created.
5007 
5008  EaLength - Supplies the length of the EaBuffer.
5009 
5010  CreateFileType - The type of file to create.
5011 
5012  ExtraCreateParameters - Optionally specifies a pointer to extra create
5013  parameters. The format of the parameters depends on the value of
5014  CreateFileType.
5015 
5016  Options - Specifies the options that are to be used during generation
5017  of the create IRP.
5018 
5019  DeviceObject - Specifies which device object to use when issuing the create IRP.
5020 
5021 Return Value:
5022 
5023  The function value is the final status of the create/open operation.
5024 
5025 Warning:
5026 
5027  If a pointer to ExtraCreateParameters is passed the data must be
5028  readable from kernel mode.
5029 
5030 
5031 --*/
5032 
5033 {
5034  KPROCESSOR_MODE requestorMode;
5035  NTSTATUS status;
5036  HANDLE handle;
5037  POPEN_PACKET openPacket;
5038  BOOLEAN SuccessfulIoParse;
5039  LARGE_INTEGER initialAllocationSize;
5040 
5041  PAGED_CODE();
5042 
5043  //
5044  // Get the previous mode; i.e., the mode of the caller.
5045  //
5046 
5047  requestorMode = KeGetPreviousMode();
5048 
5049  if (Options & IO_NO_PARAMETER_CHECKING) {
5050  requestorMode = KernelMode;
5051  }
5052 
5053  openPacket = IopAllocateOpenPacket();
5054  if (openPacket == NULL) {
5055  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
5056  }
5057 
5058  if (requestorMode != KernelMode || Options & IO_CHECK_CREATE_PARAMETERS) {
5059 
5060  //
5061  // Check for any invalid parameters.
5062  //
5063 
5064  if (
5065 
5066  //
5067  // Check that no invalid file attributes flags were specified.
5068  //
5069 
5070 // (FileAttributes & ~FILE_ATTRIBUTE_VALID_SET_FLAGS)
5071  (FileAttributes & ~FILE_ATTRIBUTE_VALID_FLAGS)
5072 
5073  ||
5074 
5075  //
5076  // Check that no invalid share access flags were specified.
5077  //
5078 
5079  (ShareAccess & ~FILE_SHARE_VALID_FLAGS)
5080 
5081  ||
5082 
5083  //
5084  // Ensure that the disposition value is in range.
5085  //
5086 
5087  (Disposition > FILE_MAXIMUM_DISPOSITION)
5088 
5089  ||
5090 
5091  //
5092  // Check that no invalid create options were specified.
5093  //
5094 
5095  (CreateOptions & ~FILE_VALID_OPTION_FLAGS)
5096 
5097  ||
5098 
5099  //
5100  // If the caller specified synchronous I/O, then ensure that
5101  // (s)he also asked for synchronize desired access to the
5102  // file.
5103  //
5104 
5105  (CreateOptions & (FILE_SYNCHRONOUS_IO_ALERT | FILE_SYNCHRONOUS_IO_NONALERT) &&
5106  (!(DesiredAccess & SYNCHRONIZE)))
5107 
5108  ||
5109 
5110  //
5111  // Also, if the caller specified that the file is to be deleted
5112  // on close, then ensure that delete is specified as one of the
5113  // desired accesses requested.
5114  //
5115 
5116  (CreateOptions & FILE_DELETE_ON_CLOSE &&
5117  (!(DesiredAccess & DELETE)))
5118 
5119  ||
5120 
5121  //
5122  // Likewise, ensure that if one of the synchronous I/O modes
5123  // is specified that the other one is not specified as well.
5124  //
5125 
5126  ((CreateOptions & (FILE_SYNCHRONOUS_IO_ALERT | FILE_SYNCHRONOUS_IO_NONALERT)) ==
5127  (FILE_SYNCHRONOUS_IO_ALERT | FILE_SYNCHRONOUS_IO_NONALERT))
5128 
5129  ||
5130 
5131  //
5132  // If this create or open is for a directory operation, check
5133  // that all of the other flags, dispositions, and desired
5134  // access parameters were also specified correctly.
5135  //
5136  // These are as follows:
5137  //
5138  // o No other flags other than the synchronous I/O flags,
5139  // write-through, or open by file ID are set.
5140  //
5141  // o The disposition value is one of create, open, or
5142  // open-if.
5143  //
5144  // o No non-directory accesses have been specified.
5145  //
5146 
5147  ((CreateOptions & FILE_DIRECTORY_FILE)
5148  && !(CreateOptions & FILE_NON_DIRECTORY_FILE)
5149  && ((CreateOptions & ~(FILE_DIRECTORY_FILE |
5150  FILE_SYNCHRONOUS_IO_ALERT |
5151  FILE_SYNCHRONOUS_IO_NONALERT |
5152  FILE_WRITE_THROUGH |
5153  FILE_COMPLETE_IF_OPLOCKED |
5154  FILE_OPEN_FOR_BACKUP_INTENT |
5155  FILE_DELETE_ON_CLOSE |
5156  FILE_OPEN_FOR_FREE_SPACE_QUERY |
5157  FILE_OPEN_BY_FILE_ID |
5158  FILE_NO_COMPRESSION|
5159  FILE_OPEN_REPARSE_POINT))
5160  || ((Disposition != FILE_CREATE)
5161  && (Disposition != FILE_OPEN)
5162  && (Disposition != FILE_OPEN_IF))
5163  )
5164  )
5165 
5166  ||
5167 
5168  //
5169  // FILE_COMPLETE_IF_OPLOCK and FILE_RESERVE_OPFILTER are
5170  // incompatible options.
5171  //
5172 
5173  ((CreateOptions & FILE_COMPLETE_IF_OPLOCKED) &&
5174  (CreateOptions & FILE_RESERVE_OPFILTER))
5175 
5176  ||
5177 
5178  //
5179  // Fail the create if desired access is zero.
5180  //
5181  (IopFailZeroAccessCreate && !DesiredAccess)
5182 
5183  ||
5184 
5185  //
5186  // Finally, if the no intermediate buffering option was
5187  // specified, ensure that the caller did not also request
5188  // append access to the file.
5189  //
5190 
5191  (CreateOptions & FILE_NO_INTERMEDIATE_BUFFERING &&
5192  (DesiredAccess & FILE_APPEND_DATA)) ) {
5193 
5194  IopFreeOpenPacket(openPacket);
5195  return STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER;
5196  }
5197 
5198  //
5199  // Check the file type specific creation parameters.
5200  //
5201 
5202  if (CreateFileType == CreateFileTypeNone) {
5203 
5204  NOTHING;
5205 
5206  } else if (CreateFileType == CreateFileTypeNamedPipe) {
5207 
5208  if (!ARGUMENT_PRESENT( ExtraCreateParameters ) ) {
5209 
5210  IopFreeOpenPacket(openPacket);
5211  return STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER;
5212 
5213  } else {
5214 
5215  PNAMED_PIPE_CREATE_PARAMETERS NamedPipeCreateParameters;
5216 
5217  NamedPipeCreateParameters = ExtraCreateParameters;
5218 
5219  //
5220  // Check the parameters for creating a named pipe to
5221  // ensure that no invalid parameters were passed.
5222  //
5223 
5224  if (
5225 
5226  //
5227  // Check the NamedPipeType field to ensure that it
5228  // is within range.
5229  //
5230 
5231  (NamedPipeCreateParameters->NamedPipeType >
5232  FILE_PIPE_MESSAGE_TYPE)
5233 
5234  ||
5235 
5236  //
5237  // Check the ReadMode field to ensure that it is
5238  // within range.
5239  //
5240 
5241  (NamedPipeCreateParameters->ReadMode >
5242  FILE_PIPE_MESSAGE_MODE)
5243 
5244  ||
5245 
5246  //
5247  // Check the CompletionMode field to ensure that
5248  // it is within range.
5249  //
5250 
5251  (NamedPipeCreateParameters->CompletionMode >
5252  FILE_PIPE_COMPLETE_OPERATION)
5253 
5254  ||
5255 
5256  //
5257  // Check the ShareAccess parameter to ensure that
5258  // it does not specify shared delete access. The
5259  // Named Pipe File System itself will need to ensure
5260  // that at least one of SHARE_READ or SHARE_WRITE
5261  // is specified if the first instance of the pipe
5262  // is being created.
5263  //
5264 
5265  (ShareAccess & FILE_SHARE_DELETE)
5266 
5267  ||
5268 
5269  //
5270  // Check the Disposition parameter to ensure that
5271  // is does not specify anything other than create,
5272  // open, or open if.
5273  //
5274 
5275  (Disposition < FILE_OPEN || Disposition > FILE_OPEN_IF)
5276 
5277  ||
5278 
5279  //
5280  // Finally, check the CreateOptions parameter to
5281  // ensure that it does not contain any invalid
5282  // options for named pipes.
5283  //
5284 
5285  (CreateOptions & ~FILE_VALID_PIPE_OPTION_FLAGS)) {
5286  IopFreeOpenPacket(openPacket);
5287  return STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER;
5288  }
5289 
5290  }
5291 
5292  } else if (CreateFileType == CreateFileTypeMailslot) {
5293 
5294  if (!ARGUMENT_PRESENT( ExtraCreateParameters ) ) {
5295 
5296  IopFreeOpenPacket(openPacket);
5297  return STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER;
5298 
5299  } else {
5300 
5301  PMAILSLOT_CREATE_PARAMETERS mailslotCreateParameters;
5302 
5303  mailslotCreateParameters = ExtraCreateParameters;
5304 
5305  //
5306  // Check the parameters for creating a mailslot to ensure
5307  // that no invalid parameters were passed.
5308  //
5309 
5310  if (
5311 
5312  //
5313  // Check the ShareAccess parameter to ensure that
5314  // it does not specify shared delete access.
5315  //
5316 
5317  (ShareAccess & FILE_SHARE_DELETE)
5318 
5319  ||
5320 
5321  //
5322  // Check the ShareAccess parameter to ensure that
5323  // shared write access is specified.
5324  //
5325 
5326  !(ShareAccess & ~FILE_SHARE_WRITE)
5327 
5328  ||
5329 
5330  //
5331  // Check the Disposition parameter to ensure that
5332  // it specifies that the file is to be created.
5333  //
5334 
5335  (Disposition != FILE_CREATE)
5336 
5337  ||
5338 
5339  //
5340  // Check the CreateOptions parameter to ensure that
5341  // it does not contain any options that are invalid
5342  // for mailslots.
5343  //
5344 
5345  (CreateOptions & ~FILE_VALID_MAILSLOT_OPTION_FLAGS)) {
5346  IopFreeOpenPacket(openPacket);
5347  return STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER;
5348  }
5349  }
5350  }
5351  }
5352 
5353  if (requestorMode != KernelMode) {
5354 
5355  //
5356  // The caller's access mode is not kernel so probe each of the
5357  // arguments and capture them as necessary. If any failures occur,
5358  // the condition handler will be invoked to handle them. It will
5359  // simply cleanup and return an access violation status code back
5360  // to the system service dispatcher.
5361  //
5362 
5363  openPacket->EaBuffer = (PFILE_FULL_EA_INFORMATION) NULL;
5364 
5365  try {
5366 
5367  //
5368  // The FileHandle parameter must be writeable by the caller.
5369  // Probe it for a write operation.
5370  //
5371 
5372  ProbeAndWriteHandle( FileHandle, 0L );
5373 
5374  //
5375  // The IoStatusBlock parameter must be writeable by the caller.
5376  //
5377 
5378  ProbeForWriteIoStatus( IoStatusBlock );
5379 
5380  //
5381  // The AllocationSize parameter must be readable by the caller
5382  // if it is present. If so, probe and capture it.
5383  //
5384 
5385  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( AllocationSize )) {
5386  ProbeForReadSmallStructure( AllocationSize,
5387  sizeof( LARGE_INTEGER ),
5388  sizeof( ULONG ) );
5389  initialAllocationSize = *AllocationSize;
5390  } else {
5391  initialAllocationSize.QuadPart = 0;
5392  }
5393 
5394  if (initialAllocationSize.QuadPart < 0) {
5395  ExRaiseStatus( STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER );
5396  }
5397  } except(EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
5398 
5399  //
5400  // An exception was incurred while attempting to access the
5401  // caller's parameters. Simply return the reason for the
5402  // exception as the service status.
5403  //
5404 
5405  IopFreeOpenPacket(openPacket);
5406  return GetExceptionCode();
5407  }
5408 
5409  //
5410  // Finally, if an EaBuffer was specified, ensure that it is readable
5411  // from the caller's mode and capture it.
5412  //
5413 
5414  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( EaBuffer ) && EaLength) {
5415 
5416  ULONG errorOffset;
5417 
5418  try {
5419 
5420  ProbeForRead( EaBuffer, EaLength, sizeof( ULONG ) );
5421  openPacket->EaBuffer = ExAllocatePoolWithQuotaTag( NonPagedPool,
5422  EaLength,
5423  'aEoI' );
5424  openPacket->EaLength = EaLength;
5425  RtlCopyMemory( openPacket->EaBuffer, EaBuffer, EaLength );
5426 
5427  //
5428  // Walk the buffer and ensure that its format is valid. Note
5429  // that has been probed.
5430  //
5431 
5432  status = IoCheckEaBufferValidity( openPacket->EaBuffer,
5433  EaLength,
5434  &errorOffset );
5435 
5436  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
5437  IoStatusBlock->Status = status;
5438  IoStatusBlock->Information = errorOffset;
5439  ExRaiseStatus( status );
5440  }
5441 
5442  } except(EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
5443 
5444  //
5445  // An exception was incurred while attempting to access the
5446  // caller's parameters. Check to see whether or not an EA
5447  // buffer was allocated and deallocate if so.
5448  //
5449 
5450  if (openPacket->EaBuffer != NULL) {
5451  ExFreePool( openPacket->EaBuffer );
5452  }
5453 
5454  IopFreeOpenPacket(openPacket);
5455  return GetExceptionCode();
5456 
5457  }
5458 
5459  } else {
5460 
5461  //
5462  // No EAs were specified.
5463  //
5464 
5465  openPacket->EaBuffer = (PVOID) NULL;
5466  openPacket->EaLength = 0L;
5467  }
5468 
5469  } else {
5470 
5471  //
5472  // The caller's mode is kernel. Copy the input parameters to their
5473  // expected locations for later use. Also, put move attach device
5474  // flag where it belongs.
5475  //
5476 
5477  if (CreateOptions & IO_ATTACH_DEVICE_API) {
5478  Options |= IO_ATTACH_DEVICE;
5479  CreateOptions &= ~IO_ATTACH_DEVICE_API;
5480 
5481  }
5482 
5483  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( AllocationSize )) {
5484  initialAllocationSize = *AllocationSize;
5485  } else {
5486  initialAllocationSize.QuadPart = 0;
5487  }
5488 
5489  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( EaBuffer ) && EaLength) {
5490 
5491  ULONG errorOffset;
5492 
5493  openPacket->EaBuffer = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( NonPagedPool,
5494  EaLength,
5495  'aEoI' );
5496  if (!openPacket->EaBuffer) {
5497  IopFreeOpenPacket(openPacket);
5498  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
5499  }
5500  openPacket->EaLength = EaLength;
5501  RtlCopyMemory( openPacket->EaBuffer, EaBuffer, EaLength );
5502 
5503  //
5504  // Walk the buffer and ensure that its format is valid. Note
5505  // that has been probed.
5506  //
5507 
5508  status = IoCheckEaBufferValidity( openPacket->EaBuffer,
5509  EaLength,
5510  &errorOffset );
5511 
5512  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
5513  ExFreePool(openPacket->EaBuffer);
5514  IoStatusBlock->Status = status;
5515  IoStatusBlock->Information = errorOffset;
5516  IopFreeOpenPacket(openPacket);
5517  return status;
5518  }
5519 
5520  } else {
5521  openPacket->EaBuffer = (PVOID) NULL;
5522  openPacket->EaLength = 0L;
5523  }
5524  }
5525 
5526  //
5527  // Now fill in an Open Packet (OP) to be used in calling the device object
5528  // parse routine. This packet will allow information to be passed between
5529  // this routine and the parse routine so that a common context may be kept.
5530  // For most services this would be done with an I/O Request Packet (IRP),
5531  // but this cannot be done here because the number of stack entries which
5532  // need to be allocated in the IRP is not yet known.
5533  //
5534 
5535  openPacket->Type = IO_TYPE_OPEN_PACKET;
5536  openPacket->Size = sizeof( OPEN_PACKET );
5537  openPacket->ParseCheck = 0L;
5538  openPacket->AllocationSize = initialAllocationSize;
5539  openPacket->CreateOptions = CreateOptions;
5540  openPacket->FileAttributes = (USHORT) FileAttributes;
5541  openPacket->ShareAccess = (USHORT) ShareAccess;
5542  openPacket->Disposition = Disposition;
5543  openPacket->Override = FALSE;
5544  openPacket->QueryOnly = FALSE;
5545  openPacket->DeleteOnly = FALSE;
5546  openPacket->Options = Options;
5547  openPacket->RelatedFileObject = (PFILE_OBJECT) NULL;
5548  openPacket->CreateFileType = CreateFileType;
5549  openPacket->ExtraCreateParameters = ExtraCreateParameters;
5550  openPacket->TraversedMountPoint = FALSE;
5551  openPacket->InternalFlags = InternalFlags;
5552  openPacket->TopDeviceObjectHint = DeviceObject;
5553 
5554  //
5555  // Assume that the operation is going to be successful.
5556  //
5557 
5558  openPacket->FinalStatus = STATUS_SUCCESS;
5559 
5560  //
5561  // Zero the file object field in the OP so the parse routine knows that
5562  // this is the first time through. For reparse operations it will continue
5563  // to use the same file object that it allocated the first time.
5564  //
5565 
5566  openPacket->FileObject = (PFILE_OBJECT) NULL;
5567 
5568  //
5569  // Update the open count for this process.
5570  //
5571 
5572  IopUpdateOtherOperationCount();
5573 
5574  //
5575  // Attempt to open the file object by name. This will yield the handle
5576  // that the user is to use as his handle to the file in all subsequent
5577  // calls, if it works.
5578  //
5579  // This call performs a whole lot of the work for actually getting every-
5580  // thing set up for the I/O system. The object manager will take the name
5581  // of the file and will translate it until it reaches a device object (or
5582  // it fails). If the former, then it will invoke the parse routine set up
5583  // by the I/O system for device objects. This routine will actually end
5584  // up creating the file object, allocating an IRP, filling it in, and then
5585  // invoking the driver's dispatch routine with the packet.
5586  //
5587 
5588  status = ObOpenObjectByName( ObjectAttributes,
5589  (POBJECT_TYPE) NULL,
5590  requestorMode,
5591  NULL,
5592  DesiredAccess,
5593  openPacket,
5594  &handle );
5595 
5596  //
5597  // If an EA buffer was allocated, deallocate it now before attempting to
5598  // determine whether or not the operation was successful so that it can be
5599  // done in one place rather than in two places.
5600  //
5601 
5602  if (openPacket->EaBuffer) {
5603  ExFreePool( openPacket->EaBuffer );
5604  }
5605 
5606  //
5607  // Check the status of the open. If it was not successful, cleanup and
5608  // get out. Notice that it is also possible, because this code does not
5609  // explicitly request that a particular type of object (because the Object
5610  // Manager does not check when a parse routine is present and because the
5611  // name first refers to a device object and then a file object), a check
5612  // must be made here to ensure that what was returned was really a file
5613  // object. The check is to see whether the device object parse routine
5614  // believes that it successfully returned a pointer to a file object. If
5615  // it does, then OK; otherwise, something went wrong somewhere.
5616  //
5617 
5618  SuccessfulIoParse = (BOOLEAN) (openPacket->ParseCheck == OPEN_PACKET_PATTERN);
5619 
5620  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status ) || !SuccessfulIoParse) {
5621 
5622  if (NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
5623 
5624  //
5625  // The operation was successful as far as the object system is
5626  // concerned, but the I/O system device parse routine was never
5627  // successfully completed so this operation has actually completed
5628  // with an error because of an object mismatch. Therefore, this is
5629  // the wrong type of object so dereference whatever was actually
5630  // referenced by closing the handle that was created for it.
5631  // We have to do a ZwClose as this handle can be a kernel handle if
5632  // IoCreateFile was called by a driver.
5633  //
5634 
5635  ZwClose( handle );
5636  status = STATUS_OBJECT_TYPE_MISMATCH;
5637  }
5638 
5639  //
5640  // If the final status according to the device parse routine
5641  // indicates that the operation was not successful, then use that
5642  // routine's final status because it is more descriptive than the
5643  // status which was returned by the object manager.
5644  //
5645 
5646  if (!NT_SUCCESS( openPacket->FinalStatus )) {
5647  status = openPacket->FinalStatus;
5648 
5649  if (NT_WARNING( status )) {
5650 
5651  try {
5652 
5653  IoStatusBlock->Status = openPacket->FinalStatus;
5654  IoStatusBlock->Information = openPacket->Information;
5655 
5656  } except(EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
5657 
5658  status = GetExceptionCode();
5659 
5660  }
5661 
5662  }
5663 
5664  } else if (openPacket->FileObject != NULL && !SuccessfulIoParse) {
5665 
5666  //
5667  // Otherwise, one of two things occurred:
5668  //
5669  // 1) The parse routine was invoked at least once and a
5670  // reparse was performed but the parse routine did not
5671  // actually complete.
5672  //
5673  // 2) The parse routine was successful so everything worked
5674  // but the object manager incurred an error after the
5675  // parse routine completed.
5676  //
5677  // For case #1, there is an outstanding file object that still
5678  // exists. This must be cleaned up.
5679  //
5680  // For case #2, nothing must be done as the object manager has
5681  // already dereferenced the file object. Note that this code is
5682  // not invoked if the parse routine completed with a successful
5683  // status return (SuccessfulIoParse is TRUE).
5684  //
5685 
5686  if (openPacket->FileObject->FileName.Length != 0) {
5687  ExFreePool( openPacket->FileObject->FileName.Buffer );
5688  }
5689  openPacket->FileObject->DeviceObject = (PDEVICE_OBJECT) NULL;
5690  ObDereferenceObject( openPacket->FileObject );
5691  }
5692 
5693  //
5694  // When an NTFS file junction or an NTFS directory junction is traversed
5695  // OBJ_MAX_REPARSE_ATTEMPTS namy times, the object manager gives up and
5696  // returns the code STATUS_OBJECT_NAME_NOT_FOUND.
5697  //
5698  // This can happen in the following cases:
5699  //
5700  // 1) One encounters a legal chain of directory junctions that happen
5701  // to be longer than the value of the above constant.
5702  //
5703  // 2) One encounters a self-referential file or directory junction that
5704  // is, in effect, a tight name cycle.
5705  //
5706  // 3) One encounters a name cycle composed of several NTFS junctions.
5707  //
5708  // To improve on this return code see if openPacket->Information is
5709  // the trace of an NTFS name junction.
5710  //
5711 
5712  if ((status == STATUS_OBJECT_NAME_NOT_FOUND) &&
5713  (openPacket->Information == IO_REPARSE_TAG_MOUNT_POINT)) {
5714 
5715  status = STATUS_REPARSE_POINT_NOT_RESOLVED;
5716  }
5717 
5718  } else {
5719 
5720  //
5721  // At this point, the open/create operation has been successfully
5722  // completed. There is a handle to the file object, which has been
5723  // created, and the file object has been signaled.
5724  //
5725  // The remaining work to be done is to complete the operation. This is
5726  // performed as follows:
5727  //
5728  // 1. The file object has been signaled, so no work needs to be done
5729  // for it.
5730  //
5731  // 2. The file handle is returned to the user.
5732  //
5733  // 3. The I/O status block is written with the final status.
5734  //
5735 
5736  openPacket->FileObject->Flags |= FO_HANDLE_CREATED;
5737 
5738  ASSERT( openPacket->FileObject->Type == IO_TYPE_FILE );
5739 
5740  try {
5741 
5742  //
5743  // Return the file handle.
5744  //
5745 
5746  *FileHandle = handle;
5747 
5748  //
5749  // Write the I/O status into the caller's buffer.
5750  //
5751 
5752  IoStatusBlock->Information = openPacket->Information;
5753  IoStatusBlock->Status = openPacket->FinalStatus;
5754  status = openPacket->FinalStatus;
5755 
5756  } except(EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
5757 
5758  status = GetExceptionCode();
5759 
5760  }
5761 
5762  }
5763 
5764  //
5765  // If the parse routine successfully created a file object then
5766  // dereference it here.
5767  //
5768 
5769  if (SuccessfulIoParse && openPacket->FileObject != NULL) {
5770 
5771  ObDereferenceObject( openPacket->FileObject );
5772  }
5773 
5774  IopFreeOpenPacket(openPacket);
5775  return status;
5776 }
5777 
5778 PKEVENT
5779 IoCreateNotificationEvent(
5780  IN PUNICODE_STRING EventName,
5781  OUT PHANDLE EventHandle
5782  )
5783 
5784 /*++
5785 
5786 Routine Description:
5787 
5788  This routine creates a named notification event for use in notifying
5789  different system components or drivers that an event occurred.
5790 
5791 Arguments:
5792 
5793  EventName - Supplies the full name of the event.
5794 
5795  EventHandle - Supplies a location to return a handle to the event.
5796 
5797 Return Value:
5798 
5799  The function value is a pointer to the created/opened event, or NULL if
5800  the event could not be created/opened.
5801 
5802 --*/
5803 
5804 {
5805  OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES objectAttributes;
5806  NTSTATUS status;
5807  HANDLE eventHandle;
5808  PKEVENT eventObject;
5809 
5810  PAGED_CODE();
5811 
5812  //
5813  // Begin by initializing the object attributes.
5814  //
5815 
5816  InitializeObjectAttributes( &objectAttributes,
5817  EventName,
5818  OBJ_OPENIF|OBJ_KERNEL_HANDLE,
5819  (HANDLE) NULL,
5820  (PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR) NULL );
5821 
5822  //
5823  // Now create or open the event.
5824  //
5825 
5826  status = ZwCreateEvent( &eventHandle,
5827  EVENT_ALL_ACCESS,
5828  &objectAttributes,
5829  NotificationEvent,
5830  TRUE );
5831  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
5832  return (PKEVENT) NULL;
5833  }
5834 
5835  //
5836  // Reference the object by its handle to get a pointer that can be returned
5837  // to the caller.
5838  //
5839 
5840  (VOID) ObReferenceObjectByHandle( eventHandle,
5841  0,
5842  ExEventObjectType,
5843  KernelMode,
5844  (PVOID *) &eventObject,
5845  NULL );
5846  ObDereferenceObject( eventObject );
5847 
5848  //
5849  // Return the handle and the pointer to the event.
5850  //
5851 
5852  *EventHandle = eventHandle;
5853 
5854  return eventObject;
5855 }
5856 
5857 PFILE_OBJECT
5858 IoCreateStreamFileObject(
5859  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject OPTIONAL,
5860  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject OPTIONAL
5861  )
5862 {
5863  return (IoCreateStreamFileObjectEx(FileObject, DeviceObject, NULL));
5864 }
5865 
5866 
5867 PFILE_OBJECT
5868 IoCreateStreamFileObjectEx(
5869  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject OPTIONAL,
5870  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject OPTIONAL,
5871  OUT PHANDLE FileHandle OPTIONAL
5872  )
5873 
5874 /*++
5875 
5876 Routine Description:
5877 
5878  This routine is invoked to create a new file object that represents an
5879  alternate data stream for an existing file object. The input file object
5880  represents the file object that already exists for a file, and the newly
5881  created stream file object is used to access other parts of the file
5882  other than the data. Some uses of stream file objects are the EAs or
5883  the SECURITY_DESCRIPTORs on the file. The stream file object allows
5884  the file system to cache these parts of the file just as if they were
5885  an entire to themselves.
5886 
5887  It is also possible to use stream file objects to represent virtual
5888  volume files. This allows various parts of the on-disk structure to
5889  be viewed as a virtual file and therefore be cached using the same logic
5890  in the file system. For this case, the device object pointer is used
5891  to create the file object.
5892 
5893 Arguments:
5894 
5895  FileObject - Pointer to the file object to which the new stream file
5896  is related. This pointer is optional.
5897 
5898  DeviceObject - Pointer to the device object on which the stream file
5899  is to be opened. This pointer is not optional if the FileObject
5900  pointer is not specified.
5901 
5902  FileHandle - Out parameter for handle if necessary.
5903 
5904 Return Value:
5905 
5906  The function value is a pointer to the newly created stream file object.
5907 
5908 --*/
5909 
5910 {
5911  PFILE_OBJECT newFileObject;
5912  OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES objectAttributes;
5913  HANDLE handle;
5914  NTSTATUS status;
5915 
5916  PAGED_CODE();
5917 
5918  //
5919  // Begin by getting the device object from either the file object or
5920  // the device object parameter.
5921  //
5922 
5923  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( FileObject )) {
5924  DeviceObject = FileObject->DeviceObject;
5925  }
5926 
5927  //
5928  // Increment the reference count for the target device object. Note
5929  // that no check is made to determine whether or not the device driver
5930  // is attempting to unload since this is an implicit open of a pseudo-
5931  // file that is being made, not a real file open request. In essence,
5932  // no new file is really being opened.
5933  //
5934 
5935  IopInterlockedIncrementUlong( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock,
5936  &DeviceObject->ReferenceCount );
5937 
5938  //
5939  // Initialize the object attributes that will be used to create the file
5940  // object.
5941  //
5942 
5943  InitializeObjectAttributes( &objectAttributes,
5944  (PUNICODE_STRING) NULL,
5945  OBJ_KERNEL_HANDLE,
5946  (HANDLE) NULL,
5947  (PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR) NULL );
5948 
5949  //
5950  // Create the new file object.
5951  //
5952 
5953  status = ObCreateObject( KernelMode,
5954  IoFileObjectType,
5955  &objectAttributes,
5956  KernelMode,
5957  (PVOID) NULL,
5958  (ULONG) sizeof( FILE_OBJECT ),
5959  (ULONG) sizeof( FILE_OBJECT ),
5960  0,
5961  (PVOID *) &newFileObject );
5962 
5963  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
5964  IopDecrementDeviceObjectRef( DeviceObject, FALSE, FALSE );
5965  ExRaiseStatus( status );
5966  }
5967 
5968  //
5969  // Initialize the common fields of the file object.
5970  //
5971 
5972  RtlZeroMemory( newFileObject, sizeof( FILE_OBJECT ) );
5973  newFileObject->Type = IO_TYPE_FILE;
5974  newFileObject->Size = sizeof( FILE_OBJECT );
5975  newFileObject->DeviceObject = DeviceObject;
5976  newFileObject->Flags = FO_STREAM_FILE;
5977  KeInitializeEvent( &newFileObject->Event, SynchronizationEvent, FALSE );
5978 
5979  //
5980  // Insert the device object into the table. Note that this is done w/a
5981  // pointer bias so that the object cannot go away if some random user
5982  // application closes the handle before this code is finished w/it.
5983  //
5984 
5985  status = ObInsertObject( newFileObject,
5986  NULL,
5987  FILE_READ_DATA,
5988  1,
5989  (PVOID *) &newFileObject,
5990  &handle );
5991 
5992  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
5993  ExRaiseStatus( status );
5994  }
5995 
5996  //
5997  // The insert completed successfully. Update the bookkeeping so that the
5998  // fact that there is a handle is reflected.
5999  //
6000 
6001  newFileObject->Flags |= FO_HANDLE_CREATED;
6002  ASSERT( newFileObject->Type == IO_TYPE_FILE );
6003 
6004  //
6005  // Synchronize here with the file system to make sure that
6006  // volumes don't go away while en route to the FS.
6007  //
6008 
6009  if (DeviceObject->Vpb) {
6010  IopInterlockedIncrementUlong( LockQueueIoVpbLock,
6011  (PLONG) &DeviceObject->Vpb->ReferenceCount );
6012  }
6013 
6014  //
6015  // Finally, close the handle to the file. and clear the forward cluster
6016  //
6017 
6018  if (FileHandle == NULL) {
6019  ObCloseHandle( handle , KernelMode);
6020  } else {
6021  *FileHandle = handle;
6022 
6023  //
6024  // Get rid of the reference in ObInsertObject.
6025  //
6026 
6027  ObDereferenceObject(newFileObject);
6028  }
6029 
6030  ASSERT( NT_SUCCESS( status ) );
6031 
6032  return newFileObject;
6033 }
6034 
6035 
6036 
6037 PFILE_OBJECT
6038 IoCreateStreamFileObjectLite(
6039  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject OPTIONAL,
6040  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject OPTIONAL
6041  )
6042 
6043 /*++
6044 
6045 Routine Description:
6046 
6047  This routine is invoked to create a new file object that represents an
6048  alternate data stream for an existing file object. The input file object
6049  represents the file object that already exists for a file, and the newly
6050  created stream file object is used to access other parts of the file
6051  other than the data. Some uses of stream file objects are the EAs or
6052  the SECURITY_DESCRIPTORs on the file. The stream file object allows
6053  the file system to cache these parts of the file just as if they were
6054  an entire to themselves.
6055 
6056  It is also possible to use stream file objects to represent virtual
6057  volume files. This allows various parts of the on-disk structure to
6058  be viewed as a virtual file and therefore be cached using the same logic
6059  in the file system. For this case, the device object pointer is used
6060  to create the file object.
6061 
6062  This call differs from IoCreateStreamFileObject in that it performs no
6063  handle management and does not result in a call to the file system
6064  cleanup entry.
6065 
6066 Arguments:
6067 
6068  FileObject - Pointer to the file object to which the new stream file
6069  is related. This pointer is optional.
6070 
6071  DeviceObject - Pointer to the device object on which the stream file
6072  is to be opened. This pointer is not optional if the FileObject
6073  pointer is not specified.
6074 
6075 Return Value:
6076 
6077  The function value is a pointer to the newly created stream file object.
6078 
6079 --*/
6080 
6081 {
6082  PFILE_OBJECT newFileObject;
6083  OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES objectAttributes;
6084  NTSTATUS status;
6085 
6086  PAGED_CODE();
6087 
6088  //
6089  // Begin by getting the device object from either the file object or
6090  // the device object parameter.
6091  //
6092 
6093  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( FileObject )) {
6094  DeviceObject = FileObject->DeviceObject;
6095  }
6096 
6097  //
6098  // if the driver has been marked for an unload or deleted operation, and
6099  // the reference count goes to zero, then the driver may need to be
6100  // unloaded or deleted at this point.
6101  // file that is being made, not a real file open request. In essence,
6102  // no new file is really being opened.
6103  //
6104 
6105  IopInterlockedIncrementUlong( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock,
6106  &DeviceObject->ReferenceCount );
6107 
6108  //
6109  // Initialize the object attributes that will be used to create the file
6110  // object.
6111  //
6112 
6113  InitializeObjectAttributes( &objectAttributes,
6114  (PUNICODE_STRING) NULL,
6115  0,
6116  (HANDLE) NULL,
6117  (PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR) NULL );
6118 
6119  //
6120  // Create the new file object.
6121  //
6122 
6123  status = ObCreateObject( KernelMode,
6124  IoFileObjectType,
6125  &objectAttributes,
6126  KernelMode,
6127  (PVOID) NULL,
6128  (ULONG) sizeof( FILE_OBJECT ),
6129  (ULONG) sizeof( FILE_OBJECT ),
6130  0,
6131  (PVOID *) &newFileObject );
6132 
6133  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
6134  IopDecrementDeviceObjectRef( DeviceObject, FALSE, FALSE );
6135  ExRaiseStatus( status );
6136  }
6137 
6138  //
6139  // Initialize the common fields of the file object.
6140  //
6141 
6142  RtlZeroMemory( newFileObject, sizeof( FILE_OBJECT ) );
6143  newFileObject->Type = IO_TYPE_FILE;
6144  newFileObject->Size = sizeof( FILE_OBJECT );
6145  newFileObject->DeviceObject = DeviceObject;
6146  newFileObject->Flags = FO_STREAM_FILE;
6147  KeInitializeEvent( &newFileObject->Event, SynchronizationEvent, FALSE );
6148 
6149  //
6150  // Clean up from the creation.
6151  //
6152 
6153  ObFreeObjectCreateInfoBuffer(OBJECT_TO_OBJECT_HEADER(newFileObject)->ObjectCreateInfo);
6154  OBJECT_TO_OBJECT_HEADER(newFileObject)->ObjectCreateInfo = NULL;
6155 
6156  newFileObject->Flags |= FO_HANDLE_CREATED;
6157  ASSERT( newFileObject->Type == IO_TYPE_FILE );
6158 
6159  //
6160  // Synchronize here with the file system to make sure that
6161  // volumes don't go away while en route to the FS.
6162  //
6163 
6164  if (DeviceObject->Vpb) {
6165  IopInterlockedIncrementUlong( LockQueueIoVpbLock,
6166  (PLONG) &DeviceObject->Vpb->ReferenceCount );
6167  }
6168 
6169  return newFileObject;
6170 }

6231 PKEVENT
6232 IoCreateSynchronizationEvent(
6233  IN PUNICODE_STRING EventName,
6234  OUT PHANDLE EventHandle
6235  )
6236 
6237 /*++
6238 
6239 Routine Description:
6240 
6241  This routine creates a named synchronization event for use in serialization
6242  of access to hardware between two otherwise non-related drivers. The event
6243  is created if it does not already exist, otherwise it is simply opened.
6244 
6245 Arguments:
6246 
6247  EventName - Supplies the full name of the event.
6248 
6249  EventHandle - Supplies a location to return a handle to the event.
6250 
6251 Return Value:
6252 
6253  The function value is a pointer to the created/opened event, or NULL if
6254  the event could not be created/opened.
6255 
6256 --*/
6257 
6258 {
6259  OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES objectAttributes;
6260  NTSTATUS status;
6261  HANDLE eventHandle;
6262  PKEVENT eventObject;
6263 
6264  PAGED_CODE();
6265 
6266  //
6267  // Begin by initializing the object attributes.
6268  //
6269 
6270  InitializeObjectAttributes( &objectAttributes,
6271  EventName,
6272  OBJ_OPENIF|OBJ_KERNEL_HANDLE,
6273  (HANDLE) NULL,
6274  (PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR) NULL );
6275 
6276  //
6277  // Now create or open the event.
6278  //
6279 
6280  status = ZwCreateEvent( &eventHandle,
6281  EVENT_ALL_ACCESS,
6282  &objectAttributes,
6283  SynchronizationEvent,
6284  TRUE );
6285  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
6286  return (PKEVENT) NULL;
6287  }
6288 
6289  //
6290  // Reference the object by its handle to get a pointer that can be returned
6291  // to the caller.
6292  //
6293 
6294  (VOID) ObReferenceObjectByHandle( eventHandle,
6295  0,
6296  ExEventObjectType,
6297  KernelMode,
6298  (PVOID *) &eventObject,
6299  NULL );
6300  ObDereferenceObject( eventObject );
6301 
6302  //
6303  // Return the handle and the pointer to the event.
6304  //
6305 
6306  *EventHandle = eventHandle;
6307 
6308  return eventObject;
6309 }

6417 VOID
6418 IopRemoveTimerFromTimerList(
6419  IN PIO_TIMER timer
6420  )
6421 {
6422  KIRQL irql;
6423 
6424 #if !DBG && defined(NT_UP)
6425  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER (irql);
6426 #endif
6427 
6428  ExAcquireFastLock( &IopTimerLock, &irql );
6429  RemoveEntryList( &timer->TimerList );

6431  IopTimerCount--;
6432  }

6435 
6436 VOID
6437 IoDeleteDevice(
6438  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject
6439  )
6440 
6441 /*++
6442 
6443 Routine Description:
6444 
6445  This routine deletes the specified device object from the system so that
6446  it may no longer be referenced. It is invoked when either the device
6447  driver is being unloaded from the system, or the driver's initialization
6448  routine failed to properly initialize the device or a fatal driver
6449  initialization error was encountered, or when the device is being removed
6450  from the system.
6451 
6452 Arguments:
6453 
6454  DeviceObject - Pointer to the device object that is to be deleted.
6455 
6456 Return Value:
6457 
6458  None.
6459 
6460 --*/
6461 
6462 {
6463  KIRQL irql;
6464 
6465  IOV_DELETE_DEVICE(DeviceObject);
6466 
6467  //
6468  // Check to see whether or not the device has registered a shutdown
6469  // handler if necessary, and if so, unregister it.
6470  //
6471 
6472  if (DeviceObject->Flags & DO_SHUTDOWN_REGISTERED) {
6473  IoUnregisterShutdownNotification( DeviceObject );
6474  }
6475 
6476  //
6477  // Release the pool that was allocated to contain the timer dispatch
6478  // routine and its associated context if there was one.
6479  //
6480 
6481  if (DeviceObject->Timer) {
6482  PIO_TIMER timer;
6483 
6484  timer = DeviceObject->Timer;
6485  IopRemoveTimerFromTimerList(timer);
6486  ExFreePool( timer );
6487  }
6488 
6489  //
6490  // If this device has a name, then mark the
6491  // object as temporary so that when it is dereferenced it will be
6492  // deleted.
6493  //
6494 
6495  if (DeviceObject->Flags & DO_DEVICE_HAS_NAME) {
6496  ObMakeTemporaryObject( DeviceObject );
6497  }
6498 
6499  //
6500  // PoRunDownDeviceObject will clean up any power management
6501  // structures attached to the device object.
6502  //
6503 
6504  PoRunDownDeviceObject(DeviceObject);
6505 
6506  //
6507  // Mark the device object as deleted.
6508  //
6509 
6510  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock );
6511 
6512  DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->ExtensionFlags |= DOE_DELETE_PENDING;
6513 
6514  if (!DeviceObject->ReferenceCount) {
6515  IopCompleteUnloadOrDelete( DeviceObject, FALSE, irql );
6516  } else {
6517  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
6518  }
6519 }

6522 NTSTATUS
6523 IopDeleteSessionSymLinks(
6524  IN PUNICODE_STRING LinkName
6525  )
6526 /*++
6527 
6528 Routine Description:
6529 
6530  This routine is called from IoDeleteSymbolic Link. It enumerates all the
6531  Terminal Server session specific object directories and deletes the specified
6532  symbolic link from the DosDevices object directory of each sesssion. This
6533  routine is only called when Terminal Services is enabled.
6534 
6535 Arguments:
6536 
6537  SymbolicLinkName - Provides the Unicode name string to be deassigned.
6538 
6539 Return Values:
6540 
6541  None.
6542 
6543 --*/
6544 
6545 #define PREFIX_STRING_LENGTH (sizeof(L"\\DosDevices\\")/sizeof(WCHAR))
6546 {
6547 
6548  NTSTATUS Status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
6549  UNICODE_STRING UnicodeString;
6550  UNICODE_STRING SymbolicLinkName;
6551  OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES Attributes;
6552  HANDLE DirectoryHandle;
6553  HANDLE linkHandle;
6554  POBJECT_DIRECTORY_INFORMATION DirInfo;
6555  BOOLEAN RestartScan;
6556  ULONG Context = 0;
6557  ULONG ReturnedLength;
6558  PWCHAR NameBuf;
6559  PUCHAR DirInfoBuffer;
6560  ULONG Size;
6561  WCHAR Prefix[PREFIX_STRING_LENGTH]; // sizeof L"\\DosDevices\\"
6562 
6563 
6564 
6565  //
6566  // Only delete links that start with \DosDevices\
6567  //
6568 
6569  if (LinkName->Length < (sizeof(L"\\DosDevices\\"))){
6570  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
6571  }
6572  RtlInitUnicodeString( &UnicodeString, L"\\DosDevices\\" );
6573 
6574  wcsncpy(Prefix,LinkName->Buffer, PREFIX_STRING_LENGTH - 1);
6575  Prefix[PREFIX_STRING_LENGTH - 1] = '\0';
6576  RtlInitUnicodeString( &SymbolicLinkName, Prefix);
6577 
6578  if (RtlCompareUnicodeString(&UnicodeString, &SymbolicLinkName,TRUE)) {
6579 
6580  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
6581 
6582  }
6583 
6584 
6585  //
6586  // Open the root Sessions Directory.
6587  //
6588  RtlInitUnicodeString( &UnicodeString, L"\\Sessions" );
6589 
6590  InitializeObjectAttributes( &Attributes,
6591  &UnicodeString,
6592  OBJ_CASE_INSENSITIVE|OBJ_KERNEL_HANDLE,
6593  NULL,
6594  NULL
6595  );
6596 
6597  Status = ZwOpenDirectoryObject( &DirectoryHandle,
6598  DIRECTORY_QUERY,
6599  &Attributes
6600  );
6601  if (NT_SUCCESS( Status )) {
6602 
6603 
6604  //
6605  // Since SessionId is a ULONG , the prefix (\\Sessions\<SessionId>\\DosDevices)
6606  // cannot be more that 128 characters in length
6607  //
6608  Size = (LinkName->Length + 128) * sizeof(WCHAR);
6609  NameBuf = (PWCHAR)ExAllocatePoolWithTag(PagedPool, Size, ' oI');
6610 
6611  if (NameBuf == NULL) {
6612  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
6613  }
6614 
6615  SymbolicLinkName.Buffer = (PWSTR)NameBuf;
6616  SymbolicLinkName.Length = (USHORT)Size;
6617  SymbolicLinkName.MaximumLength = (USHORT)Size;
6618 
6619 
6620  //
6621  // 4k should be more than enough to query a directory object entry
6622  //
6623  Size = 4096;
6624  DirInfoBuffer = (PUCHAR)ExAllocatePoolWithTag(PagedPool, Size, ' oI');
6625 
6626  if (DirInfoBuffer == NULL) {
6627  ExFreePool(NameBuf);
6628  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
6629  }
6630 
6631  RestartScan = TRUE;
6632  DirInfo = (POBJECT_DIRECTORY_INFORMATION)DirInfoBuffer;
6633 
6634 
6635  while (TRUE) {
6636 
6637  Status = ZwQueryDirectoryObject( DirectoryHandle,
6638  (PVOID)DirInfo,
6639  Size,
6640  TRUE,
6641  RestartScan,
6642  &Context,
6643  &ReturnedLength
6644  );
6645 
6646  RestartScan = FALSE;
6647 
6648  //
6649  // Check the status of the operation.
6650  //
6651 
6652  if (!NT_SUCCESS( Status )) {
6653  if (Status == STATUS_NO_MORE_ENTRIES) {
6654  Status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
6655  }
6656 
6657  break;
6658  }
6659 
6660 
6661  //
6662  // This generates session specific symbolic link path
6663  // \Sessions<id>\DosDevices<LinkName>
6664  //
6665  RtlInitUnicodeString( &UnicodeString, L"\\Sessions\\" );
6666  RtlCopyUnicodeString( &SymbolicLinkName, &UnicodeString );
6667  RtlAppendUnicodeStringToString( &SymbolicLinkName, &(DirInfo->Name) );
6668  RtlAppendUnicodeStringToString( &SymbolicLinkName, LinkName );
6669  //
6670  // Begin by initializing the object attributes for the symbolic link.
6671  //
6672 
6673  InitializeObjectAttributes( &Attributes,
6674  &SymbolicLinkName,
6675  OBJ_CASE_INSENSITIVE|OBJ_KERNEL_HANDLE,
6676  NULL,
6677  NULL );
6678 
6679  //
6680  // Open the symbolic link itself so that it can be marked temporary and
6681  // closed.
6682  //
6683 
6684  Status = ZwOpenSymbolicLinkObject( &linkHandle,
6685  DELETE,
6686  &Attributes );
6687  if (NT_SUCCESS( Status )) {
6688 
6689  //
6690  // The symbolic link was successfully opened. Attempt to make it a
6691  // temporary object, and then close the handle. This will cause the
6692  // object to go away.
6693  //
6694 
6695  Status = ZwMakeTemporaryObject( linkHandle );
6696  if (NT_SUCCESS( Status )) {
6697  ZwClose( linkHandle );
6698  }
6699  }
6700 
6701 
6702 
6703  }
6704 
6705  ZwClose(DirectoryHandle);
6706  ExFreePool(NameBuf);
6707  ExFreePool(DirInfoBuffer);
6708  }
6709 
6710  return Status;
6711 }
6712 
6713 
6714 NTSTATUS
6715 IoDeleteSymbolicLink(
6716  IN PUNICODE_STRING SymbolicLinkName
6717  )
6718 
6719 /*++
6720 
6721 Routine Description:
6722 
6723  This routine is invoked to remove a symbolic link from the system. This
6724  generally occurs whenever a driver that has assigned a symbolic link needs
6725  to exit. It can also be used when a driver no longer needs to redirect
6726  a name.
6727 
6728 Arguments:
6729 
6730  SymbolicLinkName - Provides the Unicode name string to be deassigned.
6731 
6732 Return Values:
6733 
6734  None.
6735 
6736 --*/
6737 
6738 {
6739  OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES objectAttributes;
6740  HANDLE linkHandle;
6741  NTSTATUS status;
6742 
6743  PAGED_CODE();
6744 
6745  //
6746  // Begin by initializing the object attributes for the symbolic link.
6747  //
6748 
6749  InitializeObjectAttributes( &objectAttributes,
6750  SymbolicLinkName,
6751  OBJ_CASE_INSENSITIVE|OBJ_KERNEL_HANDLE,
6752  (HANDLE) NULL,
6753  (PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR) NULL );
6754 
6755  //
6756  // Open the symbolic link itself so that it can be marked temporary and
6757  // closed.
6758  //
6759 
6760  status = ZwOpenSymbolicLinkObject( &linkHandle,
6761  DELETE,
6762  &objectAttributes );
6763  if (NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
6764 
6765  //
6766  // The symbolic link was successfully opened. Attempt to make it a
6767  // temporary object, and then close the handle. This will cause the
6768  // object to go away.
6769  //
6770 
6771  status = ZwMakeTemporaryObject( linkHandle );
6772  if (NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
6773  ZwClose( linkHandle );
6774  }
6775 
6776  //
6777  // When LUID DosDevices are disabled and Terminal Services are
6778  // enabled, then remove the possible multiple copies of the symbolic
6779  // link from the DosDevices in the TS sessions
6780  // When LUID DosDevices are enabled or TS is not enabled, then
6781  // the symbolic link is not copied and no cleanup is needed.
6782  //
6783 
6784  if ((ObIsLUIDDeviceMapsEnabled() == 0) &&
6785  (ExVerifySuite(TerminalServer) == TRUE)) {
6786 
6787  IopDeleteSessionSymLinks( SymbolicLinkName );
6788  }
6789  }
6790 
6791 
6792  return status;
6793 }

6795 VOID
6796 IoDetachDevice(
6797  IN OUT PDEVICE_OBJECT TargetDevice
6798  )
6799 
6800 /*++
6801 
6802 Routine Description:
6803 
6804  This routine detaches the device object which is currently attached to the
6805  target device.
6806 
6807 Arguments:
6808 
6809  TargetDevice - Pointer to device object to be detached from.
6810 
6811 Return Value:
6812 
6813  None.
6814 
6815 
6816 --*/
6817 
6818 {
6819  KIRQL irql;
6820  PDEVICE_OBJECT detachingDevice;
6821  PDEVOBJ_EXTENSION detachingExtension;
6822 
6823  //
6824  // Detach the device object attached to the target device. This also
6825  // includes decrementing the reference count for the device. Note that
6826  // if the driver has been marked for an unload operation, and the
6827  // reference count goes to zero, then the driver may need to be unloaded
6828  // at this point.
6829  //
6830 
6831  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock );
6832 
6833  //
6834  // Tell the Special IRP code the stack has changed. Code that will reexamine
6835  // the stack takes the database lock, so we can place the call here. This
6836  // also allows us to assert correct behavior *before* the stack is torn
6837  // down.
6838  //
6839  IOV_DETACH_DEVICE(TargetDevice);
6840 
6841  detachingDevice = TargetDevice->AttachedDevice;
6842  detachingExtension = detachingDevice->DeviceObjectExtension;
6843  ASSERT( detachingExtension->AttachedTo == TargetDevice );
6844 
6845  //
6846  // Unlink the device from the doubly-linked attachment chain.
6847  //
6848 
6849  detachingExtension->AttachedTo = NULL;
6850  TargetDevice->AttachedDevice = NULL;
6851 
6852  if (TargetDevice->DeviceObjectExtension->ExtensionFlags &
6853  (DOE_UNLOAD_PENDING | DOE_DELETE_PENDING | DOE_REMOVE_PENDING) &&
6854  !TargetDevice->ReferenceCount) {
6855  IopCompleteUnloadOrDelete( TargetDevice, FALSE, irql );
6856  } else {
6857  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
6858  }
6859 }
6860 
6861 VOID
6862 IoDisconnectInterrupt(
6863  IN PKINTERRUPT InterruptObject
6864  )
6865 
6866 /*++
6867 
6868 Routine Description:
6869 
6870  This routine disconnects all of the interrupt objects that were
6871  initialized and connected by the IoConnectInterrupt routine. Note
6872  that no interrupt objects directly connected using the kernel
6873  services may be input to this routine.
6874 
6875 Arguments:
6876 
6877  InterruptObject - Supplies a pointer to the interrupt object allocated
6878  by the IoConnectInterrupt routine.
6879 
6880 Return Value:
6881 
6882  None.
6883 
6884 --*/
6885 
6886 {
6887  PIO_INTERRUPT_STRUCTURE interruptStructure;
6888  ULONG i;
6889 
6890  PAGED_CODE();
6891 
6892  //
6893  // Obtain a pointer to the builtin interrupt object in the I/O interrupt
6894  // structure.
6895  //
6896 
6897  interruptStructure = CONTAINING_RECORD( InterruptObject,
6898  IO_INTERRUPT_STRUCTURE,
6899  InterruptObject );
6900 
6901  //
6902  // The builtin interrupt object is always used, so simply disconnect
6903  // it.
6904  //
6905 
6906  KeDisconnectInterrupt( &interruptStructure->InterruptObject );
6907 
6908  //
6909  // Now loop through each of the interrupt objects pointed to by the
6910  // structure and disconnect each.
6911  //
6912 
6913  for (i = 0; i < MAXIMUM_PROCESSORS; i++) {
6914  if (interruptStructure->InterruptArray[i] != NULL) {
6915  KeDisconnectInterrupt( interruptStructure->InterruptArray[i] );
6916  }
6917  }
6918 
6919  //
6920  // Finally, deallocate the memory associated with the entire structure.
6921  //
6922 
6923  ExFreePool( interruptStructure );
6924 }
6925 
6926 VOID
6927 IoEnqueueIrp(
6928  IN PIRP Irp
6929  )
6930 
6931 /*++

6935  This routine enqueues the specified I/O Request Packet (IRP) to the thread's
6936  IRP pending queue. The thread that the IRP is queued to is specified by
6937  the IRP's Thread field.
6938 
6939 Arguments:
6940 
6941  Irp - Supplies a pointer to the IRP to be enqueued.
6942 
6943 Return Value:
6944 
6945  None.
6946 
6947 --*/
6948 
6949 {
6950  PAGED_CODE();
6951 
6952  //
6953  // Simply enqueue the IRP to the thread's IRP queue.
6954  //
6955 
6956  IopQueueThreadIrp( Irp );
6957  return;
6958 }
6959 
6960 BOOLEAN
6961 IoFastQueryNetworkAttributes(
6962  IN POBJECT_ATTRIBUTES ObjectAttributes,
6963  IN ACCESS_MASK DesiredAccess,
6964  IN ULONG OpenOptions,
6965  OUT PIO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatus,
6966  OUT PFILE_NETWORK_OPEN_INFORMATION Buffer
6967  )
6968 
6969 /*++
6970 
6971 Routine Description:
6972 
6973  This routine attempts to perform a fast I/O call to obtain the network
6974  attributes for a file. This involves a specialized interface between
6975  this function and the I/O system's device parse method. This allows the
6976  parse method to have the file system pseudo-open the file, obtain the
6977  appropriate attributes for the file, and return them to the caller w/as
6978  little overhead as possible from either the Object Manager or the I/O
6979  system itself.
6980 
6981 Arguments:
6982 
6983  ObjectAttributes - Supplies the attributes to be used for opening the
6984  file (e.g., the file's name, etc).
6985 
6986  DesiredAccess - Supplies the type(s) of access that the caller would like
6987  to the file.
6988 
6989  OpenOptions - Supplies standard NtOpenFile open options.
6990 
6991  IoStatus - Supplies a pointer to a variable to receive the final status
6992  of the operation.
6993 
6994  Buffer - Supplies an output buffer to receive the network attributes for
6995  the specified file.
6996 
6997 Return Value:
6998 
6999  The final function value indicates whether or not the fast path could
7000  be taken successfully.
7001 
7002 --*/
7003 
7004 {
7005  HANDLE handle;
7006  NTSTATUS status;
7007  OPEN_PACKET openPacket;
7008  DUMMY_FILE_OBJECT localFileObject;
7009 
7010  //
7011  // Build a parse open packet that tells the parse method to open the
7012  // file and query its network attributes using the fast path, if it
7013  // exists for this file.
7014  //
7015 
7016  RtlZeroMemory( &openPacket, sizeof( OPEN_PACKET ) );
7017 
7018  openPacket.Type = IO_TYPE_OPEN_PACKET;
7019  openPacket.Size = sizeof( OPEN_PACKET );
7020  openPacket.ShareAccess = FILE_SHARE_READ | FILE_SHARE_WRITE | FILE_SHARE_DELETE;
7021  openPacket.Disposition = FILE_OPEN;
7022  openPacket.CreateOptions = OpenOptions | FILE_OPEN_REPARSE_POINT;
7023  openPacket.Options = IO_FORCE_ACCESS_CHECK;
7024  openPacket.NetworkInformation = Buffer;
7025  openPacket.QueryOnly = TRUE;
7026  openPacket.FullAttributes = TRUE;
7027  openPacket.LocalFileObject = &localFileObject;
7028 
7029  //
7030  // Open the object by its name. Because of the special QueryOnly flag set
7031  // in the open packet, the parse routine will open the file using the fast
7032  // path open and perform the query, effectively closing it as well.
7033  //
7034 
7035  status = ObOpenObjectByName( ObjectAttributes,
7036  (POBJECT_TYPE) NULL,
7037  KernelMode,
7038  NULL,
7039  DesiredAccess,
7040  &openPacket,
7041  &handle );
7042 
7043  //
7044  // The operation is successful if the parse check field of the open packet
7045  // indicates that the parse routine was actually invoked, and the final
7046  // status field of the packet is set to success. The QueryOnly field is
7047  // set to whether or not the fast path was invoked.
7048  //
7049 
7050  if (openPacket.ParseCheck != OPEN_PACKET_PATTERN) {
7051 
7052  //
7053  // The parse routine was not invoked properly so the operation did
7054  // not work at all.
7055  //
7056 
7057  if (NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
7058  ZwClose(handle);
7059  status = STATUS_OBJECT_TYPE_MISMATCH;
7060  }
7061 
7062  IoStatus->Status = status;
7063  } else {
7064 
7065  //
7066  // The fast path routine was successfully invoked so return the
7067  // final status of the operation.
7068  //
7069 
7070  IoStatus->Status = openPacket.FinalStatus;
7071  IoStatus->Information = openPacket.Information;
7072  }
7073  return TRUE;
7074 }
7075 
7076 VOID
7077 IoFreeController(
7078  IN PCONTROLLER_OBJECT ControllerObject
7079  )
7080 
7081 /*++
7082 
7083 Routine Description:
7084 
7085  This routine is invoked to deallocate the specified controller object.
7086  No checks are made to ensure that the controller is really allocated
7087  to a device object. However, if it is not, then kernel will bugcheck.
7088 
7089  If another device is waiting in the queue to allocate the controller
7090  object it will be pulled from the queue and its execution routine will
7091  be invoked.
7092 
7093 Arguments:
7094 
7095  ControllerObject - Pointer to the controller object to be deallocated.
7096 
7097 Return Value:
7098 
7099  None.
7100 
7101 --*/
7102 
7103 {
7104  PKDEVICE_QUEUE_ENTRY packet;
7105  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
7106  IO_ALLOCATION_ACTION action;
7107 
7108  //
7109  // Simply remove the next entry from the controller's device wait queue.
7110  // If one was successfully removed, invoke its execution routine.
7111  //
7112 
7113  packet = KeRemoveDeviceQueue( &ControllerObject->DeviceWaitQueue );
7114  if (packet != NULL) {
7115  deviceObject = CONTAINING_RECORD( packet,
7116  DEVICE_OBJECT,
7117  Queue.Wcb.WaitQueueEntry );
7118  action = deviceObject->Queue.Wcb.DeviceRoutine( deviceObject,
7119  deviceObject->CurrentIrp,
7120  0,
7121  deviceObject->Queue.Wcb.DeviceContext );
7122 
7123  //
7124  // If the execution routine wants the controller to be deallocate
7125  // now, deallocate it.
7126  //
7127 
7128  if (action == DeallocateObject) {
7129  IoFreeController( ControllerObject );
7130  }
7131  }
7132 }

7141 
7142 
7143 VOID
7144 IopFreeIrp(
7145  IN PIRP Irp
7146  )
7147 
7148 /*++
7149 
7150 Routine Description:
7151 
7152  This routine deallocates the specified I/O Request Packet.
7153 
7154 Arguments:
7155 
7156  Irp - I/O Request Packet to deallocate.
7157 
7158 Return Value:
7159 
7160  None.
7161 
7162 --*/
7163 
7164 {
7165  PGENERAL_LOOKASIDE lookasideList;
7166  PP_NPAGED_LOOKASIDE_NUMBER number;
7167  PKPRCB prcb;
7168 
7169  //
7170  // Ensure that the data structure being freed is really an IRP.
7171  //
7172 
7173  ASSERT( Irp->Type == IO_TYPE_IRP );
7174 
7175  if (Irp->Type != IO_TYPE_IRP) {
7176  KeBugCheckEx( MULTIPLE_IRP_COMPLETE_REQUESTS, (ULONG_PTR) Irp, __LINE__, 0, 0 );
7177  }
7178 
7179 
7180  ASSERT(IsListEmpty(&(Irp)->ThreadListEntry));
7181  Irp->Type = 0;
7182 
7183  //
7184  // Ensure that all of the owners of the IRP have at least been notified
7185  // that the request is going away.
7186  //
7187 
7188  ASSERT( Irp->CurrentLocation >= Irp->StackCount );
7189 
7190  //
7191  // Deallocate the IRP.
7192  //
7193 
7194  prcb = KeGetCurrentPrcb();
7195  if (Irp->AllocationFlags & IRP_LOOKASIDE_ALLOCATION) {
7196  Irp->AllocationFlags ^= IRP_LOOKASIDE_ALLOCATION;
7197  InterlockedIncrement( &prcb->LookasideIrpFloat );
7198  }
7199 
7200  if (!(Irp->AllocationFlags & IRP_ALLOCATED_FIXED_SIZE) ||
7201  (Irp->AllocationFlags & IRP_ALLOCATED_MUST_SUCCEED)) {
7202  ExFreePool( Irp );
7203 
7204  } else {
7205 
7206  if (IopIrpAutoSizingEnabled() &&
7207  (Irp->Size != IoSizeOfIrp(IopLargeIrpStackLocations)) &&
7208  (Irp->Size != IoSizeOfIrp(1))) {
7209 
7210  ExFreePool( Irp );
7211  return;
7212  }
7213 
7214  //
7215  // Store the size in a different field as this will get overwritten by single list entry.
7216  //
7217 
7218  Irp->IoStatus.Information = Irp->Size;
7219 
7220  number = LookasideSmallIrpList;
7221  if (Irp->StackCount != 1) {
7222  number = LookasideLargeIrpList;
7223  }
7224 
7225  lookasideList = prcb->PPLookasideList[number].P;
7226  lookasideList->TotalFrees += 1;
7227  if (ExQueryDepthSList( &lookasideList->ListHead ) >= lookasideList->Depth) {
7228  lookasideList->FreeMisses += 1;
7229  lookasideList = prcb->PPLookasideList[number].L;
7230  lookasideList->TotalFrees += 1;
7231  if (ExQueryDepthSList( &lookasideList->ListHead ) >= lookasideList->Depth) {
7232  lookasideList->FreeMisses += 1;
7233  ExFreePool( Irp );
7234 
7235  } else {
7236  if (Irp->AllocationFlags & IRP_QUOTA_CHARGED) {
7237  Irp->AllocationFlags ^= IRP_QUOTA_CHARGED;
7238  ExReturnPoolQuota( Irp );
7239  }
7240 
7241  InterlockedPushEntrySList( &lookasideList->ListHead,
7242  (PSLIST_ENTRY) Irp );
7243  }
7244 
7245  } else {
7246  if (Irp->AllocationFlags & IRP_QUOTA_CHARGED) {
7247  Irp->AllocationFlags ^= IRP_QUOTA_CHARGED;
7248  ExReturnPoolQuota( Irp );
7249  }
7250 
7251  InterlockedPushEntrySList( &lookasideList->ListHead,
7252  (PSLIST_ENTRY) Irp );
7253  }
7254  }
7255 
7256  return;
7257 }
7258 
7259 VOID
7260 IoFreeMdl(
7261  IN PMDL Mdl
7262  )
7263 
7264 /*++
7265 
7266 Routine Description:
7267 
7268  This routine frees a Memory Descriptor List (MDL). It only frees the
7269  specified MDL; any chained MDLs must be freed explicitly through another
7270  call to this routine.
7271 
7272 Arguments:
7273 
7274  Mdl - Pointer to the Memory Descriptor List to be freed.
7275 
7276 Return Value:
7277 
7278  None.
7279 
7280 --*/
7281 
7282 {
7283 
7284  //
7285  // Tell memory management that this MDL will be re-used. This will
7286  // cause MM to unmap any pages that have been mapped for this MDL if
7287  // it is a partial MDL.
7288  //
7289 
7290  MmPrepareMdlForReuse(Mdl);
7291  if (((Mdl->MdlFlags & MDL_ALLOCATED_FIXED_SIZE) == 0) ||
7292  ((Mdl->MdlFlags & MDL_ALLOCATED_MUST_SUCCEED) != 0)) {
7293  ExFreePool(Mdl);
7294 
7295  } else {
7296  ExFreeToPPLookasideList(LookasideMdlList, Mdl);
7297  }
7298 }
7299 
7300 PDEVICE_OBJECT
7301 IoGetAttachedDevice(
7302  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject
7303  )
7304 
7305 /*++
7306 
7307 Routine Description:
7308 
7309  This routine returns the highest level device object associated with
7310  the specified device.
7311 
7312  N.B. Caller must own the IopDatabaseLock. External callers of this
7313  function must ensure nobody is attaching or detaching from the stack.
7314  If they cannot, they *must* use IoGetAttachedDeviceReference.
7315 
7316 Arguments:
7317 
7318  DeviceObject - Supplies a pointer to the device for which the attached
7319  device is to be returned.
7320 
7321 Return Value:
7322 
7323  The function value is the highest level device attached to the specified
7324  device. If no devices are attached, then the pointer to the device
7325  object itself is returned.
7326 
7327 --*/
7328 
7329 {
7330  //
7331  // Loop through all of the device object's attached to the specified
7332  // device. When the last device object is found that is not attached
7333  // to, return it.
7334  //
7335 
7336  while (DeviceObject->AttachedDevice) {
7337  DeviceObject = DeviceObject->AttachedDevice;
7338  }
7339 
7340  return DeviceObject;
7341 }
7342 
7343 PDEVICE_OBJECT
7344 IoGetAttachedDeviceReference(
7345  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject
7346  )
7347 /*++
7348 
7349 Routine Description:
7350 
7351  This routine synchronizes with the Io database and returns a reference
7352  to the highest level device object associated with the specified device.
7353 
7354 Arguments:
7355 
7356  DeviceObject - Supplies a pointer to the device for which the attached
7357  device is to be returned.
7358 
7359 Return Value:
7360 
7361  The function value is a reference to the highest level device attached
7362  to the specified device. If no devices are attached, then the pointer
7363  to the device object itself is returned.
7364 
7365 --*/
7366 {
7367  KIRQL irql;
7368 
7369  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock );
7370  DeviceObject = IoGetAttachedDevice (DeviceObject);
7371  ObReferenceObject (DeviceObject);
7372  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
7373  return DeviceObject;
7374 }
7375 
7376 PDEVICE_OBJECT
7377 IoGetBaseFileSystemDeviceObject(
7378  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject
7379  )
7380 
7381 /*++
7382 
7383 Routine Description:
7384 
7385  This routine returns the base (lowest-level) file system volume device
7386  object associated with a file. I.e., it locates the file system w/o
7387  walking the attached device object list.
7388 
7389 Arguments:
7390 
7391  FileObject - Supplies a pointer to the file object for which the base
7392  file system device object is to be returned.
7393 
7394 Return Value:
7395 
7396  The function value is the lowest level volume device object associated
7397  w/the file.
7398 
7399 --*/
7400 
7401 {
7402  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
7403 
7404  //
7405  // If the file object has a mounted Vpb, use its DeviceObject.
7406  //
7407 
7408  if (FileObject->Vpb != NULL && FileObject->Vpb->DeviceObject != NULL) {
7409  deviceObject = FileObject->Vpb->DeviceObject;
7410 
7411  //
7412  // Otherwise, if the real device has a VPB that indicates that it is
7413  // mounted, then use the file system device object associated with the
7414  // VPB.
7415  //
7416 
7417  } else if (!(FileObject->Flags & FO_DIRECT_DEVICE_OPEN) &&
7418  FileObject->DeviceObject->Vpb != NULL &&
7419  FileObject->DeviceObject->Vpb->DeviceObject != NULL) {
7420 
7421  deviceObject = FileObject->DeviceObject->Vpb->DeviceObject;
7422 
7423  //
7424  // Otherwise, just return the real device object.
7425  //
7426 
7427  } else {
7428 
7429  deviceObject = FileObject->DeviceObject;
7430  }
7431 
7432  ASSERT( deviceObject != NULL );
7433 
7434  //
7435  // Simply return the resultant file object.
7436  //
7437 
7438  return deviceObject;
7439 }

7512 NTSTATUS
7513 IoGetDeviceObjectPointer(
7514  IN PUNICODE_STRING ObjectName,
7515  IN ACCESS_MASK DesiredAccess,
7516  OUT PFILE_OBJECT *FileObject,
7517  OUT PDEVICE_OBJECT *DeviceObject
7518  )
7519 
7520 /*++
7521 
7522 Routine Description:
7523 
7524  This routine returns a pointer to the device object specified by the
7525  object name. It also returns a pointer to the referenced file object
7526  that has been opened to the device that ensures that the device cannot
7527  go away.
7528 
7529  To close access to the device, the caller should dereference the file
7530  object pointer.
7531 
7532 Arguments:
7533 
7534  ObjectName - Name of the device object for which a pointer is to be
7535  returned.
7536 
7537  DesiredAccess - Access desired to the target device object.
7538 
7539  FileObject - Supplies the address of a variable to receive a pointer
7540  to the file object for the device.
7541 
7542  DeviceObject - Supplies the address of a variable to receive a pointer
7543  to the device object for the specified device.
7544 
7545 Return Value:
7546 
7547  The function value is a referenced pointer to the specified device
7548  object, if the device exists. Otherwise, NULL is returned.
7549 
7550 --*/
7551 
7552 {
7553  PFILE_OBJECT fileObject;
7554  OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES objectAttributes;
7555  HANDLE fileHandle;
7556  IO_STATUS_BLOCK ioStatus;
7557  NTSTATUS status;
7558 
7559  PAGED_CODE();
7560 
7561  //
7562  // Initialize the object attributes to open the device.
7563  //
7564 
7565  InitializeObjectAttributes( &objectAttributes,
7566  ObjectName,
7567  OBJ_KERNEL_HANDLE,
7568  (HANDLE) NULL,
7569  (PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR) NULL );
7570 
7571  status = ZwOpenFile( &fileHandle,
7572  DesiredAccess,
7573  &objectAttributes,
7574  &ioStatus,
7575  0,
7576  FILE_NON_DIRECTORY_FILE );
7577 
7578  if (NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
7579 
7580  //
7581  // The open operation was successful. Dereference the file handle
7582  // and obtain a pointer to the device object for the handle.
7583  //
7584 
7585  status = ObReferenceObjectByHandle( fileHandle,
7586  0,
7587  IoFileObjectType,
7588  KernelMode,
7589  (PVOID *) &fileObject,
7590  NULL );
7591  if (NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
7592 
7593  *FileObject = fileObject;
7594 
7595  //
7596  // Get a pointer to the device object for this file.
7597  //
7598  *DeviceObject = IoGetRelatedDeviceObject( fileObject );
7599  }
7600 
7601  (VOID) ZwClose( fileHandle );
7602  }
7603 
7604  return status;
7605 }

7644 NTKERNELAPI
7645 PVOID
7646 IoGetDriverObjectExtension(
7647  IN PDRIVER_OBJECT DriverObject,
7648  IN PVOID ClientIdentificationAddress
7649  )
7650 /*++
7651 
7652 Routine Description:
7653 
7654  This routine returns a pointer to the client driver object extension.
7655  This extension was allocated using IoAllocateDriverObjectExtension. If
7656  an extension with the create Id does not exist for the specified driver
7657  object then NULL is returned.
7658 
7659 Arguments:
7660 
7661  DriverObject - Pointer to driver object owning the extension.
7662 
7663  ClientIdentificationAddress - Supplies the unique identifier which was
7664  used to create the extension.
7665 
7666 Return Value:
7667 
7668  The function value is a pointer to the client driver object extension,
7669  or NULL.
7670 
7671 --*/
7672 
7673 {
7674  KIRQL irql;
7675  PIO_CLIENT_EXTENSION extension;
7676 
7677  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock );
7678  extension = DriverObject->DriverExtension->ClientDriverExtension;
7679  while (extension != NULL) {
7680 
7681  if (extension->ClientIdentificationAddress == ClientIdentificationAddress) {
7682  break;
7683  }
7684 
7685  extension = extension->NextExtension;
7686  }
7687 
7688  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
7689 
7690  if (extension == NULL) {
7691  return NULL;
7692  }
7693 
7694  return extension + 1;
7695 }

7697 PGENERIC_MAPPING
7698 IoGetFileObjectGenericMapping(
7699  VOID
7700  )
7701 
7702 /*++
7703 
7704 Routine Description:
7705 
7706  This routine returns a pointer to the generic mapping for a file object.
7707 
7708 Arguments:
7709 
7710  None.
7711 
7712 Return Value:
7713 
7714  A pointer to the generic mapping for a file object.
7715 
7716 --*/
7717 
7718 {
7719  PAGED_CODE()
7720 
7721  //
7722  // Simply return a pointer to the generic mapping for a file object.
7723  //
7724 
7725  return (PGENERIC_MAPPING)&IopFileMapping;
7726 }

7762 
7763 VOID
7764 IoGetStackLimits (
7765  OUT PULONG_PTR LowLimit,
7766  OUT PULONG_PTR HighLimit
7767  )
7768 /*++
7769 
7770 Routine Description:
7771 
7772  This routine returns the low/high limits of the stack currently used.
7773  This can be a thread stack or a DPC stack depending on the execution
7774  context.
7775 
7776 Arguments:
7777 
7778  LowLimit - address to write low address of the stack region currently used.
7779 
7780  HighLimit - address to write high address of the stack region currently used.
7781 
7782 Return Value:
7783 
7784  None. For any kind of error both LowLimit and HighLimit will be zeroed.
7785  For example this will happen if the driver illegally switched to a
7786  different stack.
7787 
7788 Note:
7789 
7790  This function cannot be made a macro, since fields in the thread object
7791  move from release to release, so this must remain a full function.
7792 
7793 --*/
7794 {
7795  volatile ULONG_PTR StackAddress;
7796 
7797  //
7798  // The local variable is marked volatile so that the compiler
7799  // will not get any ideas to optimize its use. We really need this
7800  // to be stack based so that its address is within current stack
7801  // limits.
7802  //
7803 
7804  StackAddress = (ULONG_PTR)(&StackAddress);
7805 
7806  //
7807  // Get the stack associated with current thread. This call is not
7808  // aware of DPCs. It will just read stack limits from current thread
7809  // control block.
7810  //
7811 
7812  RtlpGetStackLimits (LowLimit, HighLimit);
7813 
7814  //
7815  // Check if address of a local variable is within stack limits.
7816  // If not then this could be a DPC stack.
7817  //
7818 
7819  if ((StackAddress < *LowLimit) || (StackAddress > *HighLimit)) {
7820 
7821  //
7822  // It would be nice to null the limits to be returned.
7823  // This would signal error for stacks switched without kernel's
7824  // knowledge. However there are drivers switching stacks like this
7825  // and they get confused by the zeroed limits. Therefore we do not
7826  // do it.
7827  //
7828 
7829  if (KeGetCurrentIrql() >= DISPATCH_LEVEL) {
7830 
7831  PKPRCB Prcb = KeGetCurrentPrcb();
7832  ULONG_PTR DpcStack = (ULONG_PTR)(Prcb->DpcStack);
7833 
7834  if ((Prcb->DpcRoutineActive) &&
7835  (StackAddress <= DpcStack) &&
7836  (StackAddress >= DpcStack - KERNEL_STACK_SIZE)) {
7837 
7838  *HighLimit = DpcStack;
7839  *LowLimit = DpcStack - KERNEL_STACK_SIZE;
7840  }
7841  }
7842  }
7843 }
7844 
7845 
7846 NTSTATUS
7847 IoComputeDesiredAccessFileObject(
7848  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
7849  OUT PNTSTATUS DesiredAccess
7850  )
7851 
7852 /*++
7853 
7854 Routine Description
7855 
7856  This routine is called by ObReferenceFileObjectForWrite (from NtWriteFile)
7857  to determine which access is desired for the passed file object. The desired
7858  access differs if the FileObject is a file or a pipe.
7859 
7860 Arguments
7861 
7862  FileObject - the file object to access
7863 
7864  DesiredAccess - the computed access for the object
7865 
7866 Return Value
7867 
7868  STATUS_OBJECT_TYPE_MISMATCH if the object is not of type IoFileObjectType
7869  STATUS_SUCCESS if successful
7870 
7871 --*/
7872 
7873 {
7874  POBJECT_HEADER ObjectHeader = NULL;
7875  NTSTATUS Status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
7876 
7877  *DesiredAccess = 0;
7878  ObjectHeader = OBJECT_TO_OBJECT_HEADER(FileObject);
7879 
7880  if (ObjectHeader->Type == IoFileObjectType) {
7881 
7882  *DesiredAccess = (!(FileObject->Flags & FO_NAMED_PIPE) ? FILE_APPEND_DATA : 0) | FILE_WRITE_DATA;
7883  Status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
7884 
7885  } else {
7886 
7887  Status = STATUS_OBJECT_TYPE_MISMATCH;
7888  }
7889 
7890  return Status;
7891 }
7892 
7893 
7894 PDEVICE_OBJECT
7895 IoGetRelatedDeviceObject(
7896  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject
7897  )
7898 
7899 /*++
7900 
7901 Routine Description:
7902 
7903  This routine returns a pointer to the actual device object than an I/O
7904  Request Packet (IRP) should be given to based on the specified file
7905  object.
7906 
7907  N.B. - Callers of this function must ensure no device object is
7908  attaching or detaching from this stack for the duration of this call.
7909  This is because the database lock is *not* held!
7910 
7911 Arguments:
7912 
7913  FileObject - Pointer to the file object representing the open file.
7914 
7915 Return Value:
7916 
7917  The return value is a pointer to the device object for the driver to
7918  whom the request is to be given.
7919 
7920 --*/
7921 
7922 {
7923  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
7924 
7925  //
7926  // If the file object was taken out against the mounted file system, it
7927  // will have a Vpb. Traverse it to get to the DeviceObject. Note that in
7928  // this case we should never follow FileObject->DeviceObject, as that
7929  // mapping may be invalid after a forced dismount.
7930  //
7931 
7932  if (FileObject->Vpb != NULL && FileObject->Vpb->DeviceObject != NULL) {
7933 
7934  ASSERT(!(FileObject->Flags & FO_DIRECT_DEVICE_OPEN));
7935  deviceObject = FileObject->Vpb->DeviceObject;
7936 
7937 
7938  //
7939  // If a driver opened a disk device using direct device open and
7940  // later on it uses IoGetRelatedTargetDeviceObject to find the
7941  // device object it wants to send an IRP then it should not get the
7942  // filesystem device object. This is so that if the device object is in the
7943  // process of being mounted then vpb is not stable.
7944  //
7945 
7946  } else if (!(FileObject->Flags & FO_DIRECT_DEVICE_OPEN) &&
7947  FileObject->DeviceObject->Vpb != NULL &&
7948  FileObject->DeviceObject->Vpb->DeviceObject != NULL) {
7949 
7950  deviceObject = FileObject->DeviceObject->Vpb->DeviceObject;
7951 
7952  //
7953  // This is a direct open against the device stack (and there is no mounted
7954  // file system to strain the IRPs through).
7955  //
7956 
7957  } else {
7958 
7959  deviceObject = FileObject->DeviceObject;
7960  }
7961 
7962  ASSERT( deviceObject != NULL );
7963 
7964  //
7965  // Check to see whether or not the device has any associated devices.
7966  // If so, return the highest level device; otherwise, return a pointer
7967  // to the device object itself.
7968  //
7969 
7970  if (deviceObject->AttachedDevice != NULL) {
7971  if (FileObject->Flags & FO_FILE_OBJECT_HAS_EXTENSION) {
7972 
7973  PIOP_FILE_OBJECT_EXTENSION fileObjectExtension =
7974  (PIOP_FILE_OBJECT_EXTENSION)(FileObject + 1);
7975 
7976  ASSERT(!(FileObject->Flags & FO_DIRECT_DEVICE_OPEN));
7977 
7978  if (fileObjectExtension->TopDeviceObjectHint != NULL &&
7979  IopVerifyDeviceObjectOnStack(deviceObject, fileObjectExtension->TopDeviceObjectHint)) {
7980  return fileObjectExtension->TopDeviceObjectHint;
7981  }
7982  }
7983  deviceObject = IoGetAttachedDevice( deviceObject );
7984  }
7985 
7986  return deviceObject;
7987 }
7988 
7989 ULONG
7990 IoGetRequestorProcessId(
7991  IN PIRP Irp
7992  )
7993 
7994 /*++
7995 
7996 Routine Description:
7997 
7998  This routine returns a 32-bit value that is unique to the process that
7999  originally requested the specified I/O operation.
8000 
8001 Arguments:
8002 
8003  Irp - Pointer to the I/O Request Packet.
8004 
8005 Return Value:
8006 
8007  The function value is the 32-bit process ID.
8008 
8009 
8010 --*/
8011 
8012 {
8013  PEPROCESS process;
8014 
8015  process = IoGetRequestorProcess( Irp );
8016  if (process != NULL) {
8017 
8018  //
8019  // UniqueProcessId is a kernel-mode handle, safe to truncate to ULONG.
8020  //
8021 
8022  return HandleToUlong( process->UniqueProcessId );
8023  } else {
8024 
8025  //
8026  // Return a PID of zero if there is no process associated with the IRP.
8027  //
8028 
8029  return 0;
8030  }
8031 }
8032 
8033 PEPROCESS
8034 IoGetRequestorProcess(
8035  IN PIRP Irp
8036  )
8037 
8038 /*++
8039 
8040 Routine Description:
8041 
8042  This routine returns a pointer to the process that originally
8043  requested the specified I/O operation.
8044 
8045 Arguments:
8046 
8047  Irp - Pointer to the I/O Request Packet.
8048 
8049 Return Value:
8050 
8051  The function value is a pointer to the original requesting process.
8052 
8053 
8054 --*/
8055 
8056 {
8057  //
8058  // Return the address of the process that requested the I/O operation.
8059  //
8060 
8061  PETHREAD thread = Irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread;
8062  if (thread) {
8063 
8064  //
8065  // The thread was not attached when the IRP was issued. So get
8066  // the original process. Note that this API could be called from
8067  // another process or thread.
8068  //
8069 
8070  if (Irp->ApcEnvironment == OriginalApcEnvironment) {
8071  return (THREAD_TO_PROCESS(thread));
8072 
8073  //
8074  // The thread was attached when the IRP was issued. In this case
8075  // give the process to which the thread is currently attached. Note that
8076  // this only works if the thread that issued the IO request while it was
8077  // attached does not attach again. This is not allowed.
8078  //
8079 
8080  } else if (Irp->ApcEnvironment == AttachedApcEnvironment) {
8081  return (CONTAINING_RECORD(((thread)->Tcb.ApcState.Process),EPROCESS,Pcb));
8082 
8083  } else {
8084  return NULL;
8085  }
8086  } else {
8087  return NULL;
8088  }
8089 }

8110
