8125 
8126 VOID
8127 IoInitializeIrp(
8128  IN OUT PIRP Irp,
8129  IN USHORT PacketSize,
8130  IN CCHAR StackSize
8131  )
8132 
8133 /*++
8134 
8135 Routine Description:
8136 
8137  Initializes an IRP.
8138 
8139 Arguments:
8140 
8141  Irp - a pointer to the IRP to initialize.
8142 
8143  PacketSize - length, in bytes, of the IRP.
8144 
8145  StackSize - Number of stack locations in the IRP.
8146 
8147 Return Value:
8148 
8149  None.
8150 
8151 --*/
8152 
8153 {
8154  IOV_INITIALIZE_IRP(Irp, PacketSize, StackSize);
8155 
8156  //
8157  // Begin by zeroing the entire packet.
8158  //
8159 
8160  RtlZeroMemory( Irp, PacketSize );
8161 
8162  //
8163  // Initialize the remainder of the packet by setting the appropriate fields
8164  // and setting up the I/O stack locations in the packet.
8165  //
8166 
8167  Irp->Type = (CSHORT) IO_TYPE_IRP;
8168  Irp->Size = (USHORT) PacketSize;
8169  Irp->StackCount = (CCHAR) StackSize;
8170  Irp->CurrentLocation = (CCHAR) (StackSize + 1);
8171  Irp->ApcEnvironment = KeGetCurrentApcEnvironment();
8172  InitializeListHead (&(Irp)->ThreadListEntry);
8173  Irp->Tail.Overlay.CurrentStackLocation =
8174  ((PIO_STACK_LOCATION) ((UCHAR *) (Irp) +
8175  sizeof( IRP ) +
8176  ( (StackSize) * sizeof( IO_STACK_LOCATION ))));
8177 }
8178 
8179 VOID
8180 IoReuseIrp(
8181  PIRP Irp,
8182  NTSTATUS Status)
8183 /*++
8184 
8185 Routine Description:
8186 
8187  This routine is used by drivers to initialize an already allocated IRP for reuse.
8188  It does what IoInitializeIrp does but it saves the allocation flags so that we know
8189  how to free the Irp and take care of quote requirements. Drivers should call IoReuseIrp
8190  instead of calling IoInitializeIrp to reinitialize an IRP.
8191 
8192 Arguments:
8193 
8194  Irp - Pointer to Irp to be reused
8195 
8196  Status - Status to preinitialize the Iostatus field.
8197 
8198 --*/
8199 {
8200 
8201  USHORT PacketSize;
8202  CCHAR StackSize;
8203  UCHAR AllocationFlags;
8204 
8205  // Did anyone forget to pull their cancel routine?
8206  ASSERT(Irp->CancelRoutine == NULL) ;
8207 
8208  // We probably don't want thread enqueue'd IRPs to be used
8209  // ping-pong style as they cannot be dequeue unless they
8210  // complete entirely. Not really an issue for worker threads,
8211  // but definitely for operations on application threads.
8212  ASSERT(IsListEmpty(&Irp->ThreadListEntry)) ;
8213 
8214  AllocationFlags = Irp->AllocationFlags;
8215  StackSize = Irp->StackCount;
8216  PacketSize = IoSizeOfIrp(StackSize);
8217  IopInitializeIrp(Irp, PacketSize, StackSize);
8218  Irp->AllocationFlags = AllocationFlags;
8219  Irp->IoStatus.Status = Status;
8220 
8221 }

8223 
8224 
8225 NTSTATUS
8226 IoInitializeTimer(
8227  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
8228  IN PIO_TIMER_ROUTINE TimerRoutine,
8229  IN PVOID Context
8230  )
8231 
8232 /*++
8233 
8234 Routine Description:
8235 
8236  This routine is used by drivers to initialize a timer entry for a device
8237  object.
8238 
8239 Arguments:
8240 
8241  DeviceObject - Pointer to device object to be used.
8242 
8243  TimerRoutine - Driver routine to be executed when timer expires.
8244 
8245  Context - Context parameter that is passed to the driver routine.
8246 
8247 Return Value:
8248 
8249  The function value indicates whether or not the timer was initialized.
8250 
8251 --*/
8252 
8253 {
8254  PIO_TIMER timer;
8255 
8256  PAGED_CODE();
8257 
8258  //
8259  // Begin by getting the address of the timer to be used. If no timer has
8260  // been allocated, allocate one and initialize it.
8261  //
8262 
8263  timer = DeviceObject->Timer;
8264  if (!timer) {
8265  timer = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( NonPagedPool, sizeof( IO_TIMER ), 'iToI' );
8266  if (!timer) {
8267  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
8268  }
8269 
8270  //
8271  // Initialize the timer entry so that it is suitable for being placed
8272  // into the I/O system's timer queue.
8273  //
8274 
8275  RtlZeroMemory( timer, sizeof( IO_TIMER ) );
8276  timer->Type = IO_TYPE_TIMER;
8277  timer->DeviceObject = DeviceObject;
8278  DeviceObject->Timer = timer;
8279  }
8280 
8281  //
8282  // Set the address of the driver's timer routine and the context parameter
8283  // passed to it and insert it onto the timer queue. Note that the timer
8284  // enable flag is not set, so this routine will not actually be invoked
8285  // yet.
8286  //
8287 
8288  timer->TimerRoutine = TimerRoutine;
8289  timer->Context = Context;
8290 
8291  ExInterlockedInsertTailList( &IopTimerQueueHead,
8292  &timer->TimerList,
8293  &IopTimerLock );
8294  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
8295 }
8296 
8297 BOOLEAN
8298 IoIsOperationSynchronous(
8299  IN PIRP Irp
8300  )
8301 
8302 /*++
8303 
8304 Routine Description:
8305 
8306  This routine determines whether an I/O operation is to be considered
8307  synchronous or an asynchronous, from the implementors point-of-view.
8308  Synchronous I/O is defined by how the file was opened, or the API being
8309  used to perform the operation, or by the type of paging I/O being
8310  performed, if the operation is paging I/O.
8311 
8312  It is possible for asynchronous paging I/O to occur to a file that was
8313  opened for synchronous I/O. This occurs when the Modified Page Writer
8314  is doing I/O to a file that is mapped, when too many modified pages exist
8315  in the system.
8316 
8317 Arguments:
8318 
8319  Irp - Pointer to the I/O Request Packet (IRP) representing the operation
8320  to be performed.
8321 
8322 Return Value:
8323 
8324  A value of TRUE is returned if the operation is synchronous, otherwise
8325  FALSE is returned.
8326 
8327 --*/
8328 
8329 {
8330  //
8331  // Determine whether this is a synchronous I/O operation. Synchronous I/O
8332  // is defined as an operation that is:
8333  //
8334  // A file opened for synchronous I/O
8335  // OR
8336  // A synchronous API operation
8337  // OR
8338  // A synchronous paging I/O operation
8339  //
8340  // AND this is NOT an asynchronous paging I/O operation occurring to some
8341  // file that was opened for either synchronous or asynchronous I/O.
8342  //
8343 
8344  if ((IoGetCurrentIrpStackLocation( Irp )->FileObject->Flags & FO_SYNCHRONOUS_IO ||
8345  Irp->Flags & IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_API ||
8346  Irp->Flags & IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_PAGING_IO) &&
8347  !(Irp->Flags & IRP_PAGING_IO &&
8348  !(Irp->Flags & IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_PAGING_IO))) {
8349  return TRUE;
8350  } else {
8351  return FALSE;
8352  }
8353 }
8354 
8355 BOOLEAN
8356 IoIsSystemThread(
8357  IN PETHREAD Thread
8358  )
8359 
8360 /*++
8361 
8362 Routine Description:
8363 
8364  This routine returns a BOOLEAN indicating whether or not the specified
8365  thread is a system thread.
8366 
8367 Arguments:
8368 
8369  Thread - Pointer to the thread to be checked.
8370 
8371 Return Value:
8372 
8373  A value of TRUE is returned if the indicated thread is a system thread,
8374  else FALSE.
8375 
8376 Note:
8377 
8378  This function cannot be made a macro, since fields in the thread object
8379  move from release to release, so this must remain a full function.
8380 
8381 --*/
8382 
8383 {
8384  return (BOOLEAN) IS_SYSTEM_THREAD(Thread);
8385 }
8386 
8387 BOOLEAN
8388 IoIsValidNameGraftingBuffer(
8389  IN PIRP Irp,
8390  IN PREPARSE_DATA_BUFFER ReparseBuffer
8391  )
8392 
8393 /*++
8394 
8395 Routine Description:
8396 
8397  This routine returns a BOOLEAN indicating whether or not the specified
8398  buffer is a valid name grafting buffer. All internal validity checks are
8399  encapsulated in this routine.
8400 
8401  Among the checks performed is whether the name lengths stored within the
8402  buffer in the private data section are compatible with the total size of
8403  the buffer that has been passed in.
8404 
8405 Arguments:
8406 
8407  Irp - Pointer to the I/O Request Packet (IRP) representing the operation
8408  to be performed.
8409 
8410  Buffer - Pointer to a reparse data buffer that is supposed to contain
8411  a self-consistent set of names to perform name grafting.
8412 
8413 Return Value:
8414 
8415  A value of TRUE is returned if the buffer is correct for name grafting,
8416  else FALSE.
8417 
8418 Note:
8419 
8420  This function needs to be kept synchronized with the definition of
8421  REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER.
8422 
8423 --*/
8424 
8425 {
8426  PIO_STACK_LOCATION thisStackPointer = NULL;
8427  UNICODE_STRING drivePath;
8428 
8429  PAGED_CODE();
8430 
8431  ASSERT( FIELD_OFFSET( REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER, SymbolicLinkReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[0] ) ==
8432  FIELD_OFFSET( REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER, MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[0] ) );
8433  ASSERT( ReparseBuffer->ReparseDataLength < MAXIMUM_REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER_SIZE );
8434 
8435  //
8436  // Determine whether we have the correct kind of reparse tag in the buffer.
8437  //
8438 
8439  if (ReparseBuffer->ReparseTag != IO_REPARSE_TAG_MOUNT_POINT) {
8440 
8441  //
8442  // The reparse tag is not an NT name grafting tag.
8443  //
8444 
8445  return FALSE;
8446  }
8447 
8448  //
8449  // Determine whether we have enough data for all the length fields.
8450  //
8451 
8452  if (ReparseBuffer->ReparseDataLength <
8453  (FIELD_OFFSET(REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER, MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[0]) - REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER_HEADER_SIZE)) {
8454 
8455  //
8456  // The buffer is shorter than the minimum needed to express a pair of valid
8457  // names.
8458  //
8459 
8460  return FALSE;
8461  }
8462 
8463  //
8464  // Get the address of the current stack location.
8465  //
8466 
8467  thisStackPointer = IoGetCurrentIrpStackLocation( Irp );
8468 
8469  //
8470  // Determine whether the data lengths returned are consistent with the buffer in
8471  // which they are retrieved.
8472  //
8473  // This check is meaningful only when the buffer has been allocated. When this routine
8474  // is used when a name grafting is being set there is no allocated output buffer.
8475  //
8476 
8477  if ((thisStackPointer->Parameters.FileSystemControl.OutputBufferLength > 0) &&
8478  (thisStackPointer->Parameters.FileSystemControl.OutputBufferLength <
8479  (ULONG)(FIELD_OFFSET(REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER, MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[0]) +
8480  ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.SubstituteNameLength +
8481  ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PrintNameLength +
8482  2 * sizeof( UNICODE_NULL )))) {
8483 
8484  //
8485  // The length of the appropriate buffer header, plus the lengths of the substitute
8486  // and print names are longer than the length of the buffer passed in.
8487  // Thus, this data is not self-consistent.
8488  //
8489  // Note that it is only the I/O subsystem that needs to check for this internal
8490  // consistency in the buffer as it will do a blind data copy using these lengths
8491  // when transmogrifying the names. The file system returning the buffer only needs
8492  // to ascertain that the total size of the data retrieved does not exceed the size
8493  // of the output buffer.
8494  //
8495 
8496  return FALSE;
8497  }
8498 
8499  //
8500  // Now we determine whether the names were placed according to the reparse point
8501  // specification.
8502  //
8503 
8504  //
8505  // Determine whether the SubstituteNameOffset is zero.
8506  //
8507 
8508  if (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.SubstituteNameOffset != 0) {
8509 
8510  //
8511  // Incorrect offset for the substitute name.
8512  //
8513 
8514  return FALSE;
8515  }
8516 
8517  //
8518  // Determine whether PrintNameOffset is correct.
8519  //
8520 
8521  if (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PrintNameOffset !=
8522  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.SubstituteNameLength + sizeof( UNICODE_NULL )) ) {
8523 
8524  //
8525  // Incorrect offset for the print name.
8526  //
8527 
8528  return FALSE;
8529  }
8530 
8531  //
8532  // Determine whether ReparseDataLength is correct for name grafting operations.
8533  // We require a buffer of type REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER.
8534  //
8535 
8536  if (ReparseBuffer->ReparseDataLength !=
8537  (FIELD_OFFSET(REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER, MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[0]) - REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER_HEADER_SIZE) +
8538  ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.SubstituteNameLength +
8539  ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PrintNameLength +
8540  2 * sizeof( UNICODE_NULL )) {
8541 
8542  //
8543  // Incorrect length of the reparse data.
8544  //
8545 
8546  return FALSE;
8547  }
8548 
8549  //
8550  // Determine that the substitute name is not a UNC name.
8551  // This assumes that ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.SubstituteNameOffset is zero (0).
8552  //
8553 
8554  {
8555  //
8556  // This conditional is a transcription of part of the code of RtlDetermineDosPathNameType_U
8557  // present in ntos\dll\curdir.c
8558  //
8559  // The only two legal names that can begin with \\ are: \\. and \\?
8560  // All other names that begin with \\ are disallowed.
8561  //
8562 
8563  if ((ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.SubstituteNameLength > 6) &&
8564  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[0] == L'\\') &&
8565  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[1] == L'\\') &&
8566  !((ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[2] == L'.') ||
8567  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[2] == L'?'))) {
8568 
8569  //
8570  // The name is not one we want to deal with.
8571  //
8572 
8573  return FALSE;
8574  }
8575 
8576  //
8577  // When RtlDosPathNameToNtPathName_U is used, the UNC names are returned with a prefix
8578  // of the form \??\UNC\
8579  //
8580 
8581  if ((ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.SubstituteNameLength > 16) &&
8582  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[0] == L'\\') &&
8583  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[1] == L'?') &&
8584  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[2] == L'?') &&
8585  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[3] == L'\\') &&
8586  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[4] == L'U') &&
8587  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[5] == L'N') &&
8588  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[6] == L'C') &&
8589  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[7] == L'\\')) {
8590 
8591  //
8592  // The name is not one we want to deal with.
8593  //
8594 
8595  return FALSE;
8596  }
8597 
8598  //
8599  // See whether there is a drive letter that is mapped at the beginning of the name.
8600  // If the drive letter is C, then the prefix has the form \??\C:
8601  // Note that we skip the offset 4 on purpose.
8602  //
8603 
8604  if ((ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.SubstituteNameLength > 12) &&
8605  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[0] == L'\\') &&
8606  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[1] == L'?') &&
8607  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[2] == L'?') &&
8608  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[3] == L'\\') &&
8609  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[5] == L':')) {
8610 
8611  NTSTATUS status;
8612  UNICODE_STRING linkValue;
8613  OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES objectAttributes;
8614  HANDLE linkHandle;
8615  PWCHAR linkValueBuffer = NULL; // MAX_PATH is 260
8616  WCHAR pathNameValue[sizeof(L"\\??\\C:\0")];
8617 
8618  RtlCopyMemory( &pathNameValue[0], L"\\??\\C:\0", sizeof(L"\\??\\C:\0") );
8619 
8620  RtlInitUnicodeString( &drivePath, pathNameValue );
8621 
8622  //
8623  // Place the appropriate drive letter in the buffer overwriting offset 4.
8624  //
8625 
8626  drivePath.Buffer[4] = ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[4];
8627 
8628  InitializeObjectAttributes( &objectAttributes,
8629  &drivePath,
8630  OBJ_CASE_INSENSITIVE|OBJ_KERNEL_HANDLE,
8631  (HANDLE) NULL,
8632  (PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR) NULL );
8633 
8634  status = ZwOpenSymbolicLinkObject( &linkHandle,
8635  SYMBOLIC_LINK_QUERY,
8636  &objectAttributes );
8637 
8638 
8639  if ( NT_SUCCESS( status ) ) {
8640 
8641  //
8642  // Now query the link and see if there is a redirection
8643  //
8644 
8645  linkValueBuffer = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( NonPagedPool,
8646  2 * 260,
8647  ' oI' );
8648  if ( !linkValueBuffer ) {
8649 
8650  //
8651  // Insufficient resources. Return FALSE.
8652  //
8653 
8654  ZwClose( linkHandle );
8655  return FALSE;
8656  }
8657 
8658  linkValue.Buffer = linkValueBuffer;
8659  linkValue.Length = 0;
8660  linkValue.MaximumLength = (USHORT)(2 * 260);
8661 
8662  status = ZwQuerySymbolicLinkObject( linkHandle,
8663  &linkValue,
8664  NULL );
8665  ZwClose( linkHandle );
8666 
8667 
8668  if ( NT_SUCCESS( status ) ) {
8669 
8670  //
8671  // The link is a re-directed drive when it has the prefix
8672  // \Device\LanmanRedirector\
8673  //
8674 
8675  if ((linkValue.Buffer[ 0] == L'\\') &&
8676  (linkValue.Buffer[ 1] == L'D') &&
8677  (linkValue.Buffer[ 2] == L'e') &&
8678  (linkValue.Buffer[ 3] == L'v') &&
8679  (linkValue.Buffer[ 4] == L'i') &&
8680  (linkValue.Buffer[ 5] == L'c') &&
8681  (linkValue.Buffer[ 6] == L'e') &&
8682  (linkValue.Buffer[ 7] == L'\\') &&
8683  (linkValue.Buffer[ 8] == L'L') &&
8684  (linkValue.Buffer[ 9] == L'a') &&
8685  (linkValue.Buffer[10] == L'n') &&
8686  (linkValue.Buffer[14] == L'R') &&
8687  (linkValue.Buffer[15] == L'e') &&
8688  (linkValue.Buffer[16] == L'd') &&
8689  (linkValue.Buffer[17] == L'i') &&
8690  (linkValue.Buffer[18] == L'r') &&
8691  (linkValue.Buffer[23] == L'r') &
8692  (linkValue.Buffer[24] == L'\\')) {
8693 
8694  //
8695  // Free the buffer.
8696  //
8697 
8698  ExFreePool( linkValueBuffer );
8699 
8700  return FALSE;
8701  }
8702 
8703  }
8704 
8705  //
8706  // Free the buffer.
8707  //
8708 
8709  ExFreePool( linkValueBuffer );
8710  }
8711  }
8712  }
8713 
8714  //
8715  // Determine that we either have an NT file name or a volume mount point target name.
8716  //
8717  // This closes the door of having an arbitrary device name that, with the help of the
8718  // server, can be used to bypass access checks to the underlying device.
8719  //
8720 
8721  {
8722  UNICODE_STRING volumeName;
8723 
8724  if (
8725  //
8726  // The shortest valid name is one of the kind \??\C: whose length is 12 when
8727  // in Unicode. All names used by volume mount points are longer.
8728  //
8729 
8730  ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.SubstituteNameLength < 12 ) {
8731 
8732  return FALSE;
8733  }
8734 
8735  //
8736  // The name has at least 6 Unicode characters.
8737  //
8738  // We have verified above that MountPointReparseBuffer.SubstituteNameOffset
8739  // is zero.
8740  //
8741 
8742  volumeName.Length =
8743  volumeName.MaximumLength = ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.SubstituteNameLength;
8744  volumeName.Buffer = (PWSTR) ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer;
8745 
8746  //
8747  // When we do not have a name that begins with a drive letter and it is not
8748  // a valid volume mount point name then we return false.
8749  //
8750 
8751  if ( !((ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[0] == L'\\') &&
8752  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[1] == L'?') &&
8753  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[2] == L'?') &&
8754  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[3] == L'\\') &&
8755  //
8756  // Notice that we skip index 4, where the drive letter is to be.
8757  //
8758  (ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[5] == L':'))
8759 
8760  &&
8761 
8762  !MOUNTMGR_IS_VOLUME_NAME( &volumeName ) ) {
8763 
8764  return FALSE;
8765  }
8766  }
8767 
8768  //
8769  // Otherwise return TRUE.
8770  //
8771 
8772  return TRUE;
8773 }
8774 
8775 VOID
8776 IopDoNameTransmogrify(
8777  IN PIRP Irp,
8778  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
8779  IN PREPARSE_DATA_BUFFER ReparseBuffer
8780  )
8781 
8782 /*++
8783 
8784 Routine Description:
8785 
8786  This routine is called to do the name grafting needed for junctions.
8787 
8788 Arguments:
8789 
8790  Irp - Pointer to the I/O Request Packet (IRP) representing the operation
8791  to be performed.
8792 
8793  FileObject - Pointer to the file object whose name is being affected.
8794 
8795  ReparseBuffer - Pointer to a reparse data buffer that is supposed to contain
8796  a self-consistent set of names to perform name grafting.
8797 
8798 Return Value:
8799 
8800  No explicit return value. The appropriate fields off the IRP are set.
8801 
8802 Note:
8803 
8804  This function needs to be kept synchronized with the definition of
8805  REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER.
8806 
8807 --*/
8808 
8809 {
8810  USHORT pathLength = 0;
8811  USHORT neededBufferLength = 0;
8812  PVOID outBuffer = NULL;
8813  PWSTR pathBuffer = NULL;
8814 
8815  PAGED_CODE();
8816 
8817  //
8818  // We do the appropriate paste of the new name in the FileName buffer
8819  // and deallocate the buffer that brought the data from the file system.
8820  //
8821 
8822  ASSERT( Irp->IoStatus.Status == STATUS_REPARSE );
8823  ASSERT( Irp->IoStatus.Information == IO_REPARSE_TAG_MOUNT_POINT );
8824 
8825  ASSERT( Irp->Tail.Overlay.AuxiliaryBuffer != NULL );
8826 
8827  ASSERT( ReparseBuffer != NULL );
8828  ASSERT( ReparseBuffer->ReparseTag == IO_REPARSE_TAG_MOUNT_POINT );
8829  ASSERT( ReparseBuffer->ReparseDataLength < MAXIMUM_REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER_SIZE );
8830  ASSERT( ReparseBuffer->Reserved < MAXIMUM_REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER_SIZE );
8831 
8832 
8833  //
8834  // Determine whether we have enough data for all the length fields.
8835  //
8836  // Determine whether the lengths returned are consistent with the maximum
8837  // buffer. This is the best self-defense check we can do at this time as
8838  // the stack pointer is already invalid.
8839  //
8840 
8841  if (ReparseBuffer->ReparseDataLength >=
8842  (FIELD_OFFSET(REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER, MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[0]) - REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER_HEADER_SIZE)) {
8843 
8844  if (MAXIMUM_REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER_SIZE <
8845  (FIELD_OFFSET(REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER, MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer[0]) +
8846  ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.SubstituteNameLength +
8847  ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PrintNameLength)) {
8848 
8849  Irp->IoStatus.Status = STATUS_IO_REPARSE_DATA_INVALID;
8850  }
8851  } else {
8852  Irp->IoStatus.Status = STATUS_IO_REPARSE_DATA_INVALID;
8853  }
8854 
8855  //
8856  // The value in ReparseBuffer->Reserved is the length of the file
8857  // name that has still to be parsed.
8858  //
8859 
8860  //
8861  // Copy the buffer when it has the appropriate length, else return a null UNICODE name:
8862  // (1) Do defensive sanity checks on the name lengths returned.
8863  //
8864  // We only care to do this if we have no error conditions.
8865  //
8866 
8867  if (NT_SUCCESS( Irp->IoStatus.Status )) {
8868 
8869  pathBuffer = (PWSTR)((PCHAR)ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.PathBuffer +
8870  ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.SubstituteNameOffset);
8871  pathLength = ReparseBuffer->MountPointReparseBuffer.SubstituteNameLength;
8872  }
8873 
8874  //
8875  // Notice that if the data returned in AuxiliaryBuffer is not long enough then
8876  // pathLength has value 0 and pathBuffer has value NULL.
8877  //
8878  // The value in ReparseBuffer->Reserved is the length of the file name that
8879  // has still to be parsed.
8880  //
8881  // We only care to do this if we have no error conditions.
8882  //
8883 
8884  if (ReparseBuffer->Reserved < 0) {
8885 
8886  //
8887  // This is an invalid offset.
8888  //
8889 
8890  Irp->IoStatus.Status = STATUS_IO_REPARSE_DATA_INVALID;
8891  }
8892 
8893  if (NT_SUCCESS( Irp->IoStatus.Status )) {
8894 
8895  //
8896  // Check for overflow. (pathLength <= MAXIMUM_REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER_SIZE)
8897  // so pathLength + sizeof(UNICODE_NULL) cannot overflow.
8898  //
8899 
8900  if (((USHORT)MAXUSHORT - ReparseBuffer->Reserved ) > (pathLength +(USHORT)sizeof(UNICODE_NULL))) {
8901  neededBufferLength = pathLength + ReparseBuffer->Reserved + sizeof( UNICODE_NULL );
8902  //
8903  // If the out name buffer isn't large enough, allocate a new one.
8904  //
8905 
8906  if (FileObject->FileName.MaximumLength < neededBufferLength) {
8907  outBuffer = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( PagedPool,
8908  neededBufferLength,
8909  'cFoI' );
8910  if (!outBuffer) {
8911  Irp->IoStatus.Status = STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
8912  }
8913  } else {
8914  outBuffer = FileObject->FileName.Buffer;
8915  }
8916  } else {
8917  Irp->IoStatus.Status = STATUS_NAME_TOO_LONG;
8918  }
8919  }
8920 
8921  //
8922  // Place in the out name buffer the remaining part of the name.
8923  //
8924  // We only care to do this if we have no error conditions.
8925  //
8926 
8927  if (NT_SUCCESS( Irp->IoStatus.Status )) {
8928 
8929  if (ReparseBuffer->Reserved) {
8930 
8931  RtlMoveMemory ( (PCHAR)outBuffer + pathLength,
8932  (PCHAR)FileObject->FileName.Buffer +
8933  (FileObject->FileName.Length - ReparseBuffer->Reserved),
8934  ReparseBuffer->Reserved );
8935  }
8936 
8937  //
8938  // Copy into the front of the out name buffer the value of the
8939  // reparse point.
8940  //
8941 
8942  if (pathLength) {
8943 
8944  RtlCopyMemory( (PCHAR)outBuffer,
8945  (PCHAR)pathBuffer,
8946  pathLength );
8947  }
8948 
8949  FileObject->FileName.Length = neededBufferLength - sizeof( UNICODE_NULL );
8950 
8951  //
8952  // Free the old name buffer when needed and update the appropriate values.
8953  //
8954 
8955  if (outBuffer != FileObject->FileName.Buffer) {
8956 
8957  if (FileObject->FileName.Buffer != NULL) {
8958  ExFreePool( FileObject->FileName.Buffer );
8959  }
8960  FileObject->FileName.Buffer = outBuffer;
8961  FileObject->FileName.MaximumLength = neededBufferLength;
8962  ((PWSTR)outBuffer)[ (neededBufferLength / sizeof( WCHAR ))-1 ] = UNICODE_NULL;
8963  }
8964  }
8965 
8966  //
8967  // Free the buffer that came from the file system.
8968  // NULL the pointer.
8969  //
8970 
8971  ExFreePool( ReparseBuffer );
8972  ReparseBuffer = NULL;
8973 }
8974 
8975 PIRP
8976 IoMakeAssociatedIrp(
8977  IN PIRP Irp,
8978  IN CCHAR StackSize
8979  )
8980 
8981 /*++
8982 
8983 Routine Description:
8984 
8985  This routine allocates an I/O Request Packet from the system nonpaged pool
8986  and makes it an associated IRP to the specified IRP. The packet will be
8987  allocated to contain StackSize stack locations. The IRP will also be
8988  initialized.
8989 
8990  Note that it is up to the caller to have set the number of associated IRPs
8991  in the master packet before calling this routine for the first time. The
8992  count should be set in the master packet in: AssociatedIrp.IrpCount.
8993 
8994 Arguments:
8995 
8996  Irp - Pointer to master IRP to be associated with.
8997 
8998  StackSize - Specifies the maximum number of stack locations required.
8999 
9000 Return Value:
9001 
9002  The function value is the address of the associated IRP or NULL, if the
9003  IRP could be allocated.
9004 
9005 --*/
9006 
9007 {
9008  USHORT allocateSize;
9009  UCHAR fixedSize;
9010  PIRP associatedIrp;
9011  PGENERAL_LOOKASIDE lookasideList;
9012  PP_NPAGED_LOOKASIDE_NUMBER number;
9013  USHORT packetSize;
9014  PKPRCB prcb;
9015  CCHAR largeIrpStackLocations;
9016 
9017  //
9018  // If the size of the packet required is less than or equal to those on
9019  // the lookaside lists, then attempt to allocate the packet from the
9020  // lookaside lists.
9021  //
9022 
9023 
9024  associatedIrp = NULL;
9025  fixedSize = 0;
9026  packetSize = IoSizeOfIrp(StackSize);
9027  allocateSize = packetSize;
9028  largeIrpStackLocations = (CCHAR)IopLargeIrpStackLocations;
9029 
9030  if (StackSize <= largeIrpStackLocations) {
9031  fixedSize = IRP_ALLOCATED_FIXED_SIZE;
9032  number = LookasideSmallIrpList;
9033  if (StackSize != 1) {
9034  allocateSize = IoSizeOfIrp(largeIrpStackLocations);
9035  number = LookasideLargeIrpList;
9036  }
9037 
9038  prcb = KeGetCurrentPrcb();
9039  lookasideList = prcb->PPLookasideList[number].P;
9040  lookasideList->TotalAllocates += 1;
9041  associatedIrp = (PIRP)InterlockedPopEntrySList(&lookasideList->ListHead);
9042 
9043  if (associatedIrp == NULL) {
9044  lookasideList->AllocateMisses += 1;
9045  lookasideList = prcb->PPLookasideList[number].L;
9046  lookasideList->TotalAllocates += 1;
9047  associatedIrp = (PIRP)InterlockedPopEntrySList(&lookasideList->ListHead);
9048  if (!associatedIrp) {
9049  lookasideList->AllocateMisses += 1;
9050  }
9051  }
9052 
9053  if (IopIrpAutoSizingEnabled() && associatedIrp) {
9054 
9055  //
9056  // See if this IRP is a stale entry. If so just free it.
9057  // This can happen if we decided to change the lookaside list size.
9058  // We need to get the size of the IRP from the information field as the
9059  // size field is overlaid with the single list entry.
9060  //
9061 
9062  if (associatedIrp->IoStatus.Information < packetSize) {
9063  lookasideList->TotalFrees += 1;
9064  ExFreePool(associatedIrp);
9065  associatedIrp = NULL;
9066  } else {
9067 
9068  //
9069  // Update allocateSize to the correct value.
9070  //
9071  allocateSize = (USHORT)associatedIrp->IoStatus.Information;
9072  }
9073  }
9074  }
9075 
9076  //
9077  // If an IRP was not allocated from the lookaside list, then allocate
9078  // the packet from nonpaged pool.
9079  //
9080 
9081  if (!associatedIrp) {
9082 
9083  //
9084  // There are no free packets on the lookaside list, or the packet is
9085  // too large to be allocated from one of the lists, so it must be
9086  // allocated from general non-paged pool.
9087  //
9088 
9089  associatedIrp = ExAllocatePoolWithTag(NonPagedPool, allocateSize, ' prI');
9090  if (!associatedIrp) {
9091  return NULL;
9092  }
9093 
9094  }
9095 
9096  //
9097  // Initialize the packet.
9098  //
9099 
9100  IopInitializeIrp(associatedIrp, allocateSize, StackSize);
9101  associatedIrp->Flags |= IRP_ASSOCIATED_IRP;
9102  associatedIrp->Flags |= (Irp->Flags & IRP_HIGH_PRIORITY_PAGING_IO);
9103  associatedIrp->AllocationFlags |= (fixedSize);
9104 
9105  //
9106  // Set the thread ID to be that of the master.
9107  //
9108 
9109  associatedIrp->Tail.Overlay.Thread = Irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread;
9110 
9111  //
9112  // Now make the association between this packet and the master.
9113  //
9114 
9115  associatedIrp->AssociatedIrp.MasterIrp = Irp;
9116  return associatedIrp;
9117 }
9118 
9119 
9120 
9121 NTSTATUS
9122 IoPageRead(
9123  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
9124  IN PMDL MemoryDescriptorList,
9125  IN PLARGE_INTEGER StartingOffset,
9126  IN PKEVENT Event,
9127  OUT PIO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatusBlock
9128  )
9129 
9130 /*++
9131 
9132 Routine Description:
9133 
9134  This routine provides a special, fast interface for the Pager to read pages
9135  in from the disk quickly and with very little overhead. All of the special
9136  handling for this request is recognized by setting the IRP_PAGING_IO flag
9137  in the IRP flags word. In-page operations are detected by using the IRP
9138  flag IRP_INPUT_OPERATION.
9139 
9140 Arguments:
9141 
9142  FileObject - A pointer to a referenced file object describing which file
9143  the read should be performed from.
9144 
9145  MemoryDescriptorList - An MDL which describes the physical pages that the
9146  pages should be read into from the disk. All of the pages have been
9147  locked in memory. The MDL also describes the length of the read
9148  operation.
9149 
9150  If the low bit of the MDL is set, then the I/O is issued asynchronously,
9151  otherwise it is done synchronously.
9152 
9153  StartingOffset - Pointer to the offset in the file from which the read
9154  should take place.
9155 
9156  Event - A pointer to a kernel event structure to be used for synchronization
9157  purposes. The event will be set to the Signaled state once the in-page
9158  operation completes.
9159 
9160  IoStatusBlock - A pointer to the I/O status block in which the final status
9161  and information should be stored.
9162 
9163 Return Value:
9164 
9165  The function value is the final status of the queue request to the I/O
9166  system subcomponents.
9167 
9168 Notes:
9169 
9170  This routine is invoked at APC_LEVEL; this level is honored throughout the
9171  execution of the entire I/O request, including completion.
9172 
9173 --*/
9174 
9175 {
9176  PIRP irp;
9177  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
9178  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
9179 
9180  //
9181  // Begin by getting a pointer to the device object that the file resides
9182  // on.
9183  //
9184 
9185  deviceObject = IoGetRelatedDeviceObject( FileObject );
9186 
9187  //
9188  // Allocate an I/O Request Packet (IRP) for this in-page operation.
9189  //
9190 
9191  irp = IoAllocateIrp( deviceObject->StackSize, FALSE );
9192  if (!irp) {
9193  if (MmIsFileObjectAPagingFile(FileObject)) {
9194  InterlockedIncrement(&IoPageReadIrpAllocationFailure);
9195  irp = IopAllocateReserveIrp(deviceObject->StackSize);
9196  } else {
9197  InterlockedIncrement(&IoPageReadNonPagefileIrpAllocationFailure);
9198  }
9199 
9200  if (!irp) {
9201  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
9202  }
9203  }
9204 
9205  //
9206  // Get a pointer to the first stack location in the packet. This location
9207  // will be used to pass the function codes and parameters to the first
9208  // driver.
9209  //
9210 
9211  irpSp = IoGetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
9212 
9213  //
9214  // Fill in the IRP according to this request.
9215  //
9216 
9217  //
9218  // The low bit of the MDL is biased to indicate async behavior is desired.
9219  //
9220 
9221  if ((ULONG_PTR)MemoryDescriptorList & 0x1) {
9222  irp->Flags = IRP_PAGING_IO | IRP_NOCACHE | IRP_SET_USER_EVENT;
9223  MemoryDescriptorList = (PMDL) ((ULONG_PTR)MemoryDescriptorList & ~0x1);
9224  } else {
9225  irp->Flags = IRP_PAGING_IO | IRP_NOCACHE | IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_PAGING_IO | IRP_INPUT_OPERATION;
9226  }
9227 
9228  irp->MdlAddress = MemoryDescriptorList;
9229 
9230  irp->RequestorMode = KernelMode;
9231  irp->UserIosb = IoStatusBlock;
9232  irp->UserEvent = Event;
9233  irp->UserBuffer = (PVOID) ((PCHAR) MemoryDescriptorList->StartVa + MemoryDescriptorList->ByteOffset);
9234  irp->Tail.Overlay.OriginalFileObject = FileObject;
9235  irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread = PsGetCurrentThread();
9236 
9237  //
9238  // Fill in the normal read parameters.
9239  //
9240 
9241  irpSp->MajorFunction = IRP_MJ_READ;
9242  irpSp->FileObject = FileObject;
9243  irpSp->Parameters.Read.Length = MemoryDescriptorList->ByteCount;
9244  irpSp->Parameters.Read.ByteOffset = *StartingOffset;
9245 
9246  //
9247  // For debugging purposes.
9248  //
9249 
9250  IoStatusBlock->Information = (ULONG_PTR)irp;
9251 
9252  //
9253  // Increment performance counter. The Cache Manager I/Os always are
9254  // "recursive".
9255  //
9256 
9257  if (MmIsRecursiveIoFault()) {
9258  *CcMissCounter += (MemoryDescriptorList->ByteCount + PAGE_SIZE - 1) >> PAGE_SHIFT;
9259  }
9260 
9261  //
9262  // Queue the packet to the appropriate driver based on whether or not there
9263  // is a VPB associated with the device.
9264  //
9265 
9266  return IoCallDriver( deviceObject, irp );
9267 }

9412 
9413 VOID
9414 IoRaiseHardError(
9415  IN PIRP Irp,
9416  IN PVPB Vpb OPTIONAL,
9417  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT RealDeviceObject
9418  )
9419 
9420 /*++
9421 
9422 Routine Description:
9423 
9424  This routine pops up a hard error in the context of the thread that
9425  originally requested the I/O operation specified by the input IRP. This
9426  is done by queueing a kernel APC to the original thread, passing it a
9427  pointer to the device objects and the IRP. Once the pop up is performed,
9428  the routine either completes the I/O request then, or it calls the driver
9429  back with the same IRP.
9430 
9431  If the original request was an IoPageRead, then it was at APC level and
9432  we have to create a thread to "hold" this pop-up. Note that we have to
9433  queue to an ExWorker thread to create the thread since this can only be
9434  done from the system process.
9435 
9436 Arguments:
9437 
9438  Irp - A pointer to the I/O Request Packet (IRP) for the request that
9439  failed.
9440 
9441  Vpb - This is the volume parameter block of the offending media. If the
9442  media not yet mounted, this parameter should be absent.
9443 
9444  RealDeviceObject - A pointer to the device object that represents the
9445  device that the file system believes it has mounted. This is
9446  generally the "real" device object in the VPB, but may, in fact,
9447  be a device object attached to the physical device.
9448 
9449 Return Value:
9450 
9451  None.
9452 
9453 --*/
9454 
9455 {
9456  PIO_STACK_LOCATION IrpSp;
9457  ULONG irpFlags;
9458  PETHREAD Thread;
9459 
9460  //
9461  // If pop-ups are disabled for the requesting thread, just complete the
9462  // request.
9463  //
9464 
9465  Thread = Irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread;
9466 
9467  if ((Thread->CrossThreadFlags&PS_CROSS_THREAD_FLAGS_HARD_ERRORS_DISABLED) != 0) {
9468 
9469  //
9470  // An error was incurred, so zero out the information field before
9471  // completing the request if this was an input operation. Otherwise,
9472  // IopCompleteRequest will try to copy to the user's buffer.
9473  //
9474 
9475  if (Irp->Flags & IRP_INPUT_OPERATION) {
9476  Irp->IoStatus.Information = 0;
9477  }
9478 
9479  IoCompleteRequest( Irp, IO_DISK_INCREMENT );
9480 
9481  return;
9482  }
9483 
9484  //
9485  // If this Irp resulted from a call to IoPageRead(), the caller must
9486  // have been at APC level, so don't try enqueing an APC.
9487  //
9488  // Also if this is a cleanup Irp, force this pop-up to go to the new
9489  // thread so that it cannot be disabled.
9490  //
9491 
9492  IrpSp = IoGetCurrentIrpStackLocation(Irp);
9493 
9494  irpFlags = Irp->Flags & (~IRP_VERIFIER_MASK);
9495  if ((irpFlags == (IRP_PAGING_IO |
9496  IRP_NOCACHE |
9497  IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_PAGING_IO |
9498  IRP_INPUT_OPERATION)) ||
9499  ((IrpSp->MajorFunction == IRP_MJ_FILE_SYSTEM_CONTROL) &&
9500  (IrpSp->MinorFunction == IRP_MN_MOUNT_VOLUME)) ||
9501  (IrpSp->MajorFunction == IRP_MJ_CLEANUP)) {
9502 
9503  PIOP_APC_HARD_ERROR_PACKET packet;
9504 
9505  //
9506  // Need to check here whether hard errors are disabled for the thread
9507  // as we will be in system context later and it will be too late
9508  //
9509  if ((IrpSp->MajorFunction == IRP_MJ_FILE_SYSTEM_CONTROL) &&
9510  !IS_SYSTEM_THREAD(Thread)) {
9511 
9512  NTSTATUS status;
9513  ULONG hardErrorMode;
9514  SIZE_T bytesCopied;
9515  BOOLEAN fail = TRUE;
9516  PEPROCESS process;
9517 
9518  process = THREAD_TO_PROCESS(Thread);
9519 
9520  if (process == PsGetCurrentProcess()) {
9521  PTEB Teb = Thread->Tcb.Teb;
9522 
9523  try {
9524  if (!(Teb->HardErrorMode & RTL_ERRORMODE_FAILCRITICALERRORS)) {
9525  fail = FALSE;
9526  }
9527  } except (EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
9528  ;
9529  }
9530  } else {
9531 
9532  //
9533  // The issuing thread is in another process so we need to read the TEB from
9534  // that processes memory
9535  //
9536  status = MmCopyVirtualMemory(process,
9537  ((PUCHAR)Thread->Tcb.Teb) + FIELD_OFFSET(TEB, HardErrorMode),
9538  PsGetCurrentProcess(),
9539  &hardErrorMode,
9540  sizeof(hardErrorMode),
9541  KernelMode,
9542  &bytesCopied);
9543 
9544  if (NT_SUCCESS(status) && !(hardErrorMode & RTL_ERRORMODE_FAILCRITICALERRORS)) {
9545  fail = FALSE;
9546  }
9547  }
9548 
9549  if (fail) {
9550 
9551  Irp->IoStatus.Information = 0;
9552 
9553  IoCompleteRequest( Irp, IO_DISK_INCREMENT );
9554 
9555  return;
9556  }
9557  }
9558 
9559  packet = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( NonPagedPool,
9560  sizeof( IOP_APC_HARD_ERROR_PACKET ),
9561  'rEoI' );
9562 
9563  if ( packet == NULL ) {
9564 
9565  IoCompleteRequest( Irp, IO_DISK_INCREMENT );
9566  return;
9567  }
9568 
9569  ExInitializeWorkItem( &packet->Item, IopStartApcHardError, packet );
9570  packet->Irp = Irp;
9571  packet->Vpb = Vpb;
9572  packet->RealDeviceObject = RealDeviceObject;
9573 
9574  ExQueueWorkItem( &packet->Item, CriticalWorkQueue );
9575 
9576  } else {
9577 
9578  PKAPC apc;
9579 
9580  //
9581  // Begin by allocating and initializing an APC that can be sent to the
9582  // target thread.
9583  //
9584 
9585  apc = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( NonPagedPool, sizeof( KAPC ), 'CPAK' );
9586 
9587  //
9588  // If we could not get the pool, we have no choice but to just complete
9589  // the Irp, thereby passing the error onto the caller.
9590  //
9591 
9592  if ( apc == NULL ) {
9593 
9594  IoCompleteRequest( Irp, IO_DISK_INCREMENT );
9595  return;
9596  }
9597 
9598  KeInitializeApc( apc,
9599  &Thread->Tcb,
9600  Irp->ApcEnvironment,
9601  IopDeallocateApc,
9602  IopAbortRequest,
9603  IopRaiseHardError,
9604  KernelMode,
9605  Irp );
9606 
9607  (VOID) KeInsertQueueApc( apc,
9608  Vpb,
9609  RealDeviceObject,
9610  0 );
9611  }
9612 }
9613 
9614 BOOLEAN
9615 IoRaiseInformationalHardError(
9616  IN NTSTATUS ErrorStatus,
9617  IN PUNICODE_STRING String OPTIONAL,
9618  IN PKTHREAD Thread OPTIONAL
9619  )
9620 /*++
9621 
9622 Routine Description:
9623 
9624  This routine pops up a hard error in the hard error popup thread. The
9625  routine returns immediately, enqueuing the actual pop-up to a worker
9626  thread. The hard error that is raised is informational in the sense that
9627  only the OK button is displayed.
9628 
9629 Arguments:
9630 
9631  ErrorStatus - The error condition.
9632 
9633  String - Depending on the error, a string may have to be enqueued.
9634 
9635  Thread - If present, enqueue an APC to this thread rather than using
9636  the hard error thread.
9637 
9638 Return Value:
9639 
9640  BOOLEAN - TRUE if we decided to dispatch a pop-up. FALSE if we decided
9641  not to because:
9642 
9643  - pop-ups are disabled in the requested thread, or
9644 
9645  - a pool allocation failed, or
9646 
9647  - an equivalent pop-up is currently pending a user response (i.e.
9648  waiting for the user to press <OK>) or in the queue, or
9649 
9650  - too many pop-ups have already been queued.
9651 
9652 --*/
9653 
9654 //
9655 // This macro compares two pop-ups to see if they are content equivalent.
9656 //
9657 
9658 #define ArePacketsEquivalent(P1,P2) ( \
9659  (P1->ErrorStatus == P2->ErrorStatus) && \
9660  ((!P1->String.Buffer && !P2->String.Buffer) || \
9661  ((P1->String.Length == P2->String.Length) && \
9662  (RtlEqualMemory(P1->String.Buffer, \
9663  P2->String.Buffer, \
9664  P1->String.Length)))) \
9665 )
9666 
9667 {
9668  KIRQL oldIrql;
9669  PVOID stringBuffer;
9670  PLIST_ENTRY links;
9671 
9672  PIOP_HARD_ERROR_PACKET hardErrorPacket;
9673 
9674  //
9675  // If pop-ups are disabled for the requesting thread, just return.
9676  //
9677 
9678  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT(Thread) ?
9679  ((CONTAINING_RECORD(Thread, ETHREAD, Tcb)->CrossThreadFlags&PS_CROSS_THREAD_FLAGS_HARD_ERRORS_DISABLED) != 0) :
9680  ((PsGetCurrentThread()->CrossThreadFlags&PS_CROSS_THREAD_FLAGS_HARD_ERRORS_DISABLED) != 0)) {
9681 
9682  return FALSE;
9683  }
9684 
9685  //
9686  // If this is one of those special error popup codes that CSRSS expects
9687  // to be called with a correct set of arguments, disallow from a driver
9688  //
9689  if ( ErrorStatus == STATUS_VDM_HARD_ERROR ||
9690  ErrorStatus == STATUS_UNHANDLED_EXCEPTION ||
9691  ErrorStatus == STATUS_SERVICE_NOTIFICATION ) {
9692  return FALSE;
9693  }
9694 
9695  //
9696  // If this request is going to be sent to the hard error thread, and
9697  // there are more than 25 entries already in the queue, don't
9698  // add any more. We'll do another safe check later on.
9699  //
9700 
9701  if ( !ARGUMENT_PRESENT( Thread ) &&
9702  (KeReadStateSemaphore( &IopHardError.WorkQueueSemaphore ) >=
9703  IOP_MAXIMUM_OUTSTANDING_HARD_ERRORS) ) {
9704 
9705  return FALSE;
9706  } else {
9707  if (IopHardError.NumPendingApcPopups > IOP_MAXIMUM_OUTSTANDING_HARD_ERRORS) {
9708  return FALSE;
9709  }
9710  }
9711 
9712  //
9713  // Allocate the packet, and a buffer for the string if present.
9714  //
9715 
9716  hardErrorPacket = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( NonPagedPool,
9717  sizeof(IOP_HARD_ERROR_PACKET),
9718  'rEoI');
9719 
9720  if (!hardErrorPacket) { return FALSE; }
9721 
9722  //
9723  // Zero out the packet and fill the NT_STATUS we will pop up.
9724  //
9725 
9726  RtlZeroMemory( hardErrorPacket, sizeof(IOP_HARD_ERROR_PACKET) );
9727 
9728  hardErrorPacket->ErrorStatus = ErrorStatus;
9729 
9730  //
9731  // If there is a string, copy it.
9732  //
9733 
9734  if ( ARGUMENT_PRESENT( String ) && String->Length ) {
9735 
9736  stringBuffer = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( NonPagedPool,
9737  String->Length,
9738  'rEoI' );
9739 
9740  if (!stringBuffer) {
9741  ExFreePool( hardErrorPacket );
9742  return FALSE;
9743  }
9744 
9745  hardErrorPacket->String.Length = String->Length;
9746  hardErrorPacket->String.MaximumLength = String->Length;
9747 
9748  hardErrorPacket->String.Buffer = stringBuffer;
9749 
9750  RtlCopyMemory( stringBuffer, String->Buffer, String->Length );
9751  }
9752 
9753  //
9754  // If there is an Thread, enqueue an APC for ourself, otherwise send
9755  // it off to the to the hard error thread.
9756  //
9757 
9758  if ( ARGUMENT_PRESENT( Thread ) ) {
9759 
9760  PKAPC apc;
9761 
9762  //
9763  // Begin by allocating and initializing an APC that can be sent to the
9764  // target thread.
9765  //
9766 
9767  apc = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( NonPagedPool, sizeof( KAPC ), 'CPAK' );
9768 
9769  //
9770  // If we could not get the pool, we have no choice but to just
9771  // free the packet and return.
9772  //
9773 
9774  if ( apc == NULL ) {
9775 
9776  if ( hardErrorPacket->String.Buffer ) {
9777  ExFreePool( hardErrorPacket->String.Buffer );
9778  }
9779 
9780  ExFreePool( hardErrorPacket );
9781 
9782  return FALSE;
9783  }
9784 
9785  InterlockedIncrement(&IopHardError.NumPendingApcPopups);
9786  KeInitializeApc( apc,
9787  Thread,
9788  OriginalApcEnvironment,
9789  IopDeallocateApc,
9790  NULL,
9791  IopRaiseInformationalHardError,
9792  KernelMode,
9793  hardErrorPacket );
9794 
9795  (VOID) KeInsertQueueApc( apc, NULL, NULL, 0 );
9796 
9797  } else {
9798 
9799  //
9800  // Get exclusive access to the work queue.
9801  //
9802 
9803  ExAcquireSpinLock( &IopHardError.WorkQueueSpinLock, &oldIrql );
9804 
9805  //
9806  // Check the Signal state again, if OK, go ahead and enqueue.
9807  //
9808 
9809  if ( KeReadStateSemaphore( &IopHardError.WorkQueueSemaphore ) >=
9810  IOP_MAXIMUM_OUTSTANDING_HARD_ERRORS ) {
9811 
9812  ExReleaseSpinLock( &IopHardError.WorkQueueSpinLock, oldIrql );
9813 
9814  if ( hardErrorPacket->String.Buffer ) {
9815  ExFreePool( hardErrorPacket->String.Buffer );
9816  }
9817  ExFreePool( hardErrorPacket );
9818  return FALSE;
9819  }
9820 
9821  //
9822  // If there is a pop-up currently up, check for a match
9823  //
9824 
9825  if (IopCurrentHardError &&
9826  ArePacketsEquivalent( hardErrorPacket, IopCurrentHardError )) {
9827 
9828  ExReleaseSpinLock( &IopHardError.WorkQueueSpinLock, oldIrql );
9829 
9830  if ( hardErrorPacket->String.Buffer ) {
9831  ExFreePool( hardErrorPacket->String.Buffer );
9832  }
9833  ExFreePool( hardErrorPacket );
9834  return FALSE;
9835  }
9836 
9837  //
9838  // Run down the list of queued pop-ups looking for a match.
9839  //
9840 
9841  links = IopHardError.WorkQueue.Flink;
9842 
9843  while (links != &IopHardError.WorkQueue) {
9844 
9845  PIOP_HARD_ERROR_PACKET queueHardErrorPacket;
9846 
9847  queueHardErrorPacket = CONTAINING_RECORD( links,
9848  IOP_HARD_ERROR_PACKET,
9849  WorkQueueLinks );
9850 
9851  if (ArePacketsEquivalent( hardErrorPacket,
9852  queueHardErrorPacket )) {
9853 
9854  ExReleaseSpinLock( &IopHardError.WorkQueueSpinLock, oldIrql );
9855 
9856  if ( hardErrorPacket->String.Buffer ) {
9857  ExFreePool( hardErrorPacket->String.Buffer );
9858  }
9859  ExFreePool( hardErrorPacket );
9860  return FALSE;
9861  }
9862 
9863  links = links->Flink;
9864  }
9865 
9866  //
9867  // Enqueue this packet.
9868  //
9869 
9870  InsertTailList( &IopHardError.WorkQueue,
9871  &hardErrorPacket->WorkQueueLinks );
9872 
9873  //
9874  // Bump the count on the semaphore so that the hard error thread
9875  // will know that an entry has been placed in the queue.
9876  //
9877 
9878  (VOID) KeReleaseSemaphore( &IopHardError.WorkQueueSemaphore,
9879  0,
9880  1L,
9881  FALSE );
9882 
9883  //
9884  // If we are not currently running in an ExWorkerThread, queue
9885  // a work item.
9886  //
9887 
9888  if ( !IopHardError.ThreadStarted ) {
9889  IopHardError.ThreadStarted = TRUE;
9890  ExQueueWorkItem( &IopHardError.ExWorkItem, DelayedWorkQueue );
9891  }
9892 
9893  //
9894  // Finally, release the spinlockevent, allowing access to the work queue again.
9895  // The combination of releasing both the event and the semaphore will
9896  // enable the thread to wake up and obtain the entry.
9897  //
9898 
9899  ExReleaseSpinLock( &IopHardError.WorkQueueSpinLock, oldIrql );
9900  }
9901 
9902  return TRUE;
9903 }
9904 
9905 VOID
9906 IoRegisterBootDriverReinitialization(
9907  IN PDRIVER_OBJECT DriverObject,
9908  IN PDRIVER_REINITIALIZE DriverReinitializationRoutine,
9909  IN PVOID Context
9910  )
9911 
9912 /*++
9913 
9914 Routine Description:
9915 
9916  This routine is invoked by boot drivers during their initialization or
9917  during their reinitialization to register with the I/O system to be
9918  called again once all devices have been enumerated and started.
9919  Note that it is possible for this to occur during a normally running
9920  system, if the driver is loaded dynamically, so all references to the
9921  reinitialization queue must be synchronized.
9922 
9923 Arguments:
9924 
9925  DriverObject - Pointer to the driver's driver object.
9926 
9927  DriverReinitializationRoutine - The address of the reinitialization
9928  routine that is to be invoked.
9929 
9930  Context - Pointer to the context that is passed to the driver's
9931  reinitialization routine.
9932 
9933 Return Value:
9934 
9935  None.
9936 
9937 --*/
9938 
9939 {
9940  PREINIT_PACKET reinitEntry;
9941 
9942  PAGED_CODE();
9943 
9944  //
9945  // Allocate a reinitialization entry to be inserted onto the list. Note
9946  // that if the entry cannot be allocated, then the request is simply
9947  // dropped on the floor.
9948  //
9949 
9950  reinitEntry = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( NonPagedPool,
9951  sizeof( REINIT_PACKET ),
9952  'iRoI' );
9953  if (!reinitEntry) {
9954  return;
9955  }
9956 
9957  DriverObject->Flags |= DRVO_BOOTREINIT_REGISTERED;
9958  reinitEntry->DriverObject = DriverObject;
9959  reinitEntry->DriverReinitializationRoutine = DriverReinitializationRoutine;
9960  reinitEntry->Context = Context;
9961 
9962  IopInterlockedInsertTailList( &IopBootDriverReinitializeQueueHead,
9963  &reinitEntry->ListEntry );
9964 }
9965 
9966 VOID
9967 IoRegisterDriverReinitialization(
9968  IN PDRIVER_OBJECT DriverObject,
9969  IN PDRIVER_REINITIALIZE DriverReinitializationRoutine,
9970  IN PVOID Context
9971  )
9972 
9973 /*++
9974 
9975 Routine Description:
9976 
9977  This routine is invoked by drivers during their initialization or during
9978  their reinitialization to register with the I/O system to be called again
9979  before I/O system initialization is complete. Note that it is possible
9980  for this to occur during a normally running system, if the driver is
9981  loaded dynamically, so all references to the reinitialization queue must
9982  be synchronized.
9983 
9984 Arguments:
9985 
9986  DriverObject - Pointer to the driver's driver object.
9987 
9988  DriverReinitializationRoutine - The address of the reinitialization
9989  routine that is to be invoked.
9990 
9991  Context - Pointer to the context that is passed to the driver's
9992  reinitialization routine.
9993 
9994 Return Value:
9995 
9996  None.
9997 
9998 --*/
9999 
10000 {
10001  PREINIT_PACKET reinitEntry;
10002 
10003  PAGED_CODE();
10004 
10005  //
10006  // Allocate a reinitialization entry to be inserted onto the list. Note
10007  // that if the entry cannot be allocated, then the request is simply
10008  // dropped on the floor.
10009  //
10010 
10011  reinitEntry = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( NonPagedPool,
10012  sizeof( REINIT_PACKET ),
10013  'iRoI' );
10014  if (!reinitEntry) {
10015  return;
10016  }
10017 
10018  DriverObject->Flags |= DRVO_REINIT_REGISTERED;
10019  reinitEntry->DriverObject = DriverObject;
10020  reinitEntry->DriverReinitializationRoutine = DriverReinitializationRoutine;
10021  reinitEntry->Context = Context;
10022 
10023  IopInterlockedInsertTailList( &IopDriverReinitializeQueueHead,
10024  &reinitEntry->ListEntry );
10025 }
10026 
10027 VOID
10028 IoRegisterFileSystem(
10029  IN OUT PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject
10030  )
10031 
10032 /*++
10033 
10034 Routine Description:
10035 
10036  This routine inserts the device object for the file system which the device
10037  object represents into the list of file systems in the system.
10038 
10039 Arguments:
10040 
10041  DeviceObject - Pointer to device object for the file system.
10042 
10043 Return Value:
10044 
10045  None.
10046 
10047 
10048 --*/
10049 
10050 {
10051  PNOTIFICATION_PACKET nPacket;
10052  PLIST_ENTRY listHead = NULL;
10053  PLIST_ENTRY entry;
10054 
10055  PAGED_CODE();
10056 
10057  //
10058  // Allocate the I/O database resource for a write operation.
10059  //
10060 
10061  (VOID) ExAcquireResourceExclusiveLite( &IopDatabaseResource, TRUE );
10062 
10063  //
10064  // Insert the device object into the appropriate file system queue based on
10065  // the driver type in the device object. Notice that if the device type is
10066  // unrecognized, the file system is simply not registered.
10067  //
10068 
10069  if (DeviceObject->DeviceType == FILE_DEVICE_NETWORK_FILE_SYSTEM) {
10070  listHead = &IopNetworkFileSystemQueueHead;
10071  } else if (DeviceObject->DeviceType == FILE_DEVICE_CD_ROM_FILE_SYSTEM) {
10072  listHead = &IopCdRomFileSystemQueueHead;
10073  DeviceObject->DriverObject->Flags |= DRVO_BASE_FILESYSTEM_DRIVER;
10074  } else if (DeviceObject->DeviceType == FILE_DEVICE_DISK_FILE_SYSTEM) {
10075  listHead = &IopDiskFileSystemQueueHead;
10076  DeviceObject->DriverObject->Flags |= DRVO_BASE_FILESYSTEM_DRIVER;
10077  } else if (DeviceObject->DeviceType == FILE_DEVICE_TAPE_FILE_SYSTEM) {
10078  listHead = &IopTapeFileSystemQueueHead;
10079  DeviceObject->DriverObject->Flags |= DRVO_BASE_FILESYSTEM_DRIVER;
10080  }
10081 
10082  //
10083  // Low priority filesystems are inserted one-from-back on the queue (ahead of
10084  // raw, behind everything else), as opposed to on the front.
10085  //
10086 
10087  if (listHead != NULL) {
10088  if (DeviceObject->Flags & DO_LOW_PRIORITY_FILESYSTEM ) {
10089  InsertTailList( listHead->Blink,
10090  &DeviceObject->Queue.ListEntry );
10091  } else {
10092  InsertHeadList( listHead,
10093  &DeviceObject->Queue.ListEntry );
10094  }
10095  }
10096 
10097  IopFsRegistrationOps++;
10098 
10099  //
10100  // Ensure that this file system's device is operable.
10101  //
10102 
10103  DeviceObject->Flags &= ~DO_DEVICE_INITIALIZING;
10104 
10105  //
10106  // Notify all of the registered drivers that this file system has been
10107  // registered as an active file system of some type.
10108  //
10109 
10110  entry = IopFsNotifyChangeQueueHead.Flink;
10111  while (entry != &IopFsNotifyChangeQueueHead) {
10112  nPacket = CONTAINING_RECORD( entry, NOTIFICATION_PACKET, ListEntry );
10113  entry = entry->Flink;
10114  nPacket->NotificationRoutine( DeviceObject, TRUE );
10115  }
10116 
10117  //
10118  // Release the I/O database resource.
10119  //
10120 
10121  ExReleaseResourceLite( &IopDatabaseResource );
10122 
10123  //
10124  // Increment the number of reasons that this driver cannot be unloaded.
10125  //
10126 
10127  IopInterlockedIncrementUlong( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock,
10128  &DeviceObject->ReferenceCount );
10129 }
10130 
10131 VOID
10132 IopNotifyAlreadyRegisteredFileSystems(
10133  IN PLIST_ENTRY ListHead,
10134  IN PDRIVER_FS_NOTIFICATION DriverNotificationRoutine,
10135  IN BOOLEAN SkipRaw
10136  )
10137 /*++
10138 
10139 Routine Description:
10140 
10141  This routine calls the driver notification routine for filesystems
10142  that have already been registered at the time of the call.
10143 
10144 Arguments:
10145 
10146  ListHead - Pointer to the filesystem registration list head.
10147  DriverNotificationRoutine - Pointer to the routine that has to be called.
10148 
10149 Return Value:
10150 
10151  None.
10152 
10153 --*/
10154 {
10155  PLIST_ENTRY entry;
10156  PDEVICE_OBJECT fsDeviceObject;
10157 
10158  entry = ListHead->Flink;
10159  while (entry != ListHead) {
10160 
10161  //
10162  // Skip raw filesystem notification
10163  //
10164  if ((entry->Flink == ListHead) && (SkipRaw)) {
10165  break;
10166  }
10167 
10168  fsDeviceObject = CONTAINING_RECORD( entry, DEVICE_OBJECT, Queue.ListEntry );
10169  entry = entry->Flink;
10170  DriverNotificationRoutine( fsDeviceObject, TRUE );
10171  }
10172 }
10173 
10174 
10175 NTSTATUS
10176 IoRegisterFsRegistrationChange(
10177  IN PDRIVER_OBJECT DriverObject,
10178  IN PDRIVER_FS_NOTIFICATION DriverNotificationRoutine
10179  )
10180 
10181 /*++
10182 
10183 Routine Description:
10184 
10185  This routine registers the specified driver's notification routine to be
10186  invoked whenever a file system registers or unregisters itself as an active
10187  file system in the system.
10188 
10189 Arguments:
10190 
10191  DriverObject - Pointer to the driver object for the driver.
10192 
10193  DriverNotificationRoutine - Address of routine to invoke when a file system
10194  registers or unregisters itself.
10195 
10196 Return Value:
10197 
10198  STATUS_DEVICE_ALREADY_ATTACHED -
10199  Indicates that the caller has already registered
10200  last with the same driver object & driver notification
10201 
10202  STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES
10203  STATUS_SUCCESS
10204 
10205 --*/
10206 
10207 {
10208  PNOTIFICATION_PACKET nPacket;
10209 
10210  PAGED_CODE();
10211 
10212  ExAcquireResourceExclusiveLite( &IopDatabaseResource, TRUE );
10213 
10214  if (!IsListEmpty( &IopFsNotifyChangeQueueHead )) {
10215 
10216  //
10217  // Retrieve entry at tail of list
10218  //
10219 
10220  nPacket = CONTAINING_RECORD( IopFsNotifyChangeQueueHead.Blink, NOTIFICATION_PACKET, ListEntry );
10221 
10222  if ((nPacket->DriverObject == DriverObject) &&
10223  (nPacket->NotificationRoutine == DriverNotificationRoutine)) {
10224 
10225  ExReleaseResourceLite( &IopDatabaseResource);
10226  return STATUS_DEVICE_ALREADY_ATTACHED;
10227  }
10228  }
10229 
10230  //
10231  // Begin by attempting to allocate storage for the shutdown packet. If
10232  // one cannot be allocated, simply return an appropriate error.
10233  //
10234 
10235  nPacket = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( PagedPool|POOL_COLD_ALLOCATION,
10236  sizeof( NOTIFICATION_PACKET ),
10237  'sFoI' );
10238  if (!nPacket) {
10239 
10240  ExReleaseResourceLite( &IopDatabaseResource );
10241  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
10242  }
10243 
10244  //
10245  // Initialize the notification packet and insert it onto the tail of the
10246  // list.
10247  //
10248 
10249  nPacket->DriverObject = DriverObject;
10250  nPacket->NotificationRoutine = DriverNotificationRoutine;
10251 
10252  InsertTailList( &IopFsNotifyChangeQueueHead, &nPacket->ListEntry );
10253 
10254  IopNotifyAlreadyRegisteredFileSystems(&IopNetworkFileSystemQueueHead, DriverNotificationRoutine, FALSE);
10255  IopNotifyAlreadyRegisteredFileSystems(&IopCdRomFileSystemQueueHead, DriverNotificationRoutine, TRUE);
10256  IopNotifyAlreadyRegisteredFileSystems(&IopDiskFileSystemQueueHead, DriverNotificationRoutine, TRUE);
10257  IopNotifyAlreadyRegisteredFileSystems(&IopTapeFileSystemQueueHead, DriverNotificationRoutine, TRUE);
10258 
10259  //
10260  // Notify this driver about all already notified filesystems
10261  // registered as an active file system of some type.
10262  //
10263 
10264 
10265  ExReleaseResourceLite( &IopDatabaseResource );
10266 
10267  //
10268  // Increment the number of reasons that this driver cannot be unloaded.
10269  //
10270 
10271  ObReferenceObject( DriverObject );
10272 
10273  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
10274 }
10275

10277 NTSTATUS
10278 IoRegisterLastChanceShutdownNotification(
10279  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject
10280  )
10281 
10282 /*++
10283 
10284 Routine Description:
10285 
10286  This routine allows a driver to register that it would like to have its
10287  shutdown routine invoked at very late in system shutdown. This gives
10288  the driver an opportunity to get control just before the system is fully
10289  shutdown.
10290 
10291 Arguments:
10292 
10293  DeviceObject - Pointer to the driver's device object.
10294 
10295 Return Value:
10296 
10297  None.
10298 
10299 --*/
10300 
10301 {
10302  PSHUTDOWN_PACKET shutdown;
10303 
10304  PAGED_CODE();
10305 
10306  //
10307  // Begin by attempting to allocate storage for the shutdown packet. If
10308  // one cannot be allocated, simply return an appropriate error.
10309  //
10310 
10311  shutdown = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( NonPagedPool,
10312  sizeof( SHUTDOWN_PACKET ),
10313  'hSoI' );
10314  if (!shutdown) {
10315  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
10316  }
10317 
10318  //
10319  // Initialize the shutdown packet and insert it onto the head of the list.
10320  // Note that this is done because some drivers have dependencies on LIFO
10321  // notification ordering.
10322  //
10323 
10324  ObReferenceObject(DeviceObject); // Ensure that the driver remains
10325  shutdown->DeviceObject = DeviceObject;
10326 
10327  IopInterlockedInsertHeadList( &IopNotifyLastChanceShutdownQueueHead,
10328  &shutdown->ListEntry );
10329 
10330  //
10331  // Do the bookkeeping to indicate that this driver has successfully
10332  // registered a shutdown notification routine.
10333  //
10334 
10335  DeviceObject->Flags |= DO_SHUTDOWN_REGISTERED;
10336 
10337  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
10338 }

10465 VOID
10466 IoRemoveShareAccess(
10467  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
10468  IN OUT PSHARE_ACCESS ShareAccess
10469  )
10470 
10471 /*++
10472 
10473 Routine Description:
10474 
10475  This routine is invoked to remove the access and share access information
10476  in a file system Share Access structure for a given open instance.
10477 
10478 Arguments:
10479 
10480  FileObject - Pointer to the file object of the current access being closed.
10481 
10482  ShareAccess - Pointer to the share access structure that describes
10483  how the file is currently being accessed.
10484 
10485 Return Value:
10486 
10487  None.
10488 
10489 --*/
10490 
10491 {
10492  PAGED_CODE();
10493 
10494  //
10495  // If this accessor wanted some type of access other than READ_ or
10496  // WRITE_ATTRIBUTES, then account for the fact that he has closed the
10497  // file. Otherwise, he hasn't been accounted for in the first place
10498  // so don't do anything.
10499  //
10500 
10501  //
10502  // If this is a special filter fileobject ignore share access check if necessary.
10503  //
10504 
10505  if (FileObject->Flags & FO_FILE_OBJECT_HAS_EXTENSION) {
10506  PIOP_FILE_OBJECT_EXTENSION fileObjectExtension =(PIOP_FILE_OBJECT_EXTENSION)(FileObject + 1);
10507 
10508  if (fileObjectExtension->FileObjectExtensionFlags & FO_EXTENSION_IGNORE_SHARE_ACCESS_CHECK) {
10509  return;
10510  }
10511  }
10512 
10513  if (FileObject->ReadAccess ||
10514  FileObject->WriteAccess ||
10515  FileObject->DeleteAccess) {
10516 
10517  //
10518  // Decrement the number of opens in the Share Access structure.
10519  //
10520 
10521  ShareAccess->OpenCount--;
10522 
10523  //
10524  // For each access type, decrement the appropriate count in the Share
10525  // Access structure.
10526  //
10527 
10528  if (FileObject->ReadAccess) {
10529  ShareAccess->Readers--;
10530  }
10531 
10532  if (FileObject->WriteAccess) {
10533  ShareAccess->Writers--;
10534  }
10535 
10536  if (FileObject->DeleteAccess) {
10537  ShareAccess->Deleters--;
10538  }
10539 
10540  //
10541  // For each shared access type, decrement the appropriate count in the
10542  // Share Access structure.
10543  //
10544 
10545  if (FileObject->SharedRead) {
10546  ShareAccess->SharedRead--;
10547  }
10548 
10549  if (FileObject->SharedWrite) {
10550  ShareAccess->SharedWrite--;
10551  }
10552 
10553  if (FileObject->SharedDelete) {
10554  ShareAccess->SharedDelete--;
10555  }
10556  }
10557 }
10558 
10559 VOID
10560 IoSetDeviceToVerify(
10561  IN PETHREAD Thread,
10562  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject
10563  )

10569  This routine sets the device to verify field in the thread object. This

10587 
10588 --*/
