10598 VOID
10599 IoSetHardErrorOrVerifyDevice(
10600  IN PIRP Irp,
10601  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject
10602  )
10603 
10604 /*++
10605 
10606 Routine Description:
10607 
10608  This routine is invoked when a driver realizes that the media
10609  has possibly changed on a device, and it must be verified before
10610  continuing, or a hard error has occured. The device is stored
10611  in the thread local storage of the Irp's originating thread.
10612 
10613 Arguments:
10614 
10615  Irp - Pointer to an I/O Request Packet to get the thread.
10616 
10617  DeviceObject - This is the device that needs to be verified.
10618 
10619 Return Value:
10620 
10621  None.
10622 
10623 --*/
10624 
10625 {
10626 
10627  //
10628  // If this IRP is not associated with a thread do nothing.
10629  // Its a defensive check to catch drivers that pass
10630  // all kinds of IRPs to this routine.
10631  //
10632 
10633  if (!Irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread) {
10634  return;
10635  }
10636 
10637 
10638  //
10639  // Store the address of the device object that needs verification in
10640  // the appropriate field of the thread pointed to by the specified I/O
10641  // Request Packet.
10642  //
10643 
10644 
10645 
10646  Irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread->DeviceToVerify = DeviceObject;
10647 }
10648 
10649 NTSTATUS
10650 IoSetInformation(
10651  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
10652  IN FILE_INFORMATION_CLASS FileInformationClass,
10653  IN ULONG Length,
10654  IN PVOID FileInformation
10655  )
10656 
10657 /*++
10658 
10659 Routine Description:
10660 
10661  This routine sets the requested information for the specified file.
10662  The information that is set is determined by the FileInformationClass
10663  parameter, and the information itself is passed in the FileInformation
10664  buffer.
10665 
10666 Arguments:
10667 
10668  FileObject - Supplies a pointer to the file object for the file that
10669  is to be changed.
10670 
10671  FileInformationClass - Specifies the type of information that should
10672  be set on the file.
10673 
10674  Length - Supplies the length of the FileInformation buffer in bytes.
10675 
10676  FileInformation - A buffer containing the file information to set. This
10677  buffer must not be pageable and must reside in system space.
10678 
10679 Return Value:
10680 
10681  The status returned is the final completion status of the operation.
10682 
10683 
10684 --*/
10685 
10686 {
10687  PIRP irp;
10688  NTSTATUS status;
10689  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
10690  KEVENT event;
10691  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
10692  IO_STATUS_BLOCK localIoStatus;
10693  HANDLE targetHandle = NULL;
10694  BOOLEAN synchronousIo;
10695 
10696  PAGED_CODE();
10697 
10698  //
10699  // Reference the file object here so that no special checks need be made
10700  // in I/O completion to determine whether or not to dereference the file
10701  // object.
10702  //
10703 
10704  ObReferenceObject( FileObject );
10705 
10706  //
10707  // Make a special check here to determine whether this is a synchronous
10708  // I/O operation. If it is, then wait here until the file is owned by
10709  // the current thread. If this is not a (serialized) synchronous I/O
10710  // operation, then initialize the local event.
10711  //
10712 
10713  if (FileObject->Flags & FO_SYNCHRONOUS_IO) {
10714 
10715  BOOLEAN interrupted;
10716 
10717  if (!IopAcquireFastLock( FileObject )) {
10718  status = IopAcquireFileObjectLock( FileObject,
10719  KernelMode,
10720  (BOOLEAN) ((FileObject->Flags & FO_ALERTABLE_IO) != 0),
10721  &interrupted );
10722  if (interrupted) {
10723  ObDereferenceObject( FileObject );
10724  return status;
10725  }
10726  }
10727  KeClearEvent( &FileObject->Event );
10728  synchronousIo = TRUE;
10729  } else {
10730  KeInitializeEvent( &event, SynchronizationEvent, FALSE );
10731  synchronousIo = FALSE;
10732  }
10733 
10734  //
10735  // Get the address of the target device object.
10736  //
10737 
10738  deviceObject = IoGetRelatedDeviceObject( FileObject );
10739 
10740  //
10741  // Allocate and initialize the I/O Request Packet (IRP) for this operation.
10742  // The allocation is performed with an exception handler in case there is
10743  // not enough memory to satisfy the request.
10744  //
10745 
10746  irp = IoAllocateIrp( deviceObject->StackSize, !synchronousIo );
10747  if (!irp) {
10748 
10749  //
10750  // An IRP could not be allocated. Cleanup and return an appropriate
10751  // error status code.
10752  //
10753 
10754  IopAllocateIrpCleanup( FileObject, (PKEVENT) NULL );
10755 
10756  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
10757  }
10758  irp->Tail.Overlay.OriginalFileObject = FileObject;
10759  irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread = PsGetCurrentThread();
10760  irp->RequestorMode = KernelMode;
10761 
10762  //
10763  // Fill in the service independent parameters in the IRP.
10764  //
10765 
10766  if (synchronousIo) {
10767  irp->UserEvent = (PKEVENT) NULL;
10768  } else {
10769  irp->UserEvent = &event;
10770  irp->Flags = IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_API;
10771  }
10772  irp->UserIosb = &localIoStatus;
10773 
10774  //
10775  // Get a pointer to the stack location for the first driver. This will be
10776  // used to pass the original function codes and parameters.
10777  //
10778 
10779  irpSp = IoGetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
10780  irpSp->MajorFunction = IRP_MJ_SET_INFORMATION;
10781  irpSp->FileObject = FileObject;
10782 
10783  //
10784  // Set the system buffer address to the address of the caller's buffer and
10785  // set the flags so that the buffer is not deallocated.
10786  //
10787 
10788  irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer = FileInformation;
10789  irp->Flags |= IRP_BUFFERED_IO;
10790 
10791  //
10792  // Copy the caller's parameters to the service-specific portion of the IRP.
10793  //
10794 
10795  irpSp->Parameters.SetFile.Length = Length;
10796  irpSp->Parameters.SetFile.FileInformationClass = FileInformationClass;
10797 
10798  //
10799  // Insert the packet at the head of the IRP list for the thread.
10800  //
10801 
10802  IopQueueThreadIrp( irp );
10803 
10804  //
10805  // Everything is now set to invoke the device driver with this request.
10806  // However, it is possible that the information that the caller wants to
10807  // set is device independent (I/O system dependent). If this is the case,
10808  // then the request can be satisfied here without having to have all of
10809  // the drivers implement the same code. Note that having the IRP is still
10810  // necessary since the I/O completion code requires it.
10811  //
10812 
10813  if (FileInformationClass == FileModeInformation) {
10814 
10815  PFILE_MODE_INFORMATION modeBuffer = FileInformation;
10816 
10817  //
10818  // Set or clear the appropriate flags in the file object.
10819  //
10820 
10821  if (!(FileObject->Flags & FO_NO_INTERMEDIATE_BUFFERING)) {
10822  if (modeBuffer->Mode & FILE_WRITE_THROUGH) {
10823  FileObject->Flags |= FO_WRITE_THROUGH;
10824  } else {
10825  FileObject->Flags &= ~FO_WRITE_THROUGH;
10826  }
10827  }
10828 
10829  if (modeBuffer->Mode & FILE_SEQUENTIAL_ONLY) {
10830  FileObject->Flags |= FO_SEQUENTIAL_ONLY;
10831  } else {
10832  FileObject->Flags &= ~FO_SEQUENTIAL_ONLY;
10833  }
10834 
10835  if (modeBuffer->Mode & FO_SYNCHRONOUS_IO) {
10836  if (modeBuffer->Mode & FILE_SYNCHRONOUS_IO_ALERT) {
10837  FileObject->Flags |= FO_ALERTABLE_IO;
10838  } else {
10839  FileObject->Flags &= ~FO_ALERTABLE_IO;
10840  }
10841  }
10842 
10843  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
10844 
10845  //
10846  // Complete the I/O operation.
10847  //
10848 
10849  irp->IoStatus.Status = status;
10850  irp->IoStatus.Information = 0;
10851 
10852  IoSetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
10853  IoCompleteRequest( irp, 0 );
10854 
10855  } else if (FileInformationClass == FileRenameInformation ||
10856  FileInformationClass == FileLinkInformation ||
10857  FileInformationClass == FileMoveClusterInformation) {
10858 
10859  //
10860  // Note that the following code assumes that a rename information
10861  // and a set link information structure look exactly the same.
10862  //
10863 
10864  PFILE_RENAME_INFORMATION renameBuffer = FileInformation;
10865 
10866  //
10867  // Copy the value of the replace BOOLEAN (or the ClusterCount field)
10868  // from the caller's buffer to the I/O stack location parameter
10869  // field where it is expected by file systems.
10870  //
10871 
10872  if (FileInformationClass == FileMoveClusterInformation) {
10873  irpSp->Parameters.SetFile.ClusterCount =
10874  ((FILE_MOVE_CLUSTER_INFORMATION *) renameBuffer)->ClusterCount;
10875  } else {
10876  irpSp->Parameters.SetFile.ReplaceIfExists = renameBuffer->ReplaceIfExists;
10877  }
10878 
10879  //
10880  // Check to see whether or not a fully qualified pathname was supplied.
10881  // If so, then more processing is required.
10882  //
10883 
10884  if (renameBuffer->FileName[0] == (UCHAR) OBJ_NAME_PATH_SEPARATOR ||
10885  renameBuffer->RootDirectory != NULL) {
10886 
10887  //
10888  // A fully qualified file name was specified as the target of the
10889  // rename operation. Attempt to open the target file and ensure
10890  // that the replacement policy for the file is consistent with the
10891  // caller's request, and ensure that the file is on the same volume.
10892  //
10893 
10894  status = IopOpenLinkOrRenameTarget( &targetHandle,
10895  irp,
10896  renameBuffer,
10897  FileObject );
10898  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
10899  IoSetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
10900  IoCompleteRequest( irp, 2 );
10901 
10902  } else {
10903 
10904  //
10905  // The fully qualified file name specifies a file on the same
10906  // volume and if it exists, then the caller specified that it
10907  // should be replaced.
10908  //
10909 
10910  status = IoCallDriver( deviceObject, irp );
10911 
10912  }
10913 
10914  } else {
10915 
10916  //
10917  // This is a simple rename operation, so call the driver and let
10918  // it perform the rename operation within the same directory as
10919  // the source file.
10920  //
10921 
10922  status = IoCallDriver( deviceObject, irp );
10923 
10924  }
10925 
10926  } else {
10927 
10928  //
10929  // This is not a request that can be performed here, so invoke the
10930  // driver at its appropriate dispatch entry with the IRP.
10931  //
10932 
10933  status = IoCallDriver( deviceObject, irp );
10934 
10935  }
10936 
10937  //
10938  // If this operation was a synchronous I/O operation, check the return
10939  // status to determine whether or not to wait on the file object. If
10940  // the file object is to be waited on, wait for the operation to complete
10941  // and obtain the final status from the file object itself.
10942  //
10943 
10944  if (synchronousIo) {
10945  if (status == STATUS_PENDING) {
10946  status = KeWaitForSingleObject( &FileObject->Event,
10947  Executive,
10948  KernelMode,
10949  (BOOLEAN) ((FileObject->Flags & FO_ALERTABLE_IO) != 0),
10950  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
10951  if (status == STATUS_ALERTED) {
10952  IopCancelAlertedRequest( &FileObject->Event, irp );
10953  }
10954  status = localIoStatus.Status;
10955  }
10956  IopReleaseFileObjectLock( FileObject );
10957 
10958  } else {
10959 
10960  //
10961  // This is a normal synchronous I/O operation, as opposed to a
10962  // serialized synchronous I/O operation. For this case, wait for
10963  // the local event and copy the final status information back to
10964  // the caller.
10965  //
10966 
10967  if (status == STATUS_PENDING) {
10968  (VOID) KeWaitForSingleObject( &event,
10969  Executive,
10970  KernelMode,
10971  FALSE,
10972  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
10973  status = localIoStatus.Status;
10974  }
10975  }
10976 
10977  //
10978  // If a target handle was created because of a rename operation, close
10979  // the handle now.
10980  //
10981 
10982  if (targetHandle != (HANDLE) NULL) {
10983  ObCloseHandle( targetHandle , KernelMode);
10984  }
10985 
10986  return status;
10987 }
10988 
10989 VOID
10990 IoSetShareAccess(
10991  IN ACCESS_MASK DesiredAccess,
10992  IN ULONG DesiredShareAccess,
10993  IN OUT PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
10994  OUT PSHARE_ACCESS ShareAccess
10995  )
10996 
10997 /*++
10998 
10999 Routine Description:
11000 
11001  This routine is invoked to set the access and share access information
11002  in a file system Share Access structure for the first open.
11003 
11004 Arguments:
11005 
11006  DesiredAccess - Desired access of current open request.
11007 
11008  DesiredShareAccess - Shared access requested by current open request.
11009 
11010  FileObject - Pointer to the file object of the current open request.
11011 
11012  ShareAccess - Pointer to the share access structure that describes
11013  how the file is currently being accessed.
11014 
11015 Return Value:
11016 
11017  None.
11018 
11019 --*/
11020 
11021 {
11022  BOOLEAN update = TRUE;
11023 
11024  PAGED_CODE();
11025 
11026  //
11027  // Set the access type in the file object for the current accessor.
11028  //
11029 
11030  FileObject->ReadAccess = (BOOLEAN) ((DesiredAccess & (FILE_EXECUTE
11031  | FILE_READ_DATA)) != 0);
11032  FileObject->WriteAccess = (BOOLEAN) ((DesiredAccess & (FILE_WRITE_DATA
11033  | FILE_APPEND_DATA)) != 0);
11034  FileObject->DeleteAccess = (BOOLEAN) ((DesiredAccess & DELETE) != 0);
11035 
11036  //
11037  // If this is a special filter fileobject ignore share access check if necessary.
11038  //
11039 
11040  if (FileObject->Flags & FO_FILE_OBJECT_HAS_EXTENSION) {
11041  PIOP_FILE_OBJECT_EXTENSION fileObjectExtension =(PIOP_FILE_OBJECT_EXTENSION)(FileObject + 1);
11042 
11043  if (fileObjectExtension->FileObjectExtensionFlags & FO_EXTENSION_IGNORE_SHARE_ACCESS_CHECK) {
11044 
11045  //
11046  // This fileobject is marked to ignore share access checks
11047  // so we also don't want to affect the file/directory's
11048  // ShareAccess structure counts.
11049  //
11050 
11051  update = FALSE;
11052  }
11053  }
11054 
11055  //
11056  // Check to see whether the current file opener would like to read,
11057  // write, or delete the file. If so, account for it in the share access
11058  // structure; otherwise, skip it.
11059  //
11060 
11061  if (FileObject->ReadAccess ||
11062  FileObject->WriteAccess ||
11063  FileObject->DeleteAccess) {
11064 
11065  //
11066  // Only update the share modes if the user wants to read, write or
11067  // delete the file.
11068  //
11069 
11070  FileObject->SharedRead = (BOOLEAN) ((DesiredShareAccess & FILE_SHARE_READ) != 0);
11071  FileObject->SharedWrite = (BOOLEAN) ((DesiredShareAccess & FILE_SHARE_WRITE) != 0);
11072  FileObject->SharedDelete = (BOOLEAN) ((DesiredShareAccess & FILE_SHARE_DELETE) != 0);
11073 
11074  if (update) {
11075 
11076  //
11077  // Set the Share Access structure open count.
11078  //
11079 
11080  ShareAccess->OpenCount = 1;
11081 
11082  //
11083  // Set the number of readers, writers, and deleters in the Share Access
11084  // structure.
11085  //
11086 
11087  ShareAccess->Readers = FileObject->ReadAccess;
11088  ShareAccess->Writers = FileObject->WriteAccess;
11089  ShareAccess->Deleters = FileObject->DeleteAccess;
11090 
11091  //
11092  // Set the number of shared readers, writers, and deleters in the Share
11093  // Access structure.
11094  //
11095 
11096  ShareAccess->SharedRead = FileObject->SharedRead;
11097  ShareAccess->SharedWrite = FileObject->SharedWrite;
11098  ShareAccess->SharedDelete = FileObject->SharedDelete;
11099  }
11100 
11101  } else {
11102 
11103  //
11104  // No read, write, or delete access has been requested. Simply zero
11105  // the appropriate fields in the structure so that the next accessor
11106  // sees a consistent state.
11107  //
11108 
11109  if (update) {
11110 
11111  ShareAccess->OpenCount = 0;
11112  ShareAccess->Readers = 0;
11113  ShareAccess->Writers = 0;
11114  ShareAccess->Deleters = 0;
11115  ShareAccess->SharedRead = 0;
11116  ShareAccess->SharedWrite = 0;
11117  ShareAccess->SharedDelete = 0;
11118  }
11119  }
11120 }
11121 
11122 BOOLEAN
11123 IoSetThreadHardErrorMode(
11124  IN BOOLEAN EnableHardErrors
11125  )
11126 
11127 /*++
11128 
11129 Routine Description:
11130 
11131  This routine either enables or disables hard errors for the current
11132  thread and returns the old state of the flag.
11133 
11134 Arguments:
11135 
11136  EnableHardErrors - Supplies a BOOLEAN value indicating whether or not
11137  hard errors are to be enabled for the current thread.
11138 
11139 Return Value:
11140 
11141  The final function value is the previous state of whether or not hard
11142  errors were enabled.
11143 
11144 --*/
11145 
11146 {
11147  PETHREAD thread;
11148  BOOLEAN oldFlag;
11149 
11150  //
11151  // Get a pointer to the current thread, capture the current state of
11152  // hard errors, and set the new state.
11153  //
11154 
11155  thread = PsGetCurrentThread();
11156 
11157  if ((thread->CrossThreadFlags&PS_CROSS_THREAD_FLAGS_HARD_ERRORS_DISABLED) == 0) {
11158  oldFlag = TRUE;
11159  }
11160  else {
11161  oldFlag = FALSE;
11162  }
11163 
11164  if (EnableHardErrors) {
11165  PS_CLEAR_BITS (&thread->CrossThreadFlags, PS_CROSS_THREAD_FLAGS_HARD_ERRORS_DISABLED);
11166  } else {
11167  PS_SET_BITS (&thread->CrossThreadFlags, PS_CROSS_THREAD_FLAGS_HARD_ERRORS_DISABLED);
11168  }
11169 
11170  return oldFlag;
11171 }

11173 VOID
11174 IoSetTopLevelIrp(
11175  IN PIRP Irp
11176  )
11177 
11178 /*++
11179 
11180 Routine Description:
11181 
11182  This routine sets the top level IRP field in the current thread's thread
11183  object. This function is invoked by file systems to either set this field
11184  to the address of an I/O Request Packet (IRP) or to null it.
11185 
11186 Arguments:
11187 
11188  Irp - Pointer to the IRP to be stored in the top level IRP field.
11189 
11190 Return Value:
11191 
11192  None.
11193 
11194 Note:
11195 
11196  This function cannot be made a macro, since fields in the thread object
11197  move from release to release, so this must remain a full function.
11198 
11199 --*/
11200 
11201 {
11202  //
11203  // Simply set the top level IRP field in the current thread's thread
11204  // object.
11205  //
11206 
11207  PsGetCurrentThread()->TopLevelIrp = (ULONG_PTR) Irp;
11208  return;
11209 }
11210 
11211 VOID
11212 IoShutdownSystem (
11213  IN ULONG Phase
11214  )
11215 
11216 /*++
11217 
11218 Routine Description:
11219 
11220  This routine shuts down the I/O portion of the system in preparation
11221  for a power-off or reboot.
11222 
11223 Arguments:
11224 
11225  RebootPending - Indicates whether a reboot is imminently pending.
11226 
11227  Phase - Indicates which phase of shutdown is being performed.
11228 
11229 Return Value:
11230 
11231  None
11232 
11233 --*/
11234 
11235 {
11236  PSHUTDOWN_PACKET shutdown;
11237  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
11238  PIRP irp;
11239  PLIST_ENTRY entry;
11240  KEVENT event;
11241  IO_STATUS_BLOCK ioStatus;
11242 
11243  PAGED_CODE();
11244 
11245  //
11246  // Initialize the event used to synchronize the complete of all of the
11247  // shutdown routines.
11248  //
11249 
11250  KeInitializeEvent( &event, NotificationEvent, FALSE );
11251 
11252  if (Phase == 0) {
11253 
11254  ZwClose(IopLinkTrackingServiceEventHandle);
11255 
11256  IoShutdownPnpDevices();
11257 
11258  //
11259  // Walk the list of the drivers in the system that have registered
11260  // themselves as wanting to know when the system is about to be
11261  // shutdown and invoke each.
11262  //
11263 
11264  while ((entry = IopInterlockedRemoveHeadList( &IopNotifyShutdownQueueHead )) != NULL) {
11265  shutdown = CONTAINING_RECORD( entry, SHUTDOWN_PACKET, ListEntry );
11266 
11267  //
11268  // Another driver has been found that has indicated that it requires
11269  // shutdown notification. Invoke the driver's shutdown entry point.
11270  //
11271 
11272  deviceObject = IoGetAttachedDeviceReference( shutdown->DeviceObject );
11273 
11274  irp = IoBuildSynchronousFsdRequest( IRP_MJ_SHUTDOWN,
11275  deviceObject,
11276  (PVOID) NULL,
11277  0,
11278  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL,
11279  &event,
11280  &ioStatus );
11281 
11282  //
11283  // If we get an IRP issue the shutdown. Otherwise just skip the driver. Its unfortunate but even
11284  // drivers if they fail in memory allocations on shutdown have to skip it.
11285  //
11286 
11287  if (irp) {
11288  if (IoCallDriver( deviceObject, irp ) == STATUS_PENDING) {
11289 #if DBG
11290  PUNICODE_STRING DeviceName = ObGetObjectName( shutdown->DeviceObject );
11291 
11292  DbgPrint( "IO: Waiting for shutdown of device object (%x) - %wZ\n",
11293  shutdown->DeviceObject,
11294  DeviceName
11295  );
11296 #endif // DBG
11297  (VOID) KeWaitForSingleObject( &event,
11298  Executive,
11299  KernelMode,
11300  FALSE,
11301  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
11302  }
11303  }
11304 
11305  ObDereferenceObject(deviceObject);
11306  ObDereferenceObject(shutdown->DeviceObject);
11307  ExFreePool( shutdown );
11308  KeClearEvent( &event );
11309  }
11310 
11311  IOV_UNLOAD_DRIVERS();
11312 
11313  } else if (Phase == 1) {
11314 
11315 #if defined(REMOTE_BOOT)
11316  //
11317  // If this is a remote boot client then allow the cache to close the database and
11318  // mark it clean.
11319  //
11320 
11321  IopShutdownCsc();
11322 #endif // defined(REMOTE_BOOT)
11323 
11324  // Gain access to the file system header queues by acquiring the
11325  // database resource for shared access.
11326  //
11327 
11328  ExAcquireResourceExclusiveLite( &IopDatabaseResource, TRUE );
11329 
11330  IopShutdownBaseFileSystems(&IopDiskFileSystemQueueHead);
11331 
11332  IopShutdownBaseFileSystems(&IopCdRomFileSystemQueueHead);
11333 
11334  IopShutdownBaseFileSystems(&IopTapeFileSystemQueueHead);
11335 
11336 
11337  //
11338  // Walk the list of the drivers in the system that have registered
11339  // themselves as wanting to know at the last chance when the system
11340  // is about to be shutdown and invoke each.
11341  //
11342 
11343  while ((entry = IopInterlockedRemoveHeadList( &IopNotifyLastChanceShutdownQueueHead )) != NULL) {
11344  shutdown = CONTAINING_RECORD( entry, SHUTDOWN_PACKET, ListEntry );
11345 
11346  //
11347  // Another driver has been found that has indicated that it requires
11348  // shutdown notification. Invoke the driver's shutdown entry point.
11349  //
11350 
11351  deviceObject = IoGetAttachedDeviceReference( shutdown->DeviceObject );
11352 
11353  irp = IoBuildSynchronousFsdRequest( IRP_MJ_SHUTDOWN,
11354  deviceObject,
11355  (PVOID) NULL,
11356  0,
11357  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL,
11358  &event,
11359  &ioStatus );
11360 
11361  if (irp) {
11362  if (IoCallDriver( deviceObject, irp ) == STATUS_PENDING) {
11363 #if DBG
11364  PUNICODE_STRING DeviceName = ObGetObjectName( shutdown->DeviceObject );
11365 
11366  DbgPrint( "IO: Waiting for last chance shutdown of device object (%x) - %wZ\n",
11367  shutdown->DeviceObject,
11368  DeviceName
11369  );
11370 #endif // DBG
11371  (VOID) KeWaitForSingleObject( &event,
11372  Executive,
11373  KernelMode,
11374  FALSE,
11375  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
11376  }
11377  }
11378 
11379  ObDereferenceObject(deviceObject);
11380  ObDereferenceObject(shutdown->DeviceObject);
11381 
11382  ExFreePool( shutdown );
11383  KeClearEvent( &event );
11384  }
11385 
11386  //
11387  // N.B. The system has stopped. The IopDatabaseResource lock is
11388  // not released so that no other mount operations can take place.
11389  //
11390  // ExReleaseResourceLite( &IopDatabaseResource );
11391  //
11392  }
11393 
11394  return ;
11395 }
11396 
11397 VOID
11398 IopShutdownBaseFileSystems(
11399  IN PLIST_ENTRY ListHead
11400  )
11401 {
11402  PLIST_ENTRY entry;
11403  KEVENT event;
11404  IO_STATUS_BLOCK ioStatus;
11405  PDEVICE_OBJECT baseDeviceObject;
11406  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
11407  PIRP irp;
11408 
11409  //
11410  // Loop through each of the disk file systems, invoking each to shutdown
11411  // each of their mounted volumes.
11412  //
11413 
11414  KeInitializeEvent( &event, NotificationEvent, FALSE );
11415  entry = RemoveHeadList(ListHead);
11416 
11417  while (entry != ListHead) {
11418 
11419  baseDeviceObject = CONTAINING_RECORD( entry, DEVICE_OBJECT, Queue.ListEntry );
11420 
11421  //
11422  // We have removed the entry. If the filesystem in this thread calls IoUnregisterFileSystem
11423  // then we won't remove the entry from the list as the Flink == NULL.
11424  //
11425 
11426 
11427  baseDeviceObject->Queue.ListEntry.Flink = NULL;
11428  baseDeviceObject->Queue.ListEntry.Blink = NULL;
11429 
11430  //
11431  // Prevent the driver from getting unloaded while shutdown handler is in progress.
11432  // Also prevent the base device object from going away as we need to decrement the
11433  // reasons for unload count later.
11434  //
11435 
11436  ObReferenceObject(baseDeviceObject);
11437  IopInterlockedIncrementUlong( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock,
11438  &baseDeviceObject->ReferenceCount );
11439 
11440  deviceObject = baseDeviceObject;
11441  if (baseDeviceObject->AttachedDevice) {
11442  deviceObject = IoGetAttachedDevice( baseDeviceObject );
11443  }
11444 
11445  //
11446  // Another file system has been found. Invoke this file system at
11447  // its shutdown entry point.
11448  //
11449 
11450  irp = IoBuildSynchronousFsdRequest( IRP_MJ_SHUTDOWN,
11451  deviceObject,
11452  (PVOID) NULL,
11453  0,
11454  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL,
11455  &event,
11456  &ioStatus );
11457  //
11458  // Its possible that the drivers are unloaded before this call returns but IoCallDriver
11459  // takes a reference to the device object before calling the driver. So the image will not
11460  // get unloaded.
11461  //
11462 
11463  if (irp) {
11464  if (IoCallDriver( deviceObject, irp ) == STATUS_PENDING) {
11465  (VOID) KeWaitForSingleObject( &event,
11466  Executive,
11467  KernelMode,
11468  FALSE,
11469  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
11470  }
11471  }
11472  entry = RemoveHeadList(ListHead);
11473 
11474  KeClearEvent( &event );
11475 
11476  IopDecrementDeviceObjectRef(baseDeviceObject, FALSE, TRUE);
11477  ObDereferenceObject(baseDeviceObject);
11478  }
11479 }
11480 
11481 
11482 VOID
11483 IopStartNextPacket(
11484  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
11485  IN LOGICAL Cancelable
11486  )
11487 
11488 /*++
11489 
11490 Routine Description:
11491 
11492  This routine is invoked to dequeue the next packet (IRP) from the
11493  specified device work queue and invoke the device driver's start I/O
11494  routine for it. If the Cancelable parameter is TRUE, then the update of
11495  current IRP is synchronized using the cancel spinlock.
11496 
11497 Arguments:
11498 
11499  DeviceObject - Pointer to device object itself.
11500 
11501  Cancelable - Indicates that IRPs in the device queue may be cancelable.
11502 
11503 Return Value:
11504 
11505  None.
11506 
11507 --*/
11508 
11509 {
11510  KIRQL cancelIrql = PASSIVE_LEVEL;
11511  PIRP irp;
11512  PKDEVICE_QUEUE_ENTRY packet;
11513 
11514  //
11515  // Begin by checking to see whether or not this driver's requests are
11516  // to be considered cancelable. If so, then acquire the cancel spinlock.
11517  //
11518 
11519  if (Cancelable) {
11520  IoAcquireCancelSpinLock( &cancelIrql );
11521  }
11522 
11523  //
11524  // Clear the current IRP field before starting another request.
11525  //
11526 
11527  DeviceObject->CurrentIrp = (PIRP) NULL;
11528 
11529  //
11530  // Remove the next packet from the head of the queue. If a packet was
11531  // found, then process it.
11532  //
11533 
11534  packet = KeRemoveDeviceQueue( &DeviceObject->DeviceQueue );
11535 
11536  if (packet) {
11537  irp = CONTAINING_RECORD( packet, IRP, Tail.Overlay.DeviceQueueEntry );
11538 
11539  //
11540  // A packet was located so make it the current packet for this
11541  // device.
11542  //
11543 
11544  DeviceObject->CurrentIrp = irp;
11545  if (Cancelable) {
11546 
11547  //
11548  // If the driver does not want the IRP in the cancelable state
11549  // then set the routine to NULL
11550  //
11551 
11552  if (DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->StartIoFlags & DOE_STARTIO_NO_CANCEL) {
11553  irp->CancelRoutine = NULL;
11554  }
11555 
11556  IoReleaseCancelSpinLock( cancelIrql );
11557  }
11558 
11559  //
11560  // Invoke the driver's start I/O routine for this packet.
11561  //
11562 
11563  DeviceObject->DriverObject->DriverStartIo( DeviceObject, irp );
11564  } else {
11565 
11566  //
11567  // No packet was found, so simply release the cancel spinlock if
11568  // it was acquired.
11569  //
11570 
11571  if (Cancelable) {
11572  IoReleaseCancelSpinLock( cancelIrql );
11573  }
11574  }
11575 }
11576 
11577 VOID
11578 IopStartNextPacketByKey(
11579  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
11580  IN LOGICAL Cancelable,
11581  IN ULONG Key
11582  )
11583 
11584 /*++
11585 
11586 Routine Description:
11587 
11588  This routine is invoked to dequeue the next packet (IRP) from the
11589  specified device work queue by key and invoke the device driver's start
11590  I/O routine for it. If the Cancelable parameter is TRUE, then the
11591  update of current IRP is synchronized using the cancel spinlock.
11592 
11593 Arguments:
11594 
11595  DeviceObject - Pointer to device object itself.
11596 
11597  Cancelable - Indicates that IRPs in the device queue may be cancelable.
11598 
11599  Key - Specifics the Key used to remove the entry from the queue.
11600 
11601 Return Value:
11602 
11603  None.
11604 
11605 --*/
11606 
11607 {
11608  KIRQL cancelIrql = PASSIVE_LEVEL;
11609  PIRP irp;
11610  PKDEVICE_QUEUE_ENTRY packet;
11611 
11612  //
11613  // Begin by determining whether or not requests for this device are to
11614  // be considered cancelable. If so, then acquire the cancel spinlock.
11615  //
11616 
11617  if (Cancelable) {
11618  IoAcquireCancelSpinLock( &cancelIrql );
11619  }
11620 
11621  //
11622  // Clear the current IRP field before starting another request.
11623  //
11624 
11625  DeviceObject->CurrentIrp = (PIRP) NULL;
11626 
11627  //
11628  // Attempt to remove the indicated packet according to the key from the
11629  // device queue. If one is found, then process it.
11630  //
11631 
11632  packet = KeRemoveByKeyDeviceQueue( &DeviceObject->DeviceQueue, Key );
11633 
11634  if (packet) {
11635  irp = CONTAINING_RECORD( packet, IRP, Tail.Overlay.DeviceQueueEntry );
11636 
11637  //
11638  // A packet was successfully located. Make it the current packet
11639  // and invoke the driver's start I/O routine for it.
11640  //
11641 
11642  DeviceObject->CurrentIrp = irp;
11643 
11644  if (Cancelable) {
11645 
11646  //
11647  // If the driver does not want the IRP in the cancelable state
11648  // then set the routine to NULL
11649  //
11650 
11651  if (DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->StartIoFlags & DOE_STARTIO_NO_CANCEL) {
11652  irp->CancelRoutine = NULL;
11653  }
11654 
11655  IoReleaseCancelSpinLock( cancelIrql );
11656  }
11657 
11658  DeviceObject->DriverObject->DriverStartIo( DeviceObject, irp );
11659 
11660  } else {
11661 
11662  //
11663  // No packet was found, so release the cancel spinlock if it was
11664  // acquired.
11665  //
11666 
11667  if (Cancelable) {
11668  IoReleaseCancelSpinLock( cancelIrql );
11669  }
11670  }
11671 }
11672 
11673 VOID
11674 IoStartPacket(
11675  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
11676  IN PIRP Irp,
11677  IN PULONG Key OPTIONAL,
11678  IN PDRIVER_CANCEL CancelFunction OPTIONAL
11679  )
11680 
11681 /*++
11682 
11683 Routine Description:
11684 
11685  This routine attempts to start the specified packet request (IRP) on the
11686  specified device. If the device is already busy, then the packet is
11687  simply queued to the device queue. If a non-NULL CancelFunction is
11688  supplied, it will be put in the IRP. If the IRP has been canceled, the
11689  CancelFunction will be called after the IRP has been inserted into the
11690  queue or made the current packet.
11691 
11692 Arguments:
11693 
11694  DeviceObject - Pointer to device object itself.
11695 
11696  Irp - I/O Request Packet which should be started on the device.
11697 
11698  Key - Key to be used in inserting packet into device queue; optional
11699  (if not specified, then packet is inserted at the tail).
11700 
11701  CancelFunction - Pointer to an optional cancel routine.
11702 
11703 Return Value:
11704 
11705  None.
11706 
11707 --*/
11708 
11709 {
11710  KIRQL oldIrql;
11711  KIRQL cancelIrql = PASSIVE_LEVEL;
11712  BOOLEAN i;
11713 
11714  //
11715  // Raise the IRQL of the processor to dispatch level for synchronization.
11716  //
11717 
11718  KeRaiseIrql( DISPATCH_LEVEL, &oldIrql );
11719 
11720  //
11721  // If the driver has indicated that packets are cancelable, then acquire
11722  // the cancel spinlock and set the address of the cancel function to
11723  // indicate that the packet is not only cancelable, but indicates what
11724  // routine to invoke should it be cancelled.
11725  //
11726 
11727  if (CancelFunction) {
11728  IoAcquireCancelSpinLock( &cancelIrql );
11729  Irp->CancelRoutine = CancelFunction;
11730  }
11731 
11732  //
11733  // If a key parameter was specified, then insert the request into the
11734  // work queue according to the key; otherwise, simply insert it at the
11735  // tail.
11736  //
11737 
11738  if (Key) {
11739  i = KeInsertByKeyDeviceQueue( &DeviceObject->DeviceQueue,
11740  &Irp->Tail.Overlay.DeviceQueueEntry,
11741  *Key );
11742  } else {
11743  i = KeInsertDeviceQueue( &DeviceObject->DeviceQueue,
11744  &Irp->Tail.Overlay.DeviceQueueEntry );
11745  }
11746 
11747  //
11748  // If the packet was not inserted into the queue, then this request is
11749  // now the current packet for this device. Indicate so by storing its
11750  // address in the current IRP field, and begin processing the request.
11751  //
11752 
11753  if (!i) {
11754 
11755  DeviceObject->CurrentIrp = Irp;
11756 
11757  if (CancelFunction) {
11758 
11759  //
11760  // If the driver does not want the IRP in the cancelable state
11761  // then set the routine to NULL
11762  //
11763 
11764  if (DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->StartIoFlags & DOE_STARTIO_NO_CANCEL) {
11765  Irp->CancelRoutine = NULL;
11766  }
11767 
11768  IoReleaseCancelSpinLock( cancelIrql );
11769  }
11770 
11771  //
11772  // Invoke the driver's start I/O routine to get the request going on the device.
11773  // The StartIo routine should handle the cancellation.
11774  //
11775 
11776  DeviceObject->DriverObject->DriverStartIo( DeviceObject, Irp );
11777 
11778  } else {
11779 
11780  //
11781  // The packet was successfully inserted into the device's work queue.
11782  // Make one last check to determine whether or not the packet has
11783  // already been marked cancelled. If it has, then invoke the
11784  // driver's cancel routine now. Note that because the cancel
11785  // spinlock is currently being held, an attempt to cancel the request
11786  // from another processor at this point will simply wait until this
11787  // routine is finished, and then get it cancelled.
11788  //
11789 
11790  if (CancelFunction) {
11791  if (Irp->Cancel) {
11792  Irp->CancelIrql = cancelIrql;
11793  Irp->CancelRoutine = (PDRIVER_CANCEL) NULL;
11794  CancelFunction( DeviceObject, Irp );
11795  } else {
11796  IoReleaseCancelSpinLock( cancelIrql );
11797  }
11798  }
11799  }
11800 
11801  //
11802  // Restore the IRQL back to its value upon entry to this function before
11803  // returning to the caller.
11804  //
11805 
11806  KeLowerIrql( oldIrql );
11807 }
11808 
11809 VOID
11810 IopStartNextPacketByKeyEx(
11811  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
11812  IN ULONG Key,
11813  IN int Flags)
11814 /*++
11815 
11816 Routine Description:
11817 
11818  This routine ensures that if the IoStartPacket* routines are called from inside StartIo then
11819  it defers calling the startio until after the StartIo call returns. It does this by keeping a count.
11820  It also keeps track of whether its cancelable or has a key by storing the value in the
11821  device object extension. They are updated without a lock because its incorrect to have two parallel
11822  calls to IoStartNextPacket or IoStartNextPacketByKey.
11823 
11824 Arguments:
11825 
11826  DeviceObject - Pointer to device object itself.
11827 
11828  Key - Specifics the Key used to remove the entry from the queue.
11829 
11830  Flags - Specifies if the deferred call has a key or is cancelable.
11831 
11832 Return Value:
11833 
11834  None.
11835 
11836 --*/
11837 {
11838  LOGICAL Cancelable;
11839  int doAnotherIteration;
11840 
11841  do {
11842  doAnotherIteration = 0;
11843  if (InterlockedIncrement(&(DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->StartIoCount)) > 1) {
11844  DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->StartIoFlags |= Flags;
11845  DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->StartIoKey = Key;
11846  } else {
11847  Cancelable = Flags & DOE_STARTIO_CANCELABLE;
11848  DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->StartIoFlags &=
11849  ~(DOE_STARTIO_REQUESTED|DOE_STARTIO_REQUESTED_BYKEY|DOE_STARTIO_CANCELABLE);
11850  DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->StartIoKey = 0;
11851  if (Flags & DOE_STARTIO_REQUESTED_BYKEY) {
11852  IopStartNextPacketByKey(DeviceObject, Cancelable, Key);
11853  }else if (Flags &DOE_STARTIO_REQUESTED){
11854  IopStartNextPacket(DeviceObject, Cancelable);
11855  }
11856  }
11857  if (InterlockedDecrement(&(DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->StartIoCount)) == 0) {
11858  Flags = DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->StartIoFlags &
11859  (DOE_STARTIO_REQUESTED|DOE_STARTIO_REQUESTED_BYKEY|DOE_STARTIO_CANCELABLE);
11860  Key = DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->StartIoKey;
11861  if (Flags & (DOE_STARTIO_REQUESTED|DOE_STARTIO_REQUESTED_BYKEY)) {
11862  doAnotherIteration++;
11863  }
11864  }
11865  } while (doAnotherIteration);
11866 }
11867 
11868 
11869 VOID
11870 IoStartNextPacket(
11871  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
11872  IN BOOLEAN Cancelable)
11873 /*++
11874 
11875 Routine Description:
11876 
11877  This routine checks the DOE flags to see if StartIO has to be deferred.
11878  If so it calls the appropriate function.
11879 
11880 Arguments:
11881 
11882  DeviceObject - Pointer to device object itself.
11883 
11884  Cancelable - Indicates that IRPs in the device queue may be cancelable.
11885 
11886 Return Value:
11887 
11888  None.
11889 
11890 --*/
11891 {
11892  if (DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->StartIoFlags & DOE_STARTIO_DEFERRED) {
11893  IopStartNextPacketByKeyEx(DeviceObject, 0, DOE_STARTIO_REQUESTED|(Cancelable ? DOE_STARTIO_CANCELABLE : 0));
11894  } else {
11895  IopStartNextPacket(DeviceObject, Cancelable);
11896  }
11897 }
11898 
11899 VOID
11900 IoStartNextPacketByKey(
11901  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
11902  IN BOOLEAN Cancelable,
11903  IN ULONG Key)
11904 /*++
11905 
11906 Routine Description:
11907 
11908  This routine checks the DOE flags to see if StartIO has to be deferred.
11909  If so it calls the appropriate function.
11910 
11911 Arguments:
11912 
11913  DeviceObject - Pointer to device object itself.
11914 
11915  Cancelable - Indicates that IRPs in the device queue may be cancelable.
11916 
11917  Key - Specifics the Key used to remove the entry from the queue.
11918 
11919 Return Value:
11920 
11921  None.
11922 
11923 --*/
11924 {
11925  if (DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->StartIoFlags & DOE_STARTIO_DEFERRED) {
11926  IopStartNextPacketByKeyEx(DeviceObject, Key, DOE_STARTIO_REQUESTED_BYKEY|(Cancelable ? DOE_STARTIO_CANCELABLE : 0));
11927  } else {
11928  IopStartNextPacketByKey(DeviceObject, Cancelable, Key);
11929  }
11930 }

11933 VOID
11934 IoSetStartIoAttributes(
11935  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
11936  IN BOOLEAN DeferredStartIo,
11937  IN BOOLEAN NonCancelable
11938  )
11939 /*++
11940 
11941 Routine Description:
11942 
11943  This routine sets the StartIo attributes so that drivers can change the
11944  behavior of when StartIo can be called.
11945 
11946 Arguments:
11947 
11948  DeviceObject - Pointer to device object itself.
11949 
11950  NonCancelable - If TRUE that IRP passed to StartIo is not in the cancelable state.
11951 
11952  DeferredStartIo - If TRUE startIo is not called recursively and is deferred until the previous
11953  StartIo call returns to the IO manager.
11954 
11955 Return Value:
11956 
11957  None.
11958 
11959 --*/
11960 {
11961  if (DeferredStartIo) {
11962  DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->StartIoFlags |= DOE_STARTIO_DEFERRED;
11963  }
11964 
11965  if (NonCancelable) {
11966  DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->StartIoFlags |= DOE_STARTIO_NO_CANCEL;
11967  }
11968 }

11971 VOID
11972 IoStartTimer(
11973  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject
11974  )
11975 
11976 /*++
11977 
11978 Routine Description:
11979 
11980  This routine starts the timer associated with the specified device object.
11981 
11982 Arguments:
11983 
11984  DeviceObject - Device object associated with the timer to be started.
11985 
11986 Return Value:
11987 
11988  None.
11989 
11990 --*/
11991 
11992 {
11993  PIO_TIMER timer;
11994  KIRQL irql;
11995 
11996 #if !DBG && defined(NT_UP)
11997  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER (irql);
11998 #endif
11999 
12000  //
12001  // Get the address of the timer.
12002  //
12003 
12004  timer = DeviceObject->Timer;
12005 
12006  //
12007  // If the driver is not being unloaded, then it is okay to start timers.
12008  //
12009 
12010  if (!(DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->ExtensionFlags &
12011  (DOE_UNLOAD_PENDING | DOE_DELETE_PENDING | DOE_REMOVE_PENDING | DOE_REMOVE_PROCESSED))) {
12012 
12013  //
12014  // Likewise, check to see whether or not the timer is already
12015  // enabled. If so, then simply exit. Otherwise, enable the timer
12016  // by placing it into the I/O system timer queue.
12017  //
12018 
12019  ExAcquireFastLock( &IopTimerLock, &irql );
12020  if (!timer->TimerFlag) {
12021  timer->TimerFlag = TRUE;
12022  IopTimerCount++;
12023  }
12024  ExReleaseFastLock( &IopTimerLock, irql );
12025  }
12026 }
12027 
12028 VOID
12029 IoStopTimer(
12030  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject
12031  )
12032 
12033 /*++
12034 
12035 Routine Description:
12036 
12037  This routines stops the timer associated with the specified device object
12038  from invoking being invoked.
12039 
12040 Arguments:
12041 
12042  DeviceObject - Device object associated with the timer to be stopped.
12043 
12044 Return Value:
12045 
12046  None.
12047 
12048 --*/
12049 
12050 {
12051  KIRQL irql;
12052  PIO_TIMER timer;
12053 
12054 #if !DBG && defined(NT_UP)
12055  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER (irql);
12056 #endif
12057 
12058  //
12059  // Obtain the I/O system timer queue lock, and disable the specified
12060  // timer.
12061  //
12062 
12063  timer = DeviceObject->Timer;
12064 
12065  ExAcquireFastLock( &IopTimerLock, &irql );
12066  if (timer->TimerFlag) {
12067  timer->TimerFlag = FALSE;
12068  IopTimerCount--;
12069  }
12070  ExReleaseFastLock( &IopTimerLock, irql );
12071 }
12072 
12073 NTSTATUS
12074 IoSynchronousPageWrite(
12075  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
12076  IN PMDL MemoryDescriptorList,
12077  IN PLARGE_INTEGER StartingOffset,
12078  IN PKEVENT Event,
12079  OUT PIO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatusBlock
12080  )
12081 
12082 /*++
12083 
12084 Routine Description:
12085 
12086  This routine provides a special, fast interface for the Modified Page Writer
12087  (MPW) to write pages to the disk quickly and with very little overhead. All
12088  of the special handling for this request is recognized by setting the
12089  IRP_PAGING_IO flag in the IRP flags word.
12090 
12091 Arguments:
12092 
12093  FileObject - A pointer to a referenced file object describing which file
12094  the write should be performed on.
12095 
12096  MemoryDescriptorList - An MDL which describes the physical pages that the
12097  pages should be written to the disk. All of the pages have been locked
12098  in memory. The MDL also describes the length of the write operation.
12099 
12100  StartingOffset - Pointer to the offset in the file from which the write
12101  should take place.
12102 
12103  Event - A pointer to a kernel event structure to be used for synchronization
12104  purposes. The event will be set to the Signaled state once the pages
12105  have been written.
12106 
12107  IoStatusBlock - A pointer to the I/O status block in which the final status
12108  and information should be stored.
12109 
12110 Return Value:
12111 
12112  The function value is the final status of the queue request to the I/O
12113  system subcomponents.
12114 
12115 
12116 --*/
12117 
12118 {
12119  PIRP irp;
12120  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
12121  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
12122 
12123  //
12124  // Increment performance counters
12125  //
12126 
12127  if (CcIsFileCached(FileObject)) {
12128  CcDataFlushes += 1;
12129  CcDataPages += (MemoryDescriptorList->ByteCount + PAGE_SIZE - 1) >> PAGE_SHIFT;
12130  }
12131 
12132  //
12133  // Begin by getting a pointer to the device object that the file resides
12134  // on.
12135  //
12136 
12137  deviceObject = IoGetRelatedDeviceObject( FileObject );
12138 
12139  //
12140  // Allocate an I/O Request Packet (IRP) for this out-page operation.
12141  //
12142 
12143  irp = IoAllocateIrp( deviceObject->StackSize, FALSE );
12144  if (!irp) {
12145  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
12146  }
12147 
12148  //
12149  // Get a pointer to the first stack location in the packet. This location
12150  // will be used to pass the function codes and parameters to the first
12151  // driver.
12152  //
12153 
12154  irpSp = IoGetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
12155 
12156  //
12157  // Fill in the IRP according to this request.
12158  //
12159 
12160  irp->MdlAddress = MemoryDescriptorList;
12161  irp->Flags = IRP_PAGING_IO | IRP_NOCACHE | IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_PAGING_IO;
12162 
12163  irp->RequestorMode = KernelMode;
12164  irp->UserIosb = IoStatusBlock;
12165  irp->UserEvent = Event;
12166  irp->UserBuffer = (PVOID) ((PCHAR) MemoryDescriptorList->StartVa + MemoryDescriptorList->ByteOffset);
12167  irp->Tail.Overlay.OriginalFileObject = FileObject;
12168  irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread = PsGetCurrentThread();
12169 
12170  //
12171  // Fill in the normal write parameters.
12172  //
12173 
12174  irpSp->MajorFunction = IRP_MJ_WRITE;
12175  irpSp->Parameters.Write.Length = MemoryDescriptorList->ByteCount;
12176  irpSp->Parameters.Write.ByteOffset = *StartingOffset;
12177  irpSp->FileObject = FileObject;
12178 
12179  //
12180  // Queue the packet to the appropriate driver based on whether or not there
12181  // is a VPB associated with the device.
12182  //
12183 
12184  return IoCallDriver( deviceObject, irp );
12185 }
12186 
12187 PEPROCESS
12188 IoThreadToProcess(
12189  IN PETHREAD Thread
12190  )
12191 
12192 /*++
12193 
12194 Routine Description:
12195 
12196  This routine returns a pointer to the process for the specified thread.
12197 
12198 Arguments:
12199 
12200  Thread - Thread whose process is to be returned.
12201 
12202 Return Value:
12203 
12204  A pointer to the thread's process.
12205 
12206 Note:
12207 
12208  This function cannot be made a macro, since fields in the thread object
12209  move from release to release, so this must remain a full function.
12210 
12211 
12212 --*/
12213 
12214 {
12215  //
12216  // Simply return the thread's process.
12217  //
12218 
12219  return THREAD_TO_PROCESS( Thread );
12220 }
