12222 VOID
12223 IoUnregisterFileSystem(
12224  IN OUT PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject
12225  )
12226 
12227 /*++
12228 
12229 Routine Description:
12230 
12231  This routine removes the device object for the file system from the active
12232  list of file systems in the system.
12233 
12234 Arguments:
12235 
12236  DeviceObject - Pointer to device object for the file system.
12237 
12238 Return Value:
12239 
12240  None.
12241 
12242 
12243 --*/
12244 
12245 {
12246  PNOTIFICATION_PACKET nPacket;
12247  PLIST_ENTRY entry;
12248 
12249  PAGED_CODE();
12250 
12251  //
12252  // Acquire the I/O database resource for a write operation.
12253  //
12254 
12255  (VOID)ExAcquireResourceExclusiveLite( &IopDatabaseResource, TRUE );
12256 
12257  //
12258  // Remove the device object from whatever queue it happens to be in at the
12259  // moment. There is no need to check here to determine if the device queue
12260  // is in a queue since it is assumed that the caller registered it as a
12261  // valid file system.
12262  //
12263 
12264  if (DeviceObject->Queue.ListEntry.Flink != NULL) {
12265  RemoveEntryList( &DeviceObject->Queue.ListEntry );
12266  }
12267 
12268  //
12269  // Notify all of the registered drivers that this file system has been
12270  // unregistered as an active file system of some type.
12271  //
12272 
12273  entry = IopFsNotifyChangeQueueHead.Flink;
12274  while (entry != &IopFsNotifyChangeQueueHead) {
12275  nPacket = CONTAINING_RECORD( entry, NOTIFICATION_PACKET, ListEntry );
12276  entry = entry->Flink;
12277  nPacket->NotificationRoutine( DeviceObject, FALSE );
12278  }
12279 
12280  IopFsRegistrationOps++;
12281 
12282  //
12283  // Release the I/O database resource.
12284  //
12285 
12286  ExReleaseResourceLite( &IopDatabaseResource );
12287 
12288  //
12289  // Decrement the number of reasons that this driver cannot be unloaded.
12290  //
12291 
12292  IopInterlockedDecrementUlong( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock,
12293  &DeviceObject->ReferenceCount );
12294 }
12295 
12296 VOID
12297 IoUnregisterFsRegistrationChange(
12298  IN PDRIVER_OBJECT DriverObject,
12299  IN PDRIVER_FS_NOTIFICATION DriverNotificationRoutine
12300  )
12301 
12302 /*++
12303 
12304 Routine Description:
12305 
12306  This routine unregisters the specified driver's notification routine from
12307  begin invoked whenever a file system registers or unregisters itself as an
12308  active file system in the system.
12309 
12310 Arguments:
12311 
12312  DriverObject - Pointer to the driver object for the driver.
12313 
12314  DriverNotificationRoutine - Address of routine to unregister.
12315 
12316 Return Value:
12317 
12318  None.
12319 
12320 --*/
12321 
12322 {
12323  PNOTIFICATION_PACKET nPacket;
12324  PLIST_ENTRY entry;
12325 
12326  PAGED_CODE();
12327 
12328  //
12329  // Begin by acquiring the database resource exclusively.
12330  //
12331 
12332  ExAcquireResourceExclusiveLite( &IopDatabaseResource, TRUE );
12333 
12334  //
12335  // Walk the list of registered notification routines and unregister the
12336  // specified routine.
12337  //
12338 
12339  for (entry = IopFsNotifyChangeQueueHead.Flink;
12340  entry != &IopFsNotifyChangeQueueHead;
12341  entry = entry->Flink) {
12342  nPacket = CONTAINING_RECORD( entry, NOTIFICATION_PACKET, ListEntry );
12343  if (nPacket->DriverObject == DriverObject &&
12344  nPacket->NotificationRoutine == DriverNotificationRoutine) {
12345  RemoveEntryList( entry );
12346  ExFreePool( nPacket );
12347  break;
12348  }
12349  }
12350 
12351  ExReleaseResourceLite( &IopDatabaseResource );
12352 
12353  ObDereferenceObject( DriverObject );
12354 
12355 }
12356 
12357 VOID
12358 IoUnregisterShutdownNotification(
12359  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject
12360  )
12361 
12362 /*++
12363 
12364 Routine Description:
12365 
12366  This routine removes a registered driver from the shutdown notification
12367  queue. Henceforth, the driver will not be notified when the system is
12368  being shutdown.
12369 
12370 Arguments:
12371 
12372  DeviceObject - Pointer to the driver's device object.
12373 
12374 Return Value:
12375 
12376  None.
12377 
12378 --*/
12379 
12380 {
12381  PLIST_ENTRY entry;
12382  PSHUTDOWN_PACKET shutdown;
12383  KIRQL irql;
12384 
12385  PAGED_CODE();
12386 
12387  //
12388  // Lock this code into memory for the duration of this function's execution.
12389  //
12390 
12391  ASSERT(ExPageLockHandle);
12392  MmLockPageableSectionByHandle( ExPageLockHandle );
12393 
12394  //
12395  // Acquire the spinlock that protects the shutdown notification queue, and
12396  // walk the queue looking for the caller's entry. Once found, remove it
12397  // from the queue. It is an error to not find it, but it is ignored here.
12398  //
12399 
12400  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock );
12401 
12402  for (entry = IopNotifyShutdownQueueHead.Flink;
12403  entry != &IopNotifyShutdownQueueHead;
12404  entry = entry->Flink) {
12405 
12406  //
12407  // An entry has been located. If it is the one that is being searched
12408  // for, simply remove it from the list and deallocate it.
12409  //
12410 
12411  shutdown = CONTAINING_RECORD( entry, SHUTDOWN_PACKET, ListEntry );
12412  if (shutdown->DeviceObject == DeviceObject) {
12413  RemoveEntryList( entry );
12414  entry = entry->Blink;
12415  ObDereferenceObject(DeviceObject);
12416  ExFreePool( shutdown );
12417  }
12418  }
12419 
12420  for (entry = IopNotifyLastChanceShutdownQueueHead.Flink;
12421  entry != &IopNotifyLastChanceShutdownQueueHead;
12422  entry = entry->Flink) {
12423 
12424  //
12425  // An entry has been located. If it is the one that is being searched
12426  // for, simply remove it from the list and deallocate it.
12427  //
12428 
12429  shutdown = CONTAINING_RECORD( entry, SHUTDOWN_PACKET, ListEntry );
12430  if (shutdown->DeviceObject == DeviceObject) {
12431  RemoveEntryList( entry );
12432  entry = entry->Blink;
12433  ObDereferenceObject(DeviceObject);
12434  ExFreePool( shutdown );
12435  }
12436  }
12437 
12438  //
12439  // Release the spinlock.
12440  //
12441 
12442  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
12443 
12444  MmUnlockPageableImageSection( ExPageLockHandle );
12445 
12446  DeviceObject->Flags &= ~DO_SHUTDOWN_REGISTERED;
12447 
12448 }
12449 
12450 VOID
12451 IoUpdateShareAccess(
12452  IN OUT PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
12453  IN OUT PSHARE_ACCESS ShareAccess
12454  )
12455 
12456 /*++
12457 
12458 Routine Description:
12459 
12460  This routine updates the share access context for a file according to
12461  the desired access and share access by the current open requestor. The
12462  IoCheckShareAccess routine must already have been invoked and succeeded
12463  in order to invoke this routine. Note that when the former routine was
12464  invoked the Update parameter must have been FALSE.
12465 
12466 Arguments:
12467 
12468  FileObject - Pointer to the file object of the current open request.
12469 
12470  ShareAccess - Pointer to the share access structure that describes how
12471  the file is currently being accessed.
12472 
12473 Return Value:
12474 
12475  None.
12476 
12477 --*/
12478 
12479 {
12480  BOOLEAN update = TRUE;
12481 
12482  PAGED_CODE();
12483 
12484  //
12485  // If this is a special filter fileobject ignore share access check if necessary.
12486  //
12487 
12488  if (FileObject->Flags & FO_FILE_OBJECT_HAS_EXTENSION) {
12489  PIOP_FILE_OBJECT_EXTENSION fileObjectExtension =(PIOP_FILE_OBJECT_EXTENSION)(FileObject + 1);
12490 
12491  if (fileObjectExtension->FileObjectExtensionFlags & FO_EXTENSION_IGNORE_SHARE_ACCESS_CHECK) {
12492 
12493  //
12494  // This fileobject is marked to ignore share access checks
12495  // so we also don't want to affect the file/directory's
12496  // ShareAccess structure counts.
12497  //
12498 
12499  update = FALSE;
12500  }
12501  }
12502 
12503  //
12504  // Check to see whether or not the desired accesses need read, write,
12505  // or delete access to the file.
12506  //
12507 
12508  if ((FileObject->ReadAccess ||
12509  FileObject->WriteAccess ||
12510  FileObject->DeleteAccess) &&
12511  update) {
12512 
12513  //
12514  // The open request requires read, write, or delete access so update
12515  // the share access context for the file.
12516  //
12517 
12518  ShareAccess->OpenCount++;
12519 
12520  ShareAccess->Readers += FileObject->ReadAccess;
12521  ShareAccess->Writers += FileObject->WriteAccess;
12522  ShareAccess->Deleters += FileObject->DeleteAccess;
12523 
12524  ShareAccess->SharedRead += FileObject->SharedRead;
12525  ShareAccess->SharedWrite += FileObject->SharedWrite;
12526  ShareAccess->SharedDelete += FileObject->SharedDelete;
12527  }
12528 }
12529 
12530 
12531 NTSTATUS
12532 IoVerifyVolume(
12533  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
12534  IN BOOLEAN AllowRawMount
12535  )
12536 
12537 /*++
12538 
12539 Routine Description:
12540 
12541  This routine is invoked to check a mounted volume on the specified device
12542  when it appears as if the media may have changed since it was last
12543  accessed. If the volume is not the same volume, and a new mount is not
12544  to be attempted, return the error.
12545 
12546  If the verify fails, this routine is used to perform a new mount operation
12547  on the device. In this case, a "clean" VPB is allocated and a new mount
12548  operation is attempted. If no mount operation succeeds, then again the
12549  error handling described above occurs.
12550 
12551 Arguments:
12552 
12553  DeviceObject - Pointer to device object on which the volume is to be
12554  mounted.
12555 
12556  AllowRawMount - Indicates that this verify is on behalf of a DASD open
12557  request, thus we want to allow a raw mount if the verify fails.
12558 
12559 Return Value:
12560 
12561  The function value is a successful status code if a volume was successfully
12562  mounted on the device. Otherwise, an error code is returned.
12563 
12564 
12565 --*/
12566 
12567 {
12568  NTSTATUS status;
12569  KEVENT event;
12570  PIRP irp;
12571  IO_STATUS_BLOCK ioStatus;
12572  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
12573  BOOLEAN verifySkipped = FALSE;
12574  PDEVICE_OBJECT fsDeviceObject;
12575  PDEVICE_OBJECT fsBaseDeviceObject;
12576  PVPB mountVpb;
12577  PVPB vpb;
12578 
12579  PAGED_CODE();
12580 
12581  //
12582  // Acquire the DeviceObject lock. Nothing in this routine can raise
12583  // so no try {} finally {} is required.
12584  //
12585 
12586  status = KeWaitForSingleObject( &DeviceObject->DeviceLock,
12587  Executive,
12588  KernelMode,
12589  FALSE,
12590  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
12591 
12592  ASSERT( status == STATUS_SUCCESS );
12593 
12594  //
12595  // If this volume is not mounted by anyone, skip the verify operation,
12596  // but do the mount.
12597  //
12598 
12599  if (!IopReferenceVerifyVpb(DeviceObject, &vpb, &fsBaseDeviceObject)) {
12600 
12601 
12602  verifySkipped = TRUE;
12603 
12604  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
12605 
12606  } else {
12607 
12608  //
12609  // This volume needs to be verified. Initialize the event to be
12610  // used while waiting for the operation to complete.
12611  //
12612 
12613  KeInitializeEvent( &event, NotificationEvent, FALSE );
12614  status = STATUS_UNSUCCESSFUL;
12615 
12616  //
12617  // Allocate and initialize an IRP for this verify operation. Notice
12618  // that the flags for this operation appear the same as a page read
12619  // operation. This is because the completion code for both of the
12620  // operations is exactly the same logic.
12621  //
12622 
12623  fsDeviceObject = fsBaseDeviceObject;
12624 
12625  while (fsDeviceObject->AttachedDevice) {
12626  fsDeviceObject = fsDeviceObject->AttachedDevice;
12627  }
12628  irp = IoAllocateIrp( fsDeviceObject->StackSize, FALSE );
12629  if (!irp) {
12630 
12631  KeSetEvent( &DeviceObject->DeviceLock, 0, FALSE );
12632  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
12633  }
12634  irp->Flags = IRP_MOUNT_COMPLETION | IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_PAGING_IO;
12635  irp->RequestorMode = KernelMode;
12636  irp->UserEvent = &event;
12637  irp->UserIosb = &ioStatus;
12638  irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread = PsGetCurrentThread();
12639  irpSp = IoGetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
12640  irpSp->MajorFunction = IRP_MJ_FILE_SYSTEM_CONTROL;
12641  irpSp->MinorFunction = IRP_MN_VERIFY_VOLUME;
12642  irpSp->Flags = AllowRawMount ? SL_ALLOW_RAW_MOUNT : 0;
12643  irpSp->Parameters.VerifyVolume.Vpb = vpb;
12644  irpSp->Parameters.VerifyVolume.DeviceObject = fsBaseDeviceObject;
12645 
12646  status = IoCallDriver( fsDeviceObject, irp );
12647 
12648  // IopLoadFileSystemDriver
12649  // Wait for the I/O operation to complete.
12650  //
12651 
12652  if (status == STATUS_PENDING) {
12653  (VOID) KeWaitForSingleObject( &event,
12654  Executive,
12655  KernelMode,
12656  FALSE,
12657  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
12658  status = ioStatus.Status;
12659  }
12660 
12661  //
12662  // Deref the VPB obtained above.
12663  //
12664 
12665  IopDereferenceVpbAndFree(vpb);
12666  }
12667 
12668  //
12669  // If the verify operation was skipped or unsuccessful perform a mount
12670  // operation.
12671  //
12672 
12673  if ((status == STATUS_WRONG_VOLUME) || verifySkipped) {
12674 
12675  //
12676  // A mount operation is to be attempted. Allocate a new VPB
12677  // for this device and attempt to mount it.
12678  //
12679 
12680  if (NT_SUCCESS(IopCreateVpb (DeviceObject))) {
12681 
12682  PoVolumeDevice (DeviceObject);
12683 
12684  //
12685  // Now mount the volume.
12686  //
12687 
12688  mountVpb = NULL;
12689  if (!NT_SUCCESS( IopMountVolume( DeviceObject, AllowRawMount, TRUE, FALSE, &mountVpb ) )) {
12690  DeviceObject->Flags &= ~DO_VERIFY_VOLUME;
12691  } else {
12692  if (mountVpb) {
12693 
12694  //
12695  // Decrement the reference allocated in IopMountVolume.
12696  //
12697 
12698  IopInterlockedDecrementUlong( LockQueueIoVpbLock,
12699  (PLONG) &mountVpb->ReferenceCount );
12700  }
12701  }
12702  } else {
12703  DeviceObject->Flags &= ~DO_VERIFY_VOLUME;
12704  }
12705  }
12706 
12707  //
12708  // Release the device lock.
12709  //
12710 
12711  KeSetEvent( &DeviceObject->DeviceLock, 0, FALSE );
12712 
12713  //
12714  // Return the status from the verify operation as the final status of
12715  // this function.
12716  //
12717 
12718  return status;
12719 }
12720 
12721 VOID
12722 IoWriteErrorLogEntry(
12723  IN OUT PVOID ElEntry
12724  )
12725 
12726 /*++
12727 
12728 Routine Description:
12729 
12730  This routine places the error log entry specified by the input argument
12731  onto the queue of buffers to be written to the error log process's port.
12732  The error log thread will then actually send it.
12733 
12734 Arguments:
12735 
12736  ElEntry Pointer to the error log entry.
12737 
12738 Return Value:
12739 
12740  None.
12741 
12742 --*/
12743 
12744 {
12745  PERROR_LOG_ENTRY entry;
12746  KIRQL oldIrql;
12747 
12748  //
12749  // Get the address of the error log entry header, acquire the spin lock,
12750  // insert the entry onto the queue, if there are no pending requests
12751  // then queue a worker thread request and release the spin lock.
12752  //
12753 
12754  entry = ((PERROR_LOG_ENTRY) ElEntry) - 1;
12755 
12756  if (IopErrorLogDisabledThisBoot) {
12757  //
12758  // Do nothing, drop the reference.
12759  //
12760 
12761  if (entry->DeviceObject != NULL) {
12762  //
12763  // IopErrorLogThread tests for NULL before derefing.
12764  // So do the same here.
12765  //
12766  ObDereferenceObject (entry->DeviceObject);
12767  }
12768  if (entry->DriverObject != NULL) {
12769  ObDereferenceObject (entry->DriverObject);
12770  }
12771 
12772  InterlockedExchangeAdd( &IopErrorLogAllocation,
12773  -((LONG) (entry->Size )));
12774  ExFreePool (entry);
12775  return;
12776 
12777  }
12778 
12779  //
12780  // Set the time that the entry was logged.
12781  //
12782 
12783  KeQuerySystemTime( (PVOID) &entry->TimeStamp );
12784 
12785  ExAcquireSpinLock( &IopErrorLogLock, &oldIrql );
12786 
12787  //
12788  // Queue the request to the error log queue.
12789  //
12790 
12791  InsertTailList( &IopErrorLogListHead, &entry->ListEntry );
12792 
12793  //
12794  // If there is no pending work, then queue a request to a worker thread.
12795  //
12796 
12797  if (!IopErrorLogPortPending) {
12798 
12799  IopErrorLogPortPending = TRUE;
12800 
12801  ExInitializeWorkItem( &IopErrorLogWorkItem, IopErrorLogThread, NULL );
12802  ExQueueWorkItem( &IopErrorLogWorkItem, DelayedWorkQueue );
12803 
12804  }
12805 
12806  ExReleaseSpinLock(&IopErrorLogLock, oldIrql);
12807 }
12808 
12809 NTSTATUS
12810 IoGetBootDiskInformation(
12811  IN OUT PBOOTDISK_INFORMATION BootDiskInformation,
12812  IN ULONG Size
12813  )
12814 
12815 /*++
12816 
12817 Routine Description:
12818 
12819  This routine provides the caller with the signature and offset of
12820  the boot disk and system disk. This information is obtained from the
12821  loader block. The callers have to be boot drivers which have registered
12822  for a callback once all disk devices have been started
12823 Arguments:
12824 
12825  BootDiskInformation - Supplies a pointer to the structure allocated by the
12826  caller for requested information.
12827  Size - Size of the BootDiskInformation structure.
12828 
12829 Return Value:
12830 
12831  STATUS_SUCCESS - successful.
12832  STATUS_TOO_LATE - indicates that the Loader Block has already been freed
12833  STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER - size allocated for boot disk information
12834  is insufficient.
12835 
12836 --*/
12837 
12838 {
12839  PLOADER_PARAMETER_BLOCK LoaderBlock = NULL;
12840  STRING arcBootDeviceString;
12841  CHAR deviceNameBuffer[128];
12842  STRING deviceNameString;
12843  UNICODE_STRING deviceNameUnicodeString;
12844  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
12845  CHAR arcNameBuffer[128];
12846  STRING arcNameString;
12847  PFILE_OBJECT fileObject;
12848  NTSTATUS status;
12849  IO_STATUS_BLOCK ioStatusBlock;
12850  DISK_GEOMETRY diskGeometry;
12851  PDRIVE_LAYOUT_INFORMATION_EX driveLayout;
12852  PLIST_ENTRY listEntry;
12853  PARC_DISK_SIGNATURE diskBlock;
12854  ULONG diskNumber;
12855  ULONG partitionNumber;
12856  PCHAR arcName;
12857  PIRP irp;
12858  KEVENT event;
12859  BOOLEAN singleBiosDiskFound;
12860  PARC_DISK_INFORMATION arcInformation;
12861  ULONG totalDriverDisksFound = IoGetConfigurationInformation()->DiskCount;
12862  STRING arcSystemDeviceString;
12863  PARTITION_INFORMATION_EX PartitionInfo;
12864  PBOOTDISK_INFORMATION_EX bootDiskInformationEx;
12865  ULONG diskSignature = 0;
12866 
12867  PAGED_CODE();
12868 
12869  if (IopLoaderBlock == NULL) {
12870  return STATUS_TOO_LATE;
12871  }
12872 
12873  if (Size < sizeof(BOOTDISK_INFORMATION)) {
12874  return STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER;
12875  }
12876 
12877  if (Size < sizeof(BOOTDISK_INFORMATION_EX)) {
12878  bootDiskInformationEx = NULL;
12879  } else {
12880  bootDiskInformationEx = (PBOOTDISK_INFORMATION_EX)BootDiskInformation;
12881  }
12882 
12883  LoaderBlock = (PLOADER_PARAMETER_BLOCK)IopLoaderBlock;
12884  arcInformation = LoaderBlock->ArcDiskInformation;
12885 
12886  //
12887  // If a single bios disk was found if there is only a
12888  // single entry on the disk signature list.
12889  //
12890  singleBiosDiskFound = (arcInformation->DiskSignatures.Flink->Flink ==
12891  &arcInformation->DiskSignatures) ? (TRUE) : (FALSE);
12892 
12893  //
12894  // Get ARC boot device name from loader block.
12895  //
12896 
12897  RtlInitAnsiString( &arcBootDeviceString,
12898  LoaderBlock->ArcBootDeviceName );
12899  //
12900  // Get ARC system device name from loader block.
12901  //
12902 
12903  RtlInitAnsiString( &arcSystemDeviceString,
12904  LoaderBlock->ArcHalDeviceName );
12905  //
12906  // For each disk, get its drive layout and check to see if the
12907  // signature is among the list of signatures in the loader block.
12908  // If yes, check to see if the disk contains the boot or system
12909  // partitions. If yes, fill up the requested structure.
12910  //
12911 
12912  for (diskNumber = 0;
12913  diskNumber < totalDriverDisksFound;
12914  diskNumber++) {
12915 
12916  //
12917  // Construct the NT name for a disk and obtain a reference.
12918  //
12919 
12920  sprintf( deviceNameBuffer,
12921  "\\Device\\Harddisk%d\\Partition0",
12922  diskNumber );
12923  RtlInitAnsiString( &deviceNameString, deviceNameBuffer );
12924  status = RtlAnsiStringToUnicodeString( &deviceNameUnicodeString,
12925  &deviceNameString,
12926  TRUE );
12927  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
12928  continue;
12929  }
12930 
12931  status = IoGetDeviceObjectPointer( &deviceNameUnicodeString,
12932  FILE_READ_ATTRIBUTES,
12933  &fileObject,
12934  &deviceObject );
12935  RtlFreeUnicodeString( &deviceNameUnicodeString );
12936 
12937  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
12938  continue;
12939  }
12940 
12941  //
12942  // Create IRP for get drive geometry device control.
12943  //
12944 
12945  irp = IoBuildDeviceIoControlRequest( IOCTL_DISK_GET_DRIVE_GEOMETRY,
12946  deviceObject,
12947  NULL,
12948  0,
12949  &diskGeometry,
12950  sizeof(DISK_GEOMETRY),
12951  FALSE,
12952  &event,
12953  &ioStatusBlock );
12954  if (!irp) {
12955  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
12956  continue;
12957  }
12958 
12959  KeInitializeEvent( &event,
12960  NotificationEvent,
12961  FALSE );
12962  status = IoCallDriver( deviceObject,
12963  irp );
12964 
12965  if (status == STATUS_PENDING) {
12966  KeWaitForSingleObject( &event,
12967  Suspended,
12968  KernelMode,
12969  FALSE,
12970  NULL );
12971  status = ioStatusBlock.Status;
12972  }
12973 
12974  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
12975  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
12976  continue;
12977  }
12978 
12979  //
12980  // Get partition information for this disk.
12981  //
12982 
12983  status = IoReadPartitionTableEx( deviceObject,
12984  &driveLayout );
12985 
12986 
12987  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
12988  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
12989  continue;
12990  }
12991 
12992  //
12993  // Make sure sector size is at least 512 bytes.
12994  //
12995 
12996  if (diskGeometry.BytesPerSector < 512) {
12997  diskGeometry.BytesPerSector = 512;
12998  }
12999 
13000 
13001 
13002  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
13003 
13004  //
13005  // For each ARC disk information record in the loader block
13006  // match the disk signature and checksum to determine its ARC
13007  // name and construct the NT ARC names symbolic links.
13008  //
13009 
13010  for (listEntry = arcInformation->DiskSignatures.Flink;
13011  listEntry != &arcInformation->DiskSignatures;
13012  listEntry = listEntry->Flink) {
13013 
13014  //
13015  // Get next record and compare disk signatures.
13016  //
13017 
13018  diskBlock = CONTAINING_RECORD( listEntry,
13019  ARC_DISK_SIGNATURE,
13020  ListEntry );
13021 
13022  //
13023  // Compare disk signatures.
13024  //
13025  // Or if there is only a single disk drive from
13026  // both the bios and driver viewpoints then
13027  // assign an arc name to that drive.
13028  //
13029 
13030  if ((singleBiosDiskFound &&
13031  (totalDriverDisksFound == 1) &&
13032  (driveLayout->PartitionStyle == PARTITION_STYLE_MBR)) ||
13033  IopVerifyDiskSignature(driveLayout, diskBlock, &diskSignature)) {
13034 
13035  //
13036  // Create unicode ARC name for this partition.
13037  //
13038 
13039  arcName = diskBlock->ArcName;
13040  sprintf( arcNameBuffer,
13041  "\\ArcName\\%s",
13042  arcName );
13043  RtlInitAnsiString( &arcNameString, arcNameBuffer );
13044 
13045  //
13046  // Create an ARC name for every partition on this disk.
13047  //
13048 
13049  for (partitionNumber = 0;
13050  partitionNumber < driveLayout->PartitionCount;
13051  partitionNumber++) {
13052 
13053  //
13054  // Create unicode NT device name.
13055  //
13056 
13057  sprintf( deviceNameBuffer,
13058  "\\Device\\Harddisk%d\\Partition%d",
13059  diskNumber,
13060  partitionNumber+1 );
13061  RtlInitAnsiString( &deviceNameString, deviceNameBuffer );
13062 
13063  status = RtlAnsiStringToUnicodeString(
13064  &deviceNameUnicodeString,
13065  &deviceNameString,
13066  TRUE );
13067 
13068  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
13069  continue;
13070  }
13071 
13072 
13073  //
13074  // If we came through the single disk case.
13075  //
13076 
13077  if (diskSignature == 0) {
13078  diskSignature = driveLayout->Mbr.Signature;
13079  }
13080 
13081  //
13082  // Create unicode ARC name for this partition and
13083  // check to see if this is the boot disk.
13084  //
13085 
13086  sprintf( arcNameBuffer,
13087  "%spartition(%d)",
13088  arcName,
13089  partitionNumber+1 );
13090  RtlInitAnsiString( &arcNameString, arcNameBuffer );
13091  if (RtlEqualString( &arcNameString,
13092  &arcBootDeviceString,
13093  TRUE )) {
13094 
13095 
13096  BootDiskInformation->BootDeviceSignature = diskSignature;
13097 
13098  //
13099  // Get Partition Information for the offset of the
13100  // partition within the disk
13101  //
13102  status = IoGetDeviceObjectPointer(
13103  &deviceNameUnicodeString,
13104  FILE_READ_ATTRIBUTES,
13105  &fileObject,
13106  &deviceObject );
13107 
13108  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
13109  RtlFreeUnicodeString( &deviceNameUnicodeString );
13110  continue;
13111  }
13112 
13113  //
13114  // Create IRP for get drive geometry device control.
13115  //
13116 
13117  irp = IoBuildDeviceIoControlRequest(
13118  IOCTL_DISK_GET_PARTITION_INFO_EX,
13119  deviceObject,
13120  NULL,
13121  0,
13122  &PartitionInfo,
13123  sizeof(PARTITION_INFORMATION_EX),
13124  FALSE,
13125  &event,
13126  &ioStatusBlock );
13127  if (!irp) {
13128  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
13129  RtlFreeUnicodeString( &deviceNameUnicodeString );
13130  continue;
13131  }
13132 
13133  KeInitializeEvent( &event,
13134  NotificationEvent,
13135  FALSE );
13136  status = IoCallDriver( deviceObject,
13137  irp );
13138 
13139  if (status == STATUS_PENDING) {
13140  KeWaitForSingleObject( &event,
13141  Suspended,
13142  KernelMode,
13143  FALSE,
13144  NULL );
13145  status = ioStatusBlock.Status;
13146  }
13147 
13148  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
13149  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
13150  RtlFreeUnicodeString( &deviceNameUnicodeString );
13151  continue;
13152  }
13153  BootDiskInformation->BootPartitionOffset =
13154  PartitionInfo.StartingOffset.QuadPart;
13155 
13156  if (driveLayout->PartitionStyle == PARTITION_STYLE_GPT) {
13157  if (bootDiskInformationEx) {
13158  bootDiskInformationEx->BootDeviceIsGpt = TRUE;
13159 
13160  //
13161  // Structure copy.
13162  //
13163 
13164  bootDiskInformationEx->BootDeviceGuid = driveLayout->Gpt.DiskId;
13165  }
13166  } else {
13167  if (bootDiskInformationEx) {
13168  bootDiskInformationEx->BootDeviceIsGpt = FALSE;
13169  }
13170  }
13171 
13172  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
13173  }
13174 
13175  //
13176  // See if this is the system partition.
13177  //
13178  if (RtlEqualString( &arcNameString,
13179  &arcSystemDeviceString,
13180  TRUE )) {
13181  BootDiskInformation->SystemDeviceSignature = diskSignature;
13182  //
13183  // Get Partition Information for the offset of the
13184  // partition within the disk
13185  //
13186 
13187  status = IoGetDeviceObjectPointer(
13188  &deviceNameUnicodeString,
13189  FILE_READ_ATTRIBUTES,
13190  &fileObject,
13191  &deviceObject );
13192 
13193  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
13194  RtlFreeUnicodeString( &deviceNameUnicodeString );
13195  continue;
13196  }
13197 
13198  //
13199  // Create IRP for get drive geometry device control.
13200  //
13201 
13202  irp = IoBuildDeviceIoControlRequest(
13203  IOCTL_DISK_GET_PARTITION_INFO_EX,
13204  deviceObject,
13205  NULL,
13206  0,
13207  &PartitionInfo,
13208  sizeof(PARTITION_INFORMATION_EX),
13209  FALSE,
13210  &event,
13211  &ioStatusBlock );
13212  if (!irp) {
13213  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
13214  RtlFreeUnicodeString( &deviceNameUnicodeString );
13215  continue;
13216  }
13217 
13218  KeInitializeEvent( &event,
13219  NotificationEvent,
13220  FALSE );
13221  status = IoCallDriver( deviceObject,
13222  irp );
13223 
13224  if (status == STATUS_PENDING) {
13225  KeWaitForSingleObject( &event,
13226  Suspended,
13227  KernelMode,
13228  FALSE,
13229  NULL );
13230  status = ioStatusBlock.Status;
13231  }
13232 
13233  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
13234  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
13235  RtlFreeUnicodeString( &deviceNameUnicodeString );
13236  continue;
13237  }
13238  BootDiskInformation->SystemPartitionOffset =
13239  PartitionInfo.StartingOffset.QuadPart;
13240 
13241  if (driveLayout->PartitionStyle == PARTITION_STYLE_GPT) {
13242  if (bootDiskInformationEx) {
13243  bootDiskInformationEx->SystemDeviceIsGpt = TRUE;
13244 
13245  //
13246  // Structure copy.
13247  //
13248 
13249  bootDiskInformationEx->SystemDeviceGuid = driveLayout->Gpt.DiskId;
13250  }
13251  } else {
13252  if (bootDiskInformationEx) {
13253  bootDiskInformationEx->SystemDeviceIsGpt = FALSE;
13254  }
13255  }
13256 
13257  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
13258  }
13259 
13260  RtlFreeUnicodeString( &deviceNameUnicodeString );
13261  }
13262  }
13263  }
13264  ExFreePool( driveLayout );
13265  }
13266  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
13267 }
13268 
13269 PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR
13270 IopCreateDefaultDeviceSecurityDescriptor(
13271  IN DEVICE_TYPE DeviceType,
13272  IN ULONG DeviceCharacteristics,
13273  IN BOOLEAN DeviceHasName,
13274  IN PUCHAR Buffer,
13275  OUT PACL *AllocatedAcl,
13276  OUT PSECURITY_INFORMATION SecurityInformation OPTIONAL
13277  )
13278 /*++
13279 
13280 Routine Description:
13281 
13282  This routine creates a security descriptor for a device object. The security descriptor is
13283  set based on the device type.
13284  This can be called from PnP MGR or IoCreateDevice.
13285 
13286 Arguments:
13287 
13288  DeviceType - Type of Device
13289  DeviceCharacteristics - Characteristics of the device.
13290  DeviceHasName - TRUE if device object has a name
13291  Buffer - Storage for security descriptor
13292  AllocatedAcl - Is non-null if this routine allocated an ACL.
13293  SecurityInformation - OUT parameter where SecurityInformation is passed.
13294 
13295 Return Value:
13296 
13297  PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR. NULL on error.
13298 --*/
13299 {
13300  PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR descriptor = (PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR) Buffer;
13301 
13302  NTSTATUS status;
13303 
13304  PAGED_CODE();
13305 
13306  if(ARGUMENT_PRESENT(SecurityInformation)) {
13307  (*SecurityInformation) = 0;
13308  }
13309 
13310  *AllocatedAcl = NULL;
13311 
13312 
13313  switch ( DeviceType ) {
13314 
13315  case FILE_DEVICE_DISK_FILE_SYSTEM:
13316  case FILE_DEVICE_CD_ROM_FILE_SYSTEM:
13317  case FILE_DEVICE_FILE_SYSTEM:
13318  case FILE_DEVICE_TAPE_FILE_SYSTEM: {
13319 
13320  //
13321  // Use the standard public default protection for these types of devices.
13322  //
13323  status = IopCreateSecurityDescriptorPerType(
13324  descriptor,
13325  IO_SD_SYS_ALL_ADM_ALL_WORLD_E_RES_E,
13326  SecurityInformation
13327  );
13328 
13329  break;
13330  }
13331 
13332  case FILE_DEVICE_CD_ROM:
13333  case FILE_DEVICE_MASS_STORAGE:
13334  case FILE_DEVICE_DISK:
13335  case FILE_DEVICE_VIRTUAL_DISK:
13336  case FILE_DEVICE_NETWORK_FILE_SYSTEM:
13337  case FILE_DEVICE_DFS_FILE_SYSTEM:
13338  case FILE_DEVICE_NETWORK: {
13339 
13340  if ((DeviceHasName) &&
13341  ((DeviceCharacteristics & FILE_FLOPPY_DISKETTE) != 0)) {
13342 
13343  status = IopCreateSecurityDescriptorPerType(
13344  descriptor,
13345  IO_SD_SYS_ALL_ADM_ALL_WORLD_RWE_RES_RE,
13346  SecurityInformation
13347  );
13348 
13349  } else {
13350 
13351  UCHAR i;
13352  PACL acl;
13353  BOOLEAN aceFound;
13354  BOOLEAN aceFoundForCDROM;
13355  PACCESS_ALLOWED_ACE ace;
13356 
13357  //
13358  // Protect the device so that an administrator can run chkdsk
13359  // on it. This is done by making a copy of the default public
13360  // ACL and changing the accesses granted to the administrators
13361  // alias.
13362  //
13363  // The logic here is:
13364  //
13365  // - Copy the public default dacl into another buffer
13366  //
13367  // - Find the ACE granting ADMINISTRATORS access
13368  //
13369  // - Change the granted access mask of that ACE to give
13370  // administrators write access.
13371  //
13372  //
13373 
13374  acl = ExAllocatePoolWithTag(
13375  PagedPool,
13376  SePublicDefaultUnrestrictedDacl->AclSize,
13377  'eSoI' );
13378 
13379  if (!acl) {
13380  return NULL;
13381  }
13382 
13383  RtlCopyMemory( acl,
13384  SePublicDefaultUnrestrictedDacl,
13385  SePublicDefaultUnrestrictedDacl->AclSize );
13386 
13387  //
13388  // Find the Administrators ACE
13389  //
13390 
13391  aceFound = FALSE;
13392  aceFoundForCDROM = FALSE;
13393 
13394  for ( i = 0, status = RtlGetAce(acl, 0, &ace);
13395  NT_SUCCESS(status);
13396  i++, status = RtlGetAce(acl, i, &ace)) {
13397 
13398  PSID sid;
13399 
13400  sid = &(ace->SidStart);
13401  if (RtlEqualSid( SeAliasAdminsSid, sid )) {
13402 
13403  ace->Mask |= ( GENERIC_READ |
13404  GENERIC_WRITE |
13405  GENERIC_EXECUTE );
13406 
13407  aceFound = TRUE;
13408  }
13409 
13410  if (DeviceType == FILE_DEVICE_CD_ROM) {
13411 
13412  if (RtlEqualSid( SeWorldSid, sid )) {
13413  ace->Mask |= GENERIC_READ;
13414  aceFoundForCDROM = TRUE;
13415  }
13416  }
13417  }
13418 
13419  //
13420  // If the ACE wasn't found, then the public default ACL has been
13421  // changed. For this case, this code needs to be updated to match
13422  // the new public default DACL.
13423  //
13424 
13425  ASSERT(aceFound == TRUE);
13426 
13427  if (DeviceType == FILE_DEVICE_CD_ROM) {
13428  ASSERT(aceFoundForCDROM == TRUE);
13429  }
13430 
13431  //
13432  // Finally, build a full security descriptor from the above DACL.
13433  //
13434 
13435  RtlCreateSecurityDescriptor( descriptor,
13436  SECURITY_DESCRIPTOR_REVISION );
13437 
13438  RtlSetDaclSecurityDescriptor( descriptor,
13439  TRUE,
13440  acl,
13441  FALSE );
13442 
13443  if(ARGUMENT_PRESENT(SecurityInformation)) {
13444  (*SecurityInformation) |= DACL_SECURITY_INFORMATION;
13445  }
13446 
13447  *AllocatedAcl = acl;
13448  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
13449  }
13450 
13451  break;
13452  }
13453 
13454  default: {
13455 
13456  status = IopCreateSecurityDescriptorPerType(
13457  descriptor,
13458  IO_SD_SYS_ALL_ADM_ALL_WORLD_RWE_RES_RE,
13459  SecurityInformation
13460  );
13461 
13462  break;
13463  }
13464  }
13465 
13466  if (!NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
13467  return NULL;
13468  }
13469  return descriptor;
13470 }
13471 
13472 NTSTATUS
13473 IopCreateSecurityDescriptorPerType(
13474  IN PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR Descriptor,
13475  IN ULONG SecurityDescriptorFlavor,
13476  OUT PSECURITY_INFORMATION SecurityInformation OPTIONAL
13477  )
13478 /*++
13479 
13480 Routine Description:
13481 
13482  This routine creates a security descriptor based on the flavor.
13483 
13484 Arguments:
13485 
13486  Descriptor - Storage for security descriptor
13487  SecurityInformation - OUT parameter where SecurityInformation is passed.
13488  SecurityDescriptorFlavor - Type used to determine the security descriptor flavor.
13489 
13490 Return Value:
13491 
13492  NTSTATUS
13493 --*/
13494 {
13495  NTSTATUS status;
13496  PACL acl;
13497 
13498  switch (SecurityDescriptorFlavor) {
13499  case IO_SD_SYS_ALL_ADM_ALL_WORLD_E :
13500  acl = SePublicDefaultDacl;
13501  break;
13502  case IO_SD_SYS_ALL_ADM_ALL_WORLD_E_RES_E :
13503  acl = SePublicDefaultUnrestrictedDacl;
13504  break;
13505  case IO_SD_SYS_ALL_ADM_ALL_WORLD_RWE :
13506  acl = SePublicOpenDacl;
13507  break;
13508  case IO_SD_SYS_ALL_ADM_ALL_WORLD_RWE_RES_RE :
13509  acl = SePublicOpenUnrestrictedDacl;
13510  break;
13511  case IO_SD_SYS_ALL_ADM_RE :
13512  acl = SeSystemDefaultDacl;
13513  break;
13514  default:
13515  ASSERT(0);
13516  return STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER;
13517  }
13518 
13519  status = RtlCreateSecurityDescriptor(
13520  Descriptor,
13521  SECURITY_DESCRIPTOR_REVISION );
13522 
13523  ASSERT( NT_SUCCESS( status ) );
13524 
13525  status = RtlSetDaclSecurityDescriptor(
13526  Descriptor,
13527  TRUE,
13528  acl,
13529  FALSE );
13530 
13531 
13532  if(ARGUMENT_PRESENT(SecurityInformation)) {
13533  (*SecurityInformation) |= DACL_SECURITY_INFORMATION;
13534  }
13535  return status;
13536 }
13537 
13538 NTSTATUS
13539 IoGetRequestorSessionId(
13540  IN PIRP Irp,
13541  OUT PULONG pSessionId
13542  )
13543 
13544 /*++
13545 
13546 Routine Description:
13547 
13548  This routine returns the session ID for process that originally
13549  requested the specified I/O operation.
13550 
13551 Arguments:
13552 
13553  Irp - Pointer to the I/O Request Packet.
13554 
13555  pSessionId - Pointer to the session Id which is set upon successful return.
13556 
13557 Return Value:
13558 
13559  Returns STATUS_SUCCESS if the session ID was available, otherwise
13560  STATUS_UNSUCCESSFUL.
13561 
13562 --*/
13563 
13564 {
13565  PEPROCESS Process;
13566 
13567  //
13568  // Get the address of the process that requested the I/O operation.
13569  //
13570 
13571  if (Irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread) {
13572  Process = THREAD_TO_PROCESS( Irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread );
13573  *pSessionId = MmGetSessionId(Process);
13574  return(STATUS_SUCCESS);
13575  }
13576 
13577  *pSessionId = (ULONG) -1;
13578  return(STATUS_UNSUCCESSFUL);
13579 }
13580 
13581 VOID
13582 IoCancelFileOpen(
13583  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
13584  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject
13585  )
13586 /*++
13587 
13588 Routine Description:
13589 
13590  This routine is invoked by a filter driver to send a close to the
13591  next filesystem driver below. It's needed as part of the file open
13592  process. The filter driver forwards the open to the FSD and the FSD
13593  returns success. The filter driver then examines some stuff and
13594  decides that the open has to be failed. In this case it has to send
13595  a close to the FSD.
13596 
13597  We can safely assume a thread context because it has to be called only
13598  in the context of file open. If the file object already has a handle
13599  then the owner of the handle can then simply close the handle to the
13600  file object and we will close the file.
13601 
13602  This code is extracted from IopCloseFile and IopDeleteFile. So it is
13603  duplication of code but it prevents duplication elsewhere in other FSDs.
13604 
13605 Arguments:
13606 
13607  FileObject - Points to the file that needs to be closed.
13608 
13609  DeviceObject - Points to the device object of the filesystem driver below
13610  the filter driver.
13611 
13612 Return Value:
13613 
13614  None
13615 
13616 --*/
13617 
13618 {
13619  PIRP irp;
13620  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
13621  NTSTATUS status;
13622  KEVENT event;
13623  KIRQL irql;
13624 
13625  //
13626  // Cannot call this function if a handle has already been created
13627  // for this file.
13628  //
13629  ASSERT(!(FileObject->Flags & FO_HANDLE_CREATED));
13630 
13631  if (FileObject->Flags & FO_HANDLE_CREATED) {
13632  KeBugCheckEx( INVALID_CANCEL_OF_FILE_OPEN, (ULONG_PTR) FileObject, (ULONG_PTR)DeviceObject, 0, 0 );
13633  return;
13634  }
13635 
13636  //
13637  // Initialize the local event that will be used to synchronize access
13638  // to the driver completing this I/O operation.
13639  //
13640 
13641  KeInitializeEvent( &event, SynchronizationEvent, FALSE );
13642 
13643  //
13644  // Reset the event in the file object.
13645  //
13646 
13647  KeClearEvent( &FileObject->Event );
13648 
13649  //
13650  // Allocate and initialize the I/O Request Packet (IRP) for this
13651  // operation.
13652  //
13653 
13654  irp = IopAllocateIrpMustSucceed( DeviceObject->StackSize );
13655  irp->Tail.Overlay.OriginalFileObject = FileObject;
13656  irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread = PsGetCurrentThread();
13657  irp->RequestorMode = KernelMode;
13658 
13659  //
13660  // Fill in the service independent parameters in the IRP.
13661  //
13662 
13663  irp->UserEvent = &event;
13664  irp->UserIosb = &irp->IoStatus;
13665  irp->Overlay.AsynchronousParameters.UserApcRoutine = (PIO_APC_ROUTINE) NULL;
13666  irp->Flags = IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_API | IRP_CLOSE_OPERATION;
13667 
13668  //
13669  // Get a pointer to the stack location for the first driver. This will
13670  // be used to pass the original function codes and parameters. No
13671  // function-specific parameters are required for this operation.
13672  //
13673 
13674  irpSp = IoGetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
13675  irpSp->MajorFunction = IRP_MJ_CLEANUP;
13676  irpSp->FileObject = FileObject;
13677 
13678  //
13679  // Insert the packet at the head of the IRP list for the thread.
13680  //
13681 
13682  IopQueueThreadIrp( irp );
13683 
13684  //
13685  // Invoke the driver at its appropriate dispatch entry with the IRP.
13686  //
13687 
13688  status = IoCallDriver( DeviceObject, irp );
13689 
13690  //
13691  // If no error was incurred, wait for the I/O operation to complete.
13692  //
13693 
13694  if (status == STATUS_PENDING) {
13695  (VOID) KeWaitForSingleObject( &event,
13696  UserRequest,
13697  KernelMode,
13698  FALSE,
13699  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
13700  }
13701 
13702  //
13703  // The following code tears down the IRP by hand since it may not
13704  // be possible for it to be completed (either because this code was
13705  // invoked as APC_LEVEL in the first place - or because the reference
13706  // count on the object cannot be incremented due to this routine
13707  // being invoked by the delete file procedure below). Cleanup IRPs
13708  // therefore use close semantics (the close operation flag is set
13709  // in the IRP) so that the I/O complete request routine itself sets
13710  // the event to the Signaled state.
13711  //
13712 
13713  KeRaiseIrql( APC_LEVEL, &irql );
13714  IopDequeueThreadIrp( irp );
13715  KeLowerIrql( irql );
13716 
13717  //
13718  // Reuse the IRP for the next operation.
13719  //
13720 
13721  IoFreeIrp( irp );
13722 
13723  //
13724  // Reset the event in the file object.
13725  //
13726 
13727  KeClearEvent( &FileObject->Event );
13728 
13729  FileObject->Flags |= FO_FILE_OPEN_CANCELLED;
13730 
13731 }
13732 
13733 VOID
13734 IoRetryIrpCompletions(
13735  VOID
13736  )
13737 /*++
13738 
13739 Routine Description:
13740 
13741  This routine is called from Mm when a page fault has completed. It's
13742  called on the special occasion when a thread faults a page and then when
13743  it's waiting for the inpage to complete, an IopCompleteRequest APC fires
13744  and we fault the same page again (say if the user buffer falls on the
13745  same page). Note the fault during the APC may be referencing the same or
13746  a different user virtual address but this is irrelevant - the problem lies
13747  in the fact that both virtual address references are to the same physical
13748  page and thus result in a collided fault in the Mm.
13749 
13750  Mm detects this case (to avoid deadlock) and returns STATUS_FAULT_COLLISION
13751  and the I/O manager bails out the APC after marking the Irp with the flag
13752  IRP_RETRY_IO_COMPLETION. Later on when Mm has decided the fault has
13753  progressed far enough to avoid deadlock, it calls back into this routine
13754  which calls IopCompleteRequest again. The code in IopCompleteRequest is
13755  written in a reentrant way so that the retry knows the completion is only
13756  partially processed so far. We can fault in two places in IopCompleteRequest
13757  and in both cases if we call IopCompleteRequest again they will now work.
13758 
13759  This call must be called in the context of the thread that is faulting.
13760  This function is called at APC_LEVEL or below.
13761 
13762 Arguments:
13763 
13764  None.
13765 
13766 Return Value:
13767 
13768  None.
13769 
13770 --*/
13771 {
13772  KIRQL irql;
13773  PLIST_ENTRY header;
13774  PLIST_ENTRY entry;
13775  PETHREAD thread;
13776  PIRP irp;
13777  PVOID saveAuxiliaryPointer = NULL;
13778  PFILE_OBJECT fileObject;
13779 
13780  thread = PsGetCurrentThread();
13781 
13782  //
13783  // Raise the IRQL so that the IrpList cannot be modified by a completion
13784  // APC.
13785  //
13786 
13787  KeRaiseIrql( APC_LEVEL, &irql );
13788 
13789  header = &thread->IrpList;
13790  entry = thread->IrpList.Flink;
13791 
13792  //
13793  // Walk the list of pending IRPs, completing each of them.
13794  //
13795 
13796  while (header != entry) {
13797 
13798  irp = CONTAINING_RECORD( entry, IRP, ThreadListEntry );
13799  entry = entry->Flink;
13800 
13801  if (irp->Flags & IRP_RETRY_IO_COMPLETION) {
13802 
13803  ASSERT(!(irp->Flags & IRP_CREATE_OPERATION));
13804 
13805  irp->Flags &= ~IRP_RETRY_IO_COMPLETION;
13806  fileObject = irp->Tail.Overlay.OriginalFileObject;
13807  IopCompleteRequest(
13808  &irp->Tail.Apc,
13809  NULL,
13810  NULL,
13811  &fileObject,
13812  &saveAuxiliaryPointer);
13813  }
13814  }
13815 
13816  KeLowerIrql( irql );
13817 }
13818 
13819 #if defined(_WIN64)
13820 BOOLEAN
13821 IoIs32bitProcess(
13822  IN PIRP Irp OPTIONAL
13823  )
13824 /*+++
13825 
13826 Routine Description:
13827 
13828  This API returns TRUE if the process that originated the IRP is running a 32 bit x86
13829  application. If there is no IRP then a NULL can be passed to the API and that implies
13830  that the current process context is used to test if its running a 32 bit x86 application.
13831  Its assumed a NULL will be passed by drivers executing in the fast io path.
13832 
13833 Arguments:
13834 
13835  IRP OPTIONAL.
13836 
13837 Return Value:
13838 
13839  None.
13840 
13841 --*/
13842 {
13843  if (Irp) {
13844  if (Irp->RequestorMode == UserMode) {
13845  PEPROCESS Process;
13846  Process = IoGetRequestorProcess(Irp);
13847  if (Process && PsGetProcessWow64Process(Process)) {
13848  return TRUE;
13849  }
13850  }
13851  } else {
13852  if ((ExGetPreviousMode() == UserMode) &&
13853  (PsGetProcessWow64Process(PsGetCurrentProcess()))) {
13854  return TRUE;
13855  }
13856  }
13857  return FALSE;
13858 }
13859 #endif
13860 
13861 NTSTATUS
13862 IoQueryFileDosDeviceName(
13863  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
13864  OUT POBJECT_NAME_INFORMATION *ObjectNameInformation
13865  )
13866 
13867 /*++
13868 
13869 Routine Description:
13870 
13871  Thin shell around IopQueryNameInternal that returns a dos device name
13872  for a file e.g c:\foo
13873 
13874 Arguments:
13875 
13876  FileObject - Points to the file that needs to be closed.
13877 
13878  ObjectNameInformation - structure to return name in note this will be a flat
13879  unicode string where the buffer is adjacent to the string
13880 
13881  RetLength - returned length of structure
13882 
13883 Return Value:
13884 
13885  None
13886 
13887 --*/
13888 
13889 {
13890  ULONG ObjectNameInfoLength;
13891  POBJECT_NAME_INFORMATION ObjectNameInfo;
13892  NTSTATUS Status;
13893 
13894  //
13895  // Allocate an initial buffer to query the filename, query, then
13896  // retry if needed with the correct length.
13897  //
13898 
13899  ObjectNameInfoLength = 96*sizeof(WCHAR) + sizeof(UNICODE_STRING);
13900 
13901  while (TRUE) {
13902 
13903  ObjectNameInfo = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( PagedPool, ObjectNameInfoLength, 'nDoI');
13904 
13905  if (ObjectNameInfo == NULL) {
13906  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
13907  }
13908 
13909  Status = IopQueryNameInternal( FileObject,
13910  TRUE,
13911  TRUE,
13912  ObjectNameInfo,
13913  ObjectNameInfoLength,
13914  &ObjectNameInfoLength,
13915  KernelMode );
13916 
13917  if (Status == STATUS_SUCCESS) {
13918  *ObjectNameInformation = ObjectNameInfo;
13919  break;
13920  }
13921 
13922  ExFreePool( ObjectNameInfo );
13923 
13924  if (Status != STATUS_BUFFER_OVERFLOW) {
13925  break;
13926  }
13927  }
13928 
13929  return Status;
13930 }

13933 NTSTATUS
13934 IopUnloadSafeCompletion(
13935  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
13936  IN PIRP Irp,
13937  IN PVOID Context
13938  )
13939 {
13940  PIO_UNLOAD_SAFE_COMPLETION_CONTEXT Usc = Context;
13941  NTSTATUS Status;
13942 
13943  ObReferenceObject (Usc->DeviceObject);
13944 
13945  Status = Usc->CompletionRoutine (DeviceObject, Irp, Usc->Context);
13946 
13947  ObDereferenceObject (Usc->DeviceObject);
13948  ExFreePool (Usc);
13949  return Status;
13950 }
13951 
13952 
13953 NTSTATUS
13954 IoSetCompletionRoutineEx(
13955  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
13956  IN PIRP Irp,
13957  IN PIO_COMPLETION_ROUTINE CompletionRoutine,
13958  IN PVOID Context,
13959  IN BOOLEAN InvokeOnSuccess,
13960  IN BOOLEAN InvokeOnError,
13961  IN BOOLEAN InvokeOnCancel
13962  )
13963 //++
13964 // Routine Description:
13965 //
13966 // This routine is invoked to set the address of a completion routine which
13967 // is to be invoked when an I/O packet has been completed by a lower-level
13968 // driver. This routine obtains a reference count to the specified device object
13969 // to protect the completion routine from unload problems.
13970 //
13971 // Arguments:
13972 //
13973 // DeviceObject - Device object to take references on.
13974 //
13975 // Irp - Pointer to the I/O Request Packet itself.
13976 //
13977 // CompletionRoutine - Address of the completion routine that is to be
13978 // invoked once the next level driver completes the packet.
13979 //
13980 // Context - Specifies a context parameter to be passed to the completion
13981 // routine.
13982 //
13983 // InvokeOnSuccess - Specifies that the completion routine is invoked when the
13984 // operation is successfully completed.
13985 //
13986 // InvokeOnError - Specifies that the completion routine is invoked when the
13987 // operation completes with an error status.
13988 //
13989 // InvokeOnCancel - Specifies that the completion routine is invoked when the
13990 // operation is being canceled.
13991 //
13992 // Return Value:
13993 //
13994 // None.
13995 //
13996 //--
13997 {
13998  PIO_UNLOAD_SAFE_COMPLETION_CONTEXT Usc;
13999 
14000  Usc = ExAllocatePoolWithTag (NonPagedPool, sizeof (*Usc), 'sUoI');
14001  if (Usc == NULL) {
14002  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
14003  }
14004  Usc->DeviceObject = DeviceObject;
14005  Usc->CompletionRoutine = CompletionRoutine;
14006  Usc->Context = Context;
14007  IoSetCompletionRoutine (Irp, IopUnloadSafeCompletion, Usc, InvokeOnSuccess, InvokeOnError, InvokeOnCancel);
14008  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
14009 }
14010 
14011 NTSTATUS
14012 IoCreateDriver(
14013  IN PUNICODE_STRING DriverName OPTIONAL,
14014  IN PDRIVER_INITIALIZE InitializationFunction
14015  )
14016 /*++
14017 
14018 Routine Description:
14019 
14020  This routine creates a driver object for a kernel component that
14021  was not loaded as a driver. If the creation of the driver object
14022  succeeds, Initialization function is invoked with the same parameters
14023  as passed to DriverEntry.
14024 
14025 Parameters:
14026 
14027  DriverName - Supplies the name of the driver for which a driver object
14028  is to be created.
14029 
14030  InitializationFunction - Equivalent to DriverEntry().
14031 
14032 ReturnValue:
14033 
14034  Status code that indicates whether or not the function was successful.
14035 
14036 Notes:
14037 
14038 --*/
14039 {
14040  OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES objectAttributes;
14041  NTSTATUS status;
14042  PDRIVER_OBJECT driverObject;
14043  HANDLE driverHandle;
14044  ULONG objectSize;
14045  USHORT length;
14046  UNICODE_STRING driverName, serviceName;
14047  WCHAR buffer[60];
14048  ULONG i;
14049 
14050  PAGED_CODE();
14051 
14052  if (DriverName == NULL) {
14053 
14054  //
14055  // Made-up a name for the driver object.
14056  //
14057 
14058  length = (USHORT) _snwprintf(buffer, (sizeof(buffer) / sizeof(WCHAR)) - 1, L"\\Driver\\%08u", KiQueryLowTickCount());
14059  driverName.Length = length * sizeof(WCHAR);
14060  driverName.MaximumLength = driverName.Length + sizeof(UNICODE_NULL);
14061  driverName.Buffer = buffer; \
14062  } else {
14063  driverName = *DriverName;
14064  }
14065 
14066  //
14067  // Attempt to create the driver object
14068  //
14069 
14070  InitializeObjectAttributes( &objectAttributes,
14071  &driverName,
14072  OBJ_PERMANENT | OBJ_CASE_INSENSITIVE,
14073  NULL,
14074  NULL );
14075 
14076  objectSize = sizeof( DRIVER_OBJECT ) + sizeof( DRIVER_EXTENSION );
14077  status = ObCreateObject( KernelMode,
14078  IoDriverObjectType,
14079  &objectAttributes,
14080  KernelMode,
14081  NULL,
14082  objectSize,
14083  0,
14084  0,
14085  &driverObject );
14086 
14087  if( !NT_SUCCESS( status )){
14088 
14089  //
14090  // Driver object creation failed
14091  //
14092 
14093  return status;
14094  }
14095 
14096  //
14097  // We've created a driver object, initialize it.
14098  //
14099 
14100  RtlZeroMemory( driverObject, objectSize );
14101  driverObject->DriverExtension = (PDRIVER_EXTENSION)(driverObject + 1);
14102  driverObject->DriverExtension->DriverObject = driverObject;
14103  driverObject->Type = IO_TYPE_DRIVER;
14104  driverObject->Size = sizeof( DRIVER_OBJECT );
14105  driverObject->Flags = DRVO_BUILTIN_DRIVER;
14106  for (i = 0; i <= IRP_MJ_MAXIMUM_FUNCTION; i++)
14107  driverObject->MajorFunction[i] = IopInvalidDeviceRequest;
14108  driverObject->DriverInit = InitializationFunction;
14109 
14110  serviceName.Buffer = (PWSTR)ExAllocatePool(PagedPool, driverName.Length + sizeof(WCHAR));
14111  if (serviceName.Buffer) {
14112  serviceName.MaximumLength = driverName.Length + sizeof(WCHAR);
14113  serviceName.Length = driverName.Length;
14114  RtlCopyMemory(serviceName.Buffer, driverName.Buffer, driverName.Length);
14115  serviceName.Buffer[serviceName.Length / sizeof(WCHAR)] = UNICODE_NULL;
14116  driverObject->DriverExtension->ServiceKeyName = serviceName;
14117  } else {
14118  status = STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
14119  goto errorFreeDriverObject;
14120  }
14121 
14122  //
14123  // Insert it into the object table.
14124  //
14125 
14126  status = ObInsertObject( driverObject,
14127  NULL,
14128  FILE_READ_DATA,
14129  OBJ_KERNEL_HANDLE,
14130  NULL,
14131  &driverHandle );
14132 
14133  if( !NT_SUCCESS( status )){
14134 
14135  //
14136  // Couldn't insert the driver object into the table.
14137  // The object got dereferenced by the object manager. Just exit
14138  //
14139 
14140  goto errorReturn;
14141  }
14142 
14143  //
14144  // Reference the handle and obtain a pointer to the driver object so that
14145  // the handle can be deleted without the object going away.
14146  //
14147 
14148  status = ObReferenceObjectByHandle( driverHandle,
14149  0,
14150  IoDriverObjectType,
14151  KernelMode,
14152  (PVOID *) &driverObject,
14153  (POBJECT_HANDLE_INFORMATION) NULL );
14154  if( !NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
14155  //
14156  // Backout here is probably bogus. If the ref didn't work then the handle is probably bad
14157  // Do this right though just in case there are other common error returns for ObRef...
14158  //
14159  ZwMakeTemporaryObject( driverHandle ); // Cause handle close to free the object
14160  ZwClose( driverHandle ); // Close the handle.
14161  goto errorReturn;
14162  }
14163 
14164  ZwClose( driverHandle );
14165 
14166  //
14167  // Store the name of the device driver in the driver object so that it
14168  // can be easily found by the error log thread.
14169  //
14170 
14171  driverObject->DriverName.Buffer = ExAllocatePool( PagedPool,
14172  driverName.MaximumLength );
14173  if (driverObject->DriverName.Buffer) {
14174  driverObject->DriverName.MaximumLength = driverName.MaximumLength;
14175  driverObject->DriverName.Length = driverName.Length;
14176 
14177  RtlCopyMemory( driverObject->DriverName.Buffer,
14178  driverName.Buffer,
14179  driverName.MaximumLength );
14180  }
14181 
14182  //
14183  // Call the driver initialization routine
14184  //
14185 
14186  status = (*InitializationFunction)(driverObject, NULL);
14187 
14188  if( !NT_SUCCESS( status )){
14189 
14190 errorFreeDriverObject:
14191 
14192  //
14193  // If we were unsuccessful, we need to get rid of the driverObject
14194  // that we created.
14195  //
14196 
14197  ObMakeTemporaryObject( driverObject );
14198  ObDereferenceObject( driverObject );
14199  }
14200 errorReturn:
14201  return status;
14202 }
14203 
14204 VOID
14205 IoDeleteDriver(
14206  IN PDRIVER_OBJECT DriverObject
14207  )
14208 /*++
14209 
14210 Routine Description:
14211 
14212  This routine deletes a driver object created explicitly through
14213  IoCreateDriver.
14214 
14215 Parameters:
14216 
14217  DriverObject - Supplies a pointer to the driver object to be deleted.
14218 
14219 ReturnValue:
14220 
14221  Status code that indicates whether or not the function was successful.
14222 
14223 Notes:
14224 
14225 --*/
14226 {
14227 
14228  ObDereferenceObject(DriverObject);
14229 }
14230 
14231 PDEVICE_OBJECT
14232 IoGetLowerDeviceObject(
14233  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject
14234  )
14235 /*++
14236 
14237 Routine Description:
14238 
14239  This routine gets the next lower device object on the device stack.
14240 
14241 Parameters:
14242 
14243  DeviceObject - Supplies a pointer to the deviceObject whose next device object needs
14244  to be obtained.
14245 
14246 ReturnValue:
14247 
14248  NULL if driver is unloaded or marked for unload or if there is no attached deviceobject.
14249  Otherwise a referenced pointer to the deviceobject is returned.
14250 
14251 Notes:
14252 
14253 --*/
14254 {
14255  KIRQL irql;
14256  PDEVICE_OBJECT targetDeviceObject;
14257 
14258  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock );
14259 
14260  if ((DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->ExtensionFlags &
14261  (DOE_UNLOAD_PENDING | DOE_DELETE_PENDING | DOE_REMOVE_PENDING | DOE_REMOVE_PROCESSED))) {
14262 
14263  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
14264  return NULL;
14265  }
14266 
14267  targetDeviceObject = NULL;
14268  if (DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->AttachedTo) {
14269  targetDeviceObject = DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->AttachedTo;
14270  ObReferenceObject(targetDeviceObject);
14271  }
14272 
14273  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
14274 
14275  return targetDeviceObject;
14276 }

14278 NTSTATUS
14279 IoEnumerateDeviceObjectList(
14280  IN PDRIVER_OBJECT DriverObject,
14281  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT *DeviceObjectList,
14282  IN ULONG DeviceObjectListSize,
14283  OUT PULONG ActualNumberDeviceObjects
14284  )
14285 /*++
14286 
14287 Routine Description:
14288 
14289  This routine gets the next lower device object on the device stack.
14290 
14291 Parameters:
14292 
14293  DriverObject - Driver Object whose device objects have to be enumerated.
14294 
14295  DeviceObjectList - Pointer to an array where device object lists will be stored.
14296 
14297  DeviceObjectListSize - Size in bytes of the DeviceObjectList array
14298 
14299  ActualNumberDeviceObjects - The actual number of device objects in a driver object.
14300 
14301 ReturnValue:
14302 
14303  If size is not sufficient it will return STATUS_BUFFER_TOO_SMALL.
14304 
14305 Notes:
14306 
14307 --*/
14308 {
14309  KIRQL irql;
14310  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
14311  ULONG numListEntries;
14312  ULONG numDeviceObjects = 0;
14313  NTSTATUS status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
14314 
14315  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock );
14316 
14317  deviceObject = DriverObject->DeviceObject;
14318 
14319  numListEntries = DeviceObjectListSize / sizeof(PDEVICE_OBJECT);
14320 
14321  while (deviceObject) {
14322  numDeviceObjects++;
14323  deviceObject = deviceObject->NextDevice;
14324  }
14325 
14326  *ActualNumberDeviceObjects = numDeviceObjects;
14327 
14328  if (numDeviceObjects > numListEntries) {
14329  status = STATUS_BUFFER_TOO_SMALL;
14330  }
14331 
14332  deviceObject = DriverObject->DeviceObject;
14333 
14334  while ((numListEntries > 0) && deviceObject) {
14335  ObReferenceObject(deviceObject);
14336  *DeviceObjectList = deviceObject;
14337  DeviceObjectList++;
14338  deviceObject = deviceObject->NextDevice;
14339  numListEntries--;
14340  }
14341 
14342  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
14343 
14344  return status;
14345 }
14346 
14347 PDEVICE_OBJECT
14348 IoGetDeviceAttachmentBaseRef(
14349  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject
14350  )
14351 
14352 /*++
14353 
14354 Routine Description:
14355 
14356  This routine returns the lowest level device object associated with
14357  the specified device.
14358 
14359 Arguments:
14360 
14361  DeviceObject - Supplies a pointer to the device for which the bottom of
14362  attachment chain is to be found.
14363 
14364 Return Value:
14365 
14366  The function value is a reference to the lowest level device attached
14367  to the specified device. If the supplied device object is that device
14368  object, then a pointer to it is returned.
14369 
14370  A reference is taken on the returned device object. It is the
14371  responsibility of the caller to release it.
14372 
14373 --*/
14374 
14375 {
14376  PDEVICE_OBJECT baseDeviceObject;
14377  KIRQL irql;
14378 
14379  //
14380  // Any examination of attachment chain linkage must be done with
14381  // IopDatabaseLock taken.
14382  //
14383 
14384  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock );
14385 
14386  //
14387  // Find the base of the attachment chain.
14388  //
14389 
14390  baseDeviceObject = IopGetDeviceAttachmentBase( DeviceObject );
14391 
14392  //
14393  // Reference the device object before releasing the database lock.
14394  //
14395 
14396  ObReferenceObject( baseDeviceObject );
14397  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
14398 
14399  return baseDeviceObject;
14400 }
14401 
14402 NTSTATUS
14403 IoGetDiskDeviceObject(
14404  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT FileSystemDeviceObject,
14405  OUT PDEVICE_OBJECT *DiskDeviceObject
14406  )
14407 /*++
14408 
14409 Routine Description:
14410 
14411  This routine returns the disk device object associated with a filesystem
14412  volume device object. The disk device object need not be an actual disk but
14413  in general associated with storage.
14414 
14415 Arguments:
14416 
14417  FileSystemDeviceObject - Supplies a pointer to the device for which the bottom of
14418  attachment chain is to be found.
14419  DiskDeviceObject - Supplies storage for the return value.
14420 
14421 Return Value:
14422 
14423  The function returns the disk device object associated with a filesystem
14424  device object. Returns a referenced device object. If the VPB reference count
14425  is zero we cannot rely on the device object pointer.
14426 
14427 --*/
14428 {
14429  KIRQL irql;
14430  PVPB vpb;
14431 
14432  //
14433  // Filesystem deviceobject's VPB field should be NULL
14434  //
14435 
14436  if (FileSystemDeviceObject->Vpb) {
14437  return STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER;
14438  }
14439 
14440  IoAcquireVpbSpinLock(&irql);
14441 
14442  vpb = FileSystemDeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->Vpb;
14443 
14444  if (!vpb) {
14445  IoReleaseVpbSpinLock(irql);
14446  return STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER;
14447  }
14448 
14449  if (vpb->ReferenceCount == 0) {
14450  IoReleaseVpbSpinLock(irql);
14451  return STATUS_VOLUME_DISMOUNTED;
14452  }
14453 
14454  if (!(vpb->Flags & VPB_MOUNTED)) {
14455  IoReleaseVpbSpinLock(irql);
14456  return STATUS_VOLUME_DISMOUNTED;
14457  }
14458 
14459  *DiskDeviceObject = vpb->RealDevice;
14460  ObReferenceObject( *DiskDeviceObject);
14461  IoReleaseVpbSpinLock(irql);
14462 
14463  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
14464 }

14466 NTSTATUS
14467 IoSetSystemPartition(
14468  PUNICODE_STRING VolumeNameString
14469  )
14470 /*++
14471 
14472 Routine Description:
14473 
14474  This routine sets system partition registry key to the volume name string. Used
14475  by the mount manager in case volume name changes.
14476 
14477 Arguments:
14478 
14479  VolumeNameString - Name of the volume that is the system partition.
14480 
14481 Return Value:
14482 
14483  NTSTATUS
14484 
14485 --*/
14486 {
14487  HANDLE systemHandle, setupHandle;
14488  UNICODE_STRING nameString, machineSystemName;
14489  NTSTATUS status;
14490 
14491  //
14492  // Declare a unicode buffer big enough to contain the longest string we'll be using.
14493  // (ANSI string in 'sizeof()' below on purpose--we want the number of chars here.)
14494  //
14495  WCHAR nameBuffer[sizeof("SystemPartition")];
14496 
14497  //
14498  // Open HKLM\SYSTEM key.
14499  //
14500 
14501  RtlInitUnicodeString(&machineSystemName, L"\\REGISTRY\\MACHINE\\SYSTEM");
14502  status = IopOpenRegistryKeyEx( &systemHandle,
14503  NULL,
14504  &machineSystemName,
14505  KEY_ALL_ACCESS
14506  );
14507 
14508  if (!NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
14509  return status;
14510  }
14511 
14512  //
14513  // Now open/create the setup subkey.
14514  //
14515 
14516  ASSERT( sizeof(L"Setup") <= sizeof(nameBuffer) );
14517 
14518  nameBuffer[0] = L'S';
14519  nameBuffer[1] = L'e';
14520  nameBuffer[2] = L't';
14521  nameBuffer[3] = L'u';
14522  nameBuffer[4] = L'p';
14523  nameBuffer[5] = L'\0';
14524 
14525  nameString.MaximumLength = sizeof(L"Setup");
14526  nameString.Length = sizeof(L"Setup") - sizeof(WCHAR);
14527  nameString.Buffer = nameBuffer;
14528 
14529  status = IopCreateRegistryKeyEx( &setupHandle,
14530  systemHandle,
14531  &nameString,
14532  KEY_ALL_ACCESS,
14533  REG_OPTION_NON_VOLATILE,
14534  NULL
14535  );
14536 
14537  NtClose(systemHandle); // Don't need the handle to the HKLM\System key anymore.
14538 
14539  if (!NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
14540  return status;
14541  }
14542 
14543  ASSERT( sizeof(L"SystemPartition") <= sizeof(nameBuffer) );
14544 
14545  nameBuffer[0] = L'S';
14546  nameBuffer[1] = L'y';
14547  nameBuffer[2] = L's';
14548  nameBuffer[3] = L't';
14549  nameBuffer[4] = L'e';
14550  nameBuffer[5] = L'm';
14551  nameBuffer[6] = L'P';
14552  nameBuffer[7] = L'a';
14553  nameBuffer[8] = L'r';
14554  nameBuffer[9] = L't';
14555  nameBuffer[10] = L'i';
14556  nameBuffer[11] = L't';
14557  nameBuffer[12] = L'i';
14558  nameBuffer[13] = L'o';
14559  nameBuffer[14] = L'n';
14560  nameBuffer[15] = L'\0';
14561 
14562  nameString.MaximumLength = sizeof(L"SystemPartition");
14563  nameString.Length = sizeof(L"SystemPartition") - sizeof(WCHAR);
14564 
14565 
14566 
14567  status = ZwSetValueKey(setupHandle,
14568  &nameString,
14569  TITLE_INDEX_VALUE,
14570  REG_SZ,
14571  VolumeNameString->Buffer,
14572  VolumeNameString->Length + sizeof(WCHAR)
14573  );
14574 
14575 
14576  return status;
14577 }

14579 
14580 BOOLEAN
14581 IoIsFileOriginRemote(
14582  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject
14583  )
14584 
14585 /*++
14586 
14587 Routine Description:
14588 
14589  This routine returns the origin of the original create request for the
14590  specified file. That is, was it created locally on this machine or remotely
14591  on another machine via a network provider.
14592 
14593 Arguments:
14594 
14595  FileObject - Supplies the file object that is to be checked.
14596 
14597 Return Value:
14598 
14599  TRUE - Means the create request originated on a remote machine.
14600 
14601  FALSE - Means the create request originated on the local machine.
14602 
14603 --*/
14604 
14605 {
14606  BOOLEAN Remote;
14607 
14608 
14609  //
14610  // Check the origin flag and return the appropriate result.
14611  //
14612 
14613  if (FileObject->Flags & FO_REMOTE_ORIGIN) {
14614 
14615  Remote = TRUE;
14616 
14617  } else {
14618 
14619  Remote = FALSE;
14620  }
14621 
14622  return Remote;
14623 }
14624 
14625 NTSTATUS
14626 IoSetFileOrigin(
14627  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
14628  IN BOOLEAN Remote
14629  )
14630 
14631 /*++
14632 
14633 Routine Description:
14634 
14635  This routine sets the origin of the original create request for the
14636  specified file. That is, was it created locally on this machine or remotely
14637  on another machine via a network provider. By default file objects are
14638  considered to have a local origin. Network providers should call this
14639  function in their server for any file objects that were created to satisfy
14640  a create request from their client.
14641 
14642 Arguments:
14643 
14644  FileObject - Supplies the file object that is to be set.
14645 
14646  Remote - Supplies whether the file object is for a remote create request or not.
14647 
14648 Return Value:
14649 
14650  Returns STATUS_SUCCESS unless the origin is already set to what the caller is requesting.
14651 
14652 --*/
14653 
14654 {
14655  NTSTATUS Status = STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER_MIX;
14656 
14657 
14658  //
14659  // Set or clear the origin flag per the callers request.
14660  //
14661 
14662  if (Remote) {
14663 
14664  if ((FileObject->Flags & FO_REMOTE_ORIGIN) == 0) {
14665 
14666  FileObject->Flags |= FO_REMOTE_ORIGIN;
14667  Status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
14668  }
14669 
14670  } else {
14671 
14672  if (FileObject->Flags & FO_REMOTE_ORIGIN) {
14673 
14674  FileObject->Flags &= ~FO_REMOTE_ORIGIN;
14675  Status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
14676  }
14677  }
14678 
14679  return Status;
14680 }
14681 
14682 
14683 PVOID
14684 IoGetFileObjectFilterContext(
14685  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject
14686  )
14687 /*++
14688 
14689 Routine Description:
14690 
14691  This routine returns the filter context associated with a fileobject that has an extension.
14692 
14693 Arguments:
14694 
14695  FileObject - FileObject for which the filter context is retrieved
14696 
14697 Return Value:
14698 
14699  NTSTATUS
14700 
14701 --*/
14702 {
14703  PIOP_FILE_OBJECT_EXTENSION fileObjectExtension;
14704 
14705  if (FileObject->Flags & FO_FILE_OBJECT_HAS_EXTENSION) {
14706  fileObjectExtension =(PIOP_FILE_OBJECT_EXTENSION)(FileObject + 1);
14707  return (fileObjectExtension->FilterContext);
14708  }
14709  return NULL;
14710 }

14713 NTSTATUS
14714 IoChangeFileObjectFilterContext(
14715  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
14716  IN PVOID FilterContext,
14717  IN BOOLEAN Set
14718  )
14719 /*++
14720 
14721 Routine Description:
14722 
14723  This routine set or clear fileobject filter context. It can be set only once.
14724 
14725 Arguments:
14726 
14727  FileObject - FileObject for which the filter context is retrieved
14728  FilterContext - New Filter context to be set in the fileobject extension
14729  Set - If TRUE allows FilterContext to be set in the fileobject only if the old value is NULL
14730  If FALSE allows fileObject field to be cleared only if FileContext is the old value in the fileobject.
14731 
14732 Return Value:
14733 
14734  Returns NTSTATUS
14735 
14736 --*/
14737 {
14738  PIOP_FILE_OBJECT_EXTENSION fileObjectExtension;
14739 
14740  if (FileObject->Flags & FO_FILE_OBJECT_HAS_EXTENSION) {
14741  fileObjectExtension =(PIOP_FILE_OBJECT_EXTENSION)(FileObject + 1);
14742  if (Set) {
14743  if (InterlockedCompareExchangePointer(&fileObjectExtension->FilterContext, FilterContext, NULL) != NULL)
14744  return STATUS_ALREADY_COMMITTED;
14745  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
14746  } else {
14747  if (InterlockedCompareExchangePointer(&fileObjectExtension->FilterContext, NULL, FilterContext) != FilterContext)
14748  return STATUS_ALREADY_COMMITTED;
14749  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
14750  }
14751  }
14752  return STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER;
14753 }

14770 
14771 NTSTATUS
14772 IoValidateDeviceIoControlAccess(
14773  IN PIRP Irp,
14774  IN ULONG RequiredAccess
14775  )
14776 /*++
14777 
14778 Routine Description:
14779 
14780  This routine validates ioctl access bits based on granted access information passed in the IRP.
14781  This routine is called by a driver to validate IOCTL access bits for IOCTLs that were originally
14782  defined as FILE_ANY_ACCESS and cannot be changed for compatibility reasons but really has to be
14783  validated for read/write access.
14784 
14785 
14786 Arguments:
14787 
14788  IRP - IRP for the device control
14789  RequiredAccess - Is the expected access required by the driver. Should be FILE_READ_ACCESS, FILE_WRITE_ACCESS
14790  or both.
14791 
14792 Return Value:
14793 
14794  Returns NTSTATUS
14795 
14796 --*/
14797 {
14798  ACCESS_MASK grantedAccess;
14799  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
14800 
14801  //
14802  // Validate RequiredAccess.
14803  //
14804 
14805  if (RequiredAccess & (FILE_READ_ACCESS|FILE_WRITE_ACCESS)){
14806 
14807  irpSp = IoGetCurrentIrpStackLocation(Irp);
14808 
14809  //
14810  // If the driver passes the wrong IRP fail the API.
14811  //
14812 
14813  if ((irpSp->MajorFunction != IRP_MJ_DEVICE_CONTROL) &&
14814  (irpSp->MajorFunction != IRP_MJ_FILE_SYSTEM_CONTROL)) {
14815  return STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER;
14816  }
14817 
14818  //
14819  // Kernel mode IRPs always succeed.
14820  //
14821 
14822  if (Irp->RequestorMode == KernelMode) {
14823  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
14824  }
14825 
14826  //
14827  // Get the granted access bits from the IRP.
14828  //
14829 
14830  grantedAccess = (irpSp->Flags & SL_READ_ACCESS_GRANTED) ? FILE_READ_DATA : 0;
14831  grantedAccess |= (irpSp->Flags & SL_WRITE_ACCESS_GRANTED) ? FILE_WRITE_DATA : 0;
14832 
14833  if (SeComputeGrantedAccesses ( grantedAccess, RequiredAccess ) != RequiredAccess ) {
14834  return STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED;
14835  } else {
14836  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
14837  }
14838 
14839  } else {
14840  return STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER;
14841  }
14842 }
14843 
14844 
14845 IO_PAGING_PRIORITY
14846 FASTCALL
14847 IoGetPagingIoPriority(
14848  IN PIRP Irp
14849  )
14850 /*++
14851 
14852 Routine Description:
14853 
14854  This routine returns the paging priority for an IRP. Its
14855  called by the storage stack to determine how to queue the IRP to the
14856  disk.
14857 
14858 Arguments:
14859 
14860  IRP - IRP for paging IO.
14861 
14862 Return Value:
14863 
14864  Returns IO_PAGING_PRIORITY
14865 
14866 --*/
14867 {
14868  if (Irp->Flags & IRP_HIGH_PRIORITY_PAGING_IO) {
14869  return IoPagingPriorityHigh;
14870  }
14871  if (!(Irp->Flags & IRP_PAGING_IO)) {
14872  return IoPagingPriorityInvalid;
14873  }
14874  return IoPagingPriorityNormal;
14875 }
14876 
14877 PDEVICE_OBJECT
14878 IoFindDeviceThatFailedIrp(
14879  IN PIRP Irp
14880  )
14881 /*++
14882 
14883 Routine Description:
14884 
14885  This routine returns the top most device object in the stack
14886  that failed the IRP. It returns NULL if the IRP's status
14887  is successful. Note that its the responsibility of the caller
14888  to ensure that the device object is valid.
14889 
14890 Arguments:
14891 
14892  IRP - Pointer to IRP.
14893 
14894 Return Value:
14895 
14896  Returns DEVICE_OBJECT pointer
14897 
14898 --*/
14899 {
14900  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
14901  ULONG i;
14902  ULONG stackSize = Irp->StackCount;
14903 
14904  if (NT_SUCCESS(Irp->IoStatus.Status)) {
14905  return NULL;
14906  }
14907 
14908  irpSp = ((PIO_STACK_LOCATION) ((UCHAR *) (Irp) +
14909  sizeof( IRP ) +
14910  ( (stackSize - 1) * sizeof( IO_STACK_LOCATION ))));
14911 
14912 
14913  for (i = 0; i < stackSize; i++, irpSp--) {
14914  if (irpSp->Control & SL_ERROR_RETURNED) {
14915  return irpSp->DeviceObject;
14916  }
14917  }
14918 
14919  return NULL;
14920 }

14922 
14923 NTSTATUS
14924 IoEnumerateRegisteredFiltersList(
14925  IN PDRIVER_OBJECT *DriverObjectList,
14926  IN ULONG DriverObjectListSize,
14927  OUT PULONG ActualNumberDriverObjects
14928  )
14929 /*++
14930 
14931 Routine Description:
14932 
14933  This routine retrieves a list of driver objects associated with all of the
14934  filters which have registered with the system.
14935 
14936 Parameters:
14937 
14938  DriverObjectList - Pointer to an array where driver object lists will be stored.
14939 
14940  DriverObjectListSize - Size in bytes of the DriverObjectList array
14941 
14942  ActualNumberDriverObjects - The actual number of driver objects returned.
14943 
14944 ReturnValue:
14945 
14946  If size is not sufficient it will return STATUS_BUFFER_TOO_SMALL.
14947 
14948 Notes:
14949 
14950 --*/
14951 {
14952  PNOTIFICATION_PACKET nPacket;
14953  PLIST_ENTRY entry;
14954  ULONG numListEntries;
14955  ULONG numDriverObjects = 0;
14956  NTSTATUS status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
14957 
14958  //
14959  // Lock the list shared
14960  //
14961 
14962  ExAcquireResourceSharedLite( &IopDatabaseResource, TRUE );
14963 
14964  //
14965  // Calculate how many entries can be returned
14966  //
14967 
14968  numListEntries = DriverObjectListSize / sizeof(PDRIVER_OBJECT);
14969 
14970  //
14971  // Calculate how many entries are on the list
14972  //
14973 
14974  entry = IopFsNotifyChangeQueueHead.Flink;
14975  while (entry != &IopFsNotifyChangeQueueHead) {
14976 
14977  numDriverObjects++;
14978  entry = entry->Flink;
14979  }
14980 
14981  //
14982  // Return total number of entries on the list
14983  //
14984 
14985  *ActualNumberDriverObjects = numDriverObjects;
14986 
14987  //
14988  // If we don't have room for all of the entries, tell them about this
14989  //
14990 
14991  if (numDriverObjects > numListEntries) {
14992  status = STATUS_BUFFER_TOO_SMALL;
14993  }
14994 
14995  //
14996  // Return what entries we can
14997  //
14998 
14999  entry = IopFsNotifyChangeQueueHead.Flink;
15000 
15001  while ((numListEntries > 0) && (entry != &IopFsNotifyChangeQueueHead)) {
15002 
15003  nPacket = CONTAINING_RECORD( entry, NOTIFICATION_PACKET, ListEntry );
15004 
15005  ObReferenceObject(nPacket->DriverObject);
15006 
15007  *DriverObjectList = nPacket->DriverObject;
15008  DriverObjectList++;
15009 
15010  entry = entry->Flink;
15011  numListEntries--;
15012  }
15013 
15014  ExReleaseResourceLite( &IopDatabaseResource );
15015 
15016  return status;
15017 }
15018

15020 // Thunks to support standard call callers
15021 //
15022

15024 #undef IoCallDriver
15025 #endif
